<P N="6">6 Heb. The <HI>Red Worm.</HI> Compare <HI>I&s;a.</HI> 1.18. the &s;ame Word is u&s;ed for our <HI>Crim&s;ons Sins.</HI> Think with &s;urpri&s;e! <HI>Nazianzen</HI> ob&s;erves, Our Saviour is compared unto the weake&s;t things; A <HI>Worm,</HI> a <HI>Lamb:</HI> The <HI>Devil</HI> is compared unto the &s;tronge&s;t&mdash;A <HI>Lion,</HI> an <HI>Armed One.</HI> Yet our Saviour is too hard for the Devil.</P>
<P N="26">26 <HI>Arnobius</HI> has a fine Thought, <HI>Edent corpus ejus pauperes &s;piritu, ut &s;atientur.</HI></P>
<P N="29">29&mdash;<HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> does well to refer it unto the <HI>Dead.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="23" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="50" REF="001946_0087_0FFCB7AC0F062930">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXIII.</HI> A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 MY Shepherd is th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; I &s;hall not be in <HI>[any]</HI> want: &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In pa&s;tures of a tender gra&s;s &Verbar; he <HI>[ever]</HI> makes me to lie down: &Verbar; To waters of tran|quillities &Verbar; He gently carries me, <HI>[along,]</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 My <HI>feeble and my wandring</HI> Soul &Verbar; He <HI>[kindly]</HI> does fetch back again; &Verbar; In the plain paths of righteou&s;ne&s;s &Verbar; He does lead <HI>[and guide]</HI> me along, &Verbar; becau&s;e of the regard He has &Verbar; <HI>[ever]</HI> unto His <HI>Glorious</HI> Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Yea, when I &s;hall walk in the Vale &Verbar; of the dark <HI>[di&s;mal]</HI> &s;hade of Death, &Verbar; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> of no evil be afraid, &Verbar; becau&s;e thou <HI>[ever]</HI> art with me. &Verbar; Thy rod and thy &s;taff, the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> are what &Verbar; yield <HI>[con&s;tant]</HI> comfort unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 A Table thou do&s;t furni&s;h out &Verbar; richly <HI>[for me]</HI> before my face. &Verbar; 'Tis in view of mine Enemies; &Verbar; <HI>[And then]</HI> my head thou do&s;t anoint &Verbar; with fatning and perfuming Oil: &Verbar; my cup it <HI>[ever]</HI> overflows. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Mo&s;t certainly the thing that is &Verbar; Good, with <HI>[mo&s;t kind]</HI> Benignity, &Verbar; <HI>This</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the days that I do live &Verbar; &s;hall <HI>[&s;till an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">]</HI> ever follow me; &Verbar; Yea, I &s;hall dwell, * an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> Sabbatize, &Verbar; even to <HI>[unknown]</HI> leng<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> of days, &Verbar; <HI>Lodg'd</HI> in the Hou&s;e which d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> belong &Verbar; to <HI>[Him who's]</HI> the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="51" REF="001946_0088_0FFCB03DF3F5ECF8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, the Confidence of the Church under the Couduct of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah:</HI> He &s;ays, Joh. X. 11. <HI>I am the Good Shepherd.</HI> The Prophets have taught us how to apply the P&s;alm. See <HI>I&s;a.</HI> XI. 10. <HI>Jer.</HI> XXIII. 3. <HI>Ezck.</HI> XXXIV. 11, 23. And &s;o have the Apo&s;tles, 1 <HI>Pet.</HI> II. 25. and V. 4 <HI>Heb.</HI> XIII. 20.</P>
<P N="1">1&mdash;And, <HI>Chri&s;tians,</HI> Why &s;hould not you find in your Secular Employments, the Occa&s;ions of Divine, Devout, Heavenly Reflections! <HI>David,</HI> a <HI>Shepherd,</HI> is led by <HI>Shepherdy,</HI> to think on the Heavenly <HI>Shepherd.</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>Dru&s;ius</HI> will have <HI>David</HI> now to think of <HI>Samuel's</HI> Anointing of him.</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Good,</HI> and <HI>Benignity</HI> are Names of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah. Chri&s;tian,</HI> Thou knowe&s;t why He &s;hould be called &s;o. In the <HI>Luminous Cloud,</HI> which like a Pillar did follow the Church in the Wilderne&s;s, there was a marvellous Pre&s;ence of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> May not this be here pointed at! The <HI>Shelter</HI> which this <HI>Pillar</HI> gave, was that of an <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI> With &s;ome eye to that <HI>Mo&s;es</HI> might &s;ay, P&s;alm. XC. 1. <HI>Thou ha&s;t been our dwelling place.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="24" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXIV.</HI> A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 TO the ETERNAL God, the Earth &Verbar; and what fills it belongs; &Verbar; the ha|bitable World, and all &Verbar; that do inhabit it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 For the foundations of it He &Verbar; hath laid upon the Seas; &Verbar; and He hath firmly fixed it &Verbar; again&s;t the rolling floods. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Who &s;hall a&s;cend into the Mount &Verbar;
<PB N="52" REF="001946_0089_0FFCB7AE4A3860F8">of the ETERNAL God? And who is it &s;hall &Verbar; &s;tand in the &Verbar; place of His Holine&s;s? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 One that is clean in hands, but then &Verbar; One that is pure in heart; &Verbar; who don't re|ceive his Soul in vain, &Verbar; nor &s;wear deceit|fully: &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 This Man the Ble&s;&s;ing &s;hall receive &Verbar; from the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and Righteou&s;|ne&s;s &s;hall from the God &Verbar; of his Salvation have. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 This is the Generation of &Verbar; them that &s;eek Him aright; &Verbar; even of them that &s;ee &Verbar; thy face: &Verbar; Jacob is &s;uch as the&s;e. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Lift up your heads, O Gates, and be lift up, O la&s;ting Doors; &Verbar; and &s;o the King of Glory will &Verbar; now make His entry there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Who is the King of Glory? 'Tis &Verbar; JE|HOVAH &s;trong and great: &Verbar; 'Tis the ETER|NAL God who is &Verbar; in War a mighty one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Lift up your Heads, O Gates, and be lift up, O la&s;ting Doors; &Verbar; and &s;o the King of Glory now &Verbar; will make His entry there.</P>
<P N="10">10 Who is the King of Glory? 'Tis JEHOVAH Tzebaoth: &Verbar; <HI>'Tis the ETERNAL Lord of Ho&s;ts,</HI> &Verbar; the King of Glory's HE. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>SUppo&s;e the People now attending the Removal <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the <HI>Ark</HI> unto <HI>Zion,</HI> with extraordinary Solemni<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> They are Exhorted now to practi&s;e the mo&s;t <HI>Sub&s;ta<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|tial</HI>
<PB N="53" REF="001946_0090_0FFCB0433B0F1078">together with their <HI>Ceremonial</HI> Pi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ty. The A&s;cent of our Saviour, was repre&s;ented in that Solemnity; and m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">y here be Prophe&s;ied.</P>
<P>The Hebrews did u&s;e to Sing the P&s;alm on the <HI>Fir&s;t Day of the Week.</HI> And the LXX add a Title of that Importance. Doubtle&s;s (as Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> expre&s;&s;es it). becau&s;e their Wi&s;e Men &s;aw here a Prophecy of CHRIST, who&s;e fir&s;t &s;tep unto the Throne of His Glory, was on the <HI>Fir&s;t Day of the Week.</HI></P>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ut it is urged by Dr. <HI>Allix,</HI> that the Return of our Saviour may be as much con&s;idered here; and His coming in His Kingdom.</P>
<P>The P&s;alm contains the Characters of tho&s;e who &s;hall be admitted into it. That expre&s;&s;ion, <HI>In War &amp; Mighty One;</HI> &s;uppo&s;es His Enemies to be vanqui&s;hed. Compare, <HI>Rev.</HI> XIX. 6.</P>
<P N="4">4 Surely, He that employs a <HI>Soul</HI> only in the mean and vile purpo&s;es of impiety, <HI>Receives a Soul in vain.</HI> And, O you, who do nothing for the Souls committed unto your Charge; is not this your Character too!</P>
<P N="7">7, 9 <HI>Twice opened!</HI> Fir&s;t for thy SAVIOUR, and then for thee, O Believer, who art a Follower of Him.</P>
<P N="10">10 <HI>In War a Mighty One;</HI> Omitted in the Repe|tition: <HI>Ab<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> Ezra</HI> &s;ay, Becau&s;e in the Days of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> Men are to <HI>beat their Swords into Plow|&s;hares.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="25" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XXV. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God, To Thee &Verbar; I do lift up my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 My God, I put my tru&s;t in thee; &Verbar; let me not be a&s;ham'd. &Verbar; Let not my Adver&s;aries have &Verbar; a triumph over me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="54" REF="001946_0091_0FFCAF1EC42F7110">
3 Yea, all of them that wait on thee, &Verbar; let them not be a&s;ham'd. &Verbar; Let be a&s;hame<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> tho&s;e who do &Verbar; tran&s;gre&s;s without a cau&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O Thou ETERNAL God, &s;hew me &Verbar; thy ways, teach me thy paths. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Make thou me in thy truth to walk; &Verbar; And teach me; for thou art &Verbar; the God of my Salvation; I &Verbar; wait on thee all the day. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Remember, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; what thy kind bowels are; &Verbar; and what thy boun|ties are; for they &Verbar; have ever been of old. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Sins of my youth remember not, &Verbar; not my vile tre&s;pa&s;&s;es: &Verbar; But, Oh! according to thy Grace &Verbar; do thou remember me. &Verbar; O thou ETERNAL God, Do this, &Verbar; even for thy Goodne&s;s &s;ake. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Th' ETERNAL's Good and Right therefore &Verbar; Sinners He'll teach the way. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 The humbled meek ones He will help with judgment for to walk; &Verbar; and He the humbled meek ones will &Verbar; in&s;truct what is His way. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 All the paths of th' ETERNAL are &Verbar; Mercy and Truth to tho&s;e &Verbar; who keep His Covenant, and <HI>mind</HI> &Verbar; His Te&s;timonies there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 For the &s;ake of thy <HI>Glorious</HI> Name, O Thou ETERNAL God; &Verbar; Pardon <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> mine iniquity; &Verbar; becau&s;e that it is great.</P>
<P N="12">12 Who is the Man that has the fear &Verbar; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the ETERNAL God? &Verbar; He'l thoroughly in&s;tru<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> him in &Verbar; the way that he &s;hould chu&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13"><PB N="55" REF="001946_0092_0FFCB0456EEC7F38">
13 His Soul &s;hall &s;pend the Night in re&s;t, &Verbar; with what is good <HI>Above;</HI> &Verbar; and then his Seed &s;hall take as heirs &Verbar; the Earth <HI>he leaves to them.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 The &s;ecret of th' ETERNAL is &Verbar; with them that have His fear, &Verbar; and 'tis His Co|venant that He &Verbar; will make them for to know. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Mine eyes continually are &Verbar; to the E|TERNAL God; &Verbar; Becau&s;e 'tis He that &s;hall bring forth &Verbar; my feet out of the &s;nare. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 O turn thou unto me, and have &Verbar; thou mercy upon me; &Verbar; for I am in a lonely ca&s;e, &Verbar; and an afflicted one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 The angui&s;hes of my Heart have &Verbar; greatly enlarg'd them&s;elves; &Verbar; O do thou bring me out of all &Verbar; my &s;ore vexatious grief's &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 On my affliction, O look down, &Verbar; and on my labouring pain; &Verbar; and let thy pardon|ing mercy reach &Verbar; to all my tre&s;pa&s;&s;es. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Look down upon my Enemies &Verbar; for they are multiply'd; &Verbar; and 'tis with hatred full of rage &Verbar; that they have hated me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Into thy keeping take my Soul, &Verbar; and Oh! Deliver me; &Verbar; Let me not be a&s;ham'd, for I &Verbar; have put my tru&s;t in thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Let an entire Integrity &Verbar; and exact Rectitude, &Verbar; be my pre&s;erver; for that I &Verbar; am waiting &s;till on thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 O GOD who art the Judge of all, &Verbar;
<PB N="56" REF="001946_0093_0FFCB7B29C137448">Do thou redemption give &Verbar; unto thine I&s;rael from all &Verbar; the Troubles <HI>now</HI> on him. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>'TIS the fir&s;t of the <HI>Alphabetical P&s;alms. Acro&s;ticks</HI> were of much e&s;teem in Antiquity. But &s;ome|times the &s;trength of the In&s;piration might interrupt the method. Or, a Letter may be dropt for cau&s;es now unknown to us. There were Examples of it (as Mr. <HI>J<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ukins.</HI> ob&s;erves) among the Greek Poets.</P>
<P N="8">8 Is it not an Allu&s;ion to the care u&s;ed of Old, about the ways to the <HI>Cities of Refuge?</HI> My Jewi&s;h Expo&s;i|tors tell me &s;o.</P>
<P N="15">15&mdash;When the <HI>Off spring</HI> of a Godly Man, are entring upon the <HI>Earthly Inheritance,</HI> which, at his Death, he leaves unto them, <HI>Then</HI> the <HI>Soul</HI> of this Man, is lodged with <HI>the Good One</HI> (Chri&s;t,) or in the <HI>Good Place</HI> (Heaven,) or in Goodne&s;s it&s;elf; in Happine&s;s. The <HI>Immortality</HI> of the <HI>Soul</HI> is here a&s;&s;erted. This Hint I had from Dr. <HI>Alting</HI> the Youn|ger. But, <HI>Arnobius</HI> finds another and a better Earth for the Seed of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="26" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XXVI. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 ETERNAL, Judge me, for I've walk'd &Verbar; in my integrity; &Verbar; and on th' ETER|NAL God I've hop'd; &Verbar; I &s;hall not &s;tagger now. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O thou ETERNAL God, Do thou &Verbar; throughly examine me; &Verbar; and make a tryal of me; try &Verbar; my reins, and <HI>try</HI> my heart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="57" REF="001946_0094_0FFCB04D5CCD5638">
3 Becau&s;e thy loving kindne&s;s is &Verbar; always before mine eyes; &Verbar; and I have carried on my walk &Verbar; in thy <HI>directing</HI> truth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 I have not cho&s;e my &s;eat with Men &Verbar; of vain temerity; &Verbar; nor have I entred councils with &Verbar; Men that put on a mask. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Th' A&s;&s;embly of malignant Men &Verbar; is that which I do hate; &Verbar; and I will never &s;it with &s;uch &Verbar; as are ungodly ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 My hands I will be &s;ure to wa&s;h &Verbar; in a clean innocence; &Verbar; Thine Altar &s;o I'll walk about, &Verbar; O thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 That I may make for to be heard &Verbar; with a thank&s;giving voice, &Verbar; and that I may declare abroad &Verbar; all of thy wondrous works. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O thou ETERNAL, I have lov'd &Verbar; the dwelling of thy Hou&s;e; &Verbar; and the place where thy Glory has &Verbar; its Habitation cho&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O gather not my Soul with &s;uch &Verbar; as wander on in Sin; &Verbar; Nor <HI>take away</HI> my life with &s;uch, &Verbar; as are the Men of Blood. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 <HI>With &s;uch Men</HI> as have in their hands &Verbar; mi&s;chievous wickedne&s;s; &Verbar; and their right hands repleni&s;hed &Verbar; with a corrupting gift. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 But as for me, my walk &s;hall be &Verbar; in mine integrity; &Verbar; O do thou now redeem me, and &Verbar; be merciful to me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 My foot hath &s;till per&s;i&s;ted in &Verbar; a <HI>con|&s;tant</HI> rectitude; &Verbar; I in the Congregations will &Verbar; ble&s;s the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="58" REF="001946_0095_0FFCB0594E482C78">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P N="3">3 <HI>PSalmi&s;t,</HI> How dur&s;t thou have &s;aid, <HI>Judge me O Lord;</HI> if thou had&s;t not al&s;o &s;aid, <HI>Thy loving kindne&s;s is always before mine eyes?</HI> This Note is a very Ancient one.</P>
<P N="4">4 The <HI>Di&s;&s;emblers</HI> here, <HI>Aben Ezra</HI> &s;ays, ar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Young People</HI> who mind none but the <HI>Delights</HI> of th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> World. The Hebrew Word would favour &s;uch a Thought. O <HI>Young People,</HI> con&s;ider it.</P>
<P N="6">6 What? Was <HI>David</HI> a <HI>Prie&s;t?</HI> Our SAUIOUR <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> Con&s;ider Him &s;peaking here. Yea, <HI>David</HI> might we<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;ay. I have not &s;atisfied my &s;elf with the ceremony of <HI>wa&s;hing my Hands,</HI> before I went unto the offering of a Sacrifice, but I endeavoured &s;incerely to keep free from all moral and &s;inful impurities.</P>
<P N="9">9. q. d.&mdash;Let me not peri&s;h as if I were a Murderer.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="27" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XXVII. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 HE who to me a Glorious Light, &Verbar; an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> my Salvation gives, &Verbar; is the ETER|NAL God; <HI>and now</HI> &Verbar; who is it I &s;hall fear. The &s;trength from whence my Life's main|tain'd, &Verbar; is the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; <HI>And no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"></HI> what one is there by whom &Verbar; I need be te<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">tify'd? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 When evil ones, my troublers, who <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> were enemies to me &Verbar; drew near on me, t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> wa&s;te my fle&s;h, &Verbar; they &s;tumbled &amp; fell dow<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"></P>
<P N="3">3 Again&s;t me let an ho&s;t encamp, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">
<PB N="59" REF="001946_0096_0FFCB052A5875878">my heart &s;hall have no fear; &Verbar; again&s;t me let a War ari&s;e, &Verbar; in this I am &s;ecure. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 There is one thing I have de&s;ir'd &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; This is the thing that I will &s;eek, &Verbar; that I may ever have &Verbar; my dwel|ling, * and my Sabbath too &Verbar; a&s;&s;ign'd me, in the Hou&s;e &Verbar; of the ETERNAL all the days &Verbar; my life &s;hall be prolong'd: &Verbar; That &s;o I may enjoy the view &Verbar; of the &s;weet Beauty in &Verbar; th' ETERNAL God, and to enquire, &Verbar; in His high Temple &s;till. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For in the time of trouble He &Verbar; &s;hall hide me in His Tent; &Verbar; In's Tabernacle's co|vered part; &Verbar; There &s;hall He cover me. &Verbar; He &s;hall exalt me where I &s;hall &Verbar; be &s;et upon a Rock. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 And now my head's lift up above &Verbar; all my &s;urrounding foes. &Verbar; So Sacrifices with a &s;hout &Verbar; I'll offer in His Tent; &Verbar; I'll &s;ing, yea, I will prai&s;es &s;ing &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Hear, O ETERNAL God, my voice &Verbar; <HI>with which</HI> I cry <HI>to thee:</HI> &Verbar; Have mercy al&s;o upon me, &Verbar; and hearken unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Seek ye my face; <HI>On hearing this,</HI> &Verbar; my heart did &s;peak to thee; &Verbar; Thy face, O thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; <HI>Thy face now,</HI> I will &s;eek. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Hide not away from me thy face, &Verbar; nor &s;uffer to decline, &Verbar; in * or to anger him that is &Verbar; a &s;ervant unto Thee. &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t afford|ed help to me; &Verbar; O do not leave me <HI>now;</HI> &Verbar;
<PB N="60" REF="001946_0097_0FFCB7B4D292F1A0">not yet for&s;ake me, O thou God &Verbar; whence my Salvation comes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 My Father and my Mother, when &Verbar; they have for&s;aken me, &Verbar; Then O ETERNAL God, thou do&s;t &Verbar; take me into thy care. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 O thou ETERNAL God; do thou &Verbar; teach me what is thy way; &Verbar; And lead me in the path of Right, &Verbar; for my ob&s;ervers &s;ake. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Give me not up unto the will &Verbar; of my foes; for there ri&s;e &Verbar; fal&s;e witne&s;&s;es again&s;t me, and &Verbar; one who breaths violence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Neverthele&s;s, I do believe &Verbar; for the enjoyment of &Verbar; the Good of the ETERNAL in &Verbar; the land of living ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Look for th' ETERNAL God, and &s;o I &s;trengthen thy &s;elf <HI>in Him</HI> &Verbar;; He &s;hall confirm thy heart; Again &Verbar; look for th' ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P N="4">4 <HI>ENquire,</HI> After what? The <HI>Spani&s;h</HI> has a Good Hint upon it. <HI>Enquire in my Doubts;</HI> For direction in the Doubtful Attairs of my Kingdom.</P>
<P N="5">5 <HI>The Secret of the Tabernacle</HI> was the <HI>Holy of Ho|lles.</HI> No Man might come there. <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> is <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the Voice of thy SAVIOUR to be con&s;idered her<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"></P>
<P N="8">8 Our P&s;almi&s;t had been doubtle&s;s much a Stu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters"> in the Book of <HI>Deuteronomy.</HI> Now, See Deut. IV <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>If thou &s;eek the Lord thy God, thou &s;halt find Hi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> if thou &s;eek Him with all thy heart.</HI></P>
<P N="9">9 Yea, and remember, O Chri&s;tian, If thou art <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> le&s;t unto an <HI>Angry Impatience</HI> under thy T<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">yals, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> will ben Sign, that GOD has not <HI>put thee away.</HI></P>
<P N="10"><PB N="61" REF="001946_0098_0FFCB057CBB6EAA8">
10 Is it not an Allu&s;ion to the Journey of <HI>I&s;rael</HI> through the Wilderne&s;s? When the Three fir&s;t Squadrons were pa&s;&s;ed on, the <HI>Fourth</HI> were to <HI>gather up,</HI> the Sick, and the Weak, and the Lame, that had been left behind.</P>
<P N="13">13 This pre&s;ent World, alas, 'tis rather the <HI>Land of the Dying,</HI> than the <HI>Land of the Living. Believer,</HI> Look forwards, look upwards! The Ancients, both Jews &amp; Chri&s;tians, expounded, <HI>The Land of the Living,</HI> to mean, <HI>The World to come.</HI> Think on the <HI>New Earth,</HI> in the Kingdom of our SAVIOUR. Think on <HI>Mat.</HI> V. 3.</P>
<P N="14">14 <HI>Arnobius</HI> notes, That this Ver&s;e is the <HI>Anti|phona</HI> of the Holy Spirit, unto the Saint expre&s;&s;ing the&s;e Expectations.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="28" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XXVIII. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 TO Thee, O thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; I will &s;end forth a cry; &Verbar; O be not &s;i|lent, Thou my Rock, &Verbar; <HI>in a withdraw</HI> from me. &Verbar; Le&s;t that if thou do&s;t hold thy peace, &Verbar; <HI>witholding Help</HI> from me, &Verbar; I &s;hould be like to them who do &Verbar; go down into the pit. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Hear what my Supplications &s;peak, &Verbar; when I do cry to thee; &Verbar; when I lift up my hands towards &Verbar; thy holy Oracle. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Drag me not with ill M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n, not with &Verbar; workers of vanity; &Verbar; who &s;peak peace to their Neighbours, but &Verbar; mi&s;chief is in their hearts. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Give them according to their deeds, &Verbar; and as they've ill de&s;ign'd: &Verbar; Give them what their own hands have wrought; &Verbar; render them their de&s;ert. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4"><PB N="62" REF="001946_0099_0FFCB345E1308178">
4 Becau&s;e they don't regard the deeds &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; nor the work of His Hands; He'l them &Verbar; de&s;troy, and not build up. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Ble&s;&s;ed be the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; for this, becau&s;e that He &Verbar; hath kindly hearken'd to the voice &Verbar; my &s;upplications had. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 'Tis the ETERNAL One, who is &Verbar; my &s;trength, and is my &s;hield. &Verbar; On Him my heart has plac'd its hope, &Verbar; and I am helped &s;o. &Verbar; And <HI>for this very cau&s;e</HI> my heart &Verbar; does mightily rejoyce; &Verbar; Now with my Song His Prai&s;es I &Verbar; will gladly celebrate. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Yea, the ETERNAL God to them &Verbar; is their true fortitude; &Verbar; and of Salvation He's the &s;trength &Verbar; of His Anointed one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O &s;ave thy People, and O ble&s;s &Verbar; thou thine Inheritance; &Verbar; Be thou a Shepherd unto them, &Verbar; and lift them up for ever. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>R. <HI>Solomon</HI> &s;ays, When in the Title of a P&s;alm, we read only, <HI>Of David,</HI> it intimates, The Holy Spirit came &s;uddenly on <HI>David,</HI> without the u&s;e of the u&s;ual means to obtain His Influences. But when we read, <HI>A P&s;alm of David,</HI> it intimates, that he then had u&s;ed means to obtain the Illap&s;es of the Holy Spirit. Behold, here a Trayer for the Faithful, that they may not be joined in De&s;truction with the Followers of <HI>An|tichri&s;t;</HI> and they hope for Salvation by the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> after that He has de&s;troyed that wicked Society.</P>
<P N="2">2 Our <HI>Supplications</HI> have a further <HI>V<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ice</HI> in them,
<PB N="63" REF="001946_0100_0FFCB09D20EAC200">than what iu&s;t utters the matter of them. <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> Thy <HI>Prayers,</HI> Do they <HI>&s;peak</HI> thy <HI>Love</HI> to the Glorious GOD, thy Exaltation of <HI>His Will</HI> above <HI>thy own,</HI> thy <HI>Faith</HI> in thy SAVIOUR, thy e&s;teem for <HI>Spiritual Ble&s;&s;ings</HI> above <HI>Temporal,</HI> and thy <HI>Benignity</HI> towards thy <HI>Neighbour,</HI> wi&s;hing as well to him as to thy &s;elf? When there is a <HI>Voice</HI> in thy <HI>Supplications,</HI> import|ing &s;uch things as the&s;e, GOD will hear <HI>it,</HI> and have a great re&s;pect unto <HI>them.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 <HI>Arnobius</HI> applies it unto the unbelieving <HI>Jews,</HI> who did not regard the miraculous Works of our SAVIOUR, when He even rai&s;ed the Dead, and &s;aid, <HI>Believe my Works.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="29" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXIX.</HI> A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 A Scribe to the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; O Sons of mighty ones, &Verbar; A&s;cribe to the E|TERNAL God &Verbar; Glory and Fortitude. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 A&s;cribe to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; the Honour of His Name; &Verbar; Bow to th' ETER|NAL God in the &Verbar; Glory of holine&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 The Voice of the ETERNAL God &Verbar; is on the Waters <HI>heard:</HI> &Verbar; The Glorious God Thunders on great &Verbar; Waters; JEHOVAH's there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 The Voice of the ETERNAL is &Verbar; <HI>utter'd.</HI> with mighty pow'r; &Verbar; the Voice of the E|TERNAL is &Verbar; <HI>urter'd</HI> with maje&s;ty. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 The Voice of the ETERNAL does &Verbar; break Cedars all to &s;hivers; &Verbar; yea, the ETERNAL. One does break &Verbar; Cedars of Lebanon. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="64" REF="001946_0101_0FFCB07EB52967D0">
6 He makes them al&s;o for to leap &Verbar; as a young Calf would do; &Verbar; ev'n Lebanon and Sirion like &Verbar; a &s;on of Wild-Goats <HI>leap.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 The Voice of the ETERNAL God &Verbar; having divided them, &Verbar; He doth &s;trike down with flaming darts &Verbar; of a devouring fire. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 The Voice of the ETERNAL God &Verbar; doth &s;hake the Wilderne&s;s; &Verbar; Th' ETERNAL makes the Wilderne&s;s &Verbar; of Kade&s;h for to &s;hake. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 The Voice of the ETERNAL God &Verbar; does make the Hinds bring forth; &Verbar; And in His Temple all of His &Verbar; do &s;peak His Glory there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Th' ETERNAL God pre&s;ides upon &Verbar; the Flood, <HI>&s;till ruling it;</HI> &Verbar; yea, the ETER|NAL God &s;its King &Verbar; Enthron'd for evermore. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 His People, the ETERNAL God &Verbar; will fortify with &s;trength; &Verbar; His People the ETERNAL God &Verbar; will ble&s;s with pro&s;p'rous peace. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>WAS not the P&s;alm compo&s;ed by <HI>David,</HI> after &s;ome extraordinary <HI>Lightning</HI> and <HI>Thunder</HI> and <HI>Rain;</HI> which had perhaps a&s;&s;i&s;ted the Di&s;comfiture of His Enemies? One looks on it as an Exhortation to the Princes of the Earth, to &s;ubmit unto the re-e&s;tab|ed Kingdom of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> And the <HI>Voice</HI> here may be the Report of the wonders done in that Matter. Compare, Jer. XXV. 31. <HI>A Noi&s;e from the ends of the Earth.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 Compare, Job XXXVIII. 7. <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> notes well,
<PB N="65" REF="001946_0102_0FFCB09EA46F31B8">There is nothing &s;o high and &s;o great, but what is ob|liged unto the Prai&s;es of God.</P>
<P N="3">3 <HI>P<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">meranus</HI> whom <HI>Lather</HI> cried up as the be&s;t and the fir&s;t Interpreter of the <HI>P&s;alter,</HI> and who&s;e Com|mentaries, as <HI>Frankins</HI> notes, <HI>Referti &s;unt Meditationi|bus de CHRISTI Magnitudine et Maje&s;tate;</HI> would have what we read here about, <HI>The Voice of the Lord;</HI> compared with what the Apo&s;tle to the <HI>Hebrews</HI> writes about, <HI>The quick and powerful Word of GOD,</HI> and what <HI>John</HI> writes about, <HI>The Word of God by which all things were created.</HI></P>
<P N="9">9 But, Oh! why not the whole World a <HI>Temple</HI> of GOD! R. <HI>Mo&s;eh</HI> has this Glo&s;s. The <HI>Levites</HI> Prai&s;e GOD, for His pre&s;erving of them from hurt by <HI>Thunder.</HI></P>
<P N="10">10 <HI>Aben-Ezra</HI> notes upon it; The <HI>Waters</HI> &s;hall not overwhelm the Kingdom of God. Another con|&s;iders this Intimation; The Thunder doth not more ea&s;ily tear the Trees and the Rocks, than God can break in pieces the proude&s;t of Princes.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="30" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXX.</HI> A P&s;alm. A Song at the Dedication of the Hou&s;e of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 THEE, O ETERNAL, I'll extol; &Verbar; for thou'&s;t exalted me; &Verbar; and ha&s;t not made my enemies &Verbar; to triumph over me, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O thou ETERNAL God, thou art &Verbar; my God; I unto thee &Verbar; have made my cry <HI>in|my Di&s;tre&s;s;</HI> &Verbar; and thou ha&s;t healed me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Thou, O ETERNAL God, ha&s;t brought &Verbar; my Soul up from the pit; &Verbar; thou ha&s;t made me to live, that I &Verbar; de&s;cend not to the Grave &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4"><PB N="66" REF="001946_0103_0FFCB081B8FD0128">
4 Sing unto the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; O ye His Gracious Ones; &Verbar; and prai&s;e at the re|membrance of &Verbar; His <HI>Glorious</HI> Holine&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For but a moment's in His wrath; &Verbar; There &Verbar; in His favour life: &Verbar; weeping may with the Evening lodge; &Verbar; but in the Morning joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 But as for me, this did I &s;ay &Verbar; in my felicity; &Verbar; I &s;hall not be remov'd <HI>from thence</HI> &Verbar; to all Eternity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Thou, O ETERNAL, to my mount &Verbar; giv'&s;t by thy favour &s;trength; &Verbar; Thou <HI>for a while</HI> did&s;t hide thy face; &Verbar; my Trouble then was great. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O thou ETERNAL God, to Thee &Verbar; <HI>then</HI> did I make my cry: &Verbar; And unto the ETER|NAL God &Verbar; I then did &s;upplicate. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 What profit's in my Blood, when I &Verbar; go down into the pit? &Verbar; The Du&s;t, &s;hall that acknowledge thee? &Verbar; Shall it declare thy Truth? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Hear, O ETERNAL God, and have &Verbar; thou mercy upon me; &Verbar; O thou ETERNAL God, Be thou &Verbar; an helper unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 My mourning thou ha&s;t turn'd into &Verbar; tripudiating joy; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t put off my &s;ackcloth, and &Verbar; with gladne&s;s girded me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Glory &s;hall therefore &s;ing to thee, &Verbar; and &s;hall not hold its peace; &Verbar; O Thou E|TERNAL God, my God; &Verbar; Thee I'll forever prai&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="67" REF="001946_0104_0FFCB14BC413A7C8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P><HI>THE Hou&s;e of David</HI> is by the <HI>Midra&s;is Tillin,</HI> under&s;tood of, <HI>the Temple,</HI> called <HI>His,</HI> becau&s;e he purpo&s;ed the Building of it. But, as one Remarks; Behold, the Joy the Jews will have when the <HI>Tabernacle of David which is fallen,</HI> &s;hall, according to <HI>Amos.</HI> XI. 11. be re-e&s;tabli&s;hed. Compare the Conclu&s;ion of the P&s;alm, with <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> LX. 1.</P>
<P N="5">5&mdash;<HI>Dru&s;ius</HI> adds this Glo&s;s, <HI>Diu durat;</HI>&mdash;It is a la&s;ting favour, it will <HI>never dye.</HI> As, a <HI>Tree that never dies</HI> is called, <HI>a Tree of Life. David</HI> the Jew, has the like Paraphra&s;e; <HI>durat tempore multo, et vita longa.</HI></P>
<P N="9">9 Dr. <HI>Fuller</HI> notes on it; While a Man is alive, not only the <HI>Soul</HI> of the Man, but his <HI>Du&s;t</HI> al&s;o prai&s;es GOD; His Body has a &s;hare in the Wor&s;hip of God; Our Moiety of <HI>Du&s;t</HI> has a Counterpart in our Prai&s;ing of God. After our <HI>Death,</HI> whatever our <HI>Soul</HI> may do, our <HI>Du&s;t</HI> has no part in the Service of God, until the Re&s;urrection from the Dead.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="31" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXXI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God, I have &Verbar; placed my hope in thee: &Verbar; Let me not be a&s;ham'd, O &s;ave &Verbar; me in thy righteou&s;ne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Kindly to me bow down thine ear; &Verbar; re&s;cue me &s;peedily; &Verbar; A &s;trong Rock be to me; to &s;ave &Verbar; me, a defended hou&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For thou art He that is my Rock, &Verbar; and <HI>thou art</HI> my defence: &Verbar; and therefore for thy Name &s;ake me &Verbar; lead thou, and be my guide. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4"><PB N="68" REF="001946_0105_0FFCB0868C93BA00">
4 O do thou bring me up out of &Verbar; the Net which they have laid &Verbar; in &s;ecret for me; for that thou &Verbar; art He that is my &s;trength. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 My Spirit I re&s;igning do &Verbar; commit into thy hands; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t redeemed me, O thou &Verbar; ETERNAL God of Truth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 I hate tho&s;e who ob&s;erve what are &Verbar; but lying vanities; &Verbar; But as for me, I place my hope &Verbar; on the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 I in thy mercy will be glad, &Verbar; and very much rejoyce; &Verbar; for thou ha&s;t look'd upon my grief, &Verbar; Thou know'&s;t my Soul in &s;traits. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Nor ha&s;t thou &s;hut me up into &Verbar; the Adver&s;aries hand; &Verbar; <HI>But</HI> thou ha&s;t made my feet to &s;tand &Verbar; in a mo&s;t &s;pacious place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Pity me, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; becau&s;e I am in grief; &Verbar; my Eye, my Soul, do wa&s;te in wrath, &Verbar; my very belly too.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 For that my life is &s;pent with grief, &Verbar; and all my years in &s;ighs; &Verbar; thorough my Sin my &s;trength does fail, &Verbar; and my bones are con&s;um'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 From all my foes I had reproach, &Verbar; and from my neighbours much; &Verbar; a fear to them that knew me too, &Verbar; who fled, &s;eeing me abroad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 I am forgotten like a Man &Verbar; that's dead, <HI>and</HI> out of mind; &Verbar; I am become ju&s;t like unto &Verbar; a Ve&s;&s;el that is broke. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 For I from many heard ill fame; &Verbar;
<PB N="69" REF="001946_0106_0FFCB14D49C1AA58">fear was on every &s;ide; &Verbar; while they again&s;t me did con&s;ult; &Verbar; they thought to &s;eize my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 But as for me, I did rely &Verbar; on Thee, E|TERNAL God; &Verbar; This did I &s;ay, Thou art my God &Verbar; to whom I do adhere. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 My Times are all at thy di&s;po&s;e; &Verbar; O do thou re&s;cue me &Verbar; from the hand of mine enemies, &Verbar; and from my following foes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Upon thy Servant do thou cau&s;e &Verbar; thy countenance to &s;hine; &Verbar; in thy free mercy do thou grant &Verbar; Salvation unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 ETERNAL, Let me not be &s;ham'd; &Verbar; for I have call'd on thee; &Verbar; Let wicked ones be &s;ham'd; Let them &Verbar; be cut off in the Grave. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Let tho&s;e lips be made &s;ilent, which &Verbar; are giv'n to fal&s;ity; &Verbar; which &s;peak hard things again&s;t the ju&s;t, &Verbar; with pride and with contempt. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 How great's thy Good, which thou for them &Verbar; that fear thee ha&s;t laid up! &Verbar; Thouh'&s;t wrought for them that hope in thee, before the &s;ons of Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 In th' &s;ecret of thy face thou hid'&s;t &Verbar; them from the threats of Man; &Verbar; Thou do&s;t in a Pavilion hide &Verbar; them from the &s;trife of tongues. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Ble&s;&s;ed be the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; for He hath wondrou&s;ly &Verbar; within a City of de|fence &Verbar; &s;hown mercy unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22"><PB N="70" REF="001946_0107_0FFCB08990D6F190">
22 But I &s;aid in my ha&s;te, I'm from &Verbar; be|fore thine eyes cut off; &Verbar; yet the voice of my Prayers thou heard'&s;t, &Verbar; when I did cry to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 All ye His gracious ones, Do ye &Verbar; love the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; Th' ETERNAL keeps the faithful, and &Verbar; pays the proud doer home. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 Be of good courage, and He &s;hall &Verbar; corroborate your heart; &Verbar; All ye that with an hope do wait &Verbar; for the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE <HI>Ha&s;te</HI> of <HI>David,</HI> flying unto the Wilderne&s;s of <HI>Maou;</HI> [1 Sam. XXIII. 26.] &s;eems to be mentioned in the Twenty &s;econd Ver&s;e of the P&s;alm; <HI>I &s;aid in my ha&s;te.</HI> But, <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> Be &s;ure to be hold thy Suffering SAVIOUR here! He died with the Fifth Ver&s;e of the P&s;alm in His Mouth.</P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>David</HI> was now in a <HI>Rock;</HI> [1 Sam. XXIII. 25.] But, <HI>Lord,</HI> Thou art the only <HI>Rock!</HI></P>
<P N="4">4 The <HI>Net.</HI> The Treachery of the <HI>Ziphites,</HI> [1 Sam. XXIII. 10, 20.]</P>
<P N="8">8 God would not &s;uffer him to be &s;hut up in <HI>Kei|lah;</HI> but by Oracles admoni&s;hed him how to e&s;cape. See 1 Sam. XXIII. 7, 9.</P>
<P N="19">19 The Hebrew Word may be rendered <HI>Ex diametr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">.</HI> Dr. <HI>Gell</HI> renders it, Maugre all the <HI>Oppo&s;itions</HI> of the Sons of Men.</P>
<P N="20">20 To be &s;heltered from the mi&s;chiefs which <HI>con|tentious</HI> Men may &s;eek by their fal&s;e Tongues to bring upon us; 'Tis a Ble&s;&s;edne&s;s.</P>
<P N="21">21 See, 1 <HI>Sam.</HI> XXIII. 7.13.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="32" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="71" REF="001946_0108_0FFCB14FAE705DE0">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXXII.</HI> Of David. Ma&s;chil.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O What the Ble&s;&s;ings of <HI>the Man</HI> &Verbar; to whom Tran&s;gre&s;&s;ion is &Verbar; forgiven; of <HI>the Man</HI> to whom &Verbar; Error is covered. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O what the Ble&s;&s;ings of <HI>the Man</HI> &Verbar; to whom th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; imputeth not iniquity: &Verbar; and guile's not in his &s;pirit! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For while that I did hold my peace &Verbar; my bones were waxing old; &Verbar; and &s;o it was when I did make &Verbar; a roaring all the day. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Becau&s;e that day and night thy hand &Verbar; lay heavy upon me; &Verbar; my moi&s;ture was quite turn'd into &Verbar; the Summers parching heat. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 I of my &s;inful error made &Verbar; acknowledg|ment to thee; &Verbar; and my impure iniquity &Verbar; I did not go to hide. &Verbar; I &s;aid, To the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; I will confe&s;s my crimes; &Verbar; then of my Sin thou did&s;t remit &Verbar; the great iniquity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 For this each gracious one &s;hall pray &Verbar; to Thee in finding time; &Verbar; Surely in floods of waters great, &Verbar; they &s;hall not reach to him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Thou art my hiding place to me; &Verbar; thou keepe&s;t me from grief; &Verbar; and with &s;ongs of deliverance &Verbar; thou do&s;t encompa&s;s me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 I'll make thee wi&s;e, and teach thee in &Verbar; the way which thou &s;hould go; &Verbar; I will give coun&s;il unto thee; &Verbar; I'll on thee have my eye. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9"><PB N="72" REF="001946_0109_0FFCB08F51D333B0">
9 Be n't as the Hor&s;e, or as the Mule, &Verbar; which do not under&s;tand; &Verbar; who&s;e mouth with bit and bridle is &Verbar; held lea&s;t they in|jure thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 There &s;hall be many &s;orrows to &Verbar; him that's a wicked Man; &Verbar; But who hopes in th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; him mercy &s;hall &s;urround. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Be glad in the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; and, O ye ju&s;t, rejoyce; &Verbar; and &s;hout with a tri|umphing joy, &Verbar; all ye upright in heart. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P><HI>MA&s;chil.</HI> Twelve more P&s;alms are thus Intitu|led. Some take it for an Epithit of the Ma&s;ter of Mu&s;ic, who in&s;tructed the Sons of <HI>Korah</HI> skilfully. One &s;ays, The Felicity of the Penitent and Converted <HI>Jews,</HI> and of the Nations join'd with them in the King|dom of GOD, is here pointed at. The <HI>Syriac Title</HI> &s;eems to give a Key to an hidden &s;en&s;e of &s;everal Pa&s;&s;a|ges in the P&s;alm; <HI>De Adami Peccato, et Chri&s;ti Redemption.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 <HI>Covered.</HI> The <HI>Law</HI> in the <HI>Ark,</HI> was covered by the <HI>Mercy-Seat;</HI> So our <HI>Sin</HI> again&s;t the <HI>Law,</HI> is covered by the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> our Great <HI>Prepitiatery.</HI></P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>No guile.</HI> D. <HI>Kimchi</HI> de&s;cribes him well; He that hath a purpo&s;e, never to return unto the Sin that he repents of.</P>
<P N="3">3, 4 <HI>Au&s;tin</HI> will have the <HI>Fever</HI> here complained of, to be that of <HI>raging Concupi&s;cence.</HI> A terrible Ob&s;er|vation! That Sin keeps a &s;trong and a &s;trange hold on the minds of Men, till it be by a Penitent Confe&s;&s;ion repented of.</P>
<P N="6">6 Compare <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> LV. 6.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="33" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="73" REF="001946_0110_0FFCB152CF656418">
<HEAD>PSALM XXXIII.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BEcau&s;e of the ETERNAL God &Verbar; Rejoyce, Ye righteous ones; &Verbar; Unto the Men that are upright &Verbar; Prai&s;e is de&s;irable. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 With harp prai&s;e the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Sing with a P&s;altery; &Verbar; Sing to Him with an In&s;trument &Verbar; that has ten &s;trings in it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Sing to Him a new Song; Do well &Verbar; in &s;inging with a noi&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 For the Word of Th' ETERNAL's right; &Verbar; and His whole work in truth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Both Righteou&s;ne&s;s and Judgment <HI>are</HI> &Verbar; <HI>the things which</HI> He doth love; &Verbar; The Good|ne&s;s of th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; the Earth is full of it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The Heavens were made by the Word &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and all the ho&s;t of them <HI>made</HI> by &Verbar; the &s;pirit of His mouth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 The flowing waters of the Sea &Verbar; He ga|thers as an heap; &Verbar; <HI>as</HI> in &s;o many Store-Hou&s;es &Verbar; He layeth up the deeps. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Let all the Earth expre&s;s the fear &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; let all Inhabi|tants of the &Verbar; World &s;tand in awe of Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 For He no &s;ooner &s;poke the Word, &Verbar; but, lo, the thing is done: &Verbar; He did but give out His command, &Verbar; and then the thing &s;tood forth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Th' ETERNAL God defeats the plot &Verbar;
<PB N="74" REF="001946_0111_0FFCB095EBCBB738">laid by the Nations <HI>here;</HI> &Verbar; Devices of the People He &Verbar; makes be of none effect. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 The Coun&s;el of th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; that does for ever &s;tand; &Verbar; &s;o do the Thoughts of His Heart to &Verbar; all Generations <HI>&s;tand.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 O ble&s;&s;ed Nation that; who&s;e God &Verbar; is the ETERNAL One! &Verbar; The People He hath cho&s;en for &Verbar; His own Inheritance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 From Heaven the ETERNAL God &Verbar; continually looks down; &Verbar; He takes a tho|rough <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ogni&s;ance &Verbar; of all the Sons of Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 From the <HI>bright</HI> Habitation where &Verbar; He hath His re&s;ting-place &Verbar; He takes a view of all that do &Verbar; inhabit on the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 He hath be&s;tow'd a fa&s;hion on &Verbar; the Heart of them together; &Verbar; Animadvert He doth upon &Verbar; all the works done by them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 No King's delivered by the &Verbar; multi|tude of an ho&s;t; &Verbar; no Potent one is re&s;cued by &Verbar; the greatne&s;s of his pow'r. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 An Hor&s;e for &s;afety <HI>tru&s;ted in</HI> &Verbar; is a deceitful thing; &Verbar; for by the greatne&s;s of his &s;trength &Verbar; he &s;hall deliver none. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 The Eye of the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; be|hold, it is on them &Verbar; that fear Him; <HI>'tis</HI> on them that hope &Verbar; in His Benignity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 <HI>'Tis</HI> for to grant a re&s;cue to &Verbar; the Soul of them from Death; &Verbar; and that He may keep them alive &Verbar; when Famine &s;hall prevail. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Our Soul hath &s;till with waiting hop'd &Verbar;
<PB N="75" REF="001946_0112_0FFCB1546FD992A0">for the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; 'Tis He Him|&s;elf who is our help, &Verbar; and <HI>He</HI> that is our Shield. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 For that it is in Him our heart &Verbar; &s;hall cheerfully rejoyce; &Verbar; Becau&s;e that in His Holy Name &Verbar; we place our confidence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Thy mercy, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Let that upon us be, &Verbar; according as we do rely &Verbar; upon thy &s;elf <HI>alone.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, An Hymn of the I&s;raeliti&s;h Nation, after it is re-e&s;tabli&s;hed in the favour of GOD. And a Song upon the Ruin of the Nations that continue in enmity to Him.</P>
<P N="1">1 <HI>De&s;irable. Kimchi</HI> carries it &s;o. The <HI>Upright</HI> will <HI>de&s;ire</HI> nothing &s;o much as this, that GOD may be Prai&s;ed.</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>Word</HI>&mdash;and <HI>Work.</HI> Both have the &s;ame Voice, come on the &s;ame Errand, &s;how the &s;ame right way to us.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="34" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXXIV.</HI> Of David; When he changed his Behaviour before Abimelek; who drove him away and he departed.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BLe&s;&s;ing I'll at all times a&s;cribe &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; In my mouth &s;hall the Prai&s;e of Him &Verbar; continually be <HI>heard.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In the ETERNAL God my Soul &Verbar; &s;hall make her &s;acred boa&s;t; &Verbar; They whom affliction has brought down, &Verbar; &s;hall hear, and &s;hall be glad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="76" REF="001946_0113_0FFCB09B34046030">
3 O join with me to magnify &Verbar; <HI>now</HI> the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; And let us all together <HI>join</HI> &Verbar; for to exalt His Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 I did &s;eek the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; and He gave ear to me; &Verbar; yea, He did me deli|ver then &Verbar; from out of all my fears. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 <HI>Others too now</HI> &s;hall look to Him, &Verbar; and be enlightened <HI>thence;</HI> &Verbar; nor &s;hall their coun|tenances be &Verbar; covered with any &s;hame. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 This poor Man made his cry, and him &Verbar; th' ETERNAL God did hear; &Verbar; yea, He de|livered him from all &Verbar; of his perplexities &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 The Angel of th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; en|campeth round about &Verbar; &s;uch as do fear Him, and He doth &Verbar; extricate them from &s;traits. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O ta&s;te, and take a view, how good &Verbar; is the ETERNAL God! &Verbar; <HI>What are</HI> the Ble&s;&s;ings of the Man, &Verbar; <HI>who</HI> puts his tru&s;t in Him! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O fear ye the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; all ye His holy ones; &Verbar; for unto them that have his fear &Verbar; there is no penury. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Young Lions are red uc'd to want; &Verbar; and hunger comes on them; &Verbar; but they that fear th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; &s;hall not want any good. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Come, O ye Children, unto me, &Verbar; give an attentive ear; &Verbar; I will in&s;truct you in the Fear &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 What Man is he who doth de&s;ire &Verbar; <HI>to &s;et</HI> repeted life! &Verbar; who hath a love to days, that he &Verbar; may have the &s;ight of good! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13"><PB N="77" REF="001946_0114_0FFCB156E4463588">
13 Keep thou thy tongue from evil, and &Verbar; thy lips from &s;peaking guile. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Depart from evil, and do good; &Verbar; Seek peace, and follow it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 The Eyes of the ETERNAL God &Verbar; are <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n the righteous ones; &Verbar; and to the cry that's nade by them &Verbar; His Ears are &s;till inclin'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Again&s;t ill doers is the face &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; for to extirpate from the Earth &Verbar; the memory of them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 <HI>Men</HI> cry, and the ETERNAL God &Verbar; doth hearken <HI>to their cry;</HI> &Verbar; and out of all their troubles He &Verbar; gives them deliverance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Nigh unto broken-hearted ones &Verbar; is the TERNAL God; &Verbar; and the contrite in &s;pirit <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">le &Verbar; will give Salvation to. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Many are the calamities &Verbar; upon the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ighteous one; &Verbar; but him does the ETER|NAL God &Verbar; deliver out of all. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 He keepeth all his bones; of them &Verbar; there &s;hall not one be broke. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Wo &s;lays the wicked; and be &s;ham'd &Verbar; &s;hall they that hate the ju&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Th' ETERNAL God redeems the Soul &Verbar; of Servants unto Him; &Verbar; and none of them who tru&s;t in Him &Verbar; &s;hall a confu&s;ion &s;ee. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, The Prai&s;es which the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> gives unto His Father, for carrying Him thro' His wonderful &s;ufferings!</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="78" REF="001946_0115_0FFCB446D69DD350">
5 <HI>They;</HI> All Good Men that hear the Story, GOD will revive and quicken them, from this Experience.</P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>Encampeth.</HI> Here &s;eems to be an eye upon <HI>Ma|hanaim</HI> [Gen. XXXII. 1, 2.] And is not this the &s;pe|cial in&s;tance of Goodne&s;s, which the next Ver&s;e refers to? Upon the mention of the&s;e words, <HI>Origen</HI> has a Note, That when the Faithful Servants of GOD are a&s;&s;embled in His Churches, their <HI>Guardian-Angels</HI> are there pre|&s;ent with them, &s;o as to make a <HI>Double Church,</HI> one of <HI>Men,</HI> another of <HI>Angels.</HI> Compare, P&s;al. CXXXVIII. 1. <HI>O Holy Singer:</HI> Think of this, and be animated.</P>
<P N="19">19, 20 Now, I hope, 'tis plain that the <HI>Humiliation</HI> and <HI>Exaltation</HI> of our SAVIOUR, is here celebrated.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="35" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XXXV. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 STrive, O ETERNAL God, with them &Verbar; who are at &s;trife with me: &Verbar; Oppo&s;ing them contend with &s;uch &Verbar; as would devour me quite. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O do thou take hold of the Shield, &Verbar; and of the Buckler too; &Verbar; and ri&s;ing, O do thou &s;tand up &Verbar; <HI>now</HI> for to &s;uccour me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Draw out the &s;pear al&s;o, and &s;top &Verbar; my per&s;ecutors cour&s;e: &Verbar; O do thou &s;ay unto my Soul, &Verbar; I thy Salvation am. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 May they be &s;ham'd, &amp; may they blu&s;h, &Verbar; who do pur&s;ue my Soul; &Verbar; may they be turned back, and &s;ham'd, &Verbar; who do devi&s;e my hurt. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 May they become like to the chaff &Verbar; <HI>dri|ven</HI> before the wind; &Verbar; The Angel of th' ETER|NAL God, &Verbar; may he drive <HI>them</HI> about. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="79" REF="001946_0116_0FFCB0A2648D9310">
6 May their way have much darkne&s;s in't, &Verbar; and much of &s;lipperine&s;s; &Verbar; and th' Angel of th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; &s;till per&s;ecuting them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 For the pit of their net for me, &Verbar; they've hid without a cau&s;e; &Verbar; without a cau&s;e they for my Soul &Verbar; have dug <HI>an horrid pit.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 May unknown ruin come on him, &Verbar; and may his net which he &Verbar; hath hid, &s;urprize him&s;elf; may he &Verbar; with tumult fall into' it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 But let my Soul have glorious joy &Verbar; in the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; O let my Soul great|ly rejoyce &Verbar; in His Salvation &s;till. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 <HI>Yea, of my Body</HI> all the Bones &Verbar; let them <HI>al&s;o</HI> declare, &Verbar; O thou ETERNAL God, who is &Verbar; to be compar'd to thee? &Verbar; Thou do&s;t redeem the Poor from him &Verbar; that is too &s;trong for him; &Verbar; <HI>Redeem</HI> the poor and needy one &Verbar; from him that &s;poileth him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Again&s;t me there have ri&s;en up &Verbar; in|jurious witne&s;&s;es; &Verbar; interrogating me of things &Verbar; which I know nothing of. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Evil for good was that which they &Verbar; did recompen&s;e to me; &Verbar; to the depriving of my Soul &Verbar; <HI>of what might comfort me.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 But I when they were &s;ick, did make &Verbar; Sackcloath my covering; &Verbar; I broke my Soul with fa&s;ting, and &Verbar; my Prayer turn'd on my brea&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 I walk'd as tho' he'd been a Friend &Verbar; and Brother unto me; &Verbar; as mourning for a Mother I &Verbar; did bow down heavily. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15"><PB N="80" REF="001946_0117_0FFCB0C07126B7C8">
15 But in my halting towards a fall &Verbar; they did exult for joy; &Verbar; &s;uch as were abject wretches did &Verbar; gather them&s;elves together; &Verbar; gather them&s;elves again&s;t me, when &Verbar; I did not know of it; &Verbar; they tore me all to pieces there, &Verbar; and did not hold their peace. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 <HI>They were</HI> with mocking hypocrites &Verbar; who made a fea&s;t of &s;coffs; &Verbar; They did <HI>a|gain&s;t</HI> me fiercely gna&s;h &Verbar; with their <HI>devour|ing</HI> teeth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 O Lord, how long wilt thou look on? &Verbar; deliver thou my Soul&Verbar;from their dead &s;trokes, my only One &Verbar; Oh! from the Lions <HI>&s;ave.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 In the great Congregation then &Verbar; I will give thanks to thee; &Verbar; among much and great People I &Verbar; will render prai&s;e to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 My wrongful enemies, may they &Verbar; not triumph over me; &Verbar; nor who hate me with|out a cau&s;e &Verbar; wink with a <HI>&s;cornful</HI> eye. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Becau&s;e they &s;peak not peaceably, &Verbar; but words they do devi&s;e &Verbar; full of deceit again&s;t &s;uch as &Verbar; are quiet in the Land. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Yea, even with an open mouth &Verbar; they have upon me run; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> they have cried, Ah<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">, Aha, &Verbar; Our eyes have &s;een the thing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 O Thou ETERNAL God, Thou ha&s;t &Verbar; took cognizance <HI>of this;</HI> &Verbar; O <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> not now a &s;i|lent One; &Verbar; Lord, Be not far from me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Stir up thy &s;elf, and O awake &Verbar; unto my judgment <HI>now;</HI> &Verbar; O Thou my God, &amp; Thou my Lord, &Verbar; <HI>awake</HI> unto my cau&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24"><PB N="81" REF="001946_0118_0FFCB0A907F9B3C8">
24 According to thy Righteou&s;ne&s;s &Verbar; judge me, ETERNAL God; &Verbar; <HI>Judge me,</HI> my God, and let them not &Verbar; have triumphs ever me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 In their hearts let them not &s;ay, Ah, &Verbar; Our Soul <HI>would have it &s;o!</HI> &Verbar; O let them not have room to &s;ay, &Verbar; We have devoured him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 Let them be &s;ham'd, &amp; blu&s;h together, &Verbar; who of my hurt are glad; &Verbar; may they be cloath'd with &s;hame, and blu&s;h, &Verbar; who look &s;o big on me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27">27 Let them &s;hout with triumphant joy, &Verbar; and be exceeding glad, &Verbar; who&s;e favourable &s;entiments &Verbar; believe my righteou&s;ne&s;s. &Verbar; Yea, may they &s;ay continually, &Verbar; Let the ETER|NAL God &Verbar; be magnified, who takes delight &Verbar; in His true Servants peace. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 And now my tongue &s;hall dwell upon &Verbar; thy glorious Righteou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; <HI>My Tongue &s;hall celebrate</HI> thy prai&s;e &Verbar; all day * and every day.</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, A P&s;alm of Wi&s;hes, to &s;ee the Kingdom of <HI>Antichri&s;t,</HI> whereof we have here a de&s;cription, de&s;troyed! But, O <HI>Chri&s;tian Singer,</HI> Take here, once for all, a Noble In&s;truction of <HI>A<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">nobius. Cave ne<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ad homines adver&s;antes <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ibi pules i&s;ta competere.</HI> Dont think to Pray at this rate again&s;t thy per&s;onal Enemies; But employ tho&s;e Prayers, <HI>contra Spiritus hugus aerie, qui quotidie noc<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">,</HI> again&s;t thy <HI>Spiritual Enemies.</HI> again&s;t which thou art engaged in a continual <HI>Warfare.</HI></P>
<P N="2"><PB N="82" REF="001946_0119_0FFCB0ECC68261C0">
2 Good Men a&s;&s;aulted or endangered by Enemies at fir&s;t will de&s;ire no more than to be <HI>defended</HI> from them. They are not for <HI>offending</HI> of them. Anon, if there be no other way, they are content that the Holy One take the <HI>Spear</HI> al&s;o.</P>
<P N="4">4 Compare, <HI>Job.</HI> XVIII. 6. The LXX here u&s;es the &s;ame Word that is there.</P>
<P N="8">8 R. <HI>Obadiah</HI> thinks, here is an Allu&s;ion to 2 Sam. XVIII. 13.&mdash;<HI>Bring Ropes to the City.</HI></P>
<P N="13">13 q. d. I wi&s;h'd my &s;elf no better than I de&s;ired God to do for them. The <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e. The Glo&s;s of the Ancients upon it was; <HI>Non alium ora|bam, quam illum qui mihi per&s;onaliter junctus e&s;t, dicit CHRISTUS; Secundum quod homo, &s;ecundum quod orat. Sed oratio convertitur in &s;inum; ide&s;t, ad Verbum in quo erat Pater.</HI></P>
<P N="15">15 q. d. The Scum of the People who were &s;o vile, that I did not &s;o much as know there were &s;uch Wret|ches in the World. The LXX reads it, The <HI>Scourges, Ain&s;worth</HI> &s;uppo&s;es it refers to the <HI>Scourge</HI> of the Tongue. [Job VI. 21.] <HI>Hammond</HI> &s;uppo&s;es it means People worthy of the <HI>Scourge.</HI></P>
<P N="16">16 Hebr. <HI>Mockers for a Cake. Sycophants</HI> who flatter at the Table for a belly full of Meat. Compare 2 Sam. XI. 8. &mdash; <HI>there followed a me&s;s of Meat from the King,</HI> R. <HI>Obadiah</HI> thinks that the&s;e Mockers em|ployed their Squibs particularly on that unhappy <HI>Me&s;s of Meat,</HI></P>
<P N="21">21 q. d. &mdash; We have now found him out.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="36" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXXVI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Of David, the Servant of the ETERNAL God.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 THE Wicked Mans Tran&s;gre&s;&s;ion doth, &Verbar; &s;peak this within my heart; &Verbar; That there's not any fear of God &Verbar; at all before his eyes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="83" REF="001946_0120_0FFCB0AE1525E8F0">
2 For in his own <HI>deceived</HI> eyes &Verbar; he flat|tereth him&s;elf, &Verbar; till his iniquity be found &Verbar; to be an hateful thing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Iniquity and ba&s;e deceit &Verbar; are the words of his mouth; &Verbar; he hath left off to under|&s;tand; &Verbar; to do the thing that's good. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Iniquity he does devi&s;e &Verbar; while he lies on his bed; &Verbar; he &s;ets upon a way not good; &Verbar; evil he don't abhor. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Thy Mercy, OETERNAL God, &Verbar; is in the Heavens <HI>&s;een;</HI> &Verbar; Thy faithfulne&s;s is what does reach &Verbar; unto the Heav'nly clouds.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Like mounts of God's thy Righteou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; thy Judgments a great deep; &Verbar; ETERNAL God, Thou do&s;t pre&s;erve &Verbar; Man, and <HI>in&s;eriour</HI> Bea&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 O God, How wondrous excellent &Verbar; thy loving kindne&s;s is! &Verbar; Now in the &s;hadow of thy wings &Verbar; the Sons of Men will tru&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 They from the fatne&s;s of thy Hou&s;e &Verbar; &s;hall be repleni&s;hed; &Verbar; and of the &s;tream of thy Delights &Verbar; thou &s;halt make them to drink. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Becau&s;e there is the Fountain of &Verbar; <HI>all of our</HI> Lives with thee; &Verbar; <HI>Enlightned</HI> by thy <HI>glorious</HI> Light &Verbar; we &s;hall &s;ee Light <HI>with joy.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Extend thy loving kindne&s;s to &Verbar; them that acknowledge thee; &Verbar; <HI>extend</HI> al&s;o thy Righteou&s;ne&s;s &Verbar; to the upright in heart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 O never let the foot of pride &Verbar; make an approach to me: &Verbar; Nor let the hand of wicked ones &Verbar; cau&s;e me for to remove. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12"><PB N="84" REF="001946_0121_0FFCB449E33780C0">
12 The workers of iniquity, &Verbar; they are now fallen there; &Verbar; they are ca&s;t down, and they &s;hall not &Verbar; be able to ari&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 <HI>SAul</HI> doubtle&s;s was intended; yet he names him not, becau&s;e he would pre&s;erve all the Reverence that might be, for him.</P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>The Shadow of the Wings of the Lord,</HI> No doubt refers to <HI>Angelical</HI> Influences, and Protections. But <HI>Arnobius</HI> devoutly refers it unto the <HI>extended Arms</HI> of our SAVIOUR on the <HI>Cro&s;s.</HI></P>
<P N="8">8 The <HI>Fatne&s;s of the Hou&s;e of GOD,</HI> more imme|diately refers to the <HI>Sacrifices of Thanksgiving.</HI></P>
<P N="12">12 There!&mdash;in the very Act of their wickedne&s;s.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="37" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XXXVII. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 FRet not thy &s;elf becau&s;e of them &Verbar; that are malignant Men; &Verbar; Be'n't mov'd with envy at the Men &Verbar; that work iniquity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 For that like as the Gra&s;s they &s;hall &Verbar; be &s;peedily mown down; &Verbar; and like unto the verdant Herb, &Verbar; wither they &s;hall away. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Hope thou in the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; and &s;till be doing Good; &Verbar; Inhabit <HI>then</HI> the <HI>pro|mis'd</HI> Land, &Verbar; and make the Truth thy food. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 And do thou place thy whole delight &Verbar; in the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; &s;o He will then vouch&s;afe to thee &Verbar; the wi&s;hes of thine heart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Devolve <HI>the Cares of all</HI> thy way &Verbar;
<PB N="85" REF="001946_0122_0FFCB0B49CD82BA8">on the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and place thy confidence in Him, &Verbar; &s;o He'll accompli&s;h it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 He &s;hall therewith like as the Light &Verbar; bring forth thy Righteou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; and with meridian lu&s;tre &s;hall &Verbar; Judgments be wrought for thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 On the ETERNAL God be thou &Verbar; a &s;ilent waiter &s;till; &Verbar; and with uncea&s;ing patience wait &Verbar; expecting Him <HI>to work.</HI> &Verbar; Fret not thy &s;elf becau&s;e of him &Verbar; who pro&s;pers in his way; &Verbar; or becau&s;e of the Man who brings &Verbar; wicked de&s;igns to pa&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 De&s;i&s;t from anger, and di&s;mi&s;s &Verbar; fierce indignation: &Verbar; Do not wax hot; but &s;till be &s;ure &Verbar; to do no evil thing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 For evil-doers, they &s;hall be &Verbar; cut off; but they that wait &Verbar; on the ETERNAL God, they &s;hall &Verbar; as heirs enjoy the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 For yet a little while, and then &Verbar; the wicked &s;hall not be; &Verbar; yea, thou &s;halt clo&s;ely view his place, &Verbar; and he &s;hall not be there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 But humbled ones &s;hall have the Earth &Verbar; for their Inheritance; &Verbar; and in th' abundance of <HI>their</HI> peace &Verbar; they &s;hall delight them&s;elves. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 The wicked does devi&s;e a plot &Verbar; again&s;t the righteous man; &Verbar; and he does gna&s;h upon him with &Verbar; his <HI>ill-de&s;igning</HI> teeth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 The Lord <HI>relied-on</HI> &s;hall him &Verbar; in a de|ri&s;ion have; &Verbar; becau&s;e he does fore&s;ee his day &Verbar; <HI>of Wo</HI> is coming on. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14"><PB N="86" REF="001946_0123_0FFCB44C44B3B470">
14 The wicked have drawn out their Sword &Verbar; and they have bent their Bow, &Verbar; to make the poor and needy fall; &Verbar; to &s;lay right walking ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Their Sword &s;hall <HI>with a mortal thru&s;t</HI> &Verbar; pa&s;s into their own heart; &Verbar; their Bows al&s;o which they have bent, &Verbar; they &s;hall be broken quite. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Tho' it be but a little that &Verbar; a righte|ous Man enjoys, &Verbar; 'tis better than the heaped Wealth &Verbar; of many wicked ones.</P>
<P N="17">17 Becau&s;e the arms of wicked ones &Verbar; &s;hall be entirely broke; &Verbar; But the ETERNAL God confirms &Verbar; with &s;trength the righteous Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Th' ETERNAL God takes notice of &Verbar; the days of upright ones; &Verbar; and their Inhe|ritance &s;hall la&s;t &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 They &s;han't be put to any &s;hame &Verbar; in any evil time; &Verbar; and when the days of fa|mine come &Verbar; they &s;hall be &s;atisfy'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 But fade &s;hall ill Men, and the foes &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God &Verbar; &s;hall be con&s;um'd like fat of Lambs; &Verbar; they &s;hall con&s;ume in &s;moke. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 The wicked does receive a Loan, &Verbar; and does not pay again; &Verbar; But he that is a righ|teous Man &Verbar; &s;hews mercy and does give. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 For they who are His ble&s;&s;ed ones &Verbar; as heirs &s;hall have the Earth; &Verbar; but they that are cur&s;ed from Him &Verbar; &s;hall be cut off <HI>from thence.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23"><PB N="87" REF="001946_0124_0FFCB0B9B37F3A40">
23 The &s;teps of Man are ordered &Verbar; by the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; when the way which he takes is what &Verbar; he does take plea&s;ure in. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 Altho' he fall yet he &s;hall not &Verbar; be utterly ca&s;t down, &Verbar; becau&s;e that the ETER|NAL One &Verbar; upholds him with His Hand. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 I have been Young, and now am Old, &Verbar; yet have I never &s;een &Verbar; the Ju&s;t for&s;aken, nor his Seed, &Verbar; when asking for their Bread. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 He does &s;hew mercy every day, &Verbar; and's on the lending hand; &Verbar; and his Po&s;terity &s;hall be &Verbar; remark'd for ble&s;&s;edne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27">27 Depart from evil and do good; &Verbar; &s;o &s;halt thou dwell for ever. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 Becau&s;e that the ETERNAL One &Verbar; does love the thing that's right: &Verbar; He won't for|&s;ake His gracious ones, &Verbar; they are pre&s;erv'd for ever; &Verbar; But the Offspring of wicked ones &Verbar; is utterly our off. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="29">29 The righteous, they &s;hall have the Land &Verbar; as their Inheritance; &Verbar; and they therein forever &s;hall &Verbar; their habitation have. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="30">30 The mouth of a ju&s;t Man &s;hall &s;peak &Verbar; <HI>that which has</HI> wi&s;dom <HI>in't:</HI> &Verbar; his tongue &s;hall al&s;o utter <HI>what &Verbar; &s;hall be</HI> the thing that's right. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="31">31 The Law of God is in his heart; &Verbar; none of his &s;teps &s;hall &s;lip. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="32">32 The wicked Man does watch the Ju&s;t, &Verbar; and &s;eeks to ruin him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="33"><PB N="88" REF="001946_0125_0FFCB44E5A8B2E68">
33 Th'ETERNAL God will not leave him &Verbar; in th' hand of &s;uch an one; &Verbar; nor will he him condemn <HI>for &s;uch,</HI> &Verbar; when that he &s;hall be judg'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="34">34 Wait thou on the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; and keep thou <HI>in</HI> His way: &Verbar; and <HI>thou &s;hall find</HI> He then will &s;et &Verbar; thee in an high e&s;tate, &Verbar; That &s;o thou may'&s;t enjoy the Land &Verbar; as an Inheritance; &Verbar; <HI>whence</HI> when the wicked art cut off &Verbar; thou &s;halt behold the thing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="35">35 I have beheld the wicked one &Verbar; grown mighty in his power; &Verbar; and like unto a green Bay-tree, &Verbar; &s;preading him&s;elf abroad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="36">36 Yet he did quickly pa&s;s away, &Verbar; and lo, he was not there! &Verbar; yea, I did look for him, and he &Verbar; was not for to be found. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="37">37 Do thou ob&s;erve the perfect Man, &Verbar; and the upright behold, &Verbar; becau&s;e that &s;uch 2 Man &s;hall have &Verbar; peace in the latter end. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="38">38 But the tran&s;gre&s;&s;ors <HI>of the Law</HI> &Verbar; &s;hall be de&s;troy'd together; &Verbar; the latter end of wicked Men &Verbar; &s;hall be, <HI>to be</HI> cut off. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="39">39 But the Salvation of the Ju&s;t &Verbar; is from th' ETERNAL God; &Verbar; In the time of di&s;tre&s;s He is &Verbar; the fortitude of &s;uch. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="40">40 And the ETERNAL God does help &Verbar; them, and does re&s;cue them; &Verbar; re&s;cues them from ill Men, and &s;aves &Verbar; them; for they tru&s;t in Him &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="89" REF="001946_0126_0FFCB0BEEDD10100">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>NEce&s;&s;ary In&s;tructions for the Faithful under the Power of <HI>Antichri&s;t,</HI> who holds <HI>Pro&s;perity</HI> to be a Mark of the true Church. Behold, the Ruin of <HI>Antichri&s;t;</HI> both Head and Body; and the bright Pro&s;perity of the Faithful, after the wicked one &s;hall be de&s;iroyed. Our SAVIOUR applies the P&s;alm to an happy condition of the Church upon Earth; <HI>Matth.</HI> V. 5. Compare, <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> XI. 4.</P>
<P>The Son of <HI>Syrack</HI> gives us the Sum of the P&s;alm in, Eccl. I. 23. <HI>A Patient Man, will bear for a long time, and afterward Joy &s;hall &s;pring up unto him.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 Quite contrary the wretched <HI>Ethicks</HI> taught by that grand Apo&s;tle of <HI>Satan, Ari&s;totle;</HI> who commends for a <HI>Vertue,</HI> an Indignation at the <HI>Pro&s;perity</HI> of un|worthy Men.</P>
<P N="3">3 <HI>David Kimchi</HI> &s;o glo&s;&s;es it; <HI>Pa&s;ce alios, ubicunque habitas, in&s;iructione in vijs Domini.</HI></P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Kimchi's</HI> Glo&s;s is, Men &s;hall plainly <HI>&s;ee</HI> &amp; <HI>own,</HI> that thou art a <HI>Righteous</HI> Man.</P>
<P N="14">14 'Tis an Ob&s;ervation of R. <HI>Solomons; Pauper et egenus, in P&s;a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">mis, &s;emper de I&s;raele dicuntur.</HI> The <HI>poor</HI> and <HI>needy</HI> always mean <HI>I&s;rael.</HI></P>
<P N="16">16 A famous Jew reads it &s;o; <HI>A few Righteous Men are of more account than many Wicked ones.</HI></P>
<P N="24">24 <HI>David</HI> once begg'd his own Bread. The <HI>begging of Bread</HI> here notes, all <HI>a&s;king</HI> for it, either of God or Man. We are compell'd unto the Ver&s;ion that is now given us.</P>
<P N="35">35 We &s;ee Wicked Men pretending to <HI>Lawrels.</HI> But what comes of them?</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="38" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXXVIII.</HI> A P&s;alm of David; To bring to Remembrance.</HEAD>
<PB N="90" REF="001946_0127_0FFCB4500BADF998">
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God; in thy &Verbar; hot wrath rebuke me not; &Verbar; And in thy Anger flaming out, &Verbar; O do not cha&s;ten me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Becau&s;e thine Arrows upon me &Verbar; are &s;hot down from above; &Verbar; and thy hand from a|bove does come &Verbar; down to afflict me &s;ore. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 In my fle&s;h there is nothing &s;ound; &Verbar; thine Anger is the cau&s;e; &Verbar; nor in my bones is any re&s;t; &Verbar; becau&s;e that I have &s;inn'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Becau&s;e that mine iniquities &Verbar; over mine head are gone; &Verbar; they as an heavy burden are &Verbar; too heavy <HI>found</HI> for me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 My wounds do &s;tink and are corrupt; &Verbar; my folly is the cau&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Troubled I am, and much depre&s;s'd; &Verbar; go mourning every day. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 For my loins are inflam'd, and in &Verbar; my fle&s;h there's nothing &s;ound. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 I'm weak and broken much; I r<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> &Verbar; thro' angui&s;h of my heart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O Lord, Before thee <HI>there is laid</HI> &Verbar; the whole of my de&s;ire; &Verbar; and none of all my groaning is &Verbar; at all conceal'd from thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 My heart perplex'd turns every way; &Verbar; my &s;trength, it faileth me: &Verbar; And as for the light of mine eyes, &Verbar; even tho&s;e <HI>are</HI> not with me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 My lovers &amp; my friends do &s;tand &Verbar; where they may n't &s;ee my &s;troke; &Verbar; and they that are my Neighbours do &Verbar; &s;tand at a di&s;tance off &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12"><PB N="91" REF="001946_0128_0FFCB0C65BD28F00">
12 And they that &s;eek my life lay &s;nares; &Verbar; they too that &s;eek my hurt, &Verbar; do &s;peak mi&s;|chievous things; and plot &Verbar; all the day long deceits. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 But I am as a Man that's deaf; &Verbar; I hear not <HI>what they &s;ay;</HI> &Verbar; And I am like a Man that's dumb, &Verbar; who opens not his mouth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 And thus I was like to a Man &Verbar; who does not hear at all; &Verbar; nor is there in his mouth what he &Verbar; may an&s;wer for him&s;elf. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 For, O ETERNAL God, thou art &Verbar; He for whom I do wait; &Verbar; O Lord, Thou art my God, thou wilt &Verbar; give an&s;wer unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 For this is what I &s;aid, le&s;t they &Verbar; &s;hould triumph over me, &Verbar; while my foot &s;lips, again&s;t me they &Verbar; do magnifie them|&s;elves. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 For I'm prepar'd to halt, and ever &Verbar; before me is my grief. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 For I'll declare my crime, I will &Verbar; be &s;orry for my &s;in. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 But my foes, <HI>who are</HI> living ones, &Verbar; are mighty, &s;trong <HI>withal;</HI> &Verbar; and they who hate me wrongfully &Verbar; are greatly multiply'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 They too that render ill for good, &Verbar; are enemies to me; &Verbar; yea, it is for this very cau&s;e; &Verbar; I follow what is good. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 ETERNAL God, For&s;ake me not; &Verbar; My God, Be'nt far from me: &Verbar; make ha&s;te to help me, Lord, who art, &Verbar; my <HI>&s;ole</HI> Salvation <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">l<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="92" REF="001946_0129_0FFCB0CD52673650">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>DOes not the P&s;alm expre&s;s the condition of the <HI>Synagogue,</HI> as now groaning under the Per&s;e|cution of <HI>An<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ichri&s;t?</HI> No doubt of it. Compare the 16th <HI>Ver&s;e,</HI> with <HI>Deut.</HI> XXII. 26, 27. and the 17th <HI>Ver&s;e,</HI> with <HI>Zeph.</HI> III. 19.</P>
<P N="2">2 R. <HI>Obadiah</HI> reports a Tradition, That the P&s;almi&s;t laboured under a <HI>Lepro&s;y</HI> Six Months together, and that all this time, <HI>The Divine Pre&s;ence was witheld from him.</HI></P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Mun&s;tors</HI> glo&s;s upon <HI>Snares,</HI> is, <HI>Verba ad de&s;pe|rationom inducentia:</HI> Words of <HI>De&s;pair.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="39" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XXXIX.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician: To Jeduthun. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 I Said, I will regard my ways &Verbar; le&s;t I &s;in with my tongue; &Verbar; I'll keep a bridle on my mouth, &Verbar; while I've the vile in view. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 With &s;ilence I remain'd as dumb, &Verbar; wholly held my peace, &Verbar; not mentioning of any good; &Verbar; my grief was then renew'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 My heart within me did grow hot; &Verbar; while my thoughts were engag'd; &Verbar; the Fire did then begin to burn; &Verbar; <HI>then</HI> &s;pake I with my tongue. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O Thou ETERNAL One, Do thou &Verbar; make known to me my end; &Verbar; and what's the mea&s;ure of my days; &Verbar; to know how frail am. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="93" REF="001946_0130_0FFCB0CB977EA9E8">
5 Lo, Thou an hands breadth mak'&s;t my days, &Verbar; and my age in thy &s;ight, &Verbar; as nothing; &s;ure each man at be&s;t &Verbar; is wholly vanity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Sure, in a &s;hadow Man does walk; &Verbar; &s;ure, they're di&s;turb'd in vain; &Verbar; he heaps up trea&s;ures, and knows not &Verbar; who &s;hall make u&s;e of them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 And now, O Lord, What wait I for? &Verbar; My hope is placid on thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Deliver me from all my &s;ins; &Verbar; the Fools &s;corn make me not. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 I'm dumb, I open not my mouth; &Verbar; for 'tis what thou ha&s;t done. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Remove thy &s;troke away from me; &Verbar; by thy hand's blow I wa&s;te. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 When with rebukes thou do&s;t correct &Verbar; Man for iniquity, &Verbar; thou mak'&s;t to wa&s;te even as moth, &Verbar; that which is his de&s;ire. &Verbar; Mo&s;t certainly then every Man &Verbar; is very vanity. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Hear my Prayer, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; and hearken to my cry. &Verbar; Upon my tears, O be not deaf, &Verbar; becau&s;e I am with thee &Verbar; a &s;tranger, and a &s;ojourner, &Verbar; as all my Fa|thers were. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 O &s;pare me graciou&s;ly, that &s;o &Verbar; I may recover &s;trength, &Verbar; before that I &s;hall go <HI>from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ence,</HI> &Verbar; and be no more at all. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="94" REF="001946_0131_0FFCB454E15CC580">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XXXIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold again the Condition of the <HI>Synagogue</HI> under the Oppre&s;&s;ions of <HI>Anticbri&s;t.</HI></P>
<P N="6">6 A Man promi&s;es him&s;elf mighty matters; But he has no more than the <HI>Image</HI> and <HI>Shadone</HI> of them in his Erain; For on the &s;udden he him&s;elf vanithes and is gone. So one Paraphra&s;es. The Compari&s;on of Man to a <HI>Shadow,</HI> may be copiou&s;ly pro&s;ecuted, with much Service to Piety.</P>
<P N="12">12 A &s;ad Hint! It &s;eems, GOD and he were both <HI>Strangers</HI> here. But have an Eye to the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> here. He was a <HI>Stranger</HI> in this World.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="40" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XL.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 WIth earne&s;t waiting I did wait &Verbar; on the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and He in|clined unto me, &Verbar; He al&s;o heard my cry. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 And fetch<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">d me from the roaring pit; &Verbar; out of the miry clay; &Verbar; and on a Rock He &s;et my feet; &Verbar; He did direct my &s;teps. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 And put a new Song in my mouth, &Verbar; <HI>of</HI> Prai&s;e unto our God; &Verbar; Many &s;hall &s;ee, and fear, and tru&s;t &Verbar; in the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O ble&s;&s;ed is the Man that makes &Verbar; th' ETERNAL God his tru&s;t; &Verbar; and dont regard the proud, nor the &Verbar; decliners to a lye. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 ETERNAL God, my God, Thou&s;t wrought &Verbar; Thy many wondrous works; &Verbar;
<PB N="95" REF="001946_0132_0FFCB0D104023EC0">And thy thoughts towards us, to thee &Verbar; none can in order tell: &Verbar; Would I declare and mention them &Verbar; they're more than can be told. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 A Sacrifice and Offring thou &Verbar; did&s;t not at all de&s;ire. &Verbar; Thou <HI>for thy Service</HI> bor'&s;t the Ears &Verbar; thou'&s;t given unto me: &Verbar; Burnt-Off|ring and Sin-Offring is &Verbar; what thou ha&s;t not requir'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Then, &s;aid I, Lo, I come; <HI>to do &Verbar; that which thou ha&s;t requir'd:</HI> &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t a rolled Book wherein &Verbar; 'tis written <HI>thus</HI> of me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 That I may do thy Will, My God, &Verbar; this is what I would have; &Verbar; In the mid&s;t of my Bowels too &Verbar; thy Law <HI>is trea&s;ur'd up.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 In the great Congregation I &Verbar; have Preach'd thy Righteou&s;ne&s;s: &Verbar; Lo, I have not refrain'd my lips, &Verbar; ETERNAL God, thou know'&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Thy Righteou&s;ne&s;s I have not hid &Verbar; in the mid&s;t of my heart; &Verbar; I have thy faith|fulne&s;s and thy &Verbar; Salvation &s;hown abroad. &Verbar; Thy loving kindne&s;s I have not &Verbar; in any part conceal'd, &Verbar; nor from the Great A&s;&s;em|bly <HI>kept</HI> &Verbar; thy never-failing Truth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Withold not, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; thy kindne&s;&s;es from me; &Verbar; Thy Mercy, and thy Truth let them &Verbar; keep me continually. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 For evils have encompa&s;s'd me &Verbar; till none can number them: &Verbar; And my iniqui|ties withal &Verbar; have taken hold on me. &Verbar;
<PB N="96" REF="001946_0133_0FFCB0EB4190A668">Nor can I take a view, they are &Verbar; &s;o multi|ply'd above &Verbar; the hairs which grow upon my head; &Verbar; and my Heart faileth me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Be plea&s;ed, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; for to deliver me; &Verbar; and unto my relief make ha&s;te, &Verbar; O Thou ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Let tho&s;e be &s;ham'd, &amp; blu&s;h together &Verbar; that &s;eek my Soul, to &s;lay't; &Verbar; Let tho&s;e be driven back and &s;ham'd, &Verbar; who do de&s;ire my hurt. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 As the ju&s;t recompence of what &Verbar; is really their &s;hame; &Verbar; they &s;hall be de&s;olate, who &s;ay, &Verbar; to me, Aha, Aha!</P>
<P N="16">16 Tho&s;e who are thy true &s;eekers, let &Verbar; all &s;uch rejoyce in thee &Verbar; yea, let them all triumph in <HI>this</HI> &Verbar; with overflowing joy. &Verbar; Tho&s;e who in thy Salvation take &Verbar; a true delight, let them &Verbar; forever &s;ay, Th' ETER|NAL God, &Verbar; Let Him be magnify'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 But I'm a needy one, and poor: &Verbar; the Lord yet thinks on me: &Verbar; Thou my Help, and my Saviour art; &Verbar; My God, O tarry not. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XL. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P><HI>CHri&s;tian,</HI> Behold the Prai&s;es of thy SAVIOUR to His ETERNAL Father, for His Pre&s;ence with Him, in His Humiliation. <HI>Paul</HI> has taught us how to apply the P&s;alm.</P>
<P N="2">2 The <HI>Sepulchre</HI> of our SAVIOUR was hewed out of a <HI>Rock.</HI> Behold Him <HI>&s;etting His Fert on the Rock,</HI> and in His <HI>Re&s;urrection</HI> triumphing over the Grave.</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="97" REF="001946_0134_0FFCB0DA0AE2AEA0">
5 <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> &s;o reads it, <HI>Nemo e&s;t qui ea ordinat ad te.</HI> The Benefits of Heaven, are not ordered by Men as they &s;hould, and &s;ubordinated unto the Glory and Service of GOD.</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Mine Ear ha&s;t thou bored,</HI> is, q. d. Thou ha&s;t made me thy <HI>Servant.</HI> The Service which the Son of GOD was to do for His Eternal Father, could not be done without a <HI>Body.</HI> The Clau&s;e is with much wi&s;dom rendered in the New-Te&s;tament, <HI>A Body ha&s;t thou prepared for me.</HI> The Servant was to have part of his <HI>Body,</HI> his <HI>Ear</HI> fa&s;tned with Iron to a Po&s;t. So was the Body of our SAVIOUR, to the <HI>Cro&s;s.</HI> Yea, the Hebrew Word &s;ignifies, <HI>Apparare,</HI> as well as, <HI>Perforare.</HI> And <HI>Ozen,</HI> may &s;ignify a <HI>Body</HI> as well as an <HI>Ear.</HI> Moreover, the Greek Word <GAP DESC="foreign">, which we render, a <HI>Body,</HI> is continually u&s;ed by the Jewi&s;h Writers, to &s;ignify, <HI>A Servant.</HI> So in the Books of the <HI>Apocrypha</HI> and <HI>Jo&s;ephus.</HI></P>
<P>There is a wrong done to the Holy Spirit of GOD, by tho&s;e Criticks, who will tell you, That the Apo&s;tle followed the LXX, in his reading here, <HI>A Body ha&s;t thou prepared for me.</HI></P>
<P>In <HI>Jerom's</HI> Days, there was not this reading in the LXX. The Primitive Chri&s;tians altered the LXX in &s;everal Places, which the New-Te&s;tament cites out of the Old, and put in the Words of the New-Te&s;tament, which were not there before.</P>
<P N="7">7 Some read it, <HI>In the Head,</HI> [or Beginnin] <HI>of thy Book;</HI> And think the Prophecy in the III. of <HI>Ge|ne&s;is</HI> refer'd unto. <HI>Grotius</HI> ob&s;erves, That the He|brews wrote their <HI>Contracts</HI> and <HI>Agronnents,</HI> and <HI>Indentures</HI> in <HI>Rolls.</HI> The <HI>Volumn</HI> here implies a <HI>Cont<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">act.</HI></P>
<P N="16">16&mdash;Not expect<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">vation from any other hand. But, <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> The Love of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> SAVIOUR is al&s;o &s;uppo&s;ed her.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="41" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="98" REF="001946_0135_0FFCB456AE3E0728">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XLI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BLe&s;&s;ed the Man, who prudently &Verbar; con|&s;idereth the Poor; &Verbar; Th' ETERNAL God will re&s;cue him when 'tis an evil day.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Th' ETERNAL God will have him in &Verbar; His gracious cu&s;tody; &Verbar; and He will make him for to live, &Verbar; when <HI>Death does threaten him.</HI> &Verbar; He &s;hall be ble&s;&s;ed upon Earth; &Verbar; nor wilt thou give him up &Verbar; unto the &s;piteful will of tho&s;e &Verbar; that are his enemies. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Th' ETERNAL God will on the Bed &Verbar; of weakne&s;s &s;trengthen him: &Verbar; Thou, when that he is langui&s;hing, &Verbar; wilt turn his Bed for him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 I &s;aid, O Thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Be merciful to me; &Verbar; Heal thou my Soul, be|cau&s;e I have &Verbar; wandred from Thee by Sin. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 My Adver&s;aries, they do &s;peak &Verbar; evil concerning me; &Verbar; When &s;hall he die? <HI>They &s;ay,</HI> and when &Verbar; &s;hall his name be de&s;troy'd? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 And if he comes to vi&s;it me, &Verbar; he &s;peaks but vanity; &Verbar; his heart rakes mi&s;chief to it &s;elf; &Verbar; going abroad he tells. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Again&s;t me they that hate me do &Verbar; whi&s;per together all; &Verbar; again&s;t me they devi&s;e what may &Verbar; be mi&s;cheivous to me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 <HI>They &s;ay,</HI> Some thing of Belial &s;ure &Verbar;
<PB N="99" REF="001946_0136_0FFCB0DF44C25688">is lying upon him; &Verbar; and now that he is lying ill &Verbar; he &s;hall ri&s;e up no more. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Yea, and my own familiar friend &Verbar; in whom I tru&s;ted much; &Verbar; he who did eat my bread, has lift &Verbar; the heel <HI>to &s;trike</HI> at me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 But thou, O thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; be merciful to me; &Verbar; and O re&s;tore thou me, that I &Verbar; may make returns to them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 By this thing I am &s;en&s;ible, &Verbar; that thou do&s;t favour me; &Verbar; becau&s;e my enemy has not &Verbar; a triumph over me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 And as for me, me thou uphold&s;t &Verbar; in my integrity; &Verbar; and thou &s;ett'&s;t me before thy face &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Ble&s;&s;ed be the ETERNAL One, &Verbar; the God of I&s;rael: &Verbar; from Age even unto Age, Amen, &Verbar; <HI>And yet again,</HI> Amen. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XLI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>MAY we not &s;ee the Condition of the <HI>Sanagogue,</HI> for&s;aken of all Humane help; yet hoping for a Re&s;toration? 'Tis in view of this that GOD is ble&s;&s;ed ty the Name of, <HI>The GOD of I&s;rael;</HI> An Appellation that relates to the Re-calling of all the Tribes. The double <HI>Amen,</HI> leads us to a <HI>Second</HI> Re&s;toration.</P>
<P N="1">1 <HI>Pagnin,</HI> and others read it, <HI>Ble&s;&s;ed is he that un|der&s;tands the Poor. Aquinas</HI> notes on it, A <HI>Merci|ful</HI> Man will endeavour to <HI>inform</HI> him&s;elf of the wants of the <HI>Poor,</HI> and <HI>relieve</HI> them, even before they do them&s;elves <HI>reveal</HI> them. As <HI>Leo</HI> &s;peaks, <HI>Ut hoc ip&s;o magis gaudeant, quum et paupertati corum con&s;ultum fuerit, et pudori.</HI></P>
<P N="3"><PB N="100" REF="001946_0137_0FFCB7B7056A2778">
3 He<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">r. <HI>Turn his Bed. Mun&s;ter</HI> be&s;peaks that &s;en&s;e for it: The Lord will <HI>change</HI> his <HI>Bed;</HI> and give him Health in&s;tead of Sickne&s;s.</P>
<P N="9">9 Hearken to Old <HI>Arnobius.</HI> Here &s;uppo&s;e our Interiour a&s;&s;aulted by the <HI>Fle&s;h,</HI> and the Powers of Dar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ne&s;s. Our <HI>Name</HI> which they would have to <HI>peri&s;h,</HI> is that of, <HI>Chri&s;tian. Chri&s;tian,</HI> Thy Fle&s;h is thy <HI>Familiar Friend,</HI> and it plays the <HI>Judas</HI> with thee, When thou art <HI>Ri&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n</HI> from the deadly Circum&s;tances, which thy Spiritual Enemies bring upon thee, <HI>Requite</HI> them, De&s;troy them.</P>
<P>Ditto. <HI>Lift up the Heel.</HI> The Jewi&s;h Glo&s;s is agreeable; <HI>Ac &s;i eram &s;emita pede &s;uo trita.</HI> As if I were the dirt of the Street, for him to tread upon.</P>
<P>Ditto. Of Old, No <HI>Covenant of Friend&s;hip</HI> counted more inviolable, than what was begun at the <HI>Table,</HI> or confirm'd there. <HI>Jowi&s;h</HI> and <HI>Pagan</HI> Writers, have Curio&s;ities of this Importance. <HI>Communicants at the Table of the Lord,</HI> Con&s;ider of this.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>THE SECOND BOOK OF PSALMS.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="42" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XLII.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Ma&s;chil; for the Sons of Korah.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 AS the Hart makes a panting cry &Verbar; for cooling &s;treams of waters; &Verbar; So my Soul makes a panting cry &Verbar; to Thee, O migh|ty God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 My Soul does flame with thir&s;t for God, &Verbar; ev'n for the living God; &Verbar; when &s;hall I come, and <HI>when</HI> appear &Verbar; before the face of God? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="101" REF="001946_0138_0FFCB0E3C90BFE88">
3 My Tear has been my con&s;tant meat, &Verbar; both in the day and night, &Verbar; while they con|tinually &s;ay &Verbar; to me, Where is thy God? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 The&s;e things when I remember, I &Verbar; pour out my Soul in me. &Verbar; For I had gone in company &Verbar; once with the multitude; &Verbar; I went with them to th' Hou&s;e of God &Verbar; with voice of joy and prai&s;e; &Verbar; even with a mul|titude of them &Verbar; that kept a Fe&s;tival. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Why do&s;t thou throw thy &s;elf into &Verbar; dejections, O my Soul? &Verbar; And why art thou di&s;quieted &Verbar; in me with &s;uch a noi&s;e? &Verbar; Hope thou with waiting upon God; &Verbar; For I &s;hall prai&s;e Him yet; &Verbar; Salvations are di&s;|penc'd from the &Verbar; kind A&s;pects of His Face. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 My God, my Soul's ca&s;t down in me; &Verbar; Hence I'll remember thee &Verbar; from Jordan's Land and Hermon's Hills, &Verbar; from the Hill Mizar there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Deep calleth unto deep, at the &Verbar; noi&s;e of thy water &s;pouts; &Verbar; Thy &s;welling Bil|lows and thy Waves &Verbar; have all gone over me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Now the ETERNAL God will with &Verbar; effectual power command &Verbar; His mercy <HI>which He promi&s;ed</HI> &Verbar; when that the Day arrives, &Verbar; And when the Night comes on there is &Verbar; with me a Song of His; &Verbar; A Supplication to Him who &Verbar; is of my Life the GOD. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 I will &s;ay unto God my Rock, &Verbar; Why ha&s;t thou me forgot? &Verbar; Why go I mourning for the &s;ore &Verbar; oppre&s;&s;ion of the foe? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10"><PB N="102" REF="001946_0139_0FFCB7B996FD2990">
10 With cutting to my very bones &Verbar; my foes reproach me hard; &Verbar; While every day they unto me &Verbar; do &s;ay, Where is thy God? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Why do&s;t thou throw thy &s;elf into &Verbar; dejections, O my Soul? &Verbar; And why art thou di&s;quieted &Verbar; in me with &s;uch a noi&s;e? &Verbar; Hope thou with waiting upon God; &Verbar; for I &s;hall prai&s;e Him yet; &Verbar; Salvations He does work before &Verbar; my face; He is my God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XLII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, The &s;orrows of the <HI>Synagogue</HI> in her di&s;|per&s;ion, de&s;cribed by the <HI>Spirit of Prophecy<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI></P>
<P N="1">1 Some have applied this unto <HI>Bapti&s;m,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">fter which, even the <HI>Infant-Soul</HI> does pant, as having been invenomed by the <HI>Old Serpent.</HI> Many of the <HI>Fathers</HI> had this Notion. And <HI>Aquinas</HI> quotes it out of <HI>Jerom,</HI> That the&s;e Ver&s;es were Sung at the Solemn Times, when <HI>Bapti&s;m</HI> was admini&s;tred.</P>
<P N="2">2&mdash;Who would have expected it from a Jew? And yet <HI>Aben-E<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ra</HI> &s;ays, The coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> is here longed for.</P>
<P N="3">3 q. d. I have been &s;o taken up with <HI>Weeping,</HI> that I have had no time or heart for <HI>Eating.</HI></P>
<P N="4">4 'Twas very notably &s;o, when the P&s;almi&s;t brought the <HI>Ark</HI> to its dwelling place. Compare, I <HI>Chron.</HI> XV. 25, 28.</P>
<P N="6">6 All <HI>Jordan,</HI> from the Spring to the Mouth of it, is here mea&s;ured out.&mdash;He was bani&s;h'd unto the utmo&s;t Countr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">es, both North and South, wa&s;h'd by the River <HI>Jordan.</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 The Waters of <HI>Jordan</HI> put him in mind of his Mi&s;eries;&mdash;All rolling over him one after another.</P>
<P N="10"><PB N="103" REF="001946_0140_0FFCB0E9A14A1C28">
10 Becau&s;e the Jews had no <HI>Images</HI> of GOD, but wor&s;hipped an <HI>Invi&s;ible GOD,</HI> the Pagans derided them. <HI>Lucan</HI> &s;peaks of their <HI>Deus Incerius.</HI> And <HI>Ph<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ch</HI> owns, he did not know who he was. Quota|tions might be Numberle&s;s.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="43" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XLIII.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 JUdge me, O God, and plead again&s;t &Verbar; a Nation mercile&s;s, &Verbar; my cau&s;e. O &s;ave me from the Man &Verbar; that's cra&s;ty and unju&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 For of my &s;trength thou art the God, &Verbar; why do&s;t thou ca&s;t me off? &Verbar; Why go I mourning for the &s;ore &Verbar; oppre&s;&s;ion of the foe? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Thy light O &s;end forth, and thy truth; &Verbar; let them lead me; let them &Verbar; bring me unto thy holy hill, &Verbar; and to thy Man&s;ions <HI>there.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Then to God's Altar I will go; &Verbar; To God, Joy of my Joy: &Verbar; and on the Harp I will con|fe&s;s &Verbar; to thee, O God, my God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Why do&s;t thou throw thy &s;elf in &Verbar; dejections, O my Soul? &Verbar; And why art<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ou di&s;quieted &Verbar; in me with &s;uch a noi&s;e? &Verbar; Hope thou with waiting upon God, &Verbar; for I &s;hall prai&s;e Him yet: &Verbar; Salvations He does work before &Verbar; my face; He is my God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XLIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>TIS a &s;ervent Praver of Di&s;per&s;ed <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> for a Re&s;toration. Compare, <HI>Zeph,</HI> III. 16, 17.</P>
<P N="3">3 'Tis Remarkable. The <HI>Midra&s;h Till in</HI> finds the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> here. And &s;o does <HI>Rabbi Sol<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters">.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="44" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="104" REF="001946_0141_0FFCB7BB58FD6E30">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XLIV.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. For the Sons of Korah. Ma&s;chil.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 WE have heard with our Ears, O God; &Verbar; us have our Fathers told &Verbar; what work thou wroughte&s;t in their days; &Verbar; even in the former days. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Thou did&s;t expel the Nations with &Verbar; thy hand; but planted&s;t them: &Verbar; Thou did&s;t afflict the People <HI>there,</HI> &Verbar; and thou did&s;t &s;end them out. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For it was not by their own Sword &Verbar; they did po&s;&s;e&s;s the Land; &Verbar; nor was it any arm of theirs &Verbar; which did deliver them. &Verbar; But it was thy Right hand, it was &Verbar; thy Arm <HI>which did the thing;</HI> &Verbar; 'Twas the Light of thy face; Becau&s;e &Verbar; that thou did&s;t favout them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Thou even thou thy &s;elf &s;halt be &Verbar; ever my King, O God: &Verbar; Salvations by commande|ment &Verbar; for Jacob, O procure. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Thro' thee as with an horn we will &Verbar; pu&s;h down our Enemies; &Verbar; Them who do ri&s;e again&s;t us, we &Verbar; will tread down in thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 For in my Bow I will not place &Verbar; at all my confidence; &Verbar; nor &s;hall it be a Sword of mine &Verbar; that &s;hall deliver me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 But thou art He who &s;till do&s;t fa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">c &Verbar;
<PB N="105" REF="001946_0142_0FFCB0F06700C590"><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">s from our Enemies; &Verbar; 'tis thou who do&s;t put unto &s;hame &Verbar; them that have hated us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 We glory in the <HI>Glorious</HI> God, &Verbar; all day, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> and every day; &Verbar; And to thy Name we will confe&s;s &Verbar; unto Eternity. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 But thou ha&s;t in thy wrath ca&s;t off &Verbar; and ha&s;t put us to &s;hame; &Verbar; and with our Armed Forces <HI>now,</HI> &Verbar; thou art not going forth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Thou make&s;t us for to return &Verbar; back from the Enemy; &Verbar; and they that hate us, <HI>of our Weal<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">b</HI> &Verbar; make for them&s;elves a &s;poil. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 As if we had been Sheep for food, &s;o ha&s;t thou giv<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n us up; &Verbar; And thou among the Nations ha&s;t &Verbar; &s;catter'd us all abroad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Thou of thy People ha&s;t made &s;ale, &Verbar; and not increas'd thy Wealth; &Verbar; nor ha&s;t thou multiply'd thy Gain &Verbar; by a price paid for them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Unto our Neighhours thou do&s;t make &Verbar; us to be a reproach; a &s;corn and a deri&s;ion to &Verbar; them that encompa&s;s us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 A mere by-word of us thou do&s;t; &Verbar; a|mong the Nations make, &Verbar; Among the People we are tho&s;e &Verbar; at whom they &s;hake the head. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Before me every day is my &Verbar; confu&s;ion to be &s;een; &Verbar; and the &s;hame for to &s;how my face &Verbar; has wholly covered me.</P>
<P N="16">16 From the Voice which reproaches <HI>m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> &Verbar; and ulters Bla&s;phemies, &Verbar; from the face of the enemy, &Verbar; &Verbar; and the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ongeful one.</P>
<P N="17"><PB N="106" REF="001946_0143_0FFCB1062BBA4278">
17 All this is come on us, yet we &Verbar; have not forgotten thee; &Verbar; nor have we dealt per|fidiou&s;ly &Verbar; again&s;t thy Covenant. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Our heart is not departed <HI>in</HI> &Verbar; <HI>Apo&s;tacy from thee;</HI> &Verbar; not has our going yet been &s;uch &Verbar; as to decline thy way. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Tho' in the place of Dragons thou &Verbar; ha&s;t &s;orely broken us, &Verbar; and thou ha&s;t over|whelm'd us in &Verbar; the gloomy &s;hade of Death. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 If we have e'er forgot the Name &Verbar; of Him that is our God; &Verbar; or if unto a &s;trange God we &Verbar; have &s;tretched out our hands; &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Of &s;uch a thing would not our God &Verbar; full inqui&s;ition make? &Verbar; For the mo&s;t inward &s;ecrets of &Verbar; the heart He fully knows. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Yea, for thy cau&s;e we're put to death, &Verbar; all the day long <HI>'tis &s;o:</HI> &Verbar; We are accounted like the Sheep &Verbar; de&s;ign'd for to be &s;lain. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Awake, O Lord, <HI>our &s;trong &s;upport,</HI> &Verbar; O why art thou a&s;leep? &Verbar; Awake thou &s;o as to ari&s;e; &Verbar; ca&s;t us not off for ever. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 O wherefore do&s;t thou hide thy face? &Verbar; <HI>Wherefore</HI> do&s;t thou forget &Verbar; th' affliction which does humble us, &Verbar; and our oppre&s;&s;ion &s;ore? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 Becau&s;e our Soul is bowed down &Verbar; unto the very du&s;t; &Verbar; &s;o pro&s;trate that our belly does &Verbar; lye cleaving to the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 Ari&s;e, O thou that ever art &Verbar; the help that we propo&s;e, &Verbar; and, O do thou deliver us, &Verbar; even for thy mercy's &s;ake. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="107" REF="001946_0144_0FFCB0FA0BD7A1A8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XLIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold a Prayer for the <HI>Synagogue</HI> in her Di&s;per|&s;ion. Old <HI>Theoderet</HI> puts upon it this Title, <HI>D<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|feroci Animo Antiochi.</HI> But remember that <HI>Antio|chus</HI> was a Type of <HI>Antichri&s;t.</HI> Others, who think &s;uch In&s;pirations then cea&s;ed, apprehend the P&s;alm cal|culated for the days of <HI>Hezekiah;</HI> and the Di&s;tre&s;s which the <HI>A&s;&s;yrian</HI> brought upon <HI>Judea,</HI> in the time of that pious Reformer.</P>
<P N="4">4 Accompli&s;h <HI>Deliverances,</HI> by <HI>Commands</HI> and <HI>Or|ders</HI> given to <HI>Angels.</HI> 'Tis an Hint of <HI>Grotius.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 Compare, <HI>Deut.</HI> XXXIII. 17.</P>
<P N="12">12 God often <HI>Sold</HI> His People into the Hands of their Enemies, before the Conver&s;ion of the <HI>Gentiles.</HI> But it was not an <HI>Ab&s;olute Sale;</HI> It was only a <HI>Mortgage for Years;</HI> Redeemable after the Enemy had receiv'd his pay. God pa&s;&s;ed not away His Propriety in them; He entred a <HI>Provi&s;o</HI> of Recovery in the Command of <HI>Pre&s;erving the Evidences.</HI> [Jer. XXXII. 7] The <HI>Sel|ling</HI> all this while was <HI>for nought.</HI> God hereby did <HI>not increa&s;e His Wealth,</HI> nor add unto the heap of the Riches of that Grace, He had made over by Cove|nant unto <HI>Abraham</HI> and his Offspring. If God had utterly <HI>Sold</HI> away His People before He had &s;et up His Kingdom among the <HI>Gentiles,</HI> He had <HI>Sold them for Nought;</HI> He had lo&s;t His <HI>Vi&s;ible Kingdom</HI> in the World. But now when He Sold His People in the la&s;t <HI>Roman Captivity,</HI> it is not <HI>for Nought;</HI> it has in|troduced another and a larger People; <HI>The Riches of the World,</HI> as the Apo&s;tle expre&s;&s;es it.</P>
<P N="14">14 A Fulfilment of Deut. XXVIII. 37.</P>
<P N="19">19 <HI>Mun&s;ters</HI> Glo&s;s is, <HI>Agimur in Exilium,</HI> A Ba|ni&s;hment into a <HI>Wilderne&s;s.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="45" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="108" REF="001946_0145_0FFCB14972040FD8">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XLV.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician: Upon <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;ha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">mim; For the Sons of Korab. Ma&s;ehil. A <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ong of Loves.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 MY Heart it boils good matter out; &Verbar; I &s;peak unto the King &Verbar; what I have wrought; my Tongue is like &Verbar; a ready writers pen. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Fairer thou art than Sons of Men; &Verbar; Upon thy lips there is &Verbar; a Grace diffus'd; God therefore has &Verbar; ble&s;s'd thee for evermore. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Gird thou thy Sword upon thy thigh, &Verbar; O thou mo&s;t mighty One; &Verbar; <HI>Do it</HI> with thy Magnificence, &Verbar; and with thy Maje&s;ty. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 And in thy Maje&s;ty do thou &Verbar; proceed mo&s;t pro&s;p'rou&s;ly; &Verbar; yea, ride thou forth upon the Word &Verbar; of <HI>Everla&s;ting</HI> Truth: &Verbar; <HI>It is a Word</HI> of Meekne&s;s, and &Verbar; <HI>a Word</HI> of Righ|teou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; So thy Right-hand &s;hall &s;hew to thee &Verbar; Things very wonderful. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Sharp are thine Arrows: (under thee &Verbar; the People &s;hall fall down:) &Verbar; <HI>Sharp</HI> in the Hearts of them that have &Verbar; been enemies to the King. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 For ever and for ever is, &Verbar; thy Throne, O God, <HI>the Judge:</HI> &Verbar; The Scepter of thy Kingdom is &Verbar; a Scepter <HI>&s;way'd</HI> with right. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Thou love&s;t Righ teou&s;ne&s;s; and thou &Verbar; hate&s;t <HI>all</HI> wickedne&s;s; &Verbar; God therefore, He who is thy God, &Verbar; hath now anointed thee; &Verbar; <HI>Hath made thee His Me&s;&s;iah</HI> with &Verbar; a &s;weet re|fre&s;hing Oil, &Verbar; which does di&s;tingui&s;h thee from them &Verbar; who do partake with thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8"><PB N="109" REF="001946_0146_0FFCB0FE906C25B8">
8 With Benjamin and Aloes, &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> Ca&s;&s;ia, all thy robes, &Verbar; fetch'd from the ivory Pala|laces; &Verbar; from thence did make thee glad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Ladies of Honour unto thee &Verbar; are Daugh|ters of Great Kings; &Verbar; At thy Right-hand in Ophirs Gold &Verbar; array'd thy Con&s;ort &s;tands. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Hearken, O daughter, and behold; &Verbar; and bow thine ear <HI>to this;</HI> &Verbar; Now thine own People O forget, &Verbar; yea, and thy Fathers hou&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 So in thy Beauty &s;hall the King &Verbar; have an inten&s;e delight; &Verbar; Becau&s;e He is thy Lord, therefore &Verbar; pay homage unto Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Daughter of Tyrus, even thou; &Verbar; the wealthy People &s;hall &Verbar; &s;ollicit for thy favour with &Verbar; a Pre&s;ent <HI>made to thee.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 The Daughter of the King, &s;he is &Verbar; all glorious within; &Verbar; Her covering is of &s;pang|led Robes &Verbar; which are inlaid with Gold. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 In Robes of Needle-work &s;he &s;hall &Verbar; be brought unto the King; &Verbar; Virgins that follow and attend, &Verbar; the&s;e &s;hall be brought to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 They &s;hall brought be with wondrous joys, &Verbar; and exultations there; &Verbar; their entrance they &s;hall make into &Verbar; the Palace of the King. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 In the room of thy Fathers now &Verbar; thy Children &s;hall &s;ucceed; &Verbar; the&s;e thou &s;halt <HI>bence&s;orth</HI> con&s;titute &Verbar; Princes in all the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 In every Generation I &Verbar; will make thy Name to be &Verbar; remembred; &s;o the People &s;hall &Verbar; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ai&s;e thee for evermore. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="110" REF="001946_0147_0FFCB7BED0FB4A40">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XLV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the Marriage of the Jewi&s;h Church unto the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> when &s;he &s;hall be recalled and re&s;tored unto the favour of GOD. Compare the III. Chapter of <HI>Joremiah.</HI> R. <HI>David Kimchi,</HI> has wondrous Con|fe&s;&s;ions, That the <HI>Loves</HI> in the P&s;alm, are the <HI>Loves</HI> of GOD unto His CHRIST; That the <HI>Kings Daugh|ters</HI> are the Nations of the Farth, Subject unto the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah;</HI> and the Queen among them is <HI>I&s;rael.</HI> Others of the Rabbi's; but above all, the <HI>Chaldee Pa|raphra&s;e;</HI> are full in their Applications of the P&s;alm to the <HI>M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;&s;iah.</HI> Yea, according to the <HI>Chaldee,</HI> in the P&s;alm now before us, the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> is GOD; and in the LIII. of <HI>I&s;aiah,</HI> the Me&s;&s;iah is <HI>Man.</HI> Wonder|ful! O <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> How does thy Religion triumph over its Adver&s;aries!</P>
<P>The P&s;alm is called, <HI>A Song of De&s;ires.</HI> R. <HI>David</HI> &s;ays, The whole World will rejoyce at the coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> becau&s;e all the Nations have <HI>de&s;ired</HI> it. Compare, <HI>Hag.</HI> II. 7. Con&s;ider, <HI>Rom.</HI> VIII. 19. The &s;ame Word u&s;ed by the LXX, in <HI>Gen.</HI> XLIX. 10. Is not the Name of <HI>Jedidiah</HI> here alluded to?</P>
<P N="1">1 A Writer of <HI>Short</HI> Hand. <HI>An ba&s;ty Writer,</HI> as R. <HI>Obadiah Gaon</HI> expre&s;&s;es it, <HI>Qui principia Vocum &s;olummodo tran&s;cribit.</HI> q. d. I'll only be&s;tow a touch or Two in a contracted manner, on the <HI>Beginning</HI> of the matter.</P>
<P N="4">4 The Pro&s;pering of the Kingdom is to be by the planting of all <HI>Vertue</HI> among the Subjects of it. Our SAVIOUR goes forth as a Conquerour, not in taking of <HI>Spoils,</HI> or making of <HI>Slaves;</HI> but in Settling of the <HI>True Faith</HI> among them, and making of them to be <HI>Meck, Mode&s;t, Humble, Righteous,</HI> and <HI>Charitable.</HI> For this purpo&s;e He did <HI>Miraculous</HI> things, <HI>Luk.</HI> IV. 36. and V. 26. And then, as <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> adds <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>In&s;edit Apoll <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> veluti Equo.</HI></P>
<P N="8"><PB N="111" REF="001946_0148_0FFCB102509A4268">
8 The Super-eminent Gifts of our SAVIOUR cau&s;e an inexpre&s;sible <HI>Gladne&s;s,</HI> among His People and Sub|jects. Compare the <HI>Joy</HI> expre&s;s'd, when <HI>Solomon</HI> was <HI>Anointed,</HI> and preferred before <HI>his Brethron,</HI> 1 Kin. I. 39, 40.</P>
<P>If <HI>Solomons</HI> Wedding Garments were perfumed, much more &s;hall there be a &s;weet Odour in the Knowledge of CHRIST, when He comes to F&s;pou&s;e His People. See, 2 <HI>Cor.</HI> II. 14, 15, 16. But, Behold what was li|terally done to the Garments of our SAVIOUR! Con|&s;ider, <HI>Job.</HI> XIX. 30. <HI>Mark</HI> XVI. 1. <HI>Luk.</HI> XXIV. 1. Our SAVIOUR was <HI>made Glad,</HI> in His <HI>not &s;eeing of Corruption.</HI></P>
<P N="9">9 R. <HI>Obadiah Gaon,</HI> wittily Fxpounds the <HI>Kings Daughters</HI> to be, <HI>Op<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">niones &s;apientum Nationum Ex|terarum.</HI> The Opinions of the <HI>Wi&s;er Gentiles,</HI> are but &s;o many <HI>Confe&s;&s;ions</HI> of the true Religion; &s;o many Atten|dants on the Church of GOD. <HI>Lactantius</HI> affirms of the&s;e, That if any one would make a fair Collection of them, <HI>Is profecto non di&s;&s;entiret a nobis.</HI></P>
<P N="16">16 <HI>Arnobius</HI> here finds the <HI>Apo&s;tles</HI> coming in the room o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> the <HI>Patriarchs.</HI> By their means, the Church brings forth Children unto CHRIST, whom He makes <HI>Kings</HI> and <HI>Prie&s;ts</HI> unto GOD, and they &s;hall <HI>Reign upon the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">arth.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="46" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XLVI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. For the Sons of Korah. Upon Alamoth.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 GOD is a Refuge unto us, &Verbar; and fortify|ing &s;trength; &Verbar; and help in troubles which we have &Verbar; in great abundance found. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Therefore we will not be afraid, &Verbar; al|tho' the Earthdo &s;hake; &Verbar; and tho' the moun|tains be remov'd &Verbar; to the mid&s;t of the Seas. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Thereof the waters, let them roat; &Verbar;
<PB N="112" REF="001946_0149_0FFCB7C19214A598">and let them be di&s;turb'd; &Verbar; and let the mountains tremble for &Verbar; the raging &s;well thereof. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 A River's <HI>here;</HI> the &s;treams whereof &Verbar; rejoyce the City of God; &Verbar; the Holy place where the Mo&s;t High &Verbar; has Habitations cho&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 God is within the mid&s;t of her; &Verbar; &s;he &s;ha'n't feel any &s;hake; &Verbar; God &s;hall &s;end help to her, when that &Verbar; the Morning does ap|proach. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The Nations rag'd, the Kingdoms were &Verbar; in great Commotions roil'd; &Verbar; He did give forth His thundring Voice; &Verbar; the Earth was all di&s;&s;olv'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Th' ETERNAL God of Armies grants &Verbar; His pre&s;ence unto us; &Verbar; The God of Jacob is for us &Verbar; a lofty Citadel. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O come, Confider well the Works &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; who hath made de|&s;olations be &Verbar; upon the watted Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Unto the Borders of the Farth &Verbar; He maketh Wars to cea&s;e; &Verbar; He breaks the bow and cutts the &s;pear, &Verbar; Chariots He burns in fire. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Be &s;till and know that I am GOD, &Verbar; among the Nations I &Verbar; will be exalted; and will be &Verbar; exalted in the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Th' ETERNAL God of Armies grants &Verbar; His Pre&s;ence unto us; &Verbar; the God of Jacob is for us &Verbar; a lofty Citadel. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="113" REF="001946_0150_0FFCB104A99629F8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XLVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the Happine&s;s of re&s;tored <HI>I&s;rael!</HI> Com|pare the Ninth Ver&s;e, with <HI>I&s;a.</HI> II. 4.</P>
<P N="4">4 Take the <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e. <Q>Our Hearts &s;hall be quiet and &s;till; like the <HI>River</HI> that runs through our <HI>City,</HI> from whence the Inhabitants draw by Trenches, delightful Streams to Water their Gar|dens. &mdash;The &s;mall Forces that guard this place, which make no more noi&s;e than tho&s;e Waters, [<HI>I&s;ai.</HI> VIII. 6, 7.] &s;hall by the help of God, who in a &s;pecial manner dwelleth here; be too hard for the greate&s;t Armies; which in their Number, and their Boa&s;ts, imitate the Waves of the raging Sea.</Q></P>
<P>But after all; The intention of the <HI>Holy Spirit</HI> here will not be under&s;tood, if the <HI>Holy Spirit</HI> Him&s;elf be not under&s;tood. HE is the <HI>River;</HI> His Effu&s;ions will be wonderful!</P>
<P N="6">6 The <HI>horrible Tempe&s;t</HI> by which the <HI>A&s;&s;yrian</HI> Camp fell under &s;uch De&s;olations, was a notable Ful|filment of this Pa&s;&s;age.</P>
<P>But, if I dont mi&s;remember, &s;ome of the Ancients have l<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">d me here to con&s;ider what I read. Matth. XXVII. 50, 51. Behold, <HI>God uttereth His Voice</HI> and the <HI>Earth melteth.</HI></P>
<P N="10">10 Old <HI>Raymund</HI> in his <HI>Pugio fidei,</HI> firds a Direction for a <HI>Sabbath</HI> here. It may be rendred <HI>Sabbatize.</HI> Yea, the <HI>Great Sabbati&s;m</HI> now arrives.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="47" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XLVII.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm for the Sons of Korah.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O All ye People, every one, &Verbar; Clap ye your hands for joy; &Verbar; with a loud voice of triumph make &Verbar; a joyful &s;hout to God.</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="114" REF="001946_0151_0FFCB7C3164F45F0">
2 For the ETERNAL God mo&s;t High, &Verbar; is greatly to be fear'd; &Verbar; He as a King mag|nificent &Verbar; reigns over all the Earth, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 He &s;hall even with His Word &s;ubdue &Verbar; the People under us; &Verbar; and <HI>He &s;hall bring</HI> the Nations to &Verbar; lye pro&s;trate at our feet. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 He &s;hall make choice for us, what &s;hall &Verbar; be our Inheritance; &Verbar; <HI>Even</HI> the Excellency of &Verbar; Jacob, whom He has lov'd. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 God is gone up <HI>unto His Place</HI> &Verbar; with a triumphant &s;hout; &Verbar; Th' ETERNAL God is thither with &Verbar; the Trumpet &s;ounding gone. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Sing Prai&s;es to <HI>the Glorious</HI> God; &Verbar; &s;ing Prai&s;es <HI>yet again;</HI> &Verbar; &s;ing Prai&s;es unto Him our King; &Verbar; &s;ing Prai&s;es unto Him, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Becau&s;e <HI>the Glorious</HI> God is now &Verbar; the King in all the Earth; &Verbar; O &s;ing ye Prai&s;es unto Him, &Verbar; each under&s;tanding one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 <HI>The Glorious</HI> God does as a King &Verbar; over the Nations Reign: &Verbar; <HI>The Glorious</HI> God &s;its King upon &Verbar; His Throne of Holine&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 The Princes of the People do &Verbar; in a Convention meet; &Verbar; They do become the People of &Verbar; the God of Abraham. &Verbar; Becau&s;e that they who are Shields &Verbar; for to defend the Earth, &Verbar; belong to God, He therefore is &Verbar; exalted very high. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XLVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the Triumph of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> when He has e&s;tabli&s;h'd His Kingdom among the Nations!</P>
<P N="9"><PB N="115" REF="001946_0152_0FFCB109DCB073B0">
9 W<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">y, <HI>The People of the God of Abraham?</HI> There <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> a noble Empha&s;is in it. <HI>Abrabam</HI> was to be the <HI>F<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">her of many Nations.</HI> The <HI>God of Abraham</HI> is the God of the <HI>Gentiles,</HI> as well as of the <HI>Jews.</HI> The C<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">nverted <HI>Gentiles</HI> are now to Glorify God. The Relig<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">n of <HI>Abraham</HI> (not what the Sects of the Orient call &s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> but what is really &s;uch) will now be the Re|ligion of the Nations.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="48" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XLVIII.</HI> A Song. A P&s;alm for the Sons of Korah.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 GReat art Thou, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; and greatly to be prais'd &Verbar; in th' City of our God, in the &Verbar; Mount of His Holine&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Mount Zion, a mo&s;t lovely Seat, &Verbar; the Joy of all the Earth; &Verbar; On the North &s;ides whereof there does &Verbar; the Great Kings City lie. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 God in her Palaces is known &Verbar; for an high Citadel. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 For lo, the Kings a&s;&s;embled there; &Verbar; they pa&s;&s;ed by together. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 They &s;aw; then wondred; they were &s;car'd; &Verbar; a terror &s;eiz'd on them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Fear &s;eiz'd upon them there; a Pain &Verbar; of Women in their Pangs. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 The Ships of Tar&s;hi&s;h thou do&s;t break &Verbar; with a fierce Ea&s;tern Wind. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 According to what we have heard &Verbar; &s;o is what we have &s;een; &Verbar; In th' City of th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; to whom <HI>all</HI> Ho&s;ts belong; &Verbar;
<PB N="116" REF="001946_0153_0FFCB110B31E49D8">In th' City of our God; God will &Verbar; ever e&s;tabli&s;h it. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 With quiet meditation we &Verbar; have had our tho'ts, O God, &Verbar; in the mid&s;t of thy Temple, on &Verbar; thy kind benignity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 According to thy Name, O God, &Verbar; &s;o is thy Prai&s;e unto &Verbar; the Earth's la&s;t Borders; thy Right hand &Verbar; is full of Right'ou&s;ne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Becau&s;e of thy right Judgments now &Verbar; Mount Zion &s;hall rejoyce; &Verbar; the Daughters too of Judah &s;hall &Verbar; triumph with glorious Joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 All about Zion walk ye round, &Verbar; and round encompa&s;s her; &Verbar; Account the num|ber of her Towers, &Verbar; <HI>to &s;ee what &s;tate they're in.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Apply your mind unto the Wall &Verbar; that has defended her; &Verbar; Ob&s;erve her Palaces, that ye &Verbar; may tell the Age to come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 For this God is our God; He's &s;o &Verbar; to all Eternity; &Verbar; and He will be a guide for us &Verbar; to Death, and* over it. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XIVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>WHY may not the P&s;alm refer to the Hi&s;tory in, 2 <HI>Chron.</HI> XX. The Coming of the Kings a|gain&s;t <HI>Jeho&s;aphat,</HI> with an intention to fall upon <HI>Je|ru&s;alem?</HI> The more <HI>Prophetic Seers,</HI> here behold the Ruin of the <HI>Turks,</HI> when they come to a&s;&s;ault the <HI>I&s;raelites,</HI> after they return into their Country; And &s;uppo&s;e it explain'd in the XXXVIII, and XXXIX of <HI>Ezekiel.</HI></P>
<P N="2"><PB N="117" REF="001946_0154_0FFCB10E5A9FFAA0">
2 <HI>Pliny</HI> de&s;cribing &s;ome of the mo&s;t eminent <HI>Cities</HI> in the World, yet prefers <HI>Jeru&s;alem;</HI> calling it, <HI>Longo clari&s;&s;imans Urb<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">um Orientis.</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 Such was their Con&s;ternation, that it &s;urpriz'd them, not only as Angui&s;h does a <HI>Woman in Travail;</HI> but al&s;o as <HI>Mariners,</HI> when a Fleet of Ships richly laden from <HI>Tar&s;hi&s;h,</HI> is broken in pieces. Whether <HI>Jeho&s;haphat</HI> improved his Deliverance with due Thank|fulne&s;s or no, yet quickly after this, he had a Fleet exactly in this Condition. [2 <HI>Chron.</HI> XX. 37.]</P>
<P N="10">10 Particularly that Name, <HI>The Lord of Ho&s;ts.</HI></P>
<P N="12">12 See, if there be &s;o much as one wanting.</P>
