<DIV2 N="49" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XLIX.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm for the Sons of Korah.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BE&s;tow an hearing upon this, &Verbar; ye Peo|ple every one; &Verbar; Hearken all you In|habitants &Verbar; upon a tran&s;ient World. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>Yea, bear,</HI> ye Sons of meaner Men, &Verbar; and Sons of higher too; &Verbar; Let the Rich Man <HI>at|tend to this,</HI> &Verbar; together with the Poor. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 My mouth &s;hall &s;peak of things that have &Verbar; a wi&s;dom manifold; &Verbar; and my hearts meditation &s;hall &Verbar; yield many prudent things. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 I will incline mine ear unto &Verbar; a mo&s;t in&s;tructive &s;peech; &Verbar; I will upon the harp explain &Verbar; my &s;peech that &s;eems ob&s;cure. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 In days of evil why &s;hould I &Verbar; be anxi|ou&s;ly afraid; &Verbar; <HI>the days,</HI> when of my heels the Sin &Verbar; does compa&s;s me about. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 There are tho&s;e who do place their hope &Verbar;
<PB N="118" REF="001946_0155_0FFCB7C5334AB108">upon their &s;trengthning Wealth; &Verbar; and in the multitude of their &Verbar; Riches do boa&s;t them&s;elves. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 There is no Man <HI>of them</HI> that can &Verbar; by any means redeem &Verbar; his Brother, nor give unto God &Verbar; a price to ran&s;ome him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 For the Redemption of their Soul &Verbar; is of a weighty price; &Verbar; and it remains unfini&s;hed &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 <HI>For this,</HI> that he &s;hould always live &Verbar; to perpetuity; &Verbar; that he &s;hould never &s;ee the pit &Verbar; wherein corruption lies. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 For he may &s;ee that wi&s;e Men dye; &Verbar; &s;o does the fooli&s;h Man &Verbar; and bruiti&s;h peri&s;h; and their Wealth &Verbar; they leave to other Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 What is within them is <HI>this Thought,</HI> &Verbar; Their hou&s;es ever will &Verbar; endure; their Ta|bernacles will &Verbar; endure from age to age. &Verbar; Their own Names <HI>for that cau&s;e</HI> they do &Verbar; impo&s;e upon their Lands. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 But notwith&s;tanding all of this, &Verbar; <HI>look back on what is pa&s;t.</HI> &Verbar; Man in bright excel|lency plac'd &Verbar; continu'd not a Night; &Verbar; un|der dominion he did fall &Verbar; even like the peri&s;hing bea&s;ts. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Egregious folly unto them &Verbar; this way of theirs does prove; &Verbar; yet their Po&s;terity walk on &Verbar; in that which they have &s;aid. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 They are like Sheep laid in the Grave; &Verbar;
<PB N="119" REF="001946_0156_0FFCB125A696E418">upon them Death &s;hall feed; &Verbar; and over them the upright ones &Verbar; &s;hall a dominion have, &Verbar; when the bright morning &s;hall arrive; &Verbar; then &s;hall their Rock de&s;cend, &Verbar; Death to de&s;troy; He then &s;hall from &Verbar; His Habitation come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 But from the power of the pit &Verbar; God &s;hall redeem my Soul; &Verbar; <HI>This He will do,</HI> becau&s;e He will &Verbar;, receive me to Him&s;elf. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 When that a Man grows Wealthy, then &Verbar; be not concern'd <HI>at it;</HI> &Verbar; when that the glory of his hou&s;e &Verbar; is greatly multiply'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 For at his Death he &s;hall not take &Verbar; any of it with him; &Verbar; nor &s;hall the glory which he had &Verbar; de&s;cend then after him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Tho' in his Life he did proclaim &Verbar; his Soul a ble&s;&s;ed one; &Verbar; and other Men will prai&s;e thee when &Verbar; thou do&s;t befriend thy &s;elf. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 <HI>O dying Man,</HI> Thou &s;halt unto &Verbar; the Generation go &Verbar; of them that were thy An|ce&s;tors; &Verbar; Light they &s;hall never &s;ee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Man who in honour is advanc'd, &Verbar; and does not under&s;tand, &Verbar; under dominion &s;uch an one &Verbar; falls like the peri&s;hing bea&s;ts. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XLIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the folly of them who think, that a <HI>Re&s;ur|rection from the Dead,</HI> was not promi&s;ed or ex|pected under the Old Te&s;tament The <HI>Fir&s;t Re&s;ur|rection</HI> is here plainly pointed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="120" REF="001946_0157_0FFCB147E95D7658">
5 The <HI>Talmud,</HI> by <HI>the Iniquity of the heel,</HI> under|&s;tands the <HI>Iniquity,</HI> which Man in this World makes light of, and even tramples under foot. Some of the Ancients carried it &s;o, <HI>Homines iniqui c<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">roumdant calcaneum meum.</HI> But con&s;ider the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> &s;peaking here; and the Ancient prediction of His <HI>Heel brui&s;ed</HI> for the <HI>Iniquity</HI> of His People. <HI>Aben-Ezna</HI> takes the <HI>Iniquities of the Heels,</HI> to be the <HI>Iniquities of ill|gotten Riches;</HI> whereof, <HI>Peccatum &s;equitur<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">qua&s;i in calce, et non videtur. Arnobius</HI> has a good Admoni|tion; <HI>Hoe &s;olum tremendum e&s;t omnibus, ne in &s;ine &s;uo Iniquitate &s;ua capiantur. Patrick's</HI> Paraphra&s;e is, <HI>The Iniquity of tho&s;e that endeavour to &s;upplant me.</HI></P>
<P N="8">8 The <HI>Redemption.</HI>] The <HI>Chaldee</HI> under&s;tands it, for the <HI>Vengeance</HI> pur&s;ued upon the Soul; when the <HI>Ran&s;ome</HI> is paid for it, that now <HI>cea&s;eth forever.</HI></P>
<P N="11">11 <HI>Inward thot's,</HI> are tho&s;e that ari&s;e meerly from the <HI>Inward Principles,</HI> Di&s;po&s;itions and Inclinations of Men, and that are not &s;ugge&s;ted and excited from <HI>Outward Objects.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Ditto.</HI> Compare Gen. IV. 17. The Jewi&s;h Rablins interpret it, with the mention of <HI>Alexandria,</HI> of <HI>An|tioch,</HI> and of <HI>Tiberias.</HI></P>
<P N="12">12 Some read it, <HI>Adam continued not a Night in Excellency.</HI> What became of him? <HI>Alting</HI> ob&s;erves, That the Word <HI>Ma&s;hal,</HI> &s;ignifies not only <HI>Similitude,</HI> but al&s;o <HI>Dominion.</HI> And if it be not &s;o taken here, the Particle, <HI>Caph,</HI> before <HI>Bea&s;ts,</HI> will be &s;uperfluous.&mdash; Who&s;e <HI>Dominion?</HI> But that of <HI>Satan,</HI> the horrible Tempter.</P>
<P N="14">14 The Hebrew Word <HI>Phadah,</HI> to <HI>Redeem,</HI> is of the &s;ame Importance with the Arabic, <HI>Feda, To devote ones &s;elf to Death.</HI> A Glorious Truth! Our Lord <HI>Redeems</HI> us, by devoting Him&s;elf to <HI>Death</HI> for us.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="50" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="121" REF="001946_0158_0FFCB1460F79B738">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM L.</HI> A P&s;alm of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 THE God of God's, th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; hath &s;poke, and call'd the Earth, &Verbar; ev'n from the ri&s;ing of the Sun, &Verbar; unto its going down. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 From Zion wholly beautiful God &s;ends a lu&s;tre forth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Our God &s;hall come and He &s;hall not &Verbar; keep &s;ilence any more. &Verbar; Before His Face a wa&s;ting Fire &Verbar; &s;hall dreadfully devour, &Verbar; and round about him it &s;hall be &Verbar; very tem|pe&s;tuous. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 He &s;hall give out His call unto &Verbar; the Heavens from above; &Verbar; and <HI>He &s;hall call</HI> unto the Earth, &Verbar; to judge His People <HI>there.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 A&s;&s;emble ye His gracious ones &Verbar; together unto me, &Verbar; tho&s;e that have made a Covenant &Verbar; with me by Sacrifice. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The Heavens al&s;o &s;hall declare &Verbar; abroad His Right'ou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; Becau&s;e <HI>the Glorious</HI> God Him&s;elf <HI>in Per&s;on</HI> &s;hall be Judge. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Hear, O my People, and I'll &s;peak, &Verbar; <HI>Give ear, O</HI> I&s;rael; &Verbar; and unto thee I'll te&s;tify; &Verbar; I'm GOD, I am thy GOD.</P>
<P N="8">8 Upon thy Sacrifices I give no Reproofs to thee, &Verbar; for thy Burnt-Off<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">rings have been &s;till &Verbar; before me evermore. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 <HI>Knore that</HI> a Bullock I will not &Verbar; out of thy hou&s;e accept: &Verbar; He-goars <HI>for Off<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ings I will not</HI> eart of thy Fold; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ecei<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">.</P>
<P N="10"><PB N="122" REF="001946_0159_0FFCB7C6DD07EA50">
10 For every Bea&s;t throughout the Wood &Verbar; I as my own do claim; &Verbar; the Cattle which are on the Hills &Verbar; by thou&s;ands in a drove. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 The Fowls that on the Mountains fly, &Verbar; I know them every one; &Verbar; and the wild Bea&s;ts that range the fields &Verbar; I ever have at hand. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 If I were hungry I would not &Verbar; declare it unto thee; &Verbar; For that the World is mine, and &s;o &Verbar; is all that filleth it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Do&s;t thou imagine</HI> I &s;hall feed &Verbar; upon the fle&s;h of Bulls; &Verbar; or that I &s;hall, <HI>to quench my thir&s;t</HI> &Verbar; drink up the blood of Goats. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Confe&s;&s;ing, offer unto God &Verbar; a Sacrifice of Prai&s;e; &Verbar; and pay unto the mo&s;t High One &Verbar; the Vows which thou ha&s;t made. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 And call upon me in the day &Verbar; when trouble comes on thee; &Verbar; I will deliver thee and thou &Verbar; &s;halt glorify me then. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 But to the Wicked God hath &s;aid, &Verbar; What claim'&s;t thou to declare &Verbar; my Statutes, or my Covenant &Verbar; tak'&s;t thou into thy mouth? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 For as for thee, thou do&s;t but hate &Verbar; to be in&s;tructed well; &Verbar; and thou do&s;t ca&s;t with all contempt &Verbar; my words behind thy back. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 When thou ha&s;t &s;een a Thief thou ha&s;t &Verbar; gladly concurr'd with him; &Verbar; and with A|dulterers thou ha&s;t &Verbar; cho&s;en to have thy part. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Thou to thy mouth ha&s;t given a loo&s;e &Verbar; for evil purpo&s;es; &Verbar; and thy Tongue artfully contrives &Verbar; <HI>to carry on</HI> deceit.</P>
<P N="20"><PB N="123" REF="001946_0160_0FFCB16E2DF050A0">
20 Thou on thy &s;eat do&s;t &s;peak again&s;t &Verbar; thy Brother <HI>wrongfully</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> thou do&s;t give out a &s;tand<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">rous lye<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> again&s;t thy Mothers Son. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 The&s;e things thou did&s;t, &amp; I was dumb; thou thought<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t me like thy &s;elf; &Verbar; I will reprove thee, and will rank &Verbar; <HI>the&s;e thing,</HI> before thine Eyes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Con&s;ider now this, you that are, for|getful of a God; &Verbar; Le&s;t I tear you to pe<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ces and there's none to re&s;cue you. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 He glorify's me, who does bring an Offering of Prai&s;e: &Verbar; And unto him who takes the way &Verbar; I'll God's Salvation &s;hew. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the L. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, the Return of the <HI>Jews,</HI> with a Correction of their mi&s;take, in placing Religion only in Sa|crifices. Behold, then a Condemnation pa&s;s'd on the followers of Antichri&s;t.</P>
<P N="1">1 The Name of GOD occurring three times may &s;eem a &s;weet Indigitation of the Trinity. In the <HI>Midra&s;h Tillin</HI> there is what looks very like a Confe&s;|&s;ion of it:</P>
<P N="2">2 According to the <HI>Chaldee</HI> 'tis not <HI>Zion,</HI> but GOD the Me&s;&s;iah, who is here call'd <HI>The perfection of Beauty.</HI></P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Ju&s;tin Martyr</HI> and <HI>Origen,</HI> and many mo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">e, a&s;&s;ure us, The Heathens were of Opinion, that their Gods were <HI>nouri&s;hed,</HI> and therefore al&s;o <HI>delighted,</HI> with the &s;umes and &s;teams of the <HI>Sacrifices</HI> offered unto them.</P>
<P N="23">23 May not here be &s;ome Eye to the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah?</HI>
<PB N="124" REF="001946_0161_0FFCB18A085B34B8">Prai&s;e is a Name of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> He is the <HI>Prai&s;e of I&s;rael.</HI> God inhabits Him. He is the great One of <HI>Judah,</HI> who is to be <HI>Prai&s;ed.</HI> The Original here is. <HI>He that Sacrificeth Prai&s;e.</HI> Our Me&s;&s;iah <HI>Glorified</HI> God infinitely, when He pre&s;ented him&s;elf a <HI>Sacrifice</HI> unto God. We never <HI>glorify</HI> GOD &s;o much as when we fly to and lean on that <HI>Sacrifice.</HI></P>
<P>I find one who &s;o reads it, <HI>One Sacrificing Prai&s;e &s;hall glorify me.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="51" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician; a P&s;alm of David, when <HI>Nathan</HI> the Prophet came unto him, after he had gone in to Bath&s;heba.</HEAD>
<P N="1">HAve Mercy upon me, O God, &Verbar; <HI>[even]</HI> according to thy Grace: &Verbar; As thy Compa&s;&s;ions are mo&s;t large, &Verbar; <HI>[do thou]</HI> blot out my Tre&s;pa&s;&s;es. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O multiply my Wa&s;hing from &Verbar; <HI>[all of]</HI> my Vile Iniquity; &Verbar; And O make me en|tirely clean &Verbar; from <HI>[all of]</HI> my defiling Sin. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Since I do of my Tre&s;pa&s;s make &Verbar; a Free <HI>[and full]</HI> ackowledgment; &Verbar; and I continually have &Verbar; my <HI>[horrid]</HI> Sin before my Eyes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 To thee, To thee alone I've finn'd, &Verbar; and done ill in thy View <HI>[alone;]</HI> &Verbar; That when thou &s;peak&s;t thou may&s;t be ju&s;t, &Verbar; and <HI>[may'&s;t be]</HI> pure when thou do&s;t judge. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Behold, 'twas in Iniquity &Verbar; that I <HI>[at fir&s;t]</HI> receiv'd my Shape; &Verbar; and 'twas in Sin my Mother did &Verbar; <HI>[at fir&s;t]</HI> conceive me as her Child. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="125" REF="001946_0162_0FFCB188859E8D88">
6 Behold, Thou do&s;t de&s;ire the Truth &Verbar; <HI>[to be]</HI> in the mo&s;t inward parts; &Verbar; and thou wilt make me under&s;tand &Verbar; Wi&s;dom in what's conceal'd <HI>[within.]</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 O purge me with the Sprinkler well, &Verbar; and &s;o I &s;hall be <HI>[throughly]</HI> clean; &Verbar; O Wa&s;h thou me, and then &s;hall I &Verbar; be whit|er than the <HI>[white&s;t]</HI> Snow. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Make me to hear that which will be &Verbar; Gladne&s;s and <HI>[Glorious]</HI> Joy to me: &Verbar; The Bones which thou ha&s;t broken quite, &Verbar; O let them yet <HI>[again]</HI> rejoice. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 From the beholding of my Sins &Verbar; <HI>[kindly]</HI> hide thou away thy face; &Verbar; and all of my Iniquities &Verbar; <HI>[wholly]</HI> do thou obliterate. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 O God, Create in me an heart &Verbar; that &s;hall be <HI>[judged]</HI> throughly clean; &Verbar; and in the mid&s;t of me do thou &Verbar; renew a Spirit right <HI>[and firm.]</HI></P>
<P N="11">11 From &s;tanding &s;till before thy face &Verbar; O ca&s;t me not <HI>[in Wrath]</HI> away: &Verbar; Thine holy Spirit <HI>now</HI> from me &Verbar; away <HI>[there|fore]</HI> O take thou not. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Re&s;tore thou unto me the Joy &Verbar; of thy <HI>[de&s;ir'd]</HI> Salvation now; &Verbar; and let a Spirit free * and high &Verbar; gloriou&s;ly <HI>[lead and]</HI> &s;trengthen me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Unto Tran&s;gre&s;&s;ors I will give &Verbar; In|&s;tructions in thy <HI>[Righteous]</HI> Wayes; &Verbar;
<PB N="126" REF="001946_0163_0FFCB1C7A6AB3B20">and they who have been &s;inners &s;hall &Verbar; be <HI>[real]</HI> Converts unto thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 O God, O my Salvations God; &Verbar; De|liver me from <HI>[crying]</HI> Bloods: &Verbar; My Tongue then of thy Righteou&s;ne&s;s &Verbar; &s;hall openly proclaim <HI>[and &s;ing.]</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Lord, <HI>who art my Support,</HI> Do thou &Verbar; Open the&s;e <HI>[clo&s;ed]</HI> Lips of mine: &Verbar; and then my mouth with freedom &s;hall &Verbar; declare thy <HI>[glorious]</HI> prai&s;e abroad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 For thou de&s;ir'&s;t not Sacrifice, &Verbar; el&s;e had I <HI>[freely]</HI> given it; &Verbar; Thou do&s;t not take delight at all &Verbar; in a <HI>[common]</HI> Burnt-Offering. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 The Sacrifices own'd by God &Verbar; are <HI>in</HI> a broken Spirit [<HI>found;</HI> &Verbar;] An heart that's broken and contrite, &Verbar; O <HI>[Gracious]</HI> God, Thoul't not de&s;pi&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 In thy good plea&s;ure, O do thou &Verbar; do good to <HI>[threatned]</HI> Zion <HI>too;</HI> &Verbar; and O do thou build up the Walls &Verbar; of both <HI>[thy own]</HI> Jeru&s;alems. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Then thou with plea&s;ure wilt receive &Verbar; the <HI>[grateful]</HI> &s;acrifices which &Verbar; are to be reckon'd requi&s;ite &Verbar; unto true <HI>[and full]</HI> Rightcon&s;de&s;s. &Verbar; Burnt-offerings <HI>thou wilt then receive,</HI> &Verbar; and <HI>[even]</HI> whole Burnt-of|frings too; &Verbar; Then they &s;hall offer Bullocks on &Verbar; the <HI>[Sacred]</HI> Altar claim'd by thee. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="127" REF="001946_0164_0FFCB19F1ECC8198">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the <HI>Jews</HI> con&s;e&s;&s;ing their Murder of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah:</HI> [Compare I&s;a. 1 15 16.] And entreat|ing for a return of the Gifts, whereof they have been long depriv'd; and engaging to publi&s;h the Mercy of God among the Nations.</P>
<P>The Eighteenth Ver&s;e points to a time wherein <HI>Jeru&s;alem</HI> lies de&s;olate.</P>
<P N="3">3 What if, <HI>Sin,</HI> &s;hould here mean al&s;o <HI>Sin offering?</HI></P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>To thee alone</HI>] It means, as <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> glo&s;&s;es, <HI>In occulto foci.</HI> None but God &s;aw the Sin. <HI>David</HI> might now call to mind the Words of the Proplet. 2 Sam. 11 17. <HI>Thou did&s;t it &s;ecretly.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Be ju&s;t.</HI>] <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> would have the&s;e clau&s;es refer, not unto the next foregoing, but unto that, <HI>clean&s;e me from my Sin.</HI> The plea, is, That &s;o there may be found a <HI>Truth</HI> in the promi&s;es of Mercy and Par|don to the repenting &s;inner.</P>
<P N="6">6 Sin aggravated from a Principle of better motions in us.</P>
<P>But can we &s;ee nothing of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> here&mdash; That He &s;hould be thus in <HI>David</HI>'s Loins after he had been thus polluted!</P>
<P N="7">7 Impure as a <HI>Leper!</HI>&mdash;Far more unclean by touching <HI>Bath&s;hebah,</HI> than one could be in touching a Dead Body.</P>
<P>I chu&s;e to &s;ay, <HI>The Sprinkler;</HI> Becau&s;e I &s;u&s;pect <HI>Hy&s;&s;op</HI> was not the plant u&s;ed on the Occa&s;ion referr'd to, but <HI>Ro&s;emary.</HI></P>
<P N="11">11 Has not the P&s;almi&s;t the Condition of his Prede|ce&s;&s;or, <HI>Saul,</HI> in his Fye?</P>
<P N="16">16 For &s;ome Atrocious Crimes [like <HI>Davids</HI>] there was no <HI>Sacrifice</HI> directed or allowed in the Law of <HI>Mo&s;es.</HI> But now &s;ee Acts XIII. 39. <HI>All that believe are ju&s;tified from all things.</HI></P>
<P N="17">17 The Sacrifices were fir&s;t out in pieces (not man|gled
<PB N="128" REF="001946_0165_0FFCB1C5E1A17388">but Jointed.) That was their <HI>Breaking.</HI> They were then burnt to A&s;hes. That was their <HI>Con|trition.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Repentance</HI> has in it &s;omething Analogous.</P>
<P>But let us away, to our glorious <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> as often as we can! The &s;pecial Character which the Oracles of God put on the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> coming to be a Sacrifice for &s;in, is that of <HI>The Brui&s;ed One.</HI> Yea, the very fir&s;t time that ever the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> was mention'd in the World, His being <HI>Brui&s;ed</HI> was the main thing &s;poken of. Be&s;ure the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> was one of a <HI>Broken Spirit, a Broken and a Contrite Heart.</HI> Never &s;uch <HI>heart breaking</HI> things undergone by any one! At la&s;t his very <HI>Spirit</HI> was <HI>broken</HI> from his <HI>Body;</HI> the <HI>Vital Union</HI> was <HI>broken.</HI> Behold the <HI>Sacrifice</HI> which the P&s;almi&s;t has his Eye and his Hope upon.</P>
<P N="18">18 <HI>Both Jeru&s;alems</HI>] The Name <HI>Jeru&s;alem,</HI> is of the <HI>Dual</HI> Number; not without a My&s;tery!</P>
<P>The P&s;alm expires not, before it is evident, that the <HI>Spirit of Prophecy,</HI> which he had pray'd for, was re|turned unto him. It ends with a <HI>Prophecy.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="52" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LII.</HI> To the cheif Mu&s;ician. Ma&s;chil. Of David. When Do<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">g the Edomite came and told Soul, and &s;aid unto him, David is come to the Hou&s;e of Ahi|melech.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 IN Mi&s;chief, O thou mighty Man, &Verbar; why do&s;t thou boa&s;t thy &s;elf? &Verbar; The Mercy of a Mighty God &Verbar; endures continually. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Thy Tongue devi&s;eth things of a &Verbar; Pernicious Tendency; &Verbar; It is like a Sharp Razour; it &Verbar; &s;till works deceitfully. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="129" REF="001946_0166_0FFCB1C45EE81048">
3 Thou love&s;t evil more than good; &Verbar; more to &s;peak fal&s;e than right. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Thou love&s;t all devouring Words, &Verbar; O thou deceitful Tongue. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 And God upon thee &s;hall inflict &Verbar; end|le&s;s De&s;truction too; &Verbar; He &s;hall take thee away, and pull &Verbar; thee from thy dwelling-place. &Verbar; Yea, He &s;hall extirpate thee from &Verbar; the Land of Living Ones. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The Ju&s;t &s;hall al&s;o &s;ee and fear, &Verbar; and they &s;hall laught at him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Behold the Man who made not God &Verbar; his &s;trength, but tru&s;ted in &Verbar; his mighty Riches, and grew &s;trong &Verbar; in's Wealthy wickedne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 But I am in the Hou&s;e of God &Verbar; like a green Olive Tree; &Verbar; I have had in the Grace of God &Verbar; my everla&s;ting Hope. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Forever I'll prai&s;e thee, becau&s;e &Verbar; this is what thou ha&s;t done; &Verbar; And I'll wait on thy Name, becau&s;e &Verbar; tis good before the Saints. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>CAn't we &s;ee here a Cen&s;ure on the manners of <HI>Antichri&s;t,</HI> and his Party; and a Praediction of his De&s;truction; and the Joy of the faithful upon it?</P>
<P>But <HI>Arnobius</HI> teaches us, to apply the P&s;alm <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ain&s;t the <HI>Dovil. Ip&s;i Diabolo tot<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> ver<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">a h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">jus P&s;al|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> &s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ous in Otatiou<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> cant abis.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 It &s;eems the &s;orry wretch brag'd of what he had
<PB N="130" REF="001946_0167_0FFCB23E4749BCE8">done. The&s;e Words may be an Irony; q. d. A good|ly feat indeed for a Man to boa&s;t of &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 A <HI>Reviling Tongue,</HI> is like a <HI>Razour</HI> for this; 'twill cut every little hair, The &s;malleft pretence of Offences cannot e&s;cape it. But a <HI>Razour</HI> don't wound the Per&s;on. Hence 'tis compared [P&s;alm LVII. 4.] to a <HI>Sword.</HI> It cuts deep into the Credits of Men, and into their Spirits al&s;o. But a Sword will do mi&s;|cheif only <HI>near at hand.</HI> Hence tis compered [P&s;alm LXIV 3.] to an <HI>Arrow.</HI> It hits at a Di&s;tance; does mi&s;cheif a great way off.</P>
<P N="5">5 From the threatning to <HI>pull him from his dwell|ing place,</HI> the Jews have a Tradition of <HI>Doegs</HI> being &s;mitten with a <HI>Lepro&s;y.</HI> Tis the Phra&s;e u&s;ed in that Ca&s;e. Lev. XIV.</P>
<P><HI>Doeg</HI> is paid in the &s;ame Coin, that the <HI>Prie&s;ts of the Lord</HI> had received from him.</P>
<P N="8">8 R. <HI>Obadiah Gaon</HI> has this fine glo&s;s upon it, <HI>In oleum Splendoris, ad illuminandos alios in lege.</HI></P>
<P>The ancient People of God, had their <HI>pro&s;eucha's,</HI> or praying places. [Luk. VI. 12.] Courts open above like the <HI>Forums</HI> of the <HI>Romans.</HI> And they u&s;ually had <HI>Groves</HI> about them, Yea, Trees within them. Dr. <HI>Prideaux</HI> thinks the pa&s;&s;age of an <HI>Olive Tree in the Hou&s;e of God,</HI> may allude unto what was in the&s;e <HI>Pro&s;eucha's.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="53" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LIII.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician; upon Mahalath, Ma&s;chil, of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 THe Fool hath &s;aid within his heart, &Verbar; That there is not a God. &Verbar; <HI>Thus</HI> they corrupt; they do the thing &Verbar; that is abomi|nable. &Verbar; There is not one <HI>among them all</HI> &Verbar; who does the thing that's Good. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="131" REF="001946_0168_0FFCB1E1E309A290">
2 From heaven God who is the Judge &Verbar; looks on the Sons of Men; &Verbar; <HI>He looks</HI> to &s;ee if that there be &Verbar; one who does mind at all &Verbar; to under&s;tand, or, <HI>One who is</HI> &Verbar; a &s;eeker af|ter God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 They're every one declin'd; they are &Verbar; together putrify'd; &Verbar; there is not one doer of good, &Verbar; no, not &s;o much as one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 They that work evil, know they not? &Verbar; They eat my People up &Verbar; as they eat Bread; they do not call &Verbar; on God who is the Judge. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 There they &s;hall be in greivous fear, &Verbar; tho' there's no cau&s;e to fear: &Verbar; For God &s;cat|ters the Bones of him &Verbar; that laies a Seige to thee. &Verbar; Thou &s;halt effectually put &Verbar; them to contemptuous &s;hame; &Verbar; becau&s;e that God hath with contempt &Verbar; utterly ca&s;t them off. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 From Zion who gives I&s;raels health? &Verbar; When the ETERNAL turns &Verbar; his Captive People, Jacob will &Verbar; Joy, I&s;rael will be glad. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>IT is gue&s;&s;ed by <HI>Patrick,</HI> that the Rebellion of <HI>Ab&s;a|lom,</HI> cau&s;ed the complaint in the 14. P&s;alm. And the New Revolt of the <HI>I&s;raelites</HI> under <HI>Sheba,</HI> cau&s;ed this New Edition of it. After <HI>Sheba</HI> was beheaded, it is likely, his Body was expo&s;ed, and his <HI>Bones</HI> were <HI>&s;cattered,</HI> and all his adherents became contemptible.</P>
<P>But what &s;hall we do with the Word <HI>Captivity,</HI> in
<PB N="132" REF="001946_0169_0FFCB1FF5AB2A010">the la&s;t ver&s;e of the P&s;alm? Was the P&s;alm review'd by <HI>A&s;aph</HI> the Seer in the Days of <HI>Hezokiah,</HI> when many of the People were carried into Captivity?</P>
<P>A Prophecy of <HI>Antichri&s;t</HI> here, clears all.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="54" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LIV.</HI> To the chief Mu&s;ician; on Neginoth; Ma&s;ichil. Of David. When the Ziphims came, and &s;aid to Saul, Doth not David hide him&s;elf with us?</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BY thy Name &s;ave thou me, O God &Verbar; and judge me by thy &s;trength. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Hear thou my Prayer, O God; Give ear &Verbar; to the Words of my Mouth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For Strangers have again&s;t me ri&s;'n, &Verbar; and formidable ones &Verbar; pur&s;ued my &s;oul, they have not &s;et &Verbar; God in their view at all. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Behold, the God who's Judge is He &Verbar; who does afford me help; &Verbar; tis the Sup|porting Lord's with tho&s;e &Verbar; who do uphold my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 He &s;hall retaliate evil to &Verbar; my Prying Enemies; &Verbar; Exterminate them utterly &Verbar; as thy Truth calls for it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 With Freedom I will Sacrifice &Verbar; to thee, ETERNAL God; &Verbar; with Prai&s;es I'll adore thy Name, &Verbar; becau&s;e that it is good. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 For out of all adver&s;ity &Verbar; He has deli|ver'd me; &Verbar; mine Eye hath al&s;o &s;een <HI>what comes</HI> &Verbar; upon mine Enemies. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="133" REF="001946_0170_0FFCB1FDC0A12DB8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, a Prayer of the Faithful, under the Per&s;e|cution of <HI>Anti-chri&s;t!</HI></P>
<P><HI>David</HI> was brought into &s;uch a &s;treight that if <HI>Saul</HI> had not been &s;trangely diverted, he could not have e&s;|caped. In this di&s;tre&s;s he made the Prayer in the fir&s;t three ver&s;es of the P&s;alm. Surprized at the Tidings of the Diver&s;ion given to <HI>Saul,</HI> he breaks out into an Admiration of the Divine Goodne&s;s unto him. When the Danger was quite over, he adds the two la&s;t Ver&s;es, from his mountain beholding the retreat of <HI>Saul,</HI> and of his Forces.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="55" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LV.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. On Neginoth. Ma&s;chil; of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 GIve thou a gracious Ear, O God, &Verbar; unto my <HI>righteous</HI> prayer; &Verbar; and from my Supplication now &Verbar; O do not hide thy &s;elf. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O give attention unto me, &Verbar; and hear me graciou&s;ly; &Verbar; I in my &s;ad complaint do mourn, &Verbar; and make a Troublous noi&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 From the Foes voice, from the face of &Verbar; Grief by the wicked one; &Verbar; For fal&s;hood they do ca&s;t on me, &Verbar; and hate me furiou&s;ly. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Within the mid&s;t of me my heart &Verbar; trembles in travailing pain; &Verbar; and there are fallen upon me, &Verbar; the terribles of Death. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Terror with Trepidation hath &Verbar; now much &s;urpri&s;ed me, &Verbar; and horrid Con&s;terna|tion hath &Verbar; quite overwhelmed me, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="134" REF="001946_0171_0FFCB23C71C19838">
6 Then &s;aid I, O! who is't will give &Verbar; Wings of a Dove to me? &Verbar; <HI>with them</HI> I'd &s;wiftly fly away, &Verbar; where I might find a Re&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Behold, I would then make my flight &Verbar; to a va&s;t Di&s;tance off; &Verbar; my Lodging I would make in a &Verbar; <HI>far distant</HI> Wilderne&s;s. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 I would make all the ha&s;te I could &Verbar; in making my e&s;cape, &Verbar; from the impetuous Wind which does &Verbar; ri&s;e with a mighty &s;torm. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Lord, Send De&s;truction upon them; &Verbar; and Oh, divide their Tongues: &Verbar; for in the City I have &s;een &Verbar; fierce Violence and Strife. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Both Day and Night they compa&s;s it, &Verbar; upon the Walls thereof; &Verbar; and trouble&s;ome Iniquity &Verbar; is in the mid&s;t thereof. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Grievous Corruptions full of fraud &Verbar; are in the mid&s;t thereof, &Verbar; and from the Streets thereof Deceit &Verbar; and guile do not Depart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 For it was not an Enemy &Verbar; that has reproached me; &Verbar; For if it had been &s;uch an One, &Verbar; I could have &s;uffer'd it. &Verbar; Nor was it one who hated me &Verbar; that has in&s;ult|ed me; &Verbar; had it been &s;uch an One, I might &Verbar; have hid my &s;elf from him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 But it was thou, O man, whom I &Verbar; E&s;teemed like my &s;elf; &Verbar; 'twas my Informer, and one who &Verbar; was my familiar Friend. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14"><PB N="135" REF="001946_0172_0FFCB215ED4A0A38">
14 We &s;weetly did Communicate &Verbar; &s;e|crets to one another; &Verbar; We walk'd into the Hou&s;e of God &Verbar; in Company together. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Let Death arre&s;t them, let them go &Verbar; down to the Pitt alive; &Verbar; for mi&s;chiefs are where they do meet, &Verbar; even in the mid&s;t of them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 But as for me, <HI>This I will do,</HI> &Verbar; I upon God will call; &Verbar; and the ETERNAL God will give &Verbar; Deliverance to me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Evening and Morning, and at Noon, &Verbar; I meditate for Prayer; &Verbar; &s;o I will make a fervent Cry, &Verbar; and he will hear my Voice. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 He hath delivered my Soul &Verbar; in peace from tho&s;e who made &Verbar; again&s;t me an ho&s;tile approach; &Verbar; for many were with me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 God &s;hall hear, and &s;hall vex them; He, &Verbar; ev'n who &s;its Judge of Old. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar; There are no changes found with them; &Verbar; and &s;o they fear not God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 He &s;hall put forth his hand again&s;t &Verbar; the Men at Peace with him; &Verbar; his Covenant <HI>therein</HI> he hath &Verbar; profan'd by breaking it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Smooth were his Mouth's fine butter'd Words; &Verbar; but war was in his heart; &Verbar; much fo&s;ter were his words than oil; &Verbar; and yet drawn Swords they were. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Ca&s;t thy Load on th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; and he &s;hall &s;trengthen thee; &Verbar; The Righte|ous one He will not leave &Verbar; ever to be di|&s;turbed. &Verbar;</P>
