<P N="4">4 They run and they prepare them&s;elves; &Verbar; without <HI>my</HI> fault at all; &Verbar; Do thou awake to &s;uccour me, &Verbar; and, Oh! behold <HI>my ca&s;e.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Thou therefore, O-ETERNAL God, &Verbar; who art the God of Ho&s;ts, &Verbar; O thou the God of I&s;rael, &Verbar; do thou appear awake; &Verbar; to give a vi&s;it unto all &Verbar; the Nations <HI>of the World;</HI> &Verbar; But be not merciful to them &Verbar; who wickedly tran&s;gre&s;s. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 At Evening they return; they make &Verbar; a noi&s;e like to a dog; &Verbar; and about all the City they &Verbar; do take their compa&s;s round. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Behold, they do out of their mouth &Verbar; belch forth <HI>mo&s;t grievous things;</HI> &Verbar; &s;harp &s;words are in their lips; for who &Verbar; (<HI>&s;ay they</HI>) is there to hear? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 But, O ETERNAL God, Thou &s;halt &Verbar; but meerly laugh at them; &Verbar; all of the Na|tions thou &s;halt in &Verbar; a meer deri&s;ion have. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 His &s;trength is that for which I will &Verbar; keep waiting upon thee, &Verbar; becau&s;e that God is <HI>evermore</HI> &Verbar; my high-place of defence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 The God of <HI>all</HI> my mercy &s;hall &Verbar; pre|vent me <HI>&s;till with it;</HI> &Verbar; God &s;hall make me to &s;ee what does &Verbar; befall my enemies. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11"><PB N="145" REF="001946_0182_0FFCB2CAD33F2790">
11 Slay them not, le&s;t my People do &Verbar; for get; <HI>but</HI> by thy power &Verbar; O &s;carter them, and bring them down, &Verbar; O Lord, who art out Shield. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>For</HI> their mouth's &s;in, <HI>for</HI> their lips word, &Verbar; and for their pride let them &Verbar; be taken, and for cur&s;ing, and &Verbar; <HI>for</HI> lying <HI>which</HI> they &s;peak. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Wa&s;te <HI>them</HI> in wrath, wa&s;te <HI>them,</HI> that they &Verbar; may'nt be, and let them know, &Verbar; that God doth rule in Jacob, to &Verbar; the ends of <HI>all</HI> the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 At Evening &s;o let them return; &Verbar; let them bark like a Dog; &Verbar; and if they are not &s;atisfy'd, &Verbar; then let them murmur on. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 But as for me, I'll make my Song &Verbar; of thy victorious power; &Verbar; and of thy mercy I will in &Verbar; the morning &s;ing aloud. &Verbar; Becau&s;e that thou ha&s;t been <HI>for me</HI> &Verbar; my high-place of defence; &Verbar; and refuge in the day when there &Verbar; was trouble upon me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 O Thou that art my &s;trength, I will &Verbar; utter my Songs to thee; &Verbar; Becau&s;e God is my high defence; &Verbar; God of my mercy <HI>&s;till.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LIX. PSALM</HEAD>
<P>WE have here a Prayer again&s;t the Enemies of the Church. The Term of, <HI>The God of I&s;rael,</HI> invites us to think of the Jewi&s;h Na|tion groaning under the Oppre&s;&s;ions of <HI>Antichri&s;tian</HI> the <HI>City</HI> in the Sixth Ver&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> not <HI>Kome</HI> to be under|&s;tood?
<PB N="146" REF="001946_0183_0FFCB347F375FB10">Compare, Numb. XXIV. 19. Good Old <HI>Ar|nobius</HI> has directed the Application of the P&s;alm to the Morals of Chri&s;tianity. <HI>When the Hou&s;e of thy Body is be&s;eiged and be&s;et by the Prince of this World, with Temptations, that thou may&s;t be taken and &s;tain by the Sword of any Sin, 'tis now a time from the bottom of thy Soul to make the&s;e outories.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 In R. <HI>David Kimchi,</HI> there is an admirable inti|mation, That the P&s;almi&s;t here beholding the wicked|ne&s;s of Men, de&s;pairs of &s;eeing a Good World, until the <HI>Day of Judgment. The Day of Judgment,</HI> or the time of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah's</HI> Kingdom, is here Prayed for. At the Time when God &s;hall thus <HI>vi&s;it all the Nations,</HI> He will eminently exhibit Him&s;elf as the <HI>God of I&s;rael.</HI></P>
<P N="6">6 Compare, 1 <HI>Sam.</HI> XIX. 10, 11. Take for once a My&s;tical Interpretation, and from the Hint learn to make more &s;uch on proper Occa&s;ions. Men are guilty of great Crimes, in their Younger Years. They reform tho&s;e Crimes and live many Years unblemi&s;h'd. But if the work of <HI>Repentance</HI> in them, have not been a &s;in|cere and thorough work, they <HI>Return in the Evening</HI> to their old Crimes. God leaves them to &s;ome &s;trange Infatuation; and in their <HI>Old Age,</HI> or in the <HI>Evening</HI> of their Lives, they fall into their <HI>Old Crimes</HI> again, with &s;uch Circum&s;tances as exceedingly expo&s;e them.</P>
<P N="11">11 <HI>Au&s;tin</HI> has a Notable &s;troke upon it, <HI>Orat ut gens Judaeorum maneret.</HI>&mdash;It is not &s;o much a <HI>David,</HI> as a Per&s;ecuted JESUS, who&s;e Condition is expre&s;&s;ed throughout the P&s;alm. The Jewi&s;h Nation de&s;erved utter de&s;truction and extinction for the wrongs which they did unto the Per&s;ecuted JESUS. But he Prays, That the Nation may not be <HI>utterly Extinct,</HI> for their wickedne&s;s; but wander about in a di&s;tre&s;s'd and abject &s;tate, not altogether <HI>forgotten</HI> in the World. The <HI>Syriac</HI> Title of the P&s;alm is, <HI>A Prophecy of the Con|ver&s;ion of the Gentiles, and the Rejection of the Jews.</HI></P>
<P N="13"><PB N="147" REF="001946_0184_0FFCB2EE1A181978">
13 A fine thought <HI>Arnobius</HI> has upon it; <HI>Ibi do|minatur Dominus, ubi Fines faciunt Terrer &amp; Voluptates.</HI></P>
<P N="14">14 The <HI>Return in the Evening, is by</HI> R. <HI>Obadiah Gaon,</HI> applied unto the Prophecy of <HI>Gog</HI> and <HI>Magog.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="60" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LX.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Upon Shu&s;han Eduth. Mictam. Of David; To teach. When he &s;trove with Aram|naharaim and with Aram-Zobah; When Joab re|turned and &s;mote of Edom in the Valley of Salt, Twelve Thou&s;and.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O God, Thou ha&s;t rejected us; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t di&s;per&s;ed us; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t been angry; O do thou &Verbar; return to us again. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 To tremble thou ha&s;t made the Earth; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t divided it; &Verbar; The breaches of it, O do thou &Verbar; heal them, becau&s;e it &s;hakes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Thy People thou did&s;t cau&s;e to &s;ee &Verbar; a very grievous thing; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t made us to drink the Wine, &Verbar; which doth a&s;toni&s;h us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 A Banner thou ha&s;t given <HI>now</HI> &Verbar; to them that have thy fear, &Verbar; that it may be di&s;|play'd on high &Verbar; in the <HI>good</HI> cau&s;e of truth. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 That thy beloved ones may have &Verbar; an <HI>hep'd</HI> deliverance; &Verbar; do thou now &s;ave by thy right hand; &Verbar; and do thou an&s;wer me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 God hath &s;poke in His holine&s;s; &Verbar; I will triumph with joy; &Verbar; Shechem I will divide and will &Verbar; mea&s;ure out Succoth's Vale. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7"><PB N="148" REF="001946_0185_0FFCB30E6F4CB038">
7 Gilead is what I claim for mine; &Verbar; Me|na&s;&s;eh too is mine. &Verbar; Ephraim is of my &s;trength the head; &Verbar; Judah's my Lawgiver. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Moab's a Pot wherein I'll wa&s;h: &Verbar; On Edom I will ca&s;t &Verbar; my &s;hoe; Phili&s;tia, <HI>If thou can&s;t,</HI> &Verbar; triumph thou over me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Who will conduct me unto the &Verbar; well-fortifyed Town? &Verbar; Into the heart of Edom, who &Verbar; is it will lead me on? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Is it not thou, O God, who us &Verbar; did&s;t ca&s;t off heretofore? &Verbar; Ev'n Thou, O God, who did&s;t not go &Verbar; out with our Armed ho&s;ts? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 O give us &s;uccour from di&s;tre&s;s; &Verbar; for vain's the help of Man. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Thro' God we &s;hall do valiantly: &Verbar; and He'll tread down our foes. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>REad 2 Sam. VIII. And you under&s;tand the P&s;alm. The Sufferings of the Jewi&s;h Nation in their pre&s;ent Exile, are al&s;o to be con&s;idered. R. <HI>Solomon</HI> has a notable Glo&s;s on the fir&s;t Ver&s;e; He fore&s;aw in the Spirit, <HI>Quod Romani erant dominaturi.</HI></P>
<P N="2">2 There had been dreadful Divi&s;ions and Commo|tions among the People, [See, 2 Sam. II. 9, 10, 17. and III. 1.</P>
<P N="3">3 A Fulfilment of Deut. XXVIII. 28, 34. They were like unto Men bereft of the u&s;e of Rea&s;on, by &s;ome in|toxicating Potion; who thereupon madly de&s;troy one another.</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>David</HI> became their King; to whom they were all to repair, like Souldiers to their di&s;played En&s;ign, <HI>Becau&s;e of Truth.] Mun&s;ters</HI> Glo&s;s is; <HI>Ut promi&s;&s;i|onibus tuis &s;atisfaceres.</HI> But this is not all.</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="149" REF="001946_0186_0FFCB30CEC5CE348">
6 Take a Paraphra&s;e. <Q>God [According to His Pro|mi&s;e, 2 Sam. III. 18.] hath put me in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of all the Country about <HI>Samaria,</HI> which I will di&s;tribute under &s;uch Officers as I &s;hall &s;et over them. <HI>Gilead</HI> al&s;o and <HI>Mena&s;&s;eh.</HI> [who were lately under another King, 2 <HI>Sam.</HI> 2.9.] have &s;ubmitted them&s;elves unto me. And &s;o has the Tribe of <HI>Ephraim;</HI> which is a main &s;upport of my Authority. The&s;e and all the reft of the Tribes of <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> are now invited unto the Royal Tribe of <HI>Judah;</HI> which [according to Gen. XLIX. 10.] &s;upplies me with Able Men, to order the Affairs of my Kingdom; which now &s;hall extend it&s;elf beyond the Bounds of this Country. For I will tread <HI>Moab</HI> under my Feet, and reduce them to the vile&s;t Servitude. I will trample al&s;o on the <HI>Edomites,</HI> and make them my Slaves. The <HI>Phili&s;tines</HI> al&s;o whom I have begun to &s;mite, &s;hall add unto my triumphs.</Q></P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>My head;</HI> i. e. My chief Strength in time of Wa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">: <HI>Judah my Lawgiver.</HI> It refers to the Prophecy, Gen. XLIX. 10.</P>
<P N="8">8. To pour <HI>Water</HI> out of a Ve&s;&s;el, for the wa&s;ning of anothers hands, is the &s;ame as to be a <HI>Servant.</HI> [See, 2 Kin. III. 2.] Some of the Ancients applied it unto the Tribute of <HI>Lambs,</HI> which <HI>Moab</HI> was to pay unto the King of <HI>Judah.</HI> [2 Kin. III. 4.] The&s;e were wa&s;h'd and boil'd in <HI>Pots.</HI> q. d. <HI>Moab</HI> &s;hall keep my <HI>Pot boiling. Ca&s;t my &s;hoe.</HI>] Does not the Spani&s;h Ver&s;ion well expre&s;s the matter! <HI>Tomare Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion,</HI> or, <HI>I will take Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of Edom.</HI> [Compare, Ruth IV. 7. and Deut. XXV. 7, 9.] Plucking off the <HI>Shoe,</HI> was a Ceremony u&s;ed of Old, in Contracts and making over E&s;tates.</P>
<P N="11">11 The <HI>Trouble</HI> of the <HI>Syrians</HI> invading. See, 2 <HI>Sam.</HI> VIII. 5.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="61" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Upon Neginoth. A P&s;alm of David,</HEAD>
<PB N="150" REF="001946_0187_0FFCB07B77590588">
<P N="1">1 O God, hear thou my mighty cry; &Verbar; attend unto my pray'r. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 From the end of the Earth I will &Verbar; &s;end up my cry to thee; &Verbar; When that my heart is overwhelm'd, &Verbar; <HI>this will be &s;till my cour&s;e;</HI> &Verbar; O lead thou me unto the Rock &Verbar; that is more high than I. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For thou ha&s;t been my &s;heltring place, &Verbar; which I have hoped in; &Verbar; A Tower of &s;trength <HI>to hide</HI> from the &Verbar; face of the enemy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 I in thy Tabernacle will &Verbar; for ever make abode; &Verbar; I'll &s;eek my refuge under the &Verbar; &s;afe covert of thy wings. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Becau&s;e that thou, O God, the Judge, &Verbar; ha&s;t hearkned to my Vows; &Verbar; Thou'&s;t given me the Heritage &Verbar; of them that fear thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Days thou &s;halt add unto the days &Verbar; of Him that is the King; &Verbar; His years &s;hall be <HI>prolonged as</HI> &Verbar; an Age upon an Age. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Before the face of God He &s;hall &Verbar; abide for evermore; &Verbar; Mercy and Truth do thou prepare; &Verbar; the&s;e will continue him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 And then for evermore I will &Verbar; &s;ing prai&s;e unto thy Name; &Verbar; that I may be per|forming &s;till &Verbar; my Vows from day to day. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the Jewi&s;h Nation here de&s;per&s;ed unto the <HI>Ends of the Earth:</HI> But comforted with an hope of Re&s;toration; and of happine&s;s under the Protection <HI>of the Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> for <HI>many Generations.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="62" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="151" REF="001946_0188_0FFCB32DB0BCEDC0">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXII.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician; To Jeduthun. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 AS&s;uredly my Soul doth wait &Verbar; in &s;ilence upon God; &Verbar; From Him it is <HI>that all</HI> of my &Verbar; Salvation <HI>doth proceed.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Surely He is my Rock, and He &Verbar; is my Salvation &s;till; &Verbar; He is my high place of de|fence; &Verbar; I &s;han't be greatly mov'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Again&s;t a Man how long will ye &Verbar; plot mi&s;chief's? you &s;hall all &Verbar; be &s;lain; like to a bowing wall &Verbar; you'l be, a tott'ring fence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 They only plot to ca&s;t him down &Verbar; from his high dignity; &Verbar;: They love a lie; ble&s;s with their mouth; &Verbar; but inwardly they cur&s;e. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 My Soul, See that in &s;ilence thou &Verbar; wait upon God alone; &Verbar; becau&s;e it is from Him that I &Verbar; my expectation have. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Surely, He is my Rock, and He &Verbar; is my Salvation &s;till; &Verbar; He is my high place of de|fence; &Verbar; I &s;han't be mov'd at all. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 In God is my Salvation &s;till, &Verbar; and there's my Glory too; &Verbar; The Rock in which I'm fortify'd; &Verbar; my refuge is in God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O People, At all times repo&s;e &Verbar; your confidence in Him, &Verbar; Pour out you heart be|fore His face; &Verbar; God is our &s;afe retreat. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Sure lower Men are vanity, &Verbar; and higher Men a lie: &Verbar; Let them a&s;cend the Scales, they're le&s;s &Verbar; than vanity together. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10"><PB N="152" REF="001946_0189_0FFCB3445E18A6A0">
10 O do not in oppre&s;&s;ion tru&s;t &Verbar; and rob|bery: Be not vain; &Verbar; If riches &s;hould be multiply'd, &Verbar; &s;et not your heart <HI>thereon.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 The mighty God hath &s;poken once; &Verbar; The&s;e two things I have heard; &Verbar; <HI>One is,</HI> That there's a mighty power &Verbar; which does belong to God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 The other, That Mercy belongs &Verbar; to thee, ETERNAL God; &Verbar; For thou wilt ren|der every Man &Verbar; according to his work. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXII. PSALM</HEAD>
<P>THus the Church, under the Oppre&s;&s;ion of <HI>Anti+chri&s;t,</HI> comforts her&s;elf, with hopes in the Pro|phecies of what &s;hall be done unto the Wicked.</P>
<P N="6">6 How <HI>Piety</HI> improves in the exerci&s;e of i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> &Verbar; Four Ver&s;es ago, it was, <HI>I &s;han't be greatly mov'd.</HI> Now 'tis come to this, <HI>I &s;han't be mov'd at all.</HI></P>
<P N="11">11 The <HI>Syriac</HI> Interpreter countenances our Ver&s;ion. <HI>Once</HI> God &s;poke on Mount <HI>Sinai;</HI> And the&s;e <HI>Two things were heard,</HI> when the Sanctions of the <HI>Second Commandment</HI> were uttered. I have &s;omewhere met with &s;uch a devour Glo&s;s as this. When the Lord <HI>&s;poke once,</HI> this Pious Man <HI>heard him twice;</HI> Namely, by an after Meditation on what had been &s;poken.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="63" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXIII.</HI> A P&s;alm of David, when be was at the Wilderne&s;s of Judah.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O God, Thou art my God, I will &Verbar; &s;eek after thee betimes; &Verbar; My Soul is in a thir&s;t for thee: &Verbar; Thee does my fle&s;h de&s;ire. &Verbar; <HI>They do it</HI> in a Land that is &Verbar; a very wilder|ne&s;s: &Verbar; And in a place of wearine&s;s, &Verbar; which has no water in't.</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="153" REF="001946_0190_0FFCB3326C808848">
2 <HI>It is</HI> that I may have a view &Verbar; of what thy Power <HI>is,</HI> &Verbar; and <HI>what</HI> thy Glory; As I have &Verbar; &s;een in the holy place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Becau&s;e thy loving kindne&s;s is &Verbar; better than Lives them&s;elves; &Verbar; My lips &s;hall <HI>there|fore</HI> be imploy'd &Verbar; in &s;etting forth thy Prai&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 So in my Lives I will proclaim &Verbar; Thee the mo&s;t ble&s;&s;ed One: &Verbar; I will &s;till elevate my hands &Verbar; in thy <HI>m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">i ble&s;ed</HI> Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 So as with marrow and with fat &Verbar; my Soul &s;hall be fu&s;&s;ic'd; &Verbar; And with my joyful lips my mouth &Verbar; &s;hall celebrate thy Prai&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 It while I'm lying on my Beds &Verbar; I do remember thee, &Verbar; <HI>if</HI> in the watches of the Night &Verbar; I meditate in thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Becau&s;e that thou ha&s;t been to me &Verbar; an help once and again, &Verbar; and in the &s;hadow of thy wings &Verbar; I do triumph with joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Still clo&s;ely following after thee &Verbar; my Soul does cleave to thee: &Verbar; Thy right-hand doth &s;u&s;tain me <HI>&s;o</HI> &Verbar; <HI>that I am kept from falls.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 But they who &s;eek my Soul to bring &Verbar; de&s;truction upon it: &Verbar; The&s;e &s;hall go &s;urely down into &Verbar; the low parts of the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 By the hands of the Sword they &s;hall &Verbar; make him to flow away; &Verbar; they &s;hall become a portion to &Verbar; the Jackals <HI>of the Night.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 But the King &s;hall rejoyce in God; &Verbar; each one that &s;wears by him &Verbar; &s;hall Glory: but the mouth be &s;topt &Verbar; of them that &s;peak a lie. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="154" REF="001946_0191_0FFCB34C585FB348">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THink on the Ca&s;e of the Church under <HI>Antichri&s;t.</HI> Yea, think on the ca&s;e of the <HI>Synagogue</HI> too. Compare <HI>Ver&s;ed.</HI> with Ho&s;. II. 15. and Ezek, XX. 35. Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks, the <HI>Wilderne&s;s</HI> here was that which <HI>David</HI> went through, when he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ed from <HI>Ab&s;alom.</HI> [2 Sam. XVII. 29.] Ina&s;much as he calls him&s;elf a <HI>King;</HI> which he would not have done, during the Reign of <HI>Saul.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 Doth not he long for the Coming of God, in our Fle&s;h? It is the <HI>Son of God</HI> in His <HI>Incarnation,</HI> wherein peculiarly we enjoy the Great GOD for <HI>our God.</HI> But Methinks, I perceive the Cry of the Saints in <HI>Hades,</HI> wi&s;hing for the <HI>Re&s;urrection of the Dead.</HI> The <HI>Souls</HI> do <HI>thir&s;t</HI> for the Coming of the Lord; Their <HI>Fle&s;h</HI> does al&s;o <HI>long</HI> for it; in a <HI>Land</HI> which wants the <HI>dem</HI> of Heaven, whereby the Dead &s;hall be Revived. <HI>Singer,</HI> 06 Having this Key in thy Hands, now go into the P&s;alm with mo&s;t attentive Meditation. <HI>Dry and thir&s;ty Land.</HI>] Compare 2 Sam. XVII. 29.</P>
<P N="3">3 It plea&s;es one very much, to find the <HI>Chaldes</HI> intimating, That the <HI>Loving kindne&s;s</HI> here celebrated, is the Ble&s;&s;edne&s;s which God will vouch&s;afe unto the Ju&s;t in the World to come. This is <HI>better than any Life</HI> in this World.</P>
<P N="6">6 Old <HI>Arnobius</HI> has a &s;ingular Glo&s;s upon it: <HI>O&s;ten|dit per<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ejus Auxilium potui&s;&s;e &s;e Ca&s;timoni<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">m <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">btinui&s;&s;e.</HI></P>
<P N="10">10 The <HI>Jackals,</HI> are a Mungril Creature, deriving their Cruelty from the <HI>Wolves,</HI> their Sires; and their Craftine&s;s from the <HI>Foxes</HI> their Dams. The&s;e are &s;o ravenous that they will not only feed on Carrion above Ground, but al&s;o dig holes in the Farth, and &s;etch forth the Dead Bodies of Men, if not very deeply interrel. whereas, proper <HI>Foxes,</HI> they &s;ay, will not fee &verbar; on my Carca&s;e, but what they kill them&s;elves.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="64" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="155" REF="001946_0192_0FFCB33895BBB0B0">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXIV.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O God, Hear Thou the Voice <HI>that's in</HI> &Verbar; my Praying unto Thee; &Verbar; O do thou keep my Life from the &Verbar; fear of the Enemy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O hide me from the &s;ecret plot &Verbar; of the malignant ones; &Verbar; from the contemptuous rage of them &Verbar; that work iniquity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 <HI>The Men</HI> who like a cutting Sword &Verbar; do whet their <HI>&s;piteful</HI> tongue: &Verbar; they've bent to &s;hoot their arrows out, &Verbar; a word of bit|terne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>This they do</HI> to &s;hoot &s;ecretly &Verbar; again&s;t the perfect one; &Verbar; they &s;uddenly do &s;hoot at him, &Verbar; and they are not afraid. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 An evil matter for them&s;elves &Verbar; they give a &s;trength unto; &Verbar; they talk about their hiding &s;nares: &Verbar; Who &s;hall &s;ee them? They &s;ay &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 They &s;earch iniquities; they make &Verbar; an exact &s;crutiny. &Verbar; The inward thought of every one, &Verbar; and the heart is a deep. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 But God &s;hall &s;hoot down upon them &Verbar; an Arrow &s;uddenly: &Verbar; There &s;hall be <HI>&s;udden|ly di&s;pens'd</HI> &Verbar; &s;trokes that &s;hall be their wounds. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 And &s;o they &s;hall make their own tongue&Verbar; to fall upon them&s;elves: &Verbar; All they who do behold them &s;hall &Verbar; betake them&s;elves to flight. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9"><PB N="156" REF="001946_0193_0FFCB34DE6AD5A18">
9 So all Men are afraid, and &s;hall &Verbar; de|clare the work of God; &Verbar; For they &s;hall wi&s;ely apprehend &Verbar; the work that he hath done. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 The ju&s;t one &s;hall be very glad &Verbar; in the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and all that are up|right in heart &Verbar; &s;hall gloriou&s;ly rejoyce. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>CAn't we &s;ee here the Condition of the <HI>I&s;raeliti&s;h Na|tion</HI> di&s;per&s;ed under the Tyranny of <HI>Antichri&s;t?</HI> And the great Conver&s;ion of the Nations, which will be after they are Converted and Re&s;tored.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="65" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXV.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm; A Song of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O God, In Zion there does wait &Verbar; Prai&s;e &s;ilently for Thee; &Verbar; And unto Thee the Vow thereof &Verbar; &s;hall &s;urely be perform'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O Thou that art the hearer of &Verbar; Prayer that appeals to thee, &Verbar; <HI>&s;ince thou art &s;uch One,</HI> all fle&s;h &Verbar; will &s;till repair to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Works of iniquities again&s;t &Verbar; me have prevailed &s;ore; &Verbar; But as for our tran&s;gre&s;&s;ions thou, &Verbar; do&s;t purge them quite away. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O ble&s;&s;ed is the Man of whom &Verbar; thou mak'&s;t a gracious choice, &Verbar; and whom thou &s;halt make to approach &Verbar; near <HI>to thy Maje&s;ty. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"></HI> does dwell in thy courts;</P>
<P><PB N="157" REF="001946_0194_0FFCB350C6F186E0">
We &s;hall be &s;atisfy'd &Verbar; with the Good of thy Hou&s;e, <HI>and with</HI> &Verbar; thy Temple's holy place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 <HI>By</HI> awful things in righteou&s;ne&s;s &Verbar; an an&s;wer unto us &Verbar; thou wilt di&s;pen&s;e, the God from whom &Verbar; &s;till our Salvation comes. &Verbar; Thou'rt He that art an hope unto &Verbar; all the ends of the Earth; &Verbar; And <HI>&s;o Thou art</HI> of them that are &Verbar; far off upon the Sea. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The mountains he e&s;tabli&s;hes &Verbar; by His own mighty pow'r: &Verbar; He has a Girdle of a <HI>Great &Verbar; and wondrous</HI> fortitude. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 He does allay the raging noi&s;e &Verbar; of the <HI>di&s;turbed</HI> Seas; &Verbar; the noi&s;e rais'd by their waves: and the &Verbar; tumultuous People too. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 They who dwell in the utmo&s;t parts &Verbar; do al&s;o fear thy &s;igns; &Verbar; outgoings of the Morning and &Verbar; the Ev'ning thou mak'&s;t glad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 The Earth <HI>with Rain</HI> thou vi&s;ite&s;t, &Verbar; after that thou ha&s;t made &Verbar; it to de&s;ire <HI>the Rain,</HI> Thou do&s;t &Verbar; enrich it mightily. &Verbar; The River of God with waters is &Verbar; richly repleni&s;hed; &Verbar; Thou do&s;t prepare them Corn; 'tis &s;o &Verbar; that thou prepare&s;t it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Water its ridges plenteou&s;ly; &Verbar; On't's furrows O de&s;cend; &Verbar; With &s;howr's thou mak'&s;t it &s;oft; Thou do&s;t &Verbar; ble&s;s what does &s;pring from it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Thou with thy Goodne&s;s do&s;t adorn &Verbar; the Year as with a crown; &Verbar; and the paths that are trod by thee, &Verbar; do drop a fatne&s;s down. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11"><PB N="158" REF="001946_0195_0FFCB33DCBACC8E8">
11 They drop upon the Pa&s;tures of &Verbar; the <HI>thir&s;ty</HI> wilderne&s;s: &Verbar; and &s;o the little Hills are girt &Verbar; on ev'ry &s;ide with joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 The Pa&s;tures they are cloath'd with Flocks; &Verbar; the Valleys too with Corn &Verbar; are cover'd over: they do &s;hout, &Verbar; and &s;ing they do for joy. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the Miracles to be wrought, when <HI>I&s;rael</HI> &s;hall be returned from Exile. The <HI>Showers</HI> here Celebrated are tho&s;e of the <HI>Holy Spirit</HI> falling on the Church of GOD. Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks, the <HI>Showers</HI> that came after the Three Years Famine, which &s;uc|ceeded the Rebellion of <HI>Ab&s;alom,</HI> are here &s;poken of.</P>
<P N="1">1 The <HI>Prai&s;es</HI> of God are &s;o inexpre&s;&s;ible, that they are be&s;t expre&s;t by <HI>Silent</HI> Admiration. Yea, and God is never more effectually, never more acceptably Prai&s;ed, then by the <HI>Silence</HI> of His People; their <HI>Silent Patience,</HI> and Forbearing of all Murmuring in their Adver&s;ity.</P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> here glo&s;&s;es well, <HI>Agit P&s;almus de Regno Chri&s;ti.</HI></P>
<P N="3">3 When <HI>Unrighteous</HI> Men &s;o prevail again&s;t us, as to put unrighteous things upon us, it will be a ble&s;&s;ed Con&s;equence and Improvement of it, if we come there|by the more to reform our <HI>own Tran&s;gre&s;&s;ions.</HI></P>
<P N="4">4 The <HI>Prie&s;ts</HI> and <HI>Levites</HI> partaking of the <HI>Thanks|giving Sacrifices,</HI> are but the Figure of what is princi|pally intended here.</P>
<P N="5">5 <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> carries it &s;o; When the <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> of GOD, was by our SAVIOUR brought unto the Children of Men, the <HI>Miracles</HI> which accompanied the Di&s;pen&s;ation were very wonderful. But there are <HI>Marvellous</HI> things which yet remain to be done.</P>
<P N="8"><PB N="159" REF="001946_0196_0FFCB4450799EC40">
8 Dr. <HI>Patricks</HI> Paraphra&s;e is, The mo&s;t barbarous People, who live in the mo&s;t remote Parts of the Earth, behold with wonder the Heavenly Bodies, which God has appointed for <HI>Signs</HI> and <HI>Tokens.</HI> [Gen. I. 4.] In the Title Page of a Book about, <HI>The Go&s;pel of the RAINBOW,</HI> I have &s;een the Text &s;o tran&s;lated, <HI>They who dwell in the uttermo&s;t Parts, have a Reverence for thy Tokens; Thou vi&s;ite&s;t the Earth &amp; watere&s;t it. Al&s;ted</HI> would have the <HI>Outgoings of the Morning,</HI> refer to <HI>Man,</HI> and the <HI>Cattle,</HI> which then <HI>go out</HI> to work and feed; and the <HI>Outgoings of the Evening</HI> refer to <HI>Wild Bea&s;ts,</HI> which then <HI>go out</HI> for their Prey.</P>
<P N="8">8 <HI>Arnobius</HI> here con&s;iders the <HI>God of Salvation,</HI> as Exhibited at the fir&s;t Preaching of the Go&s;pel. Then the Apo&s;tles appeared as <HI>Mountains,</HI> from whence there was Proclaimed the <HI>Go&s;pel to every Creature.</HI> Then they who <HI>dwelt in the uttermo&s;t Parts,</HI> were &s;truck with <HI>Reverence,</HI> at the <HI>Miracles</HI> wrought by our Lord. Both <HI>Morning</HI> &amp; <HI>Evening;</HI> both <HI>Ea&s;tern</HI> and <HI>We&s;tern</HI> World, felt the joyful effect of the&s;e things, in Churches gathered every where. The Lord then <HI>vi&s;ited</HI> the Earth, and Watered it with the Heavenly Influences of His Holy Spirit. From <HI>Jordan,</HI> the River of GOD, there particularly i&s;&s;ued that which enrich'd it. GOD then prepar'd for His People the Food which endures to <HI>Everla&s;ting Life.</HI></P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Great Fruitfulne&s;s</HI> will occa&s;ion <HI>Great Joyful|ne&s;s.</HI> One who &s;hall be &s;o happy as to <HI>bring forth much Fruit,</HI> for GOD and His People, and be very &s;erviceable, will have cau&s;e to <HI>&s;ing for Joy.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="66" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXVI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A Song; A P&s;alm.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O All the Earth, Make you to God &Verbar; &s;houts of a Jubilee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Sing forth the Glory of His Name; &Verbar; put Glory on His Prai&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="160" REF="001946_0197_0FFCB342520F1F88">
3 Say unto God, Things done by Thee, &Verbar; How terrible they are! &Verbar; For thy great pow'r, thy enemies &Verbar; &s;hall &s;eem to &s;toop to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 All <HI>who do dwell upon</HI> the Earth &Verbar; &s;hall bow them&s;elves to thee: &Verbar; And they &s;hall &s;ing to thee; they &s;hall &Verbar; &s;ing to thy Glori|ous Name. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O come and take a view of the &Verbar; works that are done by God; &Verbar; How terrible in what He does &Verbar; upon the &s;ons of Men! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Into dry Land <HI>that might be trod</HI> &Verbar; once did He turn the Sea: &Verbar; Thorough the flood they pa&s;s'd on foot; &Verbar; there we rejoyc'd in Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 He by His pow'r for ever rules; &Verbar; His Eyes the Nations &s;ee: &Verbar; O now let the re|bellious ones &Verbar; no more exalt them&s;elves. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 A Benediction to our God, &Verbar; ye Peoples, offer up; &Verbar; and the voice of His Prai&s;e do you &Verbar; make to be heard aloud. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 'Tis He who by re&s;toring it &Verbar; does place our Soul in Life; &Verbar; and He does not per|mit our foot &Verbar; to &s;tumble into falls. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Becau&s;e that thou, O God, ha&s;t made &Verbar; a thorough proof of us; &Verbar; Of us thou h'&s;t &s;uch a Trial made &Verbar; as Silver &s;hould be try'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Thou ha&s;t brought us into the Net &Verbar; <HI>that was prepar'd for us;</HI> &Verbar; Affliction which doth &s;traiten us &Verbar; thou on our Loins ha&s;t put. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12"><PB N="161" REF="001946_0198_0FFCB7CA6CD35398">
12 Thou ha&s;t made Man ride o're our head; &Verbar; we went through fire and water; &Verbar; But thou ha&s;t brought us forth into &Verbar; a fructifying place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 I will with <HI>due</HI> Burnt-Offerings now &Verbar; enter into thy Hou&s;e; &Verbar; and I will render unto thee &Verbar; the Vows that I have made. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 The things which <HI>formerly</HI> my lips &Verbar; did openly pronounce; &Verbar; and what my mouth hath &s;poken when &Verbar; I was in my di&s;tre&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Burnt-Offerings of well-marrow'd things &Verbar; I'll offer up to thee; &Verbar; Rams with their Incen&s;e: Bullocks I &Verbar; with Goats will offer up. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 O come, attend; All you that have in you the fear of God; &Verbar; and I'll give a Re|lation of &Verbar; what He does for my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 A cry importunate I did &Verbar; make with my mouth to Him; &Verbar; And <HI>for that very cau&s;e</HI> He was &Verbar; extolled with my tongue. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 If in my heart I paid regard &Verbar; unto iniquity, &Verbar; &s;urely the Lord would not have heard &Verbar; <HI>my Supplication</HI> then. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 But verily, now God hath heard &Verbar; <HI>what I addre&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">'d to Him;</HI> &Verbar; He hath attended to the voice &Verbar; which my petition had. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Ble&s;&s;ed be God, who hath not tur<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">d &Verbar; my Pray'r away <HI>from Him.</HI> &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy He hath not &Verbar; turned away from me. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="162" REF="001946_0199_0FFCB826D81F1450">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>CErtainly, we have here, the Prai&s;es which the Church of <HI>I&s;rael</HI> will give unto God, after He has Par|doned her Sins, and Re&s;tored Ble&s;&s;ings to her, which will cau&s;e all other Nations al&s;o to magnify Him.</P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Mun&s;ters</HI> Glo&s;s is: <HI>Men</HI> u&s;ed them as if they had been <HI>Bea&s;ts.</HI></P>
<P N="15">15 <HI>Arnobius</HI> is very nice in his <HI>Allegories</HI> here. The <HI>Offering</HI> of <HI>Rams,</HI> he finds in Zeal for defending the Truth; Of <HI>Bcoves</HI> in Preaching the Go&s;pel; Of <HI>Goats, &mdash;cum Imperium Libidinis &s;ubjugo, vel jugulo.</HI></P>
<P N="18">18 It is the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> who has the fir&s;t and chief claim to this Pa&s;&s;age. <HI>J. Capellus</HI> ob&s;erves, The <HI>Pha|ri&s;ees</HI> laid an Imputation of <HI>Wicked Intentions,</HI> on the Miracles of our SAVIOUR. The An&s;wer of our SA|VIOUR is, GOD would never have &s;o own'd Him if He had been one of &s;uch <HI>wicked Intentions.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="67" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXVII.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. On Neginoth. A P&s;alm; A Song.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 LEt God be merciful to us; &Verbar; and ble&s;s us graciou&s;ly; &Verbar; among us let Him cau&s;e to &s;hine &Verbar; His glorious countenance. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 That they may have the knowledge of &Verbar; thy way throughout the Earth: &Verbar; That they among all Nations may &Verbar; thy <HI>Great</HI> Salva|tion <HI>know.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 O <HI>Glorious</HI> God, The People they &Verbar; &s;hall celebrate thy prai&s;e; &Verbar; <HI>yea,</HI> all the People, every one, &Verbar; &s;hall celebrate thy prai&s;e, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 The Nations let be glad, and &s;ing &Verbar; for joy; For thou &s;halt judge &Verbar; the Peoples ju&s;tly, and &s;halt lead &Verbar; the Nations on the Earth, &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="163" REF="001946_0200_0FFCB383192D6F40">
5 O <HI>Glorious</HI> God, The People, they &Verbar; &s;hall celebrate thy Prai&s;e; &Verbar; <HI>yea,</HI> all the People every one &Verbar; &s;hall celebrate thy Prai&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The Earth &s;hall yield her fruit, <HI>and</HI> us &Verbar; God, our own God, &s;hall ble&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 God &s;hall ble&s;s us, and all ends of &Verbar; the Earth &s;hall Him revere. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>A Prayer for the Second Coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah!</HI> We read, when the <HI>Ark</HI> was brought into the Tabernacle prepared for it, 2 Sam. VI. 18. <HI>David ble&s;&s;ed the People, in the Name of the Lord.</HI> It is Dr. <HI>Pa|tricks</HI> Conjecture, That he then pronounced the <HI>P&s;alm</HI> now before us; wherein he imitates the Form of <HI>Ble&s;&s;ing</HI> which the <HI>Prie&s;ts</HI> were to u&s;e on Solemn Oc|ca&s;ions, [<HI>Numb.</HI> VI. 23, 24, 25.] He Prays that God would make them the Subjects and Samples of &s;uch Ble&s;&s;ings, as might invite all Nations, to whom the fame thereof &s;hould come, to &s;ubmit unto His Government.</P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>Thy Way. Au&s;tin's</HI> Glo&s;s is, Thy CHRIST.</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Theodoret</HI> thinks the <HI>Increa&s;e,</HI> to be the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> But is not the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah's</HI> Re&s;toring of the Earth unto a <HI>Paradi&s;aick State,</HI> here In&s;inuated? The Jews as is evident from R. <HI>David</HI> on Ho&s;. XIV. and R. <HI>Solomon</HI> on P&s;alm LXXII, were of this Opinion.</P>
<P N="7">7 It was long ago thought by the Learned <HI>Orientals,</HI> That the My&s;tery of the <HI>Trinity</HI> was indicated in this Repetition.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="68" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXVIII.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm. A Song of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 MAY God ari&s;e; His Enemies, &Verbar; may they be &s;cattered; &Verbar; and &s;uch as are haters of Him &Verbar; fly from before His face. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="164" REF="001946_0201_0FFCB35A76685C28">
2 Drive them as &s;moke is driv'n away; &Verbar; as wax melts in the fire; The wicked ones &s;hall be de&s;troy'd &Verbar; before the face of God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 But righteous ones, they &s;hall be glad; &Verbar; they &s;hall rejoyce before &Verbar; the face of God; yea, they &s;hall leap &Verbar; through their exceed|ing joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 To God &s;ing; to His Name &s;ing Prai&s;e: &Verbar; He through the de&s;arts rides: &Verbar; Extol Him by the Name of JAH; &Verbar; and in His face rejoyce. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 A Father of the Fatherle&s;s; &Verbar; A Judge for Widows too: &Verbar; <HI>So</HI> God <HI>is</HI> in the dwelling place &Verbar; of His pure holine&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 God &s;ets the Only's in an hou&s;e; brings out the bound in chains: &Verbar; But the rebellious ones dwell in &Verbar; a place mo&s;t de&s;titute. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 O God, When that thou did&s;t go forth &Verbar; in thy own Peoples view, &Verbar; when thou did&s;t take thy <HI>wondrous</HI> march &Verbar; thorough the wil|derne&s;s. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 The Earth &s;hook; yea, the Heavn's drop'd, &Verbar; before the face of God; &Verbar; ev'n Sinai at the face of God, &Verbar; the God of I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O God, Thou on thy heritage &Verbar; did&s;t pour a plenteous Rain; &Verbar; ev'n when that it was langui&s;hing, &Verbar; <HI>&s;o</HI> thou confirmed&s;t it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Thy living Congregation hath &Verbar; a dwel|ling place in it; &Verbar; O God, Thou of thy Good|ne&s;s do&s;t &Verbar; provide for him that's poor. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 The Lord <HI>from whom we have &s;upport;</HI> &Verbar;
<PB N="165" REF="001946_0202_0FFCB3CD4BAA5400">He does give forth the word; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> of the Souls that publi&s;h it &Verbar; great is the company. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 The Kings that had their Armies, fled; &Verbar; <HI>and yet again,</HI> they fled: &Verbar; and &s;he who did re&s;ide at home, &Verbar; did then divide the &s;poil. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Tho' ye have lien among the pots &Verbar; wings of a dove you have &Verbar; that is with Silver cover'd, and &Verbar; her feathers with bright Gold. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 When the Almighty one therein &Verbar; did &s;catter <HI>mighty</HI> Kings, &Verbar; then very White like to the Snow &Verbar; in Salmon it became. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 <HI>Like to</HI> the Mount of Ba&s;har <HI>is</HI> &Verbar; the Mountain of <HI>our</HI> God; &Verbar; A Mountain tis of <HI>Wondrous</HI> heighths; &Verbar; the Mount of Ba&s;han's <HI>&s;o.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Why, O high Mountains, do ye leap? &Verbar; This Hill God does de&s;ire, &Verbar; to dwell there; Yea, th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; will dwell fore|ver there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 God's Chariots Twenty Thou&s;and are; &Verbar; Repeated Thou&s;ands, <HI>they!</HI> &Verbar; Among them is the Glorious Lord: &Verbar; Sinai's in's Holy Place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Thou ha&s;t on high made thy A&s;cent: &Verbar; <HI>and then</HI> Captivity &Verbar; thou ha&s;t led Captive; <HI>and</HI> thou ha&s;t &Verbar; received Gifts for Men. &Verbar; Yea, <HI>Gifts</HI> for &s;uch Men as have been &Verbar; very intracta|ble; &Verbar; That &s;o the God who&s;e Name is JAH, &Verbar; may have a dwelling place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 O ble&s;&s;ed is the Lord who doth &Verbar; lay daily Loads on us; &Verbar; <HI>O ble&s;&s;ed be</HI> the God from whom &Verbar; does our Salvation come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20"><PB N="166" REF="001946_0203_0FFCB360920111E0">
20 This God. He is to us the God &Verbar; from whom Salvations come. &Verbar; And to the ETER|NAL God, the Lord &Verbar; I&s;&s;ues of Death belong. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 But God &s;hall wound the Head of them &Verbar; that are His Enemies; &Verbar; The hairy Scalp of him that walks &Verbar; on in his tre&s;pa&s;&s;es. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 The Lord hath &s;aid, From Ba&s;han I &Verbar; will make for to return; &Verbar; from the Depths of the Sea I'll make &Verbar; my <HI>People</HI> to return. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 May'&s;t Thou dip deep thy foot in Blood; &Verbar; may'&s;t thou dip deep the Tongue &Verbar; of thy Dogs <HI>in that</HI> of thy Foes; &Verbar; yea, every One of them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 Thy Goings they have &s;een, O God; &Verbar; the Goings of my God; &Verbar; <HI>the God who is</HI> my King, <HI>and is</HI> &Verbar; <HI>lodged in</HI> Holine&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 The Singers went before, then came &Verbar; players on In&s;truments; &Verbar; The&s;e were a|mong the Dam&s;els which &Verbar; manag'd the Timbrels there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 O &s;peak well of the <HI>Glorious</HI> God, &Verbar; in Congregations <HI>&s;peak;</HI> &Verbar; Even of the Lord, <HI>you that are</HI> from &Verbar; the Spring of I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27">27 The Little Benjamin does <HI>now</HI> &Verbar; <HI>make his appearance</HI> there; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> an In&s;pired Ruler <HI>who</HI> &Verbar; <HI>does now proceed from him.</HI> &Verbar; The E|minent Ones of Judah were &Verbar; the Stones of their Support; &Verbar; The Eminent Ones of Ze|bulon; &Verbar; th' Eminent of Naphthali. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28"><PB N="167" REF="001946_0204_0FFCB439A6CD3270">
28 Thy God is He, who does Command &Verbar; confirmed Strength for thee; &Verbar; Strengthen, O God, the very thing &Verbar; which Thou ha&s;t wrought for us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="29">29 For the &s;ake of thy Temple which &Verbar; is at Jeru&s;alem, &Verbar; they that are crowned Kings &s;hall bring &Verbar; <HI>their</HI> Pre&s;ents unto thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="30">30 Do thou be&s;tow Rebukes upon &Verbar; the Wild bea&s;t of the Reeds; &Verbar; Rebuke the Mul|titude of Bulls, &Verbar; join'd with the Peoples Calves. &Verbar; With Peices of Silver <HI>each one</HI> &Verbar; <HI>of them</HI> &s;ubmits him&s;elf; &Verbar; He hath di&s;per&s;'d the People which &Verbar; do take delight in War. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="31">31 Out <HI>of the Land</HI> of Aegypt <HI>then</HI> &Verbar; there &s;hall great Princes come; &Verbar; &s;oon Ethiopia &s;hall then &Verbar; &s;tretch out her hands to God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="32">32 <HI>Now,</HI> O ye Kingdoms of the Earth, &Verbar; &s;ing to <HI>the Glorious</HI> God; &Verbar; O &s;ing ye Prai&s;es forth unto &Verbar; <HI>him that becomes your</HI> Lord. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="33">33 To Him that rides upon the Heav'ns &Verbar; of Heav'ns which were of old; &Verbar; Attend; He does give out His Voice; &Verbar; It is a mighty Voice. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="34">34 Great &s;trength a&s;cribe ye unto God; &Verbar; Now over I&s;rael &Verbar; does his Magnificence ap|pear; &Verbar; and His Strength's in the Skies. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="35">35 Thou from thy Holy Places art, &Verbar; O God, how terrible! &Verbar; <HI>He that is &s;o is He that is</HI> &Verbar; the God of I&s;rael. &Verbar; Tis He who to His People will &Verbar; give a confirmed Strength; &Verbar; Yea, forces mo&s;t invincible. &Verbar; O ble&s;&s;ed be my God! &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="168" REF="001946_0205_0FFCB43B2BB03FF8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>LO, The Conre&s;&s;ion of the <HI>Synagogue,</HI> That the JESUS who was lifted up to Heaven, at His fir&s;t Coming is her SAVIOUR; even the &s;ame who con|ducted her thro' the Wilderne&s;s; and will at la&s;t re&s;tore her to her Land, and will de&s;troy her Oppre&s;&s;ors, and pour out His Holy npirit upon her. She fore-&s;ees the Ruin of <HI>Anti-chri&s;t,</HI> and her own return upon it, and the homage that all Nations &s;hall then pay to the <HI>Me&s;|&s;iah</HI> her King and her God.</P>
<P N="1">1 Behold the Re&s;urrection of our JESUS from the Grave!&mdash;In the Days of <HI>Athana&s;ius,</HI> the Divels in the <HI>Energumens</HI> di&s;covered u&s;ually a &s;trange Horror when this Ver&s;e was recited.</P>
<P N="4">4 R. <HI>David Kimchi</HI> has a Good Glo&s;s. He <HI>Governs</HI> them as a Man does the <HI>Hor&s;e</HI> he <HI>rides</HI> on.</P>
<P N="5">5 Tho' the Lord be &s;o much above the highe&s;t Hea|vens, yet the poore&s;t and meane&s;t per&s;ons upon Earth need have no doubt of His Patronage: They may re|pair to His Fatherly Care and appeal to His Righteous Judgment.</P>
<P N="9">9 Liberal Showers &s;ell on the Dry and De&s;ert places thro' which the cho&s;en People of God were travelling. Add the <HI>Manna</HI> rain'd from Heaven.</P>
<P>But above all think on the Gifts of the <HI>Prophetic Spirit. Mun&s;ter</HI> accordingly makes the <HI>People</HI> to be meant by the <HI>Land.</HI></P>
<P N="11">11 If we con&s;ider here, what was done for the Peo|ple of God in the Fir&s;t Ages&mdash;We know they were &s;o Victorious over their Oppo&s;ers, that they re|turned with Songs of Triumph, and were met with Women ready to accompany them in the Prai&s;es of GOD. [Exod. XV. 23,] Kings and Generals fled. [Exod. XVII. Num. XXI.] Yea, they fled and left their Spoll. [Num. XXXI. 8, 11. Judges. VIII. 21, 26.
<PB N="169" REF="001946_0206_0FFCB365159ADA70">This welcome they gave to their Victorious Country Men. <Q>Tho you endured great Hard&s;hip in <HI>Aegypt,</HI> where you loo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">t more like <HI>Skullions</HI> then <HI>Souldiers,</HI> you &s;hall hereafter appear mo&s;t &s;plendid, and the Wings of your Armies &s;hall &s;hine like tho&s;e of a <HI>Dove.</HI></Q> Their Word was fulfilled at the Entrance into <HI>Canaan;</HI> when by &s;cattering of Kings God appeared mo&s;t illu&s;trious at <HI>Salmon,</HI> and gave them the Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the Country on that &s;ide of <HI>Jordan,</HI> as on the other &s;ide he &s;ubdued the King and Country of <HI>Ba&s;han,</HI> the Hill whereof (which had &s;o many fertile Ri&s;ings) became the Hill of GOD. But the lofty Mountains mu&s;t not grow proud of this. For not they but <HI>Zion</HI> had God cho&s;en for His Habitation. The Heathen al&s;o mu&s;t not brag of their many Chariots; for in <HI>Zion</HI> there are Ten Thou&s;and times more, even innumerable Ho&s;ts of <HI>An|gels</HI> attending on the Divine Maje&s;ty, who is with them there, as He was upon Mount <HI>Sinai:</HI> So much was declared by God who highly Exalted Him&s;elf, in the A&s;toni&s;hing Victories, which thro' their Mani&s;try He gave them over their Enemies; whom they carried Captive and their Spoils with them, to be Di&s;tributed among His People. All this is an Emblem of what is done by the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> This is the Sum of the <HI>Pa|trician</HI> Paraphra&s;e.</P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Potts.</HI>&mdash;The IXX render it <HI>Lotts. Hemingius</HI> thinks it an Allu&s;ion to the <HI>Decimation</HI> of Rebellious Legions, or of Captivated Enemies, for De&s;tructions, 'Twas called <HI>Sortiri ad Panam,</HI> 'twas done by <HI>Lot;</HI> and is often mentioned by many of the Ancients. q. d. <Q>You have lain in as continual Danger of Death, as poor Soldiers expecting the <HI>Lot of Decimation,</HI> for their Lives. But your <HI>Saviour</HI> obtains an happy <HI>Lot</HI> for you; you fly away like <HI>Doves.</HI></Q></P>
<P N="18">18 In the Gifts of our A&s;cended Lord for His Church, He does but <HI>Spargers Mi&s;&s;ilia,</HI> and &s;catter <HI>Medals</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">e Princes at their Coronation, or in their Triumphal
<PB N="170" REF="001946_0207_0FFCB43E8D95D438">Entries. The well-qualifyed Mini&s;ters and Publi&s;hers of the Go&s;pel, are the <HI>Medals</HI> which our Triumphing Saviour does ca&s;t about, that His Church may &s;eize upon them. Yea, But the <HI>Medals</HI> have on them the <HI>Image</HI> of the Princes who di&s;per&s;e them. O Preachers of the Go&s;pel, How much ought you to be affected with this Con&s;ideration? There is nothing of &s;o much Con&s;equence unto you, as to have the <HI>Image</HI> of your SAVIOUR very Con&s;picuous on you.</P>
<P N="20">20 The Original may be rendred, <HI>The Goings forth of Death:</HI> All the &s;everal <HI>Ways of Dying,</HI> which are found by the Children of Men are appointed &amp; ordered by God. The LXX render it, <HI>The Pa&s;&s;ages of Death.</HI> All the &s;everal and &s;ecret Avenues whereby <HI>Death</HI> invades Mankind, God is the Uncontrollable Di&s;po&s;er of them. After all, in the <HI>Goings from Death</HI> here mentioned, why &s;hould not the <HI>Re&s;urrection from the Dead</HI> be refer'd unto?</P>
<P N="24">24 There &s;eems to have been a fierce Captain who had <HI>Shaggy Hair,</HI> which gave him &s;omething of a terrible A&s;pect, here particularly referr'd unto. Why not <HI>Hadadezer?</HI> [2 Sam. VIII. 3.] Notandum. <HI>Pharaoh</HI> &s;ignifies, <HI>A long haired Man.</HI></P>
<P N="27">27 <HI>Jerom</HI> and <HI>Theodoret</HI> &s;hall now help us, and let <HI>Lyra</HI> give &s;ome very melodious Notes unto us. Let the Amiable <HI>Alting</HI> and the Admirable <HI>Wit&s;ius</HI> more di&s;tinctly modulate them. The Glorious A&s;cen&s;ion of our SAVIOUR unto Heaven is here de&s;cribed unto us. The Prai&s;es to be offered on that Occa&s;ion are inti|mated; and tho&s;e <HI>Tribes</HI> of <HI>I&s;rael</HI> are mentioned, from whence the Per&s;ons were to ari&s;e, that were to be con&s;iderable in Prai&s;ing of the Lord. The fir&s;t mentioned is <HI>Little Benjamin.</HI> As <HI>Benjamin</HI> was the Younge&s;t Son of <HI>Jacob,</HI> &s;o our Apo&s;tle <HI>Paul</HI> of this Tribe, was the la&s;t that was called unto the <HI>Apo&s;tle&s;hip.</HI> [See 1 Cor. XV. 8, 9, 10.] And if <HI>Littlene&s;s</HI> may lead us to a Thought of <HI>Humility,</HI> it was what rendered our
<PB N="171" REF="001946_0208_0FFCB36A61B79398"><HI>Paul</HI> Illu&s;irious. [Eph. 3.8.] The Word <HI>Rodem,</HI> which we render <HI>A Ruler,</HI> is found no where el&s;e. It may mean an <HI>Extatic</HI> one. [Corn pare now Acts IX. 3.12. Acts XXIII. 17.2 Cor. XII. 1.] <HI>Theodotion</HI> ren|ders it, A <HI>Teacher.</HI> [Compare now, 1 Cor. XV. 15. 2 Cor. XI. 5, 23.] Then appear the <HI>Princes of Judab,</HI> and their <HI>Council.</HI> The Word <HI>Rigmotham,</HI> is al&s;o found no where el&s;e. 'Tis by &s;ome rendred, <HI>An heap of Stones.</HI> A <HI>Stone</HI> is a Phra&s;e for an <HI>Upholder</HI> and <HI>Pre&s;erver.</HI> [Gen. XLIX. 14.] <HI>An heap of Stones,</HI> intends a Number of Colleques in the &s;ame Work. The Tribe of <HI>Judah</HI> afforded a Number of <HI>Apo&s;tles.</HI> Four or Five without mentioning of <HI>Judas</HI> of <HI>Kerioth.</HI> The <HI>Princes of Zebulon</HI> were <HI>Peter</HI> and <HI>Andrew</HI> and <HI>Philip</HI> and <HI>Bartholomew,</HI> (probably, the &s;ame with <HI>Nathanael.</HI>) the <HI>Princes of Napthali</HI> were <HI>Matthew</HI> and perhaps <HI>Th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">mas. A &s;tin's</HI> Note is, <HI>ex his Tribu|bus Apo&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ie<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ant.</HI> The <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e amounts to thus much. What a Solemn Entrance, God by His Ar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">, made into the Sanctuary! [2 Sam. VI. 13, 15, 16.] Part of the <HI>Levites</HI> went Singing before, the re&s;t with Mu&s;ical Infiruments followed after. [1 Chron. XV. 16, 28.] To compleat the Melody, <HI>Dam&s;els</HI> with <HI>Timbrels</HI> came between them both. As they went they Sang, and the Song is recited here.&mdash;The Tribes were univer&s;ally a&s;&s;embled on this occa&s;ion. There were not only the Little Tribe of <HI>Benjamin,</HI> from whence came the fir&s;t King of <HI>I&s;rael;</HI> and Princes of the Tribe of <HI>Judah,</HI> the great Support of the Kingdom. There were al&s;o, the Princes of the emoter Tribes; Of <HI>Zebulen</HI> and of <HI>Napthali.</HI></P>
<P N="30">30 Some of the Ancients would have this <HI>Wild Bea&s;t</HI> be, the Fourth Bea&s;t in the <HI>Seventh</HI> of <HI>Daniel.</HI> And R. <HI>Solomon</HI> &s;ays, <HI>Fera calami e&s;t E&s;aX.</HI> The &s;ame with <HI>P&s;al.</HI> LXXX. 14. Deep thought is required here.</P>
<P N="20">20 Does not the <HI>Roman Orater</HI> a little expound the <HI>Heb en Prophet,</HI> where he relates. <HI>Aurum Judcorum
<PB N="172" REF="001946_0209_0FFCB44131294BF0">Nomine, quotannis ex Italia, et omnibus ve&s;tris Pro|vincijs, Hiero&s;olymam exportari &s;oleret?</HI>&mdash;But it waits a further Accompli&s;hment.</P>
<P N="32">32 There is doubtle&s;s an <HI>Ethiopia</HI> of <HI>Africa,</HI> as well as of <HI>Arabia,</HI> con&s;idered in the Scriptures. <HI>Ezekiel</HI> mentions <HI>Ethiopians</HI> and <HI>Egyptians</HI> as near Neigh|bours. <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> has a good Glo&s;s here; <HI>Non caret Locus i&s;te My&s;terijs Regni Chri&s;ti.</HI></P>
