<DIV2 N="69" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXIX.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Upon Sho&s;hannim. Of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 DEliver me, O <HI>Glorious</HI> God, &Verbar; Becau&s;e the waters do &Verbar; <HI>threatning my ruin,</HI> penetrate &Verbar; into my very Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In the mire of the Deep I &s;ink; &Verbar; there is no &s;tanding there; &Verbar; Into deep waters I am come; &Verbar; and the Flood covers me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 I'm weary with my crying <HI>there;</HI> &Verbar; my very throat is dry'd; &Verbar; mine eyes do fail, while that I do &Verbar; keep waiting for my God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 They that bear hatred unto me, &Verbar; tho' &s;till without a cau&s;e, &Verbar; <HI>the&s;e Men</HI> are multi|ply'd above &Verbar; the hairs upon my head. &Verbar; My cau&s;le&s;s enemies who would &Verbar; de&s;troy me, are grown &s;trong; &Verbar; Then I made re&s;titution of &Verbar; what I took not away. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O God, Thou knowe&s;t very well &Verbar; what is my fooli&s;hne&s;s; &Verbar; and my offences have not been &Verbar; at all conceal'd from thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 ETERNAL Lord of Ho&s;ts, Let not &Verbar; be &s;ham'd who hope on thee &Verbar; thro' me; not let thy &s;eekers blu&s;h &Verbar; for me, O I&s;raels God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7"><PB N="173" REF="001946_0210_0FFCB37020B13B70">
7 Becau&s;e that I have undergone &Verbar; reproach on thy account, &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> a confu&s;ion full of &s;hame &Verbar; has covered my face. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 I am unto my Bretheren &Verbar; but as a &s;tranger held, &Verbar; and to my Mothers Children I &Verbar; am held an alien. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Becau&s;e the hot Zeal of thy hou&s;e &Verbar; has ev'n devoured me; &Verbar; Contempts from tho&s;e who thee contemn, &Verbar; have al&s;o fall'n on me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 In fa&s;ts when I wept with my Soul, &Verbar; that turn'd to my reproach. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 When I wore Sackcloth, then I was &Verbar; a by-word unto them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 They who &s;at in the Gate pur&s;u'd &Verbar; me with their obloquies; &Verbar; and I was made the Songs of tho&s;e &Verbar; who take the Drunkards cup. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 But as for me, I turn my Prayer &Verbar; to Thee, ETERNAL God, &Verbar; in &s;uch a time, as I might hope &Verbar; to find acceptance in. &Verbar; In the great multitude of thy &Verbar; Mercy, hear me, O God; &Verbar; and for the Faithfulne&s;s which is &Verbar; in thy Salvation <HI>&s;ound.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Deliver me out of the mire, &Verbar; and let me not &s;ink <HI>there;</HI> &Verbar; From them that hate me let me be &Verbar; &s;av'd, and from deep waters. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Let not the flood of waters come &Verbar; over me, nor the deep &Verbar; &s;wallow me up, nor let the pit &Verbar; upon me &s;hut her mouth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 ETERNAL God, Hear me, for good &Verbar; is thy Benignity; &Verbar; Oh, in the multitude of thy &Verbar; compa&s;&s;ions turn to me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17"><PB N="174" REF="001946_0211_0FFCB442B58EE060">
17 And from thy Servant, O do not &Verbar; Thou hide thy face away; &Verbar; for that &s;ore trouble on me lies; &Verbar; O ha&s;te, O hear thou me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 O draw near to my Soul; for it &Verbar; do the Redeemer's part; &Verbar; Becau&s;e I have &s;uch enemies, &Verbar; redeem me <HI>from them all.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Thou ha&s;t known my reproach, and what &Verbar; a &s;hame they ca&s;t on me; &Verbar; And my di&s;honour; in thy view &Verbar; are all my enemies. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Reproach has broke my heart, and I &Verbar; have griev'd; When I look'd for &Verbar; condolence, there was none, and for &Verbar; comforters, none I found. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Nay, they for my refre&s;hment gave &Verbar; unto me bitter Gall; &Verbar; and in my thir&s;t they gave to me &Verbar; &s;our Vinegar to drink. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Their Table now let that become &Verbar; be|fore them but a &s;Hare; &Verbar; and what &s;hould be intended for &Verbar; Peace-Off'rings, but a trap. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Let darkne&s;s come upon their eyes, &Verbar; &s;o that they &s;hall not &s;ee; &Verbar; and make their loins to tremble &s;till &Verbar; for fear continually. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 Upon them direfully do thou &Verbar; thine indignation pour; &Verbar; and let the burning of thy wrath &Verbar; take a fa&s;t hold of them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 Their &s;tately Palace let it be &Verbar; entirely de&s;olate; &Verbar; within their Tabernacles let &Verbar; be no inhabitant. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 Since Him whom thou ha&s;t &s;mitten, they &Verbar; jo on to per&s;ecute; &Verbar; and they talk to the grief of tho&s;e &Verbar; who are thy wounded ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27"><PB N="175" REF="001946_0212_0FFCB37472B65C60">
27 Add <HI>more</HI> iniquity upon &Verbar; their <HI>pa&s;t</HI> in|iquity; &Verbar; <HI>And</HI> let them not admi&s;&s;ion have &Verbar; into thy righteou&s;ne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 Let them be blotted out of the &Verbar; Book of the living ones; &Verbar; and let them not in Writing be &Verbar; enrolled with the Ju&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="29">29 But I'm a poor afflicted one, &Verbar; and I am &s;orrowful; &Verbar; O God, Let thy Salvation now &Verbar; exalt me gloriou&s;ly. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="30">30 The Prai&s;es of the Name of God &Verbar; I'll utter with a Song; &Verbar; and I'll with a confe&s;&s;ion Him &Verbar; thankfully magnify. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="31">31 This al&s;o will more grateful be &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; than Beef or Calf on which the horns &Verbar; as well as hoofs appear. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="32">32 The humbled meek ones &s;hall behold; &Verbar; they &s;hall be very glad; &Verbar; O you that &s;eek <HI>the Glorious</HI> God, &Verbar; ev'n &s;o your heart &s;hall live. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="33">33 Becau&s;e th' ETERNAL God attends &Verbar; unto the indigent; &Verbar; and &s;uch as He doth hold in bonds, &Verbar; the&s;e He does not de&s;pi&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="34">34 <HI>Now</HI> let the Heavens, and the Earth &Verbar; <HI>unite in</HI> prai&s;ing Him; &Verbar; the Seas, and ev'ry thing that does &Verbar; move to and fro in them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="35">35 For Zion God will &s;ave, and He &Verbar; will Judah's Cities build; &Verbar; that Men may dwell therein and have &Verbar; it their Inheritance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="36">36 The Offspring of His Servants too, &Verbar; the&s;e &s;hall inherit it; &Verbar; and they who bear love to His Name, &Verbar; the&s;e &s;hall inhabit it. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="176" REF="001946_0213_0FFCB7CCD98EC538">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>WE have here a Prayer of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> in His Humiliation. It foretells the De&s;olation of the Jewi&s;h Nation: But a Glorious E&s;tabli&s;hment.</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>Theodoret</HI> well con&s;iders our SAVIOUR, as pay|ing a <HI>Debt,</HI> which was none of his own Contracting.</P>
<P N="5">5 <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> notes; That &s;ome take it &s;o; <Q>Thou knowe&s;t I have not been &s;o <HI>fooli&s;h,</HI> as my Per&s;ecutors a&s;&s;ert I have.</Q>&mdash;But there is no need of taking it &s;o.</P>
<P N="11">11 Was it not then become a Proverb, for the utmo&s;t Hatred or Contempt of any Man; <HI>I value him no more than I do</HI> David?</P>
<P N="12">12 The Language both of Graver Senators, and of Idle Companions.</P>
<P N="27">27 q. d. Suffer them to go on in compleating their <HI>Iniquity.</HI></P>
<P N="28">28 q. d. Let them enjoy none of the Ble&s;&s;ings <HI>Written</HI> in the Promi&s;es for the <HI>Righteous.</HI> To be Remem|bred in the <HI>Genealogical Tables,</HI> was matter of no little Con&s;equence. An <HI>Inheritance</HI> in the holy Land, was implied in it. The fir&s;t, if not chief u&s;e of Let|ters, was to keep the&s;e <HI>Genealogical Tables,</HI> in every Family. When a Family was increa&s;ed, the&s;e Tables were Tran&s;cribed for the u&s;e of New De&s;cendants. In the Tran&s;cription, they <HI>Blotted out</HI> what&s;oever oc|cured unnece&s;&s;ary, to carry down the Hi&s;tory of the Succe&s;&s;ion. The <HI>I&s;&s;uele&s;s</HI> were &s;o. Of <HI>Judab's</HI> Five Sons, the Two Elde&s;t were u&s;ele&s;s in the <HI>Heraldry,</HI> and were <HI>blotted out.</HI> Unto the&s;e Tables refer, <HI>Exod.</HI> XXXII. 32. And <HI>P&s;al.</HI> CIX. 13. Here is a Key to <HI>Dent.</HI> XXV. 6. The Book of Genealogies is here called, <HI>The Book of the Living,</HI> becau&s;e the <HI>Names</HI> of Men <HI>lived</HI> here, and the Men <HI>lived</HI> in their Po&s;terity. And it is called, A being <HI>Written with the Righteous,</HI> becau&s;e <HI>Fruitfulne&s;s,</HI> was among the <HI>Jews</HI> reckoned the Re|ward
<PB N="177" REF="001946_0214_0FFCB37ADDCDD648">of <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s.</HI> The failing of their <HI>Genea|logical Tables,</HI> among the Jews, is here foretold. How Remarkably 'tis Accompli&s;hed!</P>
<P N="31">31 The Jews refer it, unto the <HI>Fir&s;t Sacrifice</HI> offered by <HI>Adam,</HI> after his Fall. Conceive the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> who is the Second <HI>Adam,</HI> &s;peaking here, and it is worth Con&s;idering.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="70" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXX.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Of David. To bring to Remembrance.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O God, For to deliver me! &Verbar; O Thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; O do thou now make ha&s;te for the &Verbar; relief of my di&s;tre&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Let them be &s;ham'd and blu&s;h, who do&Verbar; &s;eek <HI>to de&s;troy</HI> my Soul; &Verbar; Let them be turn'd back, and perplext &Verbar; who do de&s;ire my hurt. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Let them be forc'd to turn about &Verbar; for a ju&s;t recompence &Verbar; of the &s;hame that belongs to them, &Verbar; who &s;ay, Aha, Aha. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Let all be glad and joy in thee, &Verbar; who &s;eek thee, and tho&s;e who &Verbar; love thy Salva|tion, ever &s;ay, &Verbar; Let God be magnify'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 But I'm a poor and needy one; &Verbar; Make ha&s;te to me, O God; &Verbar; O Thou ETERNAL, Thou my help &Verbar; and Saviour, tarry not. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>TIS the Prayer of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> in His wonderful Sufferings. In the la&s;t Ver&s;e He takes the very Name which is in <HI>Zech.</HI> IX. 9. a&s;&s;igned unto Him. He foretells the Mi&s;eries, which the Jews would procure to them&s;elves by the I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">juries they offered unto Him.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="71" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="178" REF="001946_0215_0FFCB7CE5FA7BAB0">
<HEAD>PSALM LXXI.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 IN Thee, O Thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; I do repo&s;e my tru&s;t; &Verbar; O let me not be put to &s;hame &Verbar; unto Eternity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Save thou me in thy righteou&s;ne&s;s, &Verbar; and cau&s;e me to e&s;cape; &Verbar; Incline thou unto me thine ear; &Verbar; And, O deliver me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Be Thou the Rock where I may dwell, &Verbar; and con&s;tantly re&s;ort; &Verbar; my &s;afety thou ha&s;t order'd; for &Verbar; Thou art my rock and &s;trength. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 My God, Deliver me from the &Verbar; hand of the wicked one; &Verbar; out of the hand of the unju&s;t, &Verbar; and of the cruel one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Becau&s;e, O Lord, th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; with hope I wait on thee: &Verbar; Thou'rt He on whom I place my tru&s;t &Verbar; ev'n from my early youth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 On Thee I lean ev'n from the womb: &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t extracted me &Verbar; out of my Mothers Bowels; Prai&s;e &Verbar; &s;hall ever be to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 I unto many am become &Verbar; a wondrous prodigy: &Verbar; But thou ha&s;t ever been to me &Verbar; a refuge very &s;trong. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O let my mouth be filled with &Verbar; <HI>Ex|pre&s;&s;ions of</HI> thy Prai&s;e; &Verbar; <HI>It &s;hall be with</HI> thy Glory <HI>fill'd</HI> &Verbar; all day * and every day. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O ca&s;t me not off in the time &Verbar; of <HI>my</HI> advanced Age: &Verbar; For&s;ake me not when that my &s;trength &Verbar; is under a decay. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 For they that are my enemies &Verbar;
<PB N="179" REF="001946_0216_0FFCB3819625EFE8">do &s;pend their talk on me, &Verbar; and they con&s;ult together who &Verbar; watch <HI>for to &s;eize</HI> my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 They &s;ay, God hath for&s;aken him; &Verbar; Now per&s;ecute <HI>the Man;</HI> &Verbar; And &s;eize upon him: for there is &Verbar; none to deliver him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 O God, Be'nt far from me: my God &Verbar; make ha&s;te unto my help. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 The adver&s;aries of my Soul, &Verbar; may they confounded be. &Verbar; <HI>Yea,</HI> may they be con&s;umed <HI>all,</HI> &Verbar; they who do &s;eek my hurt: &Verbar; may they be covered with reproach, &Verbar; and with di&s;|graceful &s;hame. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 But as for me, I will maintain &Verbar; my hope continually; &Verbar; and I &s;hall make additions &s;till &Verbar; to all thy glorious prai&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 My mouth &s;hall make relation of &Verbar; thy <HI>&s;potle&s;s</HI> right'ou&s;ne&s;s: &Verbar; of thy Salvation all the day; &Verbar; for I no numbers know. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 I'll walk in the &s;trength of the Lord, &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; I'll celebrate thy righteou&s;ne&s;s, &Verbar; yea, even thine alone. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 O God, Thou from my early youth &Verbar; ha&s;t well in&s;tructed me: &Verbar; and hitherto I have declar'd &Verbar; the wonders thou ha&s;t wrought. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Yea, even to the time when I &Verbar; mu&s;t &s;ee advanced age, &Verbar; and have gray hairs upon me, then, &Verbar; O God, for&s;ake me not &Verbar; till to this Generation I &Verbar; declare thy pow'r abroad, &Verbar; and unto every one that is &Verbar; to come, thy fortitude. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Thy righteou&s;ne&s;s therewith, O God, &Verbar;
<PB N="180" REF="001946_0217_0FFCB7D01DBBF428">unto the very heighth! &Verbar; Thou who do&s;t things &s;o very great: &Verbar; O God, Who's like to thee? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Thou art He who has &s;hown to me &Verbar; Afflictions great and &s;ore: &Verbar; Thou'lt quicken me again, and rai&s;e &Verbar; me from the depths of Farth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Thou ha&s;t giv'n an increa&s;e unto &Verbar; my bright magnificence; &Verbar; and con&s;olations given me, &Verbar; returning unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 With P&s;altry help't, now Thee I'll prai&s;e &Verbar; for thy truth, O my God: &Verbar; To thee I will &s;ing with the harp, &Verbar; O I&s;raels Holy One. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 My lips they &s;hall triumph with joy, &Verbar; when I do &s;ing to thee; &Verbar; and &s;o my Soul <HI>&s;halldo,</HI> which thou &Verbar; ha&s;t thoroughly redeem'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 My tongue too tells thy righteou&s;ne&s;s &Verbar; all day * and every day; &Verbar; for they're con|founded and di&s;grac'd, &Verbar; who do pur&s;ue my hurt. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>SEE the Church (and the Spirit of Prophecy repre|&s;enting the Condition of the <HI>Synagogue</HI> al&s;o) groaning under the Tyranny of Antichri&s;t; and hoping for a Re&s;toration after &s;o many Calamities.</P>
<P N="3">3 <HI>Mun&s;ter,</HI> Glo&s;s is, <HI>Tu mandabis Angelis tuis de me.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 A Remarkable Iu&s;tance that I Sam. XVII. 33, 47.</P>
<P N="16">16 O ye Servants o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> GOD, In your Mini&s;try handling that Subject, &s;ee whether He do not remarkably <HI>Strengthen</HI> you.</P>
</DIV3>
