<DIV1 N="3" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>THE THIRD BOOK OF PSALMS.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="73" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXIII.</HI> A P&s;alm of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BUt yet, <HI>This I will &s;ay,</HI> That God &Verbar; is good to I&s;rael; &Verbar; <HI>that is to &s;ay</HI> to them that are &Verbar; of a Well clean&s;ed Heart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 But as for me, my feet almo&s;t &Verbar; de|clin'd <HI>from what is right;</HI> &Verbar; &s;carce any thing <HI>appear'd,</HI> but that &Verbar; my Steps had run abroad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Becau&s;e I had &s;ome Envy at &Verbar; the madly boa&s;ting Fools; &Verbar; When I &s;aw the Pro&s;peri|ty &Verbar; of the Ungodly Ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 For in their Death there are no Bands; &Verbar; till then their &s;trength is firm. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="185" REF="001946_0222_0FFCB7D587C4CCD0">
5 They are not in Man's Labour, nor &Verbar; are plagu'd like <HI>other</HI> Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Therefore their Pride do's like a Chain &Verbar; encompa&s;s them about; &Verbar; Iniquity does co|ver them, &Verbar; <HI>e&s;teem'd</HI> an Ornament. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Their Eyes &s;tand out with fatne&s;s; they &Verbar; have more than Heart can wi&s;h. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 They wa&s;te; and &s;peaking ill, oppre&s;s; &Verbar; they talk, how loftily! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 They re&s;olutely &s;et their Mouth &Verbar; for to bla&s;pheme the Heav'ns; &Verbar; and their Tongue with their Calumnies &Verbar; does walk about the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Therefore His People do at length &Verbar; make their Return to this; &Verbar; When Waters of a Plenteous Cup &Verbar; are poured out to them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 And <HI>this is now the thing</HI> they &s;ay; &Verbar; How is it that God knows? &Verbar; or is there any knowledge in &Verbar; Him who is God on High? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Behold, the&s;e are th' ungodly Ones &Verbar; who pro&s;per in the World; &Verbar; of Riches they've a mighty Store &Verbar; obtained for them|&s;elves. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Surely, it is in vain that I &Verbar; have pu|rify'd my Heart; &Verbar; <HI>In vain</HI> that I have wa&s;h'd my hands &Verbar; in pure&s;t Innocence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Whereas I have been &s;till cha&s;tiz'd &Verbar; all day * and every day; &Verbar; and every Morn|ing I have had &Verbar; Rebuke be&s;tow'd on me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 If now I &s;hould re&s;olve with me. &Verbar;
<PB N="186" REF="001946_0223_0FFCB3934883E6B0">I'll &s;peak at &s;uch a rate; &Verbar; Thy Children's Ge|neration, Lo, &Verbar; <HI>will &s;ay,</HI> I've done ami&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 I did propo&s;e unto my &s;elf &Verbar; that I would know this thing; &Verbar; but it appear'd before my Eyes &Verbar; a labour trouble&s;ome. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 <HI>'Twas thus,</HI> until that I into &Verbar; God's Holy Places went; &Verbar; <HI>But then</HI> I clearly un|der&s;tood &Verbar; the latter End of them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Surely in Slipp'ry Places * and &Verbar; in dark Thou &s;ette&s;t them; &Verbar; Thou do&s;t cau&s;e that they &s;hall into &Verbar; frightfull De&s;tructions fall. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 To Ruin, Oh! How are they brought! &Verbar; How very &s;uddenly! &Verbar; They peri&s;h; They are quite con&s;um'd &Verbar; from things mo&s;t ter|rible. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 <HI>It's &s;ound</HI> but as a Dream when they &Verbar; awake out of their Sleep; &Verbar; Lord, at their, ri&s;ing thou wilt on &Verbar; their Image ca&s;t Con|tempt. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Truly on this Account my Heart &Verbar; within me waxed hot, &Verbar; and in my reins I underwent &Verbar; the Piercings of a Dart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 And as for me, I was become &Verbar; a, very fooli&s;h one; &Verbar; nor had I any knowledge; <HI>But</HI> &Verbar; was with Thee like the Bea&s;ts. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Yet as for me, I now will be &Verbar; with thee continually; &Verbar; <HI>To keep me from fal&s;e Steps</HI> thou ha&s;t &Verbar; kept hold on my right hand. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 Thou by thy Coun&s;el <HI>ever</HI> wilt &Verbar; give conduct unto me; &Verbar; and me Thou in bright glory then &Verbar; wilt afterwards receive. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25"><PB N="187" REF="001946_0224_0FFCB7D70BC20A50">
25 Whom in the Heavens have I <HI>to</HI> &Verbar; <HI>im|plore or to enjoy?</HI> &Verbar; And there is none upon the Earth &Verbar; whom I de&s;ire but Thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 When my fle&s;h and my heart do now &Verbar; with a con&s;umption fail; &Verbar; God is the &s;trength of my heart, and &Verbar; my portion evermore. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27">27 For, lo, they that go far from Thee, &Verbar; &s;hall peri&s;h utterly; &Verbar; each one who does a whoring go &Verbar; from thee thou do&s;t de&s;troy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 But as for me, it's good that I &Verbar; get * and keep near to God; &Verbar; I in the Lord ETERNAL hope &Verbar; to tell of all thy works. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, the reflection of the Faithful on the Pro&s;|perity enjoyed by the Followers and Abettors of <HI>Antichri&s;t:</HI> And their comfort in the Expectation of his De&s;truction. Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks, <HI>A&s;aph the Seer,</HI> might be one who liv'd in the days of <HI>Hezekiah:</HI> [2 Chron. XXIX. 30.] probably the Father of that E|minent Per&s;on, who was then the Recorder. The mi&s;erable Havock made by the <HI>A&s;&s;yrians,</HI> notwith&s;tanding <HI>He|zekiah's</HI> Reformation, might afford &s;ufficient Occa&s;ion for the P&s;alm. Or, the common Occurrences, which produce the XXXVII. P&s;alm would yield abundant occa&s;ion for the LXXIII.</P>
<P N="4">4 So great is their Power, they are not in danger of being <HI>bound</HI> over, by any humane Ju&s;tice for their Crimes. Nor are they afflicted with &s;ore di&s;ea&s;es: After a long Life they dye ea&s;ily. <HI>Mun&s;ter's</HI> Glo&s;s is, They have no Anxiety about their <HI>Widows</HI> and <HI>Orphans;</HI> They leave enough to them.</P>
<P N="7">7 They are <HI>&s;hort-&s;ighted</HI> People.</P>
<P N="14"><PB N="188" REF="001946_0225_0FFCB7D8D30F45C0">
14 q. d. I was dealt withal as a <HI>Malafactor.</HI> Such were puni&s;hed in the Morning.</P>
<P N="17">17 Did not he hear the XCII. P&s;alm Sung in the <HI>Sanctuary?</HI></P>
<P N="20">20 The Prophets of God, in&s;pired from the <HI>Sanctu|ary,</HI> or the <HI>Holy Place</HI> of the Heavenly World, have told us, that Men &s;hall be <HI>Rai&s;ed from the Dead,</HI> and &s;hall &s;ee a <HI>Day of Judgment,</HI> which will bring all to rights, and un&s;old the My&s;teries which now puzle us in the Conduct of Providence. This <HI>Re&s;urrection of the Dead,</HI> with the following <HI>Day of Judgment,</HI> is here intimated. Yea, the Chaldee Paraphra&s;e on the Text is; <HI>In Die Judicij magni, cum fne<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">int &s;u&s;citati de Sepulchris &s;uis.</HI> At that Day, Fir&s;t, the <HI>Pro&s;pe|rity of the Wicked,</HI> &s;hall appear to have been a <HI>Dream,</HI> It &s;hall be found &s;o at their <HI>Awaking.</HI> The <HI>Awaking of the Dead</HI> is the Scriptural Term for the <HI>Re&s;ur|rection.</HI> Should the following Word, <HI>Baguir,</HI> be rendred, <HI>in the City,</HI> as it is by many and Ancient In|terpreters, it would &s;uit admirably. The Tran&s;actions of the <HI>La&s;t Judgment</HI> will be very much carried on in the <HI>Heavenly City.</HI> But render it if you plea&s;e, <HI>In&s;u&s;citando;</HI> the plain Engli&s;h is, <HI>At thy Rai&s;ing them,</HI> or, <HI>At their Ri&s;ing.</HI> Well, what &s;hall be then? <HI>Thou wilt on their Image ca&s;t contempt.</HI> A notable Key to this you have in, Dan. XII. 2.&mdash;Let the Word <HI>Image</HI> &s;ignify either their <HI>Pro&s;perity;</HI> [See P&s;ai. XXXIX. 7.] or their <HI>Corruption.</HI> [See Gen. V. 3.] or their <HI>Spirit,</HI> or their <HI>Body;</HI> or their pompous <HI>Fa&s;hion</HI> of living in this World; [See 1 Cor. VII. 31.] &s;till it will be true. By <HI>Image,</HI> I would under&s;tand, whatever they value them&s;elves upon. Let it be remembred, The Word here al&s;o carries <HI>Puni&s;hment,</HI> in the Signi|fication of it.</P>
<P N="21">21 <HI>Arnobius</HI> finds cha&s;t living here.</P>
<P N="22">22 A <HI>Bea&s;t</HI> regards nothing but what is pre&s;ent.</P>
<P N="25">25 Says the Pious <HI>Harle;</HI> It &s;eems, <HI>Heaven</HI> is the
<PB N="189" REF="001946_0226_0FFCB39AA7141EB0">Place of <HI>having, Earth</HI> but of <HI>de&s;iring.</HI> Old <HI>Ray|mund</HI> in his <HI>Pugio Fidei,</HI> gives this Glo&s;s; <HI>Who will</HI> give me <HI>to be in Heaven with Thee? On Earth I de&s;ire not</HI> to be. <HI>Arnobius</HI> makes it the Language of our Saviour, having fini&s;hed all His Work on <HI>Earth,</HI> and going to <HI>Heaven,</HI> where he had before conver&s;ed continually.</P>
<P N="28">28 The <HI>Works</HI> of Providence in pre&s;erving the Righ|teous and de&s;troying the Wicked.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="74" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXIV.</HI> A P&s;alm of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O God, why ha&s;t thou ca&s;t us off &Verbar; to perpetuity? &Verbar; Again&s;t the Sheep which thou do&s;t feed, &Verbar; why does thy Anger &s;moke? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Remember thine A&s;&s;embly, thou &Verbar; ha&s;t purcha&s;ed of Old; &Verbar; the Tribe thou ha&s;t re|deemed for &Verbar; thy own Inheritance. &Verbar; This mount of Zion in the which, &Verbar; Thou'&s;t had thy dwelling-place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Lift up thy feet, <HI>with ha&s;te to tread</HI> &Verbar; <HI>where Enemies have made</HI> &Verbar; the de&s;olations <HI>that appear</HI> &Verbar; <HI>to be</HI> perpetual; &Verbar; <HI>and &s;mite</HI> each enemy that has done &Verbar; ill to thy holy Place.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 In the mid&s;t of thy Synagogue &Verbar; the ene|mies do roar &Verbar; <HI>as if po&s;&s;e&s;s'd of Prey,</HI> they have &Verbar; &s;et up their &s;igns for &s;igns. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Notice is taken of the Man &Verbar; who car|ries up on high &Verbar; Axes among the thicke&s;t boughs &Verbar; of the Trees in the wood. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="190" REF="001946_0227_0FFCB3A1C3AC0488">
6 So now with an united force &Verbar; at once they batter down &Verbar; with the Ax and with Hammers, all &Verbar; the carved works thereof. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Thy Sanctuary they have ca&s;t &Verbar; into the wa&s;ting Fire, &Verbar; they have defil'd the dwel|ling place &Verbar; of thy Name down to Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 They &s;aid within their hearts, Let us &Verbar; de&s;troy them altogether; &Verbar; They've burnt up all the Synagogues &Verbar; of God throughout the Land. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Our Signs we &s;ee not; There is not &Verbar; a Prophet any more; &Verbar; with us there is not any one &Verbar; that knows how long 'twill be. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 The adver&s;ary, Thee, O God, &Verbar; How long &s;hall he reproach? &Verbar; The Enemy, &s;hall he bla&s;pheme &Verbar; thy Name for evermore? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Thy hand ev'n thy right hand, where|fore &Verbar; do&s;t thou withdraw <HI>from us?</HI> &Verbar; From the mid&s;t of thy bo&s;om take &Verbar; thou it, them to con&s;ume. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 For Thou, O God the Judge, do&s;t reign &Verbar; my King from ancient time; &Verbar; Salvations He does bring about &Verbar; in the mid&s;t of the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Thou by thy mighty &s;trength did&s;t make &Verbar; the Sea divide a&s;under, &Verbar; the heads of Dra|gons thou did&s;t break &Verbar; under the Waters <HI>there.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Thou did&s;i with wounding brui&s;e the head &Verbar; of the Leviathan; &Verbar; with him thou fed&s;t the People which &Verbar; dwelt in the wil|derne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15"><PB N="191" REF="001946_0228_0FFCB39FE1092F10">
15 By cleaving thou did&s;t cau&s;e to flow &Verbar; the fountain and the flood; &Verbar; Thou did&s;t dry up the Rivers which &Verbar; ran with a mighty force. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 <HI>Even</HI> the Day <HI>it&s;elf</HI> is thine, &Verbar; thine al&s;o is the Night; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t prepar'd the Light and the &Verbar; Sun <HI>which di&s;pen&s;es it.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Thou'rt He, who hath appointed all &Verbar; the Borders of the Earth; &Verbar; The Summer and the Winter, thou &Verbar; art He that formed them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Remember this, th' Enemy has &Verbar; re|proach'd th' ETERNAL God; &Verbar; The People vain thro' folly, ca&s;t &Verbar; contempt upon thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Thy Turtle-dove's Soul, O give not &Verbar; up to the multitude; &Verbar; The Congregation of thy Poor &Verbar; forget them not fore'er. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 O do thou have re&s;pect unto &Verbar; the <HI>An|cient</HI> Covenant; &Verbar; for th' Earth's dark places are fill'd with &Verbar; dwellings of cruelty. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 O let not the oppre&s;&s;ed one &Verbar; return <HI>from Thee</HI> a&s;ham'd: &Verbar; <HI>But</HI> let the meek afflicted one &Verbar; and the Poor prai&s;e thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Do thou ari&s;e, O God; appear &Verbar; thou to defend thy cau&s;e; &Verbar; Remember thy re|proach from the &Verbar; vain Fool <HI>heard</HI> every day. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Forget not thou the voice of them &Verbar; that are thine Enemies: &Verbar; The noi&s;e of them who do ri&s;e up &Verbar; again&s;t thee daily grows. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="192" REF="001946_0229_0FFCB7DBC8E000D0">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE Spirit of Prophecy here livelily repre&s;ents the &s;tate of the <HI>Jewi&s;h</HI> Nation, in their Di&s;|per&s;ion under the <HI>Romans.</HI> Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks, the <HI>A&s;aph</HI> by whom the P&s;alm was written, lived in the time of the Captivity, and perhaps near the Conclu&s;ion of it, when there was no <HI>Prophet</HI> left, who could in|form them, <HI>How Long!</HI> Was it not <HI>A&s;aph,</HI> the Keeper of the Kings Fore&s;t, in the days of <HI>Nehemiah?</HI></P>
<P N="3">3 q. a. Make ha&s;te and come and vi&s;it the Ruins that have la&s;ted a long while, and without thy power|ful help will never be repaired.</P>
<P N="12">12 A <HI>Geographical</HI> Curio&s;ity! The Land of <HI>Judea</HI> was in the middle of the then inhabited <HI>Earth.</HI> And this was the Stage whereon the Price of our Eternal <HI>Salvation</HI> was effected. Compare, <HI>Ezek.</HI> V. 5. Not only <HI>Ca&s;aubon</HI> finds that Land in the mid&s;t of the Seven Climates, then known, but <HI>Villalpandus</HI> with his Compa&s;&s;es finds it in the very <HI>Center</HI> of the World. <HI>Kimchi</HI> has much this way: E&s;pecially on <HI>Ezek.</HI> XXXVIII. 12. where 'tis called, <HI>The Navel of the Earth. Eu|cherius</HI> goes on to Remark, our SAVIOUR undergoing what He did for us in this Land. [He adds al&s;o <HI>In utero Virginali.</HI>] <HI>Au&s;tin</HI> has this Glo&s;s upon it; <HI>This was done, when the Word was made Fle&s;h and inha|bited a Body of Earth.</HI> One Mr. <HI>Smith</HI> ob&s;erves, How God accommodated the <HI>Earth,</HI> by having His Church and Word, in the <HI>mid&s;t</HI> of it.</P>
<P N="14">14 An Allu&s;ion to <HI>Pharoah's</HI> Death. <HI>The breaking the Head of the Dragons in the Waters,</HI> the An|cients with <HI>Arnobius</HI> had this Glo&s;s upon it; <HI>Con|fregi&s;ti Capita Daemonum in Bapti&s;mate,</HI> 'Tis done in <HI>Bapti&s;m.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="75" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="193" REF="001946_0230_0FFCB7DDFA3686E0">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXV.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Alta&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">bith. A P&s;alm of A&s;aph. A Song.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 WE do give thanks to Thee, O God; &Verbar; we do give thanks <HI>to Thee;</HI> &Verbar; For that thy Name is near <HI>to us</HI> &Verbar; thy wondrous works declare. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 When I &s;hall at th' appointed time &Verbar; re|ceive into my hands the Congregation, I will Judge &Verbar; Things that are wholly right. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 The Earth and all of them that are &Verbar; Inhabitants on it, &Verbar; are clean di&s;&s;olv'd; its I that do &Verbar; uphold it's Pillars now. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 I to the fooli&s;h Madmen &s;aid, &Verbar; deal not &s;o fooli&s;hly; &Verbar; and to the wicked ones I &s;aid, &Verbar; Lift you not up the horn. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Lift you not up the horn on high &Verbar; <HI>a|gain&s;t the Highe&s;t One;</HI> &Verbar; Utter not &s;peeches with a neck &Verbar; that wont receive the yoke.</P>
<P N="6">6 Becau&s;e what you look for does come not from the ri&s;ing Sun, &Verbar; nor from the &s;et|ting, nor from the &Verbar; mountainous wilderne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 But God <HI>Him&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">.</HI> He is the Judge <HI>acting with Equity:</HI> One Ma<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="5 letters">, does pu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> down, and He &Verbar; does &s;et another o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">.</P>
<P N="8">8 For the ETERNAL God has in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> hand<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> a mea&s;uring cup; &Verbar; and the Wine <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">r|tain'd therein</HI> &Verbar; is in its <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">. Its ful<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> of mixture; And He <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> the dregs &Verbar; thereof all their <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> &s;hall &s;uch, &s;hall <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"></P>
<P N="9"><PB N="194" REF="001946_0231_0FFCB3A5C94F1268">
9 But as for me, I will declare &Verbar; <HI>this thing</HI> Forevermore: &Verbar; Unto the God of Jacob I &Verbar; will &s;ing <HI>His Glorious Prai&s;e.</HI> &Verbar;.</P>
<P N="10">10 And all the horns of wicked ones, &Verbar; I'll utterly cut off; &Verbar; But the horns of the Righ|teous one &Verbar; &s;hall be lift up on high. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the Expectation which the Church has, for the future Kingdom of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> In the <HI>Fifth</HI> Ver&s;e, we have the Fate of the <HI>Little Horn,</HI> Dan. VII. 11. In the <HI>Eighth,</HI> we have the <HI>Cup</HI> &s;o re|markable in the Prophecies, <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> LI. 21, 22. <HI>Rev.</HI> XVII. 19.</P>
<P N="1">1 The Kingdom of <HI>David</HI> was now near; which was a Figure of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iab's.</HI> The Miracles done for and by him, and the Revolutions on the Nation in his favour were <HI>wondrous Works</HI> of GOD.</P>
<P N="2">2 Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> will have our <HI>A&s;aph</HI> here, to be him in, 2 Chron. XXIX. 30. &mdash; and thinks the &s;trange De|&s;truction of <HI>Senacherib's</HI> Army, referr'd unto. Here <HI>Hezekiah</HI> then re&s;olves, as &s;oon as they could have their <HI>A&s;&s;emblies</HI> again, he would perfect the Reforma|tion he had begun before.</P>
<P N="7">7 Some have had their witty De&s;cants on the <HI>North,</HI> not being mentioned here. But is not the Word, which has been rendred, <HI>The South,</HI> rather to be read, <HI>The Wilderne&s;s?</HI> Which lay to the <HI>North</HI> as well as the <HI>South.</HI> Some have thus De&s;canted on it. The <HI>Ori|entals</HI> were generally given to <HI>Afarology.</HI> They took Promotion to come from the <HI>Stars;</HI> e&s;pecially, The <HI>Sun.</HI> The P&s;almi&s;t &s;ays, No; Promotion comes not from the Planett <HI>Ri&s;ing</HI> and <HI>Setting,</HI> or exalted in the <HI>Mid-Heaven.</HI> From the <HI>North</HI> none expected it. Yea, and el&s;ewhere we read, <HI>On the North was Mount
<PB N="195" REF="001946_0232_0FFCB3C5F88C4D98">Sion, the City of the Great King.</HI> Here was the &s;pecial Pre&s;ence of the Great King from whom <HI>all Promotion.</HI></P>
<P N="8">8 The Puni&s;hments inflicted by GOD, are often like an intoxicating <HI>Wine,</HI> full of &s;tupifying Ingredients, which loo&s;ens the very Joynts, and takes away all &s;trength to re&s;i&s;t.</P>
<P N="10">10 The <HI>Midra&s;h Tillin</HI> has a notable Glo&s;s; That by the <HI>Horns of the Wicked</HI> are meant, The <HI>Ten Horns</HI> of the Fourth Monarchy in the Vi&s;ions of <HI>Daniel.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="76" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXVI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. On Neginoth. A P&s;alm of A&s;aph. A Song.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 IN Judah God is known; His Name &Verbar; is great in I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In Salem too's His tent; and in &Verbar; Zion His dwelling Place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 There did He break in pieces <HI>all</HI> &Verbar; the Arrows of the Bow; &Verbar; <HI>There did He break</HI> the Shield and Sword, &Verbar; and what belong'd War. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Illu&s;trious Thou do&s;t appear, &Verbar; wondrou&s;ly powerful, &Verbar; upon the Mountains where <HI>wild Bea&s;ts,</HI> &Verbar; <HI>and Robbers &s;eek</HI> their Prey. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Stout-hearted ones are &s;poil'd they've &s;lept &Verbar; the &s;leep <HI>de&s;ign'd</HI> for them; &Verbar; and none of all the mighty Men &Verbar; found <HI>the u&s;e</HI> of their hands. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 O God of Jacob, 'Twas at thy &Verbar; effectual rebuke &Verbar; that both the Chariot and the Hor&s;e &Verbar; were laid &s;o dead a&s;leep. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Thou, even Thou, art one that is &Verbar;
<PB N="196" REF="001946_0233_0FFCB3ADB08449C0">exceeding terrible; &Verbar; and who &s;hall &s;tand be|fore thy face &Verbar; when once thou art provok'd</P>
<P N="8">8 Thou did&s;t cau&s;e Judgment for to be &Verbar; heard from the Heav'ns above; &Verbar; the Earth was &s;truck with trembling fear, &Verbar; and then &s;aw quiet re&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 When God the Judge for to di&s;pen&s;e &Verbar; <HI>His</HI> Judgments did ari&s;e; &Verbar; for to fave all the meek who were &Verbar; afflicted on the Earth. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Surely the wrath of Man &s;hall but &Verbar; confe&s;s thy prai&s;e to thee; &Verbar; and the re|mainder of the wrath &Verbar; is what thou &s;halt re&s;train. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Vow and pay to th' ETERNAL One, &Verbar; ev'n Him who is your God; &Verbar; you that &s;ur|round Him, bring a gift &Verbar; to Him who's to be fear'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 He &s;hall cut off the &s;pirits of &Verbar; Princes in Vintage time; &Verbar; He &s;hall be terrible unto &Verbar; the Kings that rule the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXVI PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>COmpare the <HI>Fifth</HI> Ver&s;e of the P&s;alm with the XXXVIII, and XXXIX Chapters of <HI>Ezekiel,</HI> and you would here think on the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah's</HI> Triumph over <HI>Gog</HI> and <HI>Magog.</HI> The <HI>Vintage</HI> in the la&s;t Ver&s;e leads one to <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> LXIII. and <HI>Rev.</HI> XIX. Whether the for|mer P&s;alm had a reference to <HI>Sonacherib's</HI> overthrow or no, 'tis more probable that this may have &s;o. <HI>The|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">dor<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"></HI> a&s;&s;ures us, That in &s;ome Copies of the Greek Ver&s;ion, he found this Title, <HI>An Ode again&s;t the A&s;&s;y|rians.</HI></P>
<P N="4"><PB N="197" REF="001946_0234_0FFCB7E08D361098">
4 The <HI>A&s;&s;yrians</HI> had been on the Mountains about <HI>J<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ru&s;alem,</HI> committing depredations. But God ap|pear'd mo&s;t <HI>Excellent,</HI> Glorious, Illu&s;trious, in what He did on tho&s;e <HI>Mountains.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 Be&s;ure the A&s;&s;yrians lay down to <HI>Sleep</HI> and never Waked. [2 Kin. XIX. 35.]</P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Hezekiah</HI> went into the <HI>Temple,</HI> and Pray'd unto GOD who dwelt between the <HI>Cherubim.</HI> There GOD gave the Sentence and Order for this wonderful thing to be done. [See Ver&s;e 3.] To cut off the Leaders of <HI>Senacherib's</HI> Army. [2 Chron. XXXII. 21.] He took away their Lives at once, as a Gardener does the Franches of a <HI>Vine,</HI> or the Bunches of the <HI>Grape.</HI> In the Fate of <HI>Senacherib,</HI> there was done a thing <HI>terri|ble</HI> to the <HI>Kings of the Earth.</HI></P>
