<DIV2 N="77" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXVII.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician to Jeduthun. A P&s;alm of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 MY Voice was unto God, and I &Verbar; did make an earne&s;t cry; &Verbar; My voice was unto God, and He &Verbar; did hearken unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In the day of my trouble I &Verbar; did &s;eek the Lord; my wound, &Verbar; &s;pread in the Night, and re&s;ted not; &Verbar; my Soul refus'd relief. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 I did remember God, and then &Verbar; was greatly di&s;compos'd: &Verbar; I did complain; my &s;pirit then &Verbar; was overwhelm'd with grief. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 The watchings thou did&s;t apprehend &Verbar; which did attend my eyes; &Verbar; I was &s;eiz'd with a&s;toni&s;hment &Verbar; &s;o that I could not &s;leep. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 I have con&s;idered the days &Verbar; which were in Ancient time; &Verbar; <HI>I have con&s;idered</HI> the Years &Verbar; of Ages yet unknown. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="198" REF="001946_0235_0FFCB7E238A78270">
6 My Song I thought on; in the Night I commun'd with my heart; &Verbar; and then my &s;pirit made a &s;earch, &Verbar; <HI>to find the matter out.</HI>&Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 The Lord, <HI>on whom I lean,</HI> will He &Verbar; call off forevermore? &Verbar; And will he not go o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> to &s;how &Verbar; His favour any more? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 His mercy, does it wholly fail &Verbar; to perpetuity? &Verbar; What? For whole Generati|ons does &Verbar; His Word to nothing come? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 What? Has the mighty God forgot &Verbar; for to be merciful? &Verbar; Has He His tender bowels in &Verbar; great anger quite &s;hut up? &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Then, <HI>upon this,</HI> I &s;aid, This is &Verbar; but my infirmity; &Verbar; The years of Change are all in the &Verbar; Right hand of the mo&s;t High. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 I will remember the Works of &Verbar; the EVER-BEING One; &Verbar; &s;urely I'll in remem|brance have &Verbar; thy wonder done of old. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Yea, I will meditate upon &Verbar; all of thy Glorious work; &Verbar; and will * with Prayers and wonders &s;peak &Verbar; of things which thou ha&s;t done. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 O God, Thy way <HI>proceeds, and is</HI> &Verbar; <HI>bebeld</HI> in holine&s;s; &Verbar; Who is the mighty God, &s;o great &Verbar; as is <HI>our</HI> God the Judge? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Thou art the mighty God; who does &Verbar; the thing that's wonderful; &Verbar; among the Peo|ple openly &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t declar'd thy &s;trength. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Thou ha&s;t redeem'd thy People with &Verbar; thy own extended Arm; &Verbar; <HI>Thou ha&s;t redeem'd</HI> the Children of &Verbar; Jacob and Jo&s;eph &s;o. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16"><PB N="199" REF="001946_0236_0FFCB3B234EA2480">
16 The waters thee beheld, O God, &Verbar; the waters thee beheld; &Verbar; they were afraid; the deeps them&s;elves &Verbar; in a commotion were. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Thick clouds did of their waters make &Verbar; an inundation then; &Verbar; The sky gave out a thundering &s;ound; &Verbar; thy darts too went abroad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 The loud voice of thy Thunder was &Verbar; in th' Revolution heard; &Verbar; The Lighthings &s;truck light on the World; &Verbar; the Earth was mov'd and &s;hook. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 The way which thou did&s;t take was in &Verbar; the Sea, thy paths were in &Verbar; the mighty &s;welling waters; and &Verbar; thy foot&s;teps are unknown. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 <HI>Then</HI> by the hand of Mo&s;es, and &Verbar; of Aaron <HI>join'd with him;</HI> &Verbar; thy People thou did&s;t lead along &Verbar; ev'n like unto a Flock. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>SEE we not here the <HI>Jewi&s;h Nation</HI> in a Meditation on their De&s;olate Condition, as rejected of God? And yet comforting them&s;elves with reflecting on His Ancient Miracles and Promi&s;es.</P>
<P N="3">3 To Remember how kind our GOD has been to us formerly; this only gives us the Greater <HI>Trouble,</HI> when we Compare it with our pre&s;ent Mi&s;eries.</P>
<P N="10">10 q. d. I &s;aid, this is the thing that &s;orely afflicts me;&mdash;To &s;ee the change in the proceedings of the Mo&s;t High towards me. To this purpo&s;e, Dr. <HI>Patricks</HI> Paraphra&s;e.</P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Mun&s;ters</HI> reading is, <HI>In Sancto.</HI> The whole <HI>Way of Ged</HI> has a mo&s;t un&s;potted <HI>Sanctity</HI> ever Shining in it.</P>
<P N="18"><PB N="200" REF="001946_0237_0FFCB7E3E6E77900">
18 How far did the <HI>Thunder,</HI> which accompaniment the promulgation of the Law on Mount <HI>Sinai,</HI> cau&s;e the Earth to tremble? See Jo&s;h. II. 10, 11. <HI>As &s;oon <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> we heard our Hearts did molt.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
