<DIV2 N="78" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXVIII.</HI> Ma&s;chil. Of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Ye my People, Hearken well &Verbar; to my di&s;tilling law: &Verbar; Incline your ear attentively &Verbar; to the words of my mouth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 My mouth I'll open in a dark &Verbar; * Sententious Parable; &Verbar; I'll utter &s;ecret my|&s;teries &Verbar; <HI>in what fell out of</HI> old. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 They are the things which we have heard, &Verbar; and <HI>things which</HI> we have known; &Verbar; and they are what our Fathers have &Verbar; related unto us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 The&s;e we will not conceal from them &Verbar; that are Children to tho&s;e; &Verbar; They to the Generation <HI>&s;o</HI> &Verbar; to come &s;hall <HI>&s;till</HI> relate: &Verbar; Even the Prai&s;es which belong &Verbar; to the E|TERNAL God; &Verbar; and His &s;trength and His wondrous works; &Verbar; the Things which He has wrought. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 A te&s;timony He did in &Verbar; Jacob e&s;tabli&s;h <HI>&s;o;</HI> &Verbar; and He made an appointment of &Verbar; a law in I&s;rael: &Verbar; The things the which He did command &Verbar; unto our Ance&s;tors, &Verbar; that they unto their Children &s;hould &Verbar; commu|nicate the &s;ame. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="201" REF="001946_0238_0FFCB3B82441F798">
6 That &s;o the Generation &s;till &Verbar; to come might know <HI>the things;</HI> &Verbar; the Children to be born might ri&s;e &Verbar; and to their Children tell. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 That they might &s;et their hope in God, &Verbar; and not forget the works &Verbar; which God has done, but that they might &Verbar; keep His Com|mandements. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 And not be as their Fathers were, &Verbar; a Generation bent &Verbar; upon Apo&s;ta&s;y <HI>from God,</HI> &Verbar; and a rebellous <HI>Race:</HI> &Verbar; A Generation which did not &Verbar; direct their heart aright; &Verbar; nor was their &s;pirit faithfully &Verbar; adhering &s;till to God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Well-armed were the Children which &Verbar; i&s;&s;ued from Ephraim; &Verbar; with Bow they &s;hot; and yet in day &Verbar; of Battle turned back. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 For they were &s;uch as had not kept &Verbar; the Covenant of God: &Verbar; they al&s;o had refus'd to walk &Verbar; according to His law. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Yea, and they had forgotten quite &Verbar; the Works which He had wrought; &Verbar; and the Things very Marvellous &Verbar; which He had &s;hown to them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Things very Marvellous He did &Verbar; be|fore their Ance&s;tors; &Verbar; He in the Land of Egypt, <HI>in</HI> &Verbar; the field of Zoan <HI>wrought.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 He did divide the Sea, and gave &Verbar; to them a pa&s;&s;age thro'; &Verbar; The Waters He did make to &s;tand &Verbar; collected as an Heap. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 He with a Cloud did give to them &Verbar; His Conduct in the Day; &Verbar; and with the Bright|ne&s;s of a Fire &Verbar; <HI>over them</HI> all the Night. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15"><PB N="202" REF="001946_0239_0FFCB7E81C307228">
15 He in the Wilderne&s;s did cleave &Verbar; the &s;olid Rock a&s;under; &Verbar; and He did make them for to Drink &Verbar; as out of mighty Deeps. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Yea, He did bring forth flowing Streams &Verbar; out of the &s;olid Stone; &Verbar; and like to Rivers He did cau&s;e &Verbar; the Waters to run down. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 But they in Sinning again&s;t Him &Verbar; did add yet more and more; &Verbar; Thereby provok|ing the mo&s;t High &Verbar; while in the Wilder|ne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 And in their Heart Tempting of Him &Verbar; they tried the mighty God; &Verbar; <HI>They did it by</HI> De&s;iring food &Verbar; to &s;uit their Appetite. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Yea, They bla&s;phem'd the <HI>Glorious</HI> God; &Verbar; and this is what they &s;aid; &Verbar; Can God prepare a Table <HI>here</HI> &Verbar; in <HI>&s;uch</HI> a Wil|derne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Behold, He &s;mote the Rock and then &Verbar; the Waters gu&s;hed out; &Verbar; The Torrents then did running there &Verbar; an Inundation make. &Verbar; But what? can He al&s;o be&s;tow &Verbar; <HI>upon His People</HI> Bread? &Verbar; What? will He make provi&s;ion of &Verbar; fie&s;h for His People <HI>too?</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Therefore the ETERNAL heard, and was &Verbar; Angry: &s;o kindled was &Verbar; a Fire on Ja|cob, and Wrath went &Verbar; up again&s;t I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Becau&s;e that they had not reli'd &Verbar; with faith upon <HI>their</HI> God; &Verbar; not had they then their Confidence &Verbar; in His Salvation plac'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23"><PB N="203" REF="001946_0240_0FFCB7E9A2899550">
23 Altho' He from above had given &Verbar; Com|mand unto the Clouds, &Verbar; and opened wide the Gates of Heav'n, &Verbar; <HI>as of a Granary.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 And He from thence had rained down &Verbar; Manna on them to Eat; &Verbar; yea, and the Corn of Heaven too &Verbar; He had be&s;tow'd on them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 A Man was then allow'd to Eat &Verbar; the Bread of mighty ones; &Verbar; He did <HI>of that</HI> &s;end unto them &Verbar; a Diet to their full. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 He in the Heavens then did cau&s;e &Verbar; an Ea&s;tern wind to blow; &Verbar; and by His mighty power He did &Verbar; bring in a Southern wind. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27">27 He did rain down upon them Fle&s;h &Verbar; <HI>in plenty</HI> like the du&s;t; &Verbar; and like the Sand that bounds the Seas &Verbar; a Fowl that had a wing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 And in the midde&s;t of their Camps &Verbar; He cau&s;ed <HI>it</HI> to fall; &Verbar; <HI>yea, and</HI> in the whole circuit of &Verbar; their Habitations there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="29">29 So they did eat thereof, and they &Verbar; were well repleni&s;hed; &Verbar; and He did bring to them the thing &Verbar; that was their own de&s;ire. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="30">30 They were not yet e&s;tranged from &Verbar; what was their own de&s;ire: &Verbar; their Meat <HI>they had &s;o much de&s;ir'd</HI> &Verbar; as yet was in their mouth; &Verbar;</P>
<P N="31">31 When the great Wrath of God did <HI>like</HI> &Verbar; <HI>a Fire</HI> a&s;cend on them; &Verbar; and &s;lew their fat ones, and &s;mote down &Verbar; the chief of I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="32">32 But notwith&s;tanding all of this, &Verbar; they &s;till went on to Sin; &Verbar; and they did not give credit to &Verbar; His very wondrous works. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="33"><PB N="204" REF="001946_0241_0FFCB3BD6CA0E188">
33 Therefore He made their days to wa&s;te &Verbar; away in vanity; &Verbar; yea, and their years in trouble which &Verbar; quickly di&s;patched them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="34">34 When He &s;truck them with Death, on this &Verbar; then they did &s;eek to Him: &Verbar; Then they re|turn'd, and early they &Verbar; enquired after God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="35">35 Then they call'd to remembrance that &Verbar; God was their &s;heltring Rock; &Verbar; and the High God claim'd &s;till to give &Verbar; Redemption unto them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="36">36 Neverthele&s;s with a fal&s;e mouth, &Verbar; they did but flatter Him; &Verbar; and with their tongues <HI>that &s;poke &s;o fair</HI> &Verbar; they did but lie to Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="37">37 For &s;till their heart with right intents &Verbar; was not re&s;olv'd for Him; &Verbar; nor in His Co|venant did they &Verbar; u&s;e good fidelity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="38">38 But being merciful, He did &Verbar; forgive iniquity; &Verbar; And He then did not upon them &Verbar; <HI>de&s;erv'd</HI> de&s;truction bring: &Verbar; No, He did multiply the Acts &Verbar; in which He turn'd away &Verbar; His anger, and therewith He did &Verbar; not &s;tir up all His wrath. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="39">39 For He remembred this of them; &Verbar; that they were <HI>feeble</HI> Fle&s;h, &Verbar; a Spirit that pa&s;&s;eth away, &Verbar; and cometh not again. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="40">40 How often in the De&s;ert they &Verbar; pro|vok'd Him bitterly! &Verbar; <HI>Have often</HI> in the Wil|derne&s;s &Verbar; they irritated Him! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="41">41 Yea, they returned back unto &Verbar; their way or tempting God; &Verbar; Limits they al&s;o did preservable bed to Frank Holy One. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="42"><PB N="205" REF="001946_0242_0FFCB7EBA1AC4CE0">
42 They did not well remember <HI>what</HI> &Verbar; His Hand <HI>had wrought for them;</HI> &Verbar; the Day when He delivered them &Verbar; out of Adver&s;ity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="43">43 How He in Egypt <HI>wrought and</HI> &s;et &Verbar; His mo&s;t amazing Signs; &Verbar; and in the Field or Zoan there, His Works mo&s;t wonderful, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="44">44 There He had with a <HI>&s;trange turn</HI> chang'd &Verbar; their Rivers into blood, &Verbar; and chang'd their Floods at &s;uch a rate, &Verbar; they could not drink thereof. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="45">45 He &s;ent the Dog-fly upon them, &Verbar; which prey'd upon them &s;ore; &Verbar; <HI>He &s;ent</HI> the Frogs too which did bring, de&s;truction upon them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="46">46 Unto the Caterpillar He &Verbar; did give up their increa&s;e; &Verbar; and to the Locu&s;t He gave up &Verbar; what they had labour'd for. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="47">47 He kill'd their Vines with Hail, and their &Verbar; Sycomore Trees with Fro&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="48">48 And left their Cattle to the Hail, &Verbar; their Flocks to Lightning too. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="49">49 He ca&s;t on them His burning Wrath, &Verbar; Anger, and great Di&s;dain, &Verbar; with Trouble; Evil Angels were &Verbar; commi&s;&s;ion'd <HI>for the work.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="50">50 He for His Anger weigh'd a path; &Verbar; He &s;pared not their Soul &Verbar; from Death, but He gave up their life &Verbar; unto the Pe&s;tilence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="51">51 All the Fir&s;t-born of Egypt then &Verbar; He &s;mote; The Fir&s;t-fruits of &Verbar; <HI>their</HI> Forces, in the Tents that were &Verbar; inhabited by Cham. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="52">52 But He made His own People to &Verbar;
<PB N="206" REF="001946_0243_0FFCB7EE89CBB890">go forth like unto Sheep; &Verbar; and He did in the Wilderne&s;s &Verbar; guide them like as a Flock. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="53">53 He did guide them in &s;afety, &s;o &Verbar; that they were not afraid; &Verbar; But the Sea over|whelmed them &Verbar; that were their Enemies. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="54">54 He brought them to the border of &Verbar; His Sanctuary <HI>here;</HI> &Verbar; the mountain which His own right Hand &Verbar; had made a purcha&s;e of. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="55">55 And He before their faces did &Verbar; ca&s;t out the Nations <HI>there;</HI> &Verbar; yea, He did cau&s;e them for to fall &Verbar; in the divided Lotts, &Verbar; when there was to be ca&s;t a Line &Verbar; for their inheri|tance; &Verbar; and in their Tents He made to dwell &Verbar; the Tribes of I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="56">56 Yet they did by temptations try &Verbar; and bitterly provoke &Verbar; the mo&s;t High God, and they kept not &Verbar; the things He te&s;tify'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="57">57 But they returned to their wont &Verbar; and dealt perfidiou&s;ly, &Verbar; like to their Ance&s;tors; they warp'd &Verbar; like a deceitful bow. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="58">58 For that with their high places they &Verbar; provoked Him to wrath; &Verbar; and with their graven Images &Verbar; mov'd Him to jealou&s;y. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="59">59 <HI>This Thing</HI> when God the Judge did hear. &Verbar; He then was mov'd to wrath; &Verbar; yea, He with great abhorrence ca&s;t &Verbar; contempt on I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="60">60 So He the Tabernacle of &Verbar; Shiloh did then for&s;ake; &Verbar; The Tent which He had plac'd for to &Verbar; cohabit there with Man. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="61">61 And He delivered his &s;trength &Verbar;
<PB N="207" REF="001946_0244_0FFCB3C476ADFC60">into Captivity; &Verbar; yea, and His glory into the &Verbar; hand of the Enemy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="62">62 He al&s;o His own People did &Verbar; &s;hut up unto the Sword; &Verbar; and He was very angry with &Verbar; His own Inheritance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="63">63 Their choice Young Men the Fire <HI>of wrath</HI> &Verbar; did greatly wa&s;te away; &Verbar; and &s;o their Virgins could not be &Verbar; prais'd to the Marry'd State. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="64">64 They that were Prie&s;ts to Him did fall &Verbar; by the devouring Sword: &Verbar; but yet their Wi|dows did not then &Verbar; their lamentations make. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="65">65 Then did the Lord awake, as one &Verbar; that had been fa&s;t a&s;leep; &Verbar; He was like to a mighty Man &Verbar; &s;houting upon his wine. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="66">66 And He upon the hinder parts &Verbar; did &s;mite his Enemies; &Verbar; He brought upon them a di&s;grace &Verbar; that is perpetual. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="67">67 The Tabernacle al&s;o of &Verbar; Jo&s;eph He did refu&s;e; &Verbar; and He plac'd not His choice upon &Verbar; the Tribe of Ephraim. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="68">68 No, but the Tribe of Judah He &Verbar; did plea&s;e to make His choice; &Verbar; He cho&s;e the Mount of Zion which &Verbar; He &s;et His love upon. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="69">69 And He His Sanctuary did, &Verbar; build like high Palaces; &Verbar; Like to the Earth for which He does &Verbar; a long Foundation lay. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="70">70 David he al&s;o cho&s;e to be &Verbar; a Servant unto Him; &Verbar; and fetch'd him from th' In|clo&s;ures where &Verbar; the Sheep were folded in. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="71">71 From following of the Ews with young &Verbar;
<PB N="208" REF="001946_0245_0FFCB7F0105C4738">He brought him for to feed &Verbar; Jacob that was His People, and &Verbar; I&s;rael His Heritage. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="72">72 So he led them according to &Verbar; his hearts integrity; &Verbar; and led them in the manifold &Verbar; skilfulne&s;s of his hands. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE P&s;alm foretells the Refection of the <HI>Ten Tribes</HI> for Crimes committed &s;ince their Separation; with a Promi&s;e of pre&s;erving <HI>Judab,</HI> and the Hou&s;e of <HI>David,</HI> from which the <HI>Me&s;&s;ias</HI> was to be Born, who is to re-e&s;tabli&s;h <HI>Zion,</HI> and bring the People into Sub|jection to Him&s;elf.</P>
<P N="9">9 Some think, this refers to the overthrow which the <HI>I&s;raelites</HI> received, when the Phili&s;tines took from them the Ark of GOD. As the <HI>Ark</HI> &s;o the <HI>Fight</HI> was then in the Territory of the <HI>Ephramites.</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ur here are, <HI>Dark &s;ayings of Old.</HI> The Jewi&s;h Tradi|tions, and Commentaries on, 1 Chron. VII. 21. tell us; the <HI>Phili&s;tines</HI> had made &s;ome Inroads and A&s;&s;aults on the Skirts of <HI>Go&s;hon,</HI> while the <HI>I&s;raelites</HI> re&s;ided there. The <HI>I&s;raelites</HI> and particularly the Active <HI>E|phramites</HI> formed an Expedition again&s;t the <HI>Canaanites,</HI> pre&s;uming to attack them in their own Country. But they came off unhappy Lo&s;ers; The <HI>Rabb<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">s</HI> tell us, they lo&s;t no le&s;s than Eight Thou&s;and Men. This they got by <HI>Anticipating</HI> and <HI>Pracipitating</HI> what GOD had to do for them. Yea, after the Death of the <HI>Twelve Patriarchs,</HI> they fell into all manner of A|bominations. They committed innumerable <HI>Idolatries.</HI> They did forget and forego Circumci&s;ion, the <HI>Covenant</HI> of GOD: This was the Reproach of <HI>Egypt.</HI> [Jo&s;h. V. 9.]</P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Zoan,</HI> a very Ancient City, [<HI>Numb.</HI> XIII. 22.] called by the Greeks <HI>Tanis,</HI> near the Second Mouth of the <HI>Nile.</HI></P>
<P N="25">25 A Food prep<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">e! by <HI>Angels!</HI> The Glo&s;s of <HI>Sai|das</HI> is, <HI>Mini&s;tred by Angels.</HI></P>
<P N="30"><PB N="209" REF="001946_0246_0FFCB7F2F955EEC8">
30 q. d. They were not hindred from Fating as much as they plea&s;ed.</P>
<P N="32">32 q. d. They were not moved by any of His won|derful Works, to <HI>Believe,</HI> That He was able to bring them into the Land of Promi&s;e.</P>
<P N="49">49 The Apo&s;tle, <HI>Rom.</HI> II. 8, 9. u&s;es the&s;e very Words, when he mentions the Judgments of GOD on Wicked Men. An Intimation that GOD will put tho&s;e Mi&s;erables into the Hands of <HI>Evil Angels.</HI></P>
<P N="60">60 Some chu&s;e to read it, <HI>The Tent which He had fixed in Adam.</HI> There was a Town called <HI>Adam.</HI> [Je&s;h. III. 16. <HI>The waters ro&s;e up in an Heap, afaroff, in Adam.</HI>] <HI>Adam</HI> was the Center where the Waters were parted; and where was the Station of the <HI>Ark,</HI> now ready to enter <HI>Jordan.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="79" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXIX.</HI> A P&s;alm of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O God the Heathen are come in &Verbar; to thine Inheritance; &Verbar; Thy holy Temple they've defil'd; &Verbar; Jeru&s;'lem laid in heaps, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Dead Bodies of thy Servants they &Verbar; made meat for Fowls of Heav'n; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> the fle&s;h of thy gracious ones &Verbar; for the Bea&s;ts of the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Their Blood they have like water &s;hed &Verbar; around the Circuits of &Verbar; Jeru&s;alem, and there was none &Verbar; found that would bury them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 We are made a reproach unto &Verbar; tho&s;e in our Neighbourhood; &Verbar; a &s;corn and a deri|&s;ion to &Verbar; them that encompa&s;s us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 How long, O Thou ETERNAL God? &Verbar; Wilt thou forever be &Verbar; angry with us? Thy jealou&s;ly &Verbar; &s;hall it &s;till burn like fire? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Thy burning wrath, O do thou pour &Verbar;
<PB N="210" REF="001946_0247_0FFCB7F554F1F428">upon the Nations down; &Verbar; which do not render unto thee &Verbar; any acknowledgments: &Verbar; And on the Kingdoms which have not &Verbar; called upon thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 For Jacob they've devour'd, and have &Verbar; laid wa&s;te his dwelling place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Mind not again&s;t us former &s;ins; &Verbar; make ha&s;te; Thy bowels, Oh! &Verbar; let them prevent us; for that we &Verbar; are brought exceeding low. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O God whence our Salvation comes; &Verbar; Afford thy help to us; &Verbar; Becau&s;e there is con|cern'd therein &Verbar; the Glory of thy Name. &Verbar; And, Oh! do thou be&s;tow on us &Verbar; a full deliverance; &Verbar; clean&s;e thou us al&s;o from our &s;ins, &Verbar; for the &s;ake of thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Why &s;ay the Nations, Where's their God? &Verbar; Let our eyes &s;ee made known &Verbar; to Nations the revenge of blood &Verbar; they've of thy Servants &s;hed. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 The &s;ighing of the Pri&s;oner, let &Verbar; it come before thy face; &Verbar; To &s;how the greatne&s;s of thy Arm, &Verbar; Re&s;erve the &s;ons of Death. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 But to our Neighbours pay into &Verbar; their bo&s;om &s;even-fold &Verbar; the vile reproach, with which they have &Verbar; reproached thee, O Lord. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 So we thy People, and the Sheep &Verbar; Thou feede&s;t, Thee &s;hall prai&s;e &Verbar; for time un|known; from Age to Age; &Verbar; we &s;hall declare thy Prai&s;e, &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="211" REF="001946_0248_0FFCB3C9AF5416C0">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold <HI>Jeru&s;alem</HI> de&s;troyed by the <HI>Romans,</HI> and the Jewi&s;h Nation expo&s;ed unto Deri&s;ion in their long Di&s;per&s;ion. Behold a fervent Prayer, that GOD would recompence upon the Idolatrous Nations their Cruelty towards the <HI>Jews;</HI> with a Promi&s;e to Celebrate the Prai&s;es of GOD, after their Deliverance, and the De|&s;truction of <HI>Antichri&s;t.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="80" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXX.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Upon Shu&s;hannim. Eduth. A P&s;alm of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 HEar, O Thou I&s;raels Sheperd, who &Verbar; lead&s;t Jo&s;eph as a Flock; &Verbar; Thou who do&s;t make thy Seat to be &Verbar; the Cherubim, Shine forth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Before the face of Ephraim, &Verbar; al&s;o of Benjamin, &Verbar; and of Mena&s;&s;eh, &s;how thy &s;trength, &Verbar; and come with help to us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 O God, Cau&s;e thou us to return, &Verbar; and cau&s;e thy Countenance &Verbar; to &s;hine forth <HI>upon us;</HI> &s;o we &Verbar; &s;hall <HI>our</HI> Salvation &s;ee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O Thou ETERNAL One, who art &Verbar; the God of Ho&s;ts? How long &Verbar; again&s;t thy Peo|ples Prayer wilt thou &Verbar; &s;moke with incen&s;ed wrath? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Thou feede&s;t them <HI>but</HI> with a Bread &Verbar; that's mixed &s;till with tears; &Verbar; and thou do&s;t give them tears to drink, &Verbar; ev'n with a treble cup. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Thou make&s;t us a &s;trife unto &Verbar; them in our Neighbourhood; &Verbar; and they that are our Enemies &Verbar; do laugh among them&s;elves. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7"><PB N="212" REF="001946_0249_0FFCB43760EFAFB8">
7 Turn us again, O God of Ho&s;ts, &Verbar; and cau&s;e thy Countenance &Verbar; to &s;hine forth <HI>upon us;</HI> &s;o we &Verbar; &s;hall <HI>our</HI> Salvation &s;ee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">Thou from its place in Egypt ha&s;t caus'd to be brought a Vine; &Verbar; The Nations thou rejected ha&s;t; &Verbar; and thou ha&s;t planted it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Thou did&s;t evacuate all clear &Verbar; before the face of it; &Verbar; and thou did&s;t make it take deep root, &Verbar; until it fill'd the Land. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 The Mountains were well cover'd with&Verbar; the &s;preading &s;hade of it; &Verbar; and the Branches thereof did <HI>hide</HI> &Verbar; Cedars of God them&s;elves.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 She did &s;end forth her Branches wide, &Verbar; as far as to the Sea; &Verbar; and the &s;lips cut from it <HI>&s;he &s;ent</HI> &Verbar; as far as to the River, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 But, Oh! why ha&s;t thou broken down &Verbar; her hedges <HI>all of them?</HI> &Verbar; &s;o that all they who do pa&s;s by &Verbar; the way, do pluck at her. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 The Boar that comes out of the wood &Verbar; hath laid it very wa&s;te; &Verbar; and the wild Bea&s;t that ranges in &Verbar; the field, devoureth it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Return, O God of Armies, we &Verbar; do hum|bly ask for it; &Verbar; look down from Heaven, and behold &Verbar; and vi&s;it thou this Vine. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Even the Plant which thy Right Hand &Verbar; hath planted in the Earth; &Verbar; and <HI>look</HI> upon the Branch which thou &Verbar; ha&s;t &s;trengthen'd for thy &s;elf. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 It is con&s;umed with the Fire; &Verbar; 'tis ut|terly cut down; &Verbar; they peri&s;h from the &s;tern rebuke &Verbar; of thy <HI>proveked</HI> face. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17"><PB N="213" REF="001946_0250_0FFCB3CBC9423570">
17 Let thy Hand be upon the Man &Verbar; who is at thy Right Hand; &Verbar; Upon the Son of Man whom thou &Verbar; ha&s;t &s;trengthen'd for thy &s;elf.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 So we &s;hall never any more &Verbar; Apo&s;ta|tize from thee; &Verbar; O do thou quicken us, and we &Verbar; &s;hall call upon thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Make us return, ETERNAL God &Verbar; of Ho&s;ts; Thy Countenance, cau&s;e to &s;hine forth <HI>on us;</HI> &s;o we &Verbar; &s;hall <HI>our</HI> Salvation &s;ee.</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>DE. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks the P&s;alm was <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">enn<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> in the Time of <HI>Hezekiah;</HI> who wrote a Circular Letter unto the Tribes, e&s;pecially <HI>Ephraim</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">d <HI>M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|na&s;&s;eh,</HI> who were e&s;caped out of the Hand of the <HI>A&s;&s;y|rian;</HI> that they would come to the Hou&s;e of GOD at <HI>Jeru&s;al<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">m.</HI> After this the Land was invade<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;ore|ly di&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">r<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;&s;ed by <HI>Senacherib;</HI> which was dou<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">tle&s;s a grievous Di&s;couragement unto them, who had <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ned in the Reformation. This might move <HI>A&s;aph,</HI> mo&s;t earne&s;tly to be&s;eech of GOD, that He would &s;tir up Him&s;elf, before <HI>Ephraim</HI> and <HI>M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">na&s;&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">h,</HI> as well as <HI>Bon amin,</HI> (in which Tribe &s;tood part of <HI>Jeru&s;alem</HI> and the Temple<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">) and let them &s;ee by a Remarkable De|liverance, that their Zeal was acceptable to Him. The&s;e <HI>Three Tribes,</HI> may be al&s;o linked, becau&s;e they were the Tribes, which together followed the <HI>Ark,</HI> and brought up the Reer in the Camp of <HI>I&s;rael.</HI> The Greek expre&s;ly calls this, <HI>A P&s;alm concerning the A&s;&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|rian.</HI> It is remarkable <HI>Hezekiah</HI> di&s;tre&s;t by the <HI>A&s;&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|rian,</HI> appl<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">es him&s;elf to GOD in the very Language <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the P&s;alm now before us. 2 <HI>Rin.</HI> XIX. 15, 16. <HI>I&s;a</HI> XXXVII. 16, 17. But in the mid&s;t of all, Behold <HI>t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> Jewi&s;h</HI> Nation under the oppre&s;&s;ion of the <HI>Roman En|pire</HI> (called the <HI>Wild-Boar,</HI> becau&s;e it was one of t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">
<PB N="214" REF="001946_0251_0FFCB7F6D6F94578">Standards of that Impire) waiting for Deliverance by the Hand of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 <HI>Jo&s;eph</HI> per&s;onally con&s;idered, was one like an In|nocent <HI>Lamb</HI> fallen among a Company of Wolves. [<HI>Gen.</HI> XXXVII. 18.]</P>
<P N="5">5 Hebr. <HI>In a Tieble Mea&s;ure.</HI> The <HI>Talmud</HI> E<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|pounds it, that the Captivity under <HI>Edom,</HI> that i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Rome,</HI> will be a Cup <HI>Three times</HI> as large as that in <HI>Egypt,</HI> and that in <HI>Babylon,</HI> Three Times 400 Years, and Three Time 70 Years, at lea&s;t 1410 Years. D<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Kimchi</HI> ob&s;erves, That the Captivity in <HI>Babylon</HI> was a <HI>Third part</HI> &s;o long as the Capt<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">vity in Egypt.</P>
<P N="6">6 q. d. Our Neighbours are ever picking of Quarrel<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> with us, or &s;triving among them&s;elves who &s;hall make the greate&s;t Booty of us.</P>
<P N="15"><HI>Channa,</HI> which we render, <HI>The Branch,</HI> is an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Egyptian</HI> Word; very agreeably u&s;ed when a <HI>Vine brought out of Egypt,</HI> had been &s;poken of. <HI>Beehart</HI> expounds it of the <HI>Hedera Cheno&s;itis.</HI></P>
<P N="17">17 Even the <HI>Targum</HI> of <HI>Jonathan</HI> the <HI>Jew,</HI> will confe&s;s that the King MESSIAH is here &s;poken of. Behold the Two Natures of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> He is the <HI>Man of GOD's Right Hand</HI> in regard of His <HI>Di|vinity;</HI> He is the Son of <HI>Adam</HI> in regard of His <HI>Hu|manity.</HI> In the De&s;olation of the <HI>Vine</HI> here, doubt|le&s;s the Spirit of Prophecy ultimately refers to the De&s;truction of the Jews, by the <HI>Roman</HI> Power. R. <HI>Solomon</HI> &s;ays well, <HI>Innuit Captivitatem Rome.</HI> The <HI>Boar out of the Wood,</HI> he calls, <HI>E&s;au,</HI> that is the <HI>Roman;</HI> and &s;ays, 'Tis the <HI>Fourth Bea&s;t</HI> in the Vi|&s;ions of <HI>Daniel.</HI> It is Remarkable, The De&s;truction of the Jews, begun with the &s;etting up a <HI>Boar</HI> on the Gates of the Temple. GOD then &s;aid unto them, <HI>Now the Boar out of the Wood is coming upon you!</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="81" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXI.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Upon Gittith. Of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1"><PB N="215" REF="001946_0252_0FFCB3D21666C1A8">
1 O Sing aloud unto the God &Verbar; in whom we have our &s;trength; &Verbar; O make a joyful noi&s;e unto &Verbar; the God of Jacob <HI>now.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Take up a P&s;alm <HI>into your Mouth;</HI> And bring the Timbrel out; &Verbar; <HI>Bring out</HI> the plea&s;ant Harp, with it &Verbar; joining the P&s;altery. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Sound with the Trumpet at the Time &Verbar; when the New Moon appears; &Verbar; at the ap|pointed time; on the &Verbar; Day of our Fe&s;tival. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 For this to I&s;rael is ordain'd &Verbar; a Law of Jacobs God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 This for a Te&s;timony He &Verbar; to Jo&s;eph did a&s;&s;ign: &Verbar; <HI>He did it</HI> when thorough the Land of Egypt He went forth; &Verbar; <HI>A Land</HI> where I did hear a Tongue &Verbar; I did not un|der&s;tand. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Twas this,</HI> His Shoulder I remov'd &Verbar; from the load laid on it; &Verbar; his hands did from the Basket then &Verbar; make an entire e&s;cape. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 When thou wa&s;t in thy Trouble, thou &Verbar; did&s;t make a Cry to me; &Verbar; and I thereon did work for thee &Verbar; a great Deliverance. &Verbar; I'th' &s;ecret Place of Thunder I &Verbar; gave An|&s;wer unto thee; &Verbar; I prov'd thee at the Wa|ters of &Verbar; Contentious Meribah. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Hear, O my People, now, and I &Verbar; will te&s;tify to thee; &Verbar; O I&s;rael, If that thou wilt &Verbar; now hearken unto me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 There &s;hall not any &s;trange God be &Verbar; acknowledged in thee; &Verbar; Nor unto any foreign God &Verbar; &s;halt thou bow down thy &s;elf. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10"><PB N="216" REF="001946_0253_0FFCB3E5EEB49AA0">
10 I am JEHOVAH, Thy God who &Verbar; fetch'd thee up from the Land &Verbar; of Egypt; Open thou thy Mouth, &Verbar; and I'll repleni&s;h it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 But, Oh! my People, they would not hearken unto my Voice; &Verbar; and I&s;rael had no de&s;ire &Verbar; to take Delight in me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 So I did give him up unto &Verbar; the Lu&s;t of their own heart; &Verbar; they in their own In|ventions then &Verbar; went always walking on. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 My People, Oh! that they had been &Verbar; Obedient unto me; &Verbar; Oh! that in my directed Ways &Verbar; I&s;rael had walked on! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Their Adver&s;aries then I &s;hould &Verbar; have quickly vanqui&s;hed; &Verbar; and on their Enemies I &s;hould &Verbar; have quickly turn'd my hand. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 They that hate the ETERNAL God &Verbar; &s;hould &s;oon have fawn'd, on Him; &Verbar; But then their time would have endur'd &Verbar; to Per|petuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 He &s;hould have al&s;o fed him with &Verbar; the fatne&s;s of the Wheat; &Verbar; and from the Rock with Honey I &Verbar; &s;hould have repleni&s;h'd thee. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE <HI>Fir&s;t Day</HI> of the <HI>Seventh Month</HI> was above others, <HI>A Day of blowing Trumpets.</HI> [Num. XXIX. 1.] And it being the fir&s;t <HI>New Moon</HI> in the Year, the <HI>Trumpets</HI> were blown longer this Day than any other. <HI>Maimonides</HI> thinks it was to awaken their Preparation for the Solemn <HI>Day of Expiation,</HI> which was Ten Days after. It was the Day when <HI>Mo&s;es</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">te<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> being twice forty Dayes in the Mount) began to, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">e order for building the Tabernacle.</P>
<P><PB N="217" REF="001946_0254_0FFCB3D8849C2D00">
The P&s;alm was compo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ed for this Occa&s;ion. GOD Him&s;elf is introduced in it as in&s;tructing them in the End of the Solemnity. And He &s;hews the Jews (and us,) that their Di&s;obedience to Him is the Cau&s;e of all the Mi&s;eries which be<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">al them.</P>
<P N="5">5 Was it the <HI>Egyptian</HI> Language. Or, &s;hall we ra|ther take <HI>Patricks</HI> Paraphra&s;e? <Q>We heard unto our A&s;toni&s;hment, (for we never before were acquainted with it) the Voice of God.</Q></P>
<P N="6">6 They were delivered from the dirty and &s;ordid Em|ployments, wherein the <HI>Egyptians</HI> had employed them.</P>
<P N="7">7 The <HI>Arabian</HI> Interpreter, has a Notable Pa&s;&s;age here; <HI>Secret Prayers are like &s;ounding Thunder in the Ears of GOD.</HI> But the Thing mo&s;t evidently re|ferr'd unto is this; the People cried unto GOD in their Di&s;tre&s;s at the <HI>Red-Sea,</HI> and God confounded the <HI>E|gyptians</HI> with Lightning and Thunder out of the <HI>Cloudy Pillar.</HI> [See Fxod. XIV. 10, 13. P&s;alm LXXVIII. 18.]</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="82" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXII.</HI> A P&s;alm of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 IN the A&s;&s;embly of <HI>our</HI> God &Verbar; there &s;tand|eth God the Judge; &Verbar; He in the mid|de&s;t of the God's &Verbar; does the part of a Judge. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>He &s;aith,</HI> How long in Judgment will &Verbar; you do iniquity? &Verbar; and &s;o accept the per&s;ons of &Verbar; &s;uch as are wicked ones? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 In Judgment &s;ee that you defend &Verbar; the Poor and Fatherle&s;s; &Verbar; do Ju&s;tice to th' Afflicted one, &Verbar; and the impoveri&s;h'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Accompli&s;h a deliverance for &Verbar; the Poor and Needy one; &Verbar; Out of the hands of wicked ones &Verbar; &s;et them at liberty. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 They neither know nor under&s;tand: &Verbar; in darkne&s;s they walk on; &Verbar; all the foundations of the Earth &Verbar; are &s;h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="5 letters"> ou<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> of cour&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="218" REF="001946_0255_0FFCB7F9E5D45B50">
6 I've &s;aid, Ye're God's; and all of you &Verbar; are Sons of the Mo&s;t High. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 But ye &s;hall dye like Men, and as &Verbar; one of the Princes fall. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Ari&s;e, O God, <HI>and</HI> execute &Verbar; thou Judg|ment in the Earth; &Verbar; for thou &s;halt have all Nations to &Verbar; be thine Inheritance. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>IT appears by the la&s;t Ver&s;e of the P&s;alm, that it re|lates to the Time of the Divine Vengeance on the <HI>Antichri&s;tian Powers.</HI> It contains an Exhortation unto tho&s;e Powers to follow Righteou&s;ne&s;s; and fo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">etells their total De&s;truction, when the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> &s;hall come to e&s;tabli&s;h His Empire. Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> refers the P&s;alm to the days of <HI>Hezekiah;</HI> and makes it an Admonition unto the <HI>Judges</HI> then, to be more careful of their Duty, and Remember GOD who Judges them.</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Reizius</HI> thinks, The Judges of <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> on the ac|count of the peculiar <HI>Theocercy,</HI> wherein they had their Station, had a claim to the Name of <HI>Elohim,</HI> above others in the World; but that our Lord JESUS CHRIST has now &s;uper&s;ceded the Title for them.</P>
<P>Neverthele&s;s there is an Holy U&s;e, that may &s;till be made of the Title. And as the Lord <HI>Bacon</HI> ob&s;erves, All the Precepts concerning <HI>Magi&s;trates,</HI> are effectual|ly comprehended in tho&s;e two <HI>Remembrances; Remem|ber that you are Gods,</HI> and, <HI>Remember that you are Men.</HI> The One Bridles their <HI>Will,</HI> the other their <HI>Power.</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>Like Men!</HI> &mdash; and not like <HI>Bea&s;ts;</HI> For <HI>Af|ter Death the Judgment.</HI> One Ob&s;erves further, That Bea&s;ts live out their Time determined by <HI>Nature,</HI> un|le&s;s Violence or Ca&s;ualty come in between, But <HI>Man</HI> di<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">th in every Age; o&s;tner in Infancy then in any other Age</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="83" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="219" REF="001946_0256_0FFCB7FC3AC1A428">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXIII.</HI> A Song, A P&s;alm of A&s;aph.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 AN intermitting &s;ilence let &Verbar; not be with Thee, O God; &Verbar; as one deaf hold thou not thy peace; &Verbar; and be not &s;till, O God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 For that, behold thy Enemies &Verbar; make a tumultuous noi&s;e; &Verbar; and they that are thy haters do &Verbar; proudly lift up the head. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Again&s;t thy People they have had &Verbar; cun|ning contrivances; &Verbar; and have their con&s;ul|tations held &Verbar; again&s;t thy hidden ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 They've &s;aid, Come let's de&s;troy them quite &Verbar; to be no Nation now; &Verbar; That &s;o the Name of I&s;rael may &Verbar; be mentioned no more. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For they their con&s;ultations have &Verbar; clo&s;ely together held &Verbar; with one con&s;ent; again&s;t thee they &Verbar; do form a mutual league. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>'Tis what</HI> the Tents of Edom <HI>do,</HI> &Verbar; and of the I&s;hmaelites; &Verbar; Moab <HI>a&s;&s;ociates with them;</HI> &Verbar; &s;o do the Hagarens. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Gebal and Ammon <HI>do come in</HI> &Verbar; <HI>conjoin'd</HI> with Amalek; &Verbar; Phili&s;tia <HI>comes in</HI> with the &Verbar; Inhabitants of Tyre. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Yea, the A&s;&s;yrian <HI>&s;o remote,</HI> &Verbar; is al&s;o join'd with them; &Verbar; They to the Sons of Lot became &Verbar; a very &s;trengthning Arm. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O do to them as once thou did&s;t &Verbar; unto the Midianites; &Verbar; as Si&s;era, as Jabin <HI>once,</HI> &Verbar; by Ki&s;hon's Torrent <HI>were.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 They at <HI>the Place call'd</HI> Endor did &Verbar;
<PB N="220" REF="001946_0257_0FFCB3DF2838B508">de&s;truction undergo: &Verbar; They were <HI>&s;corn'd and unburied left</HI> &Verbar; as dung upon the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Make them, <HI>yea, make</HI> their Nobles like to Oreb and to Zeeb; &Verbar; yea, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ke to Zebah, and like to &Verbar; Zalmunna, all their Kings. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 They &s;aid, We will Hou&s;es of God &Verbar; f<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> our po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion take. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 My God, Make them like to a wheel, &Verbar; as chaff before the wind. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 As the fire burns the wood and as &Verbar; the flame &s;ets hills on fire; &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 So with thy Tempe&s;t follow them, &Verbar; and fright them with thy &s;torm. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Make thou their faces to be full &Verbar; of ignominious &s;hame; &Verbar; That they may &s;eek thy Name, O Thou &Verbar; that art th' ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Let them be put to &s;hame, and be &Verbar; forever terrify'd; &Verbar; with &s;hame, yea, let them hang the head; &Verbar; and let them peri&s;h quite. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Let Men know, that Thou only ha&s;t &Verbar; JEHOVAH for thy Name; &Verbar; Thou art the mo&s;t High One, who do&s;t &Verbar; rule over all the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>WAS the P&s;alm compo&s;ed on the Combination made again&s;t the Church in the days of <HI>Jeho&s;ha|phat?</HI> And was the Writer of it, either <HI>Jabaziel</HI> one of <HI>A&s;aph</HI>'s Po&s;terity in&s;pired on this Occa&s;ion? Or &s;ome other in tho&s;e days who&s;e proper Name was <HI>A&s;aph?</HI> Or, does the P&s;alm take in all the Attempts made af|ter
<PB N="221" REF="001946_0258_0FFCB7FDDFCC4628">that, until that made by the <HI>A&s;&s;yrian,</HI> who came to do what the re&s;t had not been able to do? Then Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks the <HI>A&s;aph</HI> who lived in the days of <HI>Hezekiah,</HI> may pa&s;s for the Author. But after all, Dr. <HI>Allix</HI> here &s;ees a Prayer again&s;t the Followers of <HI>Antichri&s;t,</HI> and of <HI>Mahomet,</HI> who have &s;ought the Ruin of the Jewi&s;h Nation, and the Conque&s;t of their Country. Compare the la&s;t Ver&s;e with <HI>Zech.</HI> XIV. 9. which is to be accompli&s;h'd, after the De&s;truction of the <HI>Idumaans,</HI> and the <HI>I&s;hmaelites;</HI> which are the Two Par|ties afore&s;aid.</P>
<P N="3">3 The <HI>Hidden Things,</HI> may be not only the People, whom GOD had hitherto protected as His <HI>Jewels;</HI> but al&s;o the <HI>Temple</HI> and the <HI>Secret-Place</HI> of it, which He had cho&s;en for His Dwelling-Place.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="84" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXIV.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Upon Gittith. A P&s;alm for the Sons of Korah.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 HOw lovely are thy Tents, O Thou &Verbar; ETERNAL Lord of Ho&s;ts? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 My Soul, it longs, yea, and it faints &Verbar; <HI>for to approach</HI> the Courts &Verbar; where the ETER|NAL God <HI>is pleas'd</HI> &Verbar; <HI>to manife&s;t Him&s;elf;</HI> &Verbar; My heart, yea, and my fle&s;h cry out &Verbar; t' enjoy the Living God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Even the Sparrow does find out &Verbar; an Hou&s;e where &s;he may lodge; &Verbar; The Turtle too does find a Ne&s;t &Verbar; where &s;he may lay her Young. &Verbar; <HI>But then my choice and cry is this;</HI> &Verbar; Thine Altars! <HI>There I'd be!</HI> &Verbar; O Thou E|TERNAL Lord of Ho&s;ts; &Verbar; my King, and Oh! my God! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Ble&s;&s;ed are they who in thy Hou&s;e &Verbar;
<PB N="222" REF="001946_0259_0FFCB80013677010">enjoy a dwelling place; &Verbar; they will perpetu|ally be &Verbar; engag d in prai&s;ing thee. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O the va&s;t Ble&s;&s;ings of the Man &Verbar; who hath his &s;trength in thee! &Verbar; The beaten ways <HI>that lead thereto</HI> &Verbar; are in the heart of &s;uch. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Pa&s;&s;ing a Valley full of tears &Verbar; they meet a Fountain there; &Verbar; yea, and the Rain reple|ni&s;hes &Verbar; the Ci&s;terns <HI>ready there.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 They go from one Company to &Verbar; another Company; &Verbar; <HI>Anon</HI> in Zion each appears &Verbar; before the <HI>Glorious</HI> God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O Thou ETERNAL One, who art &Verbar; the God of Armies, Hear &Verbar; my Prayer, and Thou that art the God &Verbar; of Jacob, O give ear. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O God, Behold our Shield; the Face &Verbar; of thy Anointed &s;ee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 For better than a thou&s;and is &Verbar; one Day within thy Courts; &Verbar; I on the Thre&s;hold chu&s;e to keep &Verbar; in the Hou&s;e of my God; &Verbar; rather than have my dwelling in &Verbar; the tents of wickedne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 For the ETERNAL God, God is &Verbar; a Sun and Shield <HI>to us;</HI> &Verbar; and the ETERNAL God will give &Verbar; both Grace and Glory too: &Verbar; Yea, He'll deny no good to tho&s;e &Verbar; that walk in perfect <HI>ways.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 JEHOVAH Tzebaoth, The Man &Verbar; is ble&s;s'd who hopes in thee. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="223" REF="001946_0260_0FFCB3E46A9AE7F8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>OUR <HI>Allix</HI> here &s;ees a &s;trong de&s;ire for the <HI>Jewi&s;h</HI> Nation to &s;ee them&s;elves re-e&s;tabli&s;h'd after their long Di&s;per&s;ion, and A&s;&s;emble together for the Wor|&s;hip of GOD. The <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> is here mentioned, as He by whom that Work is to be accompli&s;h'd. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks, The P&s;alm was Compo&s;ed by a Pious <HI>Levite</HI> in the Country, when <HI>Senacherib's</HI> Army had block'd up the way to <HI>Jeru&s;alem,</HI> and hindred them from waiting on the Service of GOD at the Temple; where he judged the lowe&s;t Mini&s;try, even that of a <HI>Porter,</HI> to be far more honourable, than the highe&s;t Perferment among the Pagans.</P>
<P N="1">1 The <HI>A&s;&s;emblies of Zion</HI> are, The <HI>Ho&s;ts of the Lord.</HI>&mdash;O Mini&s;ter of the Go&s;pel, Comfort thy &s;elf in this; Thou &s;halt have &s;uch <HI>A&s;&s;emblies</HI> to Preach unto, as the <HI>Lord of Ho&s;ts</HI> will order for thee.</P>
<P N="3">3 Was the Tabernacle any <HI>Ne&s;tin-Place</HI> for Birds? I rather &s;uppo&s;e a rapturous <HI>Ap<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;icp<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;is</HI> here. <Q><HI>The Sparrow hath found an Hou&s;e; and the Turtle a Ne&s;t for her &s;elf;</HI>&mdash;But as for me, the <HI>Hou&s;e,</HI> the <HI>Ne&s;t,</HI> the <HI>Delightful</HI> Place which I chu&s;e for my &s;elf; my cry is, <HI>Thine Altars, O Lord of Ho&s;ts!</HI></Q> With an abrupt outcry, he &s;ignifies, that He longed as much for the <HI>Altars</HI> of GOD, as a <HI>Sparrow</HI> for her Hou&s;e, a <HI>Turtle</HI> for her Ne&s;t.</P>
<P>But R. <HI>Solomon</HI> &s;uppo&s;ing the P&s;alm to be <HI>Written</HI> in the Time of the <HI>Chaldean</HI> Captivity, the Temple then in Ruins, might have the Fowls lodging there. What we render, <HI>A Swallow,</HI> does as <HI>Bochart</HI> proves, property intend the <HI>Ring-Dove,</HI> or the <HI>Turtle.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 q. d. <Q>Happy the Man who relying on the Divine Protection, [<HI>Exod.</HI> XXXIV, 24.] goes up Three Times a Year, to the Solemnities at <HI>Jeru&s;alem.</HI> Or, when he is debarr'd of that Liberty, as I now am, is one of tho&s;e devout Per&s;ons, who&s;e Hearts are more in the
<PB N="224" REF="001946_0261_0FFCB803263F5DD8"><HI>High-ways</HI> that lead thither, than at their own home; who travelling through the trouble&s;ome Valley of <HI>Ba|cah,</HI> where there is no water, pa&s;s it as chearfully, as if it abounded with <HI>Springs;</HI> depending on God the Fountain of all they want, for Showers to refre&s;h them in their Journey.</Q> The <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e.</P>
<P N="6">6 It may al&s;o be rendred, <HI>The Teacher is filled with Ble&s;&s;ings.</HI></P>
<P N="10">10 In the Heavenly World, there is a <HI>Temple,</HI> where the Wor&s;hip of God is after a mo&s;t Glorious manner carried on; Of which fir&s;t <HI>Mo&s;es,</HI> and afterwards <HI>David,</HI> had a marvellous Exhibition; And it was further Ex|hibited unto <HI>John,</HI> in his wonderful Vi&s;ions. The <HI>Third Heaven</HI> is the Holy of Holies in that Holy <HI>Tem|ple</HI> of the Heavens, where the Maje&s;ty of God, is pe|culiarly Exhibited in a <HI>Light</HI> that is inacce&s;&s;ible. Doubtle&s;s many Pa&s;&s;ages in the P&s;alms have an Eye ultimately unto that Glorious <HI>Temple</HI> in the <HI>Heavens,</HI> where GOD is Glorified by tho&s;e whom He receives in the <HI>Everla&s;ting Habitations.</HI> The Man&s;ions of the <HI>Paradi&s;e,</HI> where the <HI>Departed Spirits</HI> of the Faithful are lodged until the Re&s;urrection, are the <HI>Courts</HI> of the <HI>Temple. Believer,</HI> Think on tho&s;e <HI>Man&s;ions,</HI> and be <HI>caught up to Paradi&s;e,</HI> when thou &s;inge&s;t about, <HI>The Courts of the Lord.</HI> Old <HI>Arnobius,</HI> the Younger, will &s;tand by me in offering this Contemplation.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="85" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXV.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm for the Sons of Korah.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God, Thou ha&s;t &Verbar; been gracious to thy Land; &Verbar; the Captiv'd ones of Jacob thou &Verbar; ha&s;t brought them back again. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">Thou the iniquity of thy &Verbar; own People ha&s;t forgiv'n; &Verbar; all the Sin found in them thou ha&s;t &Verbar; entirely covered. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="225" REF="001946_0262_0FFCB80592250500">
3 All thy wrath thou ha&s;t utterly &Verbar; taken away from them; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t recall'd thy anger from &Verbar; the heat <HI>it ro&s;e unto.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Return thou us, O God in whom &Verbar; we our Salvation have; &Verbar; and towards us thine anger now, &Verbar; O do thou cau&s;e to cea&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Wilt thou be angry &s;till with us &Verbar; to perpetuity? &Verbar; Wilt thou make thy incen&s;ed wrath &Verbar; extend from Age to Age? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 What? Wilt thou not return again? &Verbar; Yea, Thou wilt quicken us; &Verbar; and they that are thy People &s;hall &Verbar; &s;hine with bright joy in thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 O Thou ETERNAL God, Shew thou &Verbar; thy mercy unto us; &Verbar; and thy Salvation as a Gift &Verbar; upon us, O be&s;tow. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Now will I li&s;ten well to what &Verbar; God the ETERNAL One &Verbar; will plea&s;e to &s;peak, becau&s;e He will &Verbar; &s;peak a mo&s;t happy peace: &Verbar; <HI>Peace</HI> to His People, and to them &Verbar; that are His gracious ones; &Verbar; and they &s;hall not re|turn unto &Verbar; fooli&s;hne&s;s any more. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Surely, to them that fear Him His &Verbar; Salvation's very near: &Verbar; that Glory may within our Land &Verbar; its habitation have. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Mercy and Truth will meet together; &Verbar; Ju&s;tice and Peace will ki&s;s; &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Truth will &s;pring from the Earth, and from &Verbar; the Heav'ns will Ju&s;tice look. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Yea, the ETERNAL One will give &Verbar;
<PB N="226" REF="001946_0263_0FFCB3ED81551468">the thing that's truly Good; &Verbar; and then our Land &s;hall liberally &Verbar; bring forth her joyful fruit. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Each one</HI> before his face &s;hall make &Verbar; &s;till righteou&s;ne&s;s to walk; &Verbar; and he &s;hall regulate his &s;teps &Verbar; for &s;uch a beaten way. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE <HI>Prophetic Spirit</HI> here Prays for the <HI>I&s;raelites</HI> under the marks of the Divine Anger in their Di&s;per&s;ion, and comforts them with a Meditation on the Promi&s;es which GOD hath made by all the Pro|phets, to be one Day Reconciled unto them, and bring them again unto their own Land, and ble&s;s them under the Reign of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> abundantly and wonderfully.</P>
<P N="8">8 <HI>Idolatry</HI> is emphatically <HI>Folly.</HI> It is Remarkable, The Jews have not relap&s;ed into that <HI>Folly,</HI> &s;ince their Captivity in <HI>Babylon.</HI></P>
<P N="9">9 The Coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> is thus looked for. Yea, the Words in the Original are, <HI>His JESUS is nigh them that fear Him. Glory.] Mun&s;ter's</HI> Glo&s;s is Excellent, <HI>Prae&s;entia Divinae Maje&s;tatis in|carnatae.</HI></P>
<P N="11">11 Some of the Jewi&s;h Rabbi's (as R. <HI>Hadar&s;on,</HI> and R. <HI>Joden,</HI>) have here made a marvellous Remark. It is not &s;aid here, <HI>Truth &s;hall be engendred,</HI> but, <HI>It &s;hall &s;pring Forth.</HI> To &s;ignify that the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> who&s;e Name is, <HI>The Truth,</HI> &s;hall not be begotten as other Men are. And accordingly R. <HI>Haccado&s;ch</HI> proves out of the Scriptures, That the Mother of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> mu&s;t be a <HI>Virgin.</HI> He al&s;o proves, That as the Name of Him who fir&s;t brought the Jews into the Land of Promi&s;e, was JESUS, the &s;ame &s;hould be the Name of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> who comes to repeat &s;uch a Deliverance for them.</P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Patrick's</HI> Paraphra&s;e runs thus, <Q>He &s;hall govern
<PB N="227" REF="001946_0264_0FFCB435DC4B1E48">us with great <HI>Ju&s;tice</HI> and <HI>Mercy,</HI> having His faithful Promi&s;e always before His Eyes. From that Rule He &s;hall never &s;werve, but &s;tedfa&s;tly proceed by it, as the con&s;tant method He will hold in His Divine Ad|mini&s;trations.</Q></P>
<P><HI>Mun&s;ter's</HI> Glo&s;s is notable; <HI>Ju&s;tus qui&s;que &s;tude|bit ambulare ante Deum, et ponere gre&s;&s;us &s;uos in Via Mandatorum Dei.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="86" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXVI.</HI> A Prayer of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God, Bow down &Verbar; thine Ear, and hear thou me; &Verbar; Be|cau&s;e I am an humbled one, &Verbar; and I am in|digent. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Pre&s;erve my Soul, &s;ince that I am &Verbar; one that is merciful; &Verbar; Save, thou my God, thy Servant who &Verbar; does place His hope in thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 O Lord <HI>in whom is my &s;upport,</HI> &Verbar; Be mer|ciful to me; &Verbar; Becau&s;e that I do cry to thee &Verbar; all day * and every day. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Rejoyce the Soul of him that is &Verbar; a Ser|vant unto thee; &Verbar; Becau&s;e that unto thee, O Lord, &Verbar; I do lift up my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For Thou, O Lord art Good, and art &Verbar; mo&s;t ready to forgive, &Verbar; and great in mercy unto all &Verbar; that make their cry to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 O Thou ETERNAL God, To my &Verbar; Peti|tion O give ear; &Verbar; and to the Voice of my reque&s;ts &Verbar; for favour, O attend. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 In the day when that I into &Verbar; a tribula|tion fall, &Verbar; then will I make my cry to thee; &Verbar; for thou wilt an&s;wer me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8"><PB N="228" REF="001946_0265_0FFCB807622EAFC8">
8 Among the God's, O Lord, there's none to be compar'd to thee; &Verbar; nor are there any works that may &Verbar; be lik'ned unto thine. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 The Nations all which thou ha&s;t made &s;hall come, and they &s;hall bow &Verbar; their kne<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> before thy face, O Lord, &Verbar; and glorify thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Becau&s;e that in thy Greatne&s;s thou &Verbar; art very glorious; &Verbar; and do&s;t things that are wonderful; &Verbar; yea, Thou art God alone. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 ETERNAL God, Teach me thy way; &Verbar; I in thy truth will walk; &Verbar; Unite my heart <HI>for Thee, and</HI> to &Verbar; the fearing of thy Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 I will prai&s;e thee, O Lord my God, &Verbar; even with all my heart; &Verbar; and I will glorify thy Name &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Becau&s;e thy mercy unto me &Verbar; is glori|ou&s;ly great; &Verbar; and from the pit below thou ha&s;t &Verbar; delivered my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 O God, Again&s;t me ri&s;e the proud, &Verbar; and an a&s;&s;embly of &Verbar; &s;trong ones have &s;ought my Soul, and not &Verbar; &s;et thee before them&s;elves. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 But Thou, Lord, art a God full of &Verbar; Mercy, and Gracious art; &Verbar; Long &s;uffering and plentiful &Verbar; in Mercy and in Truth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 O look on me, and pitty me; &Verbar; Afford thy &s;trength unto &Verbar; thy Servant; and the Son of thine &Verbar; Handmaid deliver thou. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Shew me a &s;ign for good, which my &Verbar; haters may &s;ee, and be &Verbar; a&s;ham'd; &s;ince Thou, ETERNAL God, &Verbar; do&s;t help and comfort me. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="229" REF="001946_0266_0FFCB3F203617A80">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE <HI>Prophetic Spirit</HI> here makes a Prayer for the Jewi&s;h Nation, oppre&s;&s;ed by the <HI>King of Pride,</HI> who is de&s;cribed in the XI Chapter of <HI>Daniel.</HI> 'Tis engaged, that when the Mercies asked and hoped for, are granted, what is done &s;hall be celebrated before all the Nations. The <HI>Signs</HI> which are to u&s;her in their Deliverance, are in the la&s;t Ver&s;e Petitioned for.</P>
<P N="16">16 R. <HI>David Kimchi</HI> thinks, the <HI>Handmaid</HI> here more peculiarly referr'd unto, may be <HI>Ruth</HI> the <HI>Moabi|te&s;s.</HI> &mdash;Behold then, in this Language of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> 2 powerful Memorial, for the Vocation of the <HI>Gentiles.</HI> But attend unto a wondrous matter. The <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> as here, &s;o el&s;ewhere, and ever, is introduced as &s;peaking of His <HI>Mother</HI> alone; without the lea&s;t intimation of His <HI>Father.</HI> An occult intimation, That He was to have a proper <HI>Mother,</HI> but no proper <HI>Father</HI> in this World, and by Con&s;equence He was to be the Son of a Pure Virgin. Compare, <HI>P&s;al.</HI> XXII. 9, 10. and XXXV. 14. and LXIX. 8. and LXXI. 6. and CXVI. 16. and CXXXI. 2. and CXXXIX. 13. and <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> XLIX. 1.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="87" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXVII.</HI> A P&s;alm. A Song for the Sons of Korah.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 HE in the holy Mountains hath &Verbar; His firm foundation laid. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Th' ETERNAL God loves Zions Gates &Verbar; more than all Jacob's Tents. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 City of God, Of thee there are &Verbar; &s;poken mo&s;t glorious things. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Of Rahab, and of Babylon &Verbar; I will make mention now &Verbar; among them that acknowledge me; &Verbar; Behold Phili&s;tia, &Verbar; and Tyre, with Ethi|opia; &Verbar; There &s;uch an one was Born. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="230" REF="001946_0267_0FFCB80AF50378E0">
5 Of Zion then it &s;hall be &s;aid, &Verbar; This and that worthy Man &Verbar; was born in her; and the mo&s;t High &Verbar; Him&s;elf &s;hall &s;tabli&s;h her. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 When the ETERNAL God &s;hall write &Verbar; the Peoples <HI>in His Roll,</HI> &Verbar; This is the thing He &s;hall declare, &Verbar; There &s;uch an one was born. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>There</HI> as the Singers are, &s;o are &Verbar; Players on in&s;truments; &Verbar; <HI>And as for me</HI> the &s;prings of all &Verbar; <HI>my Good</HI> are found in thee. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, How the <HI>I&s;raelites</HI> are one Day to be ac|knowledged among the Nations, and &s;eparated from among them; Tho' there &s;hall be then many Pro|&s;elytes. Compare <HI>I&s;a.</HI> XIX. 18.</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>Rahab</HI> (which in the Egyptian Tongue &s;ignifies a <HI>Pear</HI>) is, as <HI>Bochart</HI> Shows, the Name of that famous three Square part of <HI>Egypt,</HI> formed by the &s;everal Mouths of <HI>Nilus,</HI> which is called the <HI>Delta</HI> of <HI>Egypt.</HI> And &s;o all <HI>Egypt</HI> came to have the Name.</P>
<P>It is a Glo&s;s of <HI>Munsters</HI> here; <HI>Agno&s;cam inter Po|pulum meum, et hos qui extremifuere be&s;tes populi mei.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 Now and then, &s;ome one Single Man of Eminency born in other Countries: But in <HI>Zion,</HI> there is <HI>Man and Man,</HI> many very eminent Men.</P>
<P><HI>Again,</HI> Pro&s;elytes from all the&s;e Countries came to wor&s;hip at <HI>Jeru&s;alem.</HI> And tho' they were born in other Countries, yet the Lord writes them down as if <HI>Born</HI> in <HI>Zion.</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 The <HI>Spani&s;h</HI> Tran&s;lation reads it (as D. <HI>Kimchi</HI> does) <HI>My Eyes are upon Thee;</HI> meaning the <HI>Eyes</HI> of a Watchful Providence.</P>
<P>But R. <HI>Solomon</HI> keeping to the Term of <HI>Springs,</HI> un|der&s;tands the Fathers of whom the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> was to come. Compare P&s;alm. LXVIII. 26.</P>
<P><PB N="231" REF="001946_0268_0FFCB3F805246FD0">
Take <HI>Mun&s;ters</HI> Glo&s;s; <HI>Quicquid unquam inve|niri pote&s;t Laudis et Preconij, erit in Zion, ad Ex|tollendam Dei Bonitatem, qui filium &s;uum pro totius Mundi Salutetrad dit; meraeque Scaturigines Sancta|rum Meditationum, Cogitationum, et Locutionum divinarum erunt in eis.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="88" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXVIII.</HI> A Song. A P&s;alm for the Sons of Korah. To the Chief Mu&s;ician. Upon Mahalath Leannoth. Ma&s;chil. Of Heman the Ezrahite.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL One, the God &Verbar; whence my Salvation comes. &Verbar; By Day, by Night, before thee I &Verbar; make my Com|plaining Cry. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Before thy Face, O let my Prayer &Verbar; a free Admi&s;&s;ion have; &Verbar; Unto the Cry I make with Grief &Verbar; do Thou incline thine Ear. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For that my Soul with Trouble is &Verbar; ful|ly repleni&s;hed; &Verbar; for that my Life is very near &Verbar; come down unto the Pit. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 I reckon'd am with them who do &Verbar; de|&s;cend into the Grave; &Verbar; I am become like to a Man &Verbar; that has no &s;trength <HI>in him.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Among the Dead I am expos'd &Verbar; Free to all &s;orts of wrongs; &Verbar; I am like to the Slain who do &Verbar; Sleep in the Sepulchre. &Verbar; Such as thou do&s;t not any more &Verbar; &s;how a Remem|brance of; &Verbar; Ev'n &s;uch as Violently are &Verbar; cut off by thy Hands blow. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Thou ha&s;t for my place order'd me &Verbar; the Pit that is below; &Verbar; In Darkne&s;s <HI>Thou ha&s;t placed me,</HI> &Verbar; in the devouring Deeps. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7"><PB N="232" REF="001946_0269_0FFCB80D02DDEAD0">
7 Thy Wrath is lying upon me &Verbar; like to a mighty Weight; &Verbar; and with all thy Tempe|&s;tuous Waves &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t afflicted me. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Tho&s;e that were known to me thou ha&s;t &Verbar; put far from me; and made &Verbar; me loath&s;ome unto them; I am &Verbar; &s;hut up, and can't come forth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Mine Eye does thro' Affliction wa&s;te; &Verbar; O Thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; I call upon thee every Day; &Verbar; I &s;tretch my Hands to Thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 For &s;uch as do lye dead wilt Thou &Verbar; work a thing Wonderful? &Verbar; Shall the decea&s;ed ones ari&s;e &Verbar; and celebrate thy Prai&s;e. &Verbar;? Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Shall thy Benignity be in &Verbar; the Sepul|chre declar'd; &Verbar; or &s;hall there in de&s;truction be &Verbar; declar'd thy Faithfulne&s;s? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 In darkne&s;s &s;hall thy Work that is &Verbar; mo&s;t wonderful be known? &Verbar; Thy Righteou&s;|ne&s;s al&s;o in the &Verbar; Land of Forgetfulne&s;s? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 But O ETERNAL God, I have &Verbar; made unto Thee my Cry; &Verbar; and in the Morning &s;hall my Prayer &Verbar; anticipate Thee &s;till. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 O Thou ETERNAL God, Wherefore &Verbar; do&s;t Thou ca&s;t off my Soul? &Verbar; <HI>Wherefore</HI> do&s;t Thou <HI>&s;o</HI> hide away &Verbar; from me thy Coun|tenance? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 I am a poor afflicted One; &Verbar; and rea|dy for to dye &Verbar; from early Youth; Thy Ter|rors I &Verbar; have born till I'm amaz'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Thy Burning Indignations have &Verbar;
<PB N="233" REF="001946_0270_0FFCB3FC8AFF4AD8">been pa&s;&s;ing over me; &Verbar; Thy Terrors full of Troubles have &Verbar; utterly cut me off. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Like Water they've &s;urrounded me &Verbar; all day * and every day; &Verbar; they all toge|ther in an heap &Verbar; have round encompa&s;s'd me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Thou Lover and Companion ha&s;t &Verbar; re|moved far from me; &Verbar; and into hideous Darkne&s;s tho&s;e &Verbar; that once were known to me. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P><HI>CHri&s;tian,</HI> Behold thy Crucified SAVIOUR going down into the <HI>Pri&s;on</HI> of the <HI>Grave!</HI></P>
<P>Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks it probable, that when <HI>Jeconiab</HI> or <HI>Zedekiah,</HI> was carried Captive into <HI>Babylon,</HI> with many other principal People, this our <HI>Heman</HI> was a|mong them; and probably was ca&s;t into a Dark <HI>Pri&s;on</HI> there, and mi&s;erably treated.</P>
<P N="3">3 It notably expre&s;&s;es a <HI>Progno&s;tic</HI> and an <HI>Harbinger</HI> of <HI>Death,</HI> commonly ob&s;erved in the Experience of Godly Men. A little before their Death, when their <HI>Life draws nigh to the Grave,</HI> u&s;ually their <HI>Soul</HI> is more <HI>full of Troubles,</HI> then ever in their Life before, by rea&s;on of Trouble&s;ome Things befalling them, in their Per&s;ons and Families.</P>
<P N="5">5 <HI>Chri&s;tian Singer,</HI> Behold thy SAVIOUR here, Fir&s;t, <HI>Free among the Dead.</HI> Under&s;tand it not of that <HI>Libertas M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">rtuorum,</HI> which was the Con&s;olation of the Pagans about the actually and perfectly <HI>Dead.</HI> But under&s;tand it as the Extremity and Epitome of the Mi|&s;eries undergone by our SAVIOUR. <HI>Vitringa</HI> ob|&s;erves, The Torm notes, <HI>A Separation from all Man|kind,</HI> which mo&s;t eminently befell our Lord, when He was hanged on the Cro&s;s between Heaven and Earth, and all Commerce with Man was denied unto Him, and He was treated as the Execration of the whole World,
<PB N="234" REF="001946_0271_0FFCB80E89E2D688">and expo&s;ed as <HI>Free,</HI> &s;o that it was <HI>free</HI> for every <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> to <HI>do</HI> what they would unto Him, and <HI>&s;peak</HI> what th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> would about Him. It implies a State, <HI>In quo qu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> &s;umme mi&s;er, ab aliis de relinquitur, &s;pernitur, vif<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">+tur.</HI> A <HI>Leper</HI> was indeed &s;uch a <HI>Free-Man.</HI> Hi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> Hou&s;e was call'd, 2 Kin. XV. 5. <HI>An Hou&s;e of Liberty</HI> Our Lord on the Cro&s;s compares Him&s;elf, I&s;ai. LIII. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> to <HI>A &s;tricken Man;</HI> that is, with a <HI>Lepro&s;y.</HI> Ever<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> one abandoned &s;uch a Man. <HI>Cocceius</HI> tells us, Th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> Word u&s;ed here, is what is u&s;ed, <HI>Pro Publication Per&s;onae,</HI> for the <HI>Expo&s;ing</HI> of a Per&s;on to all manner <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> Injury, Violence, and Contumely. On the Cro&s;s <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> Saviour was as the Apo&s;tle &s;ays, <HI>Act.</HI> II. 23. Ex<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters"> <HI>Expo&s;ed</HI> unto all the Wrongs imaginable. Our Lor<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> thus <HI>Expo&s;ed</HI> here, counts Him&s;elf, <HI>Among the Dead.</HI> He was now next unto the State of <HI>Death.</HI> But more than &s;o; The <HI>Cro&s;s</HI> was e&s;teemed the Grave of the <HI>Crucified.</HI> The <HI>Romans</HI> left them there, to be corrupted or devoured. Our Lord was now, <HI>Like the Slain lying in the Grave.</HI> The Word, <HI>Slain,</HI> &s;ignifies <HI>Pierced;</HI> The Hebrews have not a more &s;ignificant Word for, <HI>The Crucified.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="89" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM LXXXIX.</HI> Ma&s;chil. Of Ethan the Ezrahito.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 THe Mercies of th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; I will forever Sing; &Verbar; Thy Faithfulne&s;s I'll with my mouth &Verbar; make known from Age to Age. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 For I have &s;aid, Benignity &Verbar; &s;hall be built up forever; &Verbar; The Heavens! thou e&s;tabli&s;h &s;halt &Verbar; thy faithfulne&s;s in them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 I've made a Covenant with Him &Verbar; that is my cho&s;en one; &Verbar; To David <HI>(the Beloved one)</HI> &Verbar;. my Servant, I have &s;worn. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4"><PB N="235" REF="001946_0272_0FFCB81050099B28">
4 Thy Seed, I will e&s;tabli&s;h <HI>it</HI> &Verbar; to perpe|tuity; &Verbar; and I will make to la&s;t and grow &Verbar; thy Throne from Age to Age. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 ETERNAL God, The Heavens &s;hall &Verbar; confe&s;s thy wondrous one; &Verbar; yea, and thy faithfulne&s;s in the &Verbar; A&s;&s;embly of the Saints. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 For who in Heav'n may be compar'd &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God? &Verbar; Among the Sons of mighty ones; &Verbar; who's like th' ETERNAL God? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 God in the great A&s;&s;embly of &Verbar; the Saints is to be fear'd; &Verbar; and to be reverenc'd above &Verbar; all that encompa&s;s Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O Thou ETERNAL God of Ho&s;ts, &Verbar; Strong JAH, Who's like to thee? &Verbar; Thy Faithfulne&s;s does al&s;o round &Verbar; about encompa&s;s thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Over the raging of the Sea &Verbar; thou thy Dominion ha&s;t; &Verbar; when that the waves thereof ari&s;e &Verbar; then thou a&s;&s;wage&s;t them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Egyptian Rahab thou ha&s;t broke, &Verbar; 'tis as a wounded one; &Verbar; with the Arm of thy &s;trength thou ha&s;t &Verbar; &s;catter'd thine Enemies. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 The Heavens, they belong to thee, &Verbar; the Earth is al&s;o thine; &Verbar; the World and all that filleth it, &Verbar; thou ha&s;t di&s;po&s;ed them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Both the North and the South al&s;o, &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t created them; &Verbar; Tabor and Her|mon, <HI>We&s;t and Ea&s;t,</HI> &Verbar; &s;hall in thy Name rejoyce. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Thou ha&s;t an Arm to which there does &Verbar; a mighty &s;trength belong; &Verbar; Mightily &s;trengthen'd be thy hand, &Verbar; exalted thy Right-Hand. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14"><PB N="236" REF="001946_0273_0FFCB402034BB060">
14 Ju&s;tice and Judgment are the firm &Verbar; Foundation of thy Throne; &Verbar; Mercy and Truth &s;hall go before &Verbar; thy face, as Officers. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 O ble&s;&s;ed are the People, who &Verbar; do know the joyful &s;ound; &Verbar; They, O ETERNAL, walk in the &Verbar; light of thy Countenance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 They in thy Name &s;hall &s;till rejoyce &Verbar; all day * and every day; &Verbar; and in thy righ|teou&s;ne&s;s they &s;hall &Verbar; an Exaltation have. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Becau&s;e thou art the Glory of &Verbar; the &s;trength which they enjoy; &Verbar; and in thy fa|vour &s;hall our horn &Verbar; be lifted up on high. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Becau&s;e that the ETERNAL One &Verbar; is our protecting Shield: &Verbar; and He that is the Holy One &Verbar; of I&s;rael is our King. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Then did&s;t thou &s;peak in vi&s;ion to &Verbar; thy gracious One, and &s;ay; &Verbar; I've laid the Help <HI>that's hoped for,</HI> &Verbar; upon a Mighty One: &Verbar; I have exalted One who is &Verbar; out of the People cho&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 My Servant David I have found; &Verbar; <HI>(even the Beloved one;)</HI> I have anointed Him with the &Verbar; Oil of my Holine&s;s; &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 With whom my hand &s;hall be confirm'd &Verbar; and my Arm &s;trengthen Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 The Enemy &s;hall not impo&s;e &Verbar; exactions upon Him; &Verbar; and the &s;on of iniquity &Verbar; &s;hall lay no yokes on Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Yea, I'll beat down before His face &Verbar; tho&s;e who do trouble Him; &Verbar; and them that are haters of Him &Verbar; I'll &s;mite with wa&s;ting plagues. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24"><PB N="237" REF="001946_0274_0FFCB81310621780">
24 But &s;till my Faithfulne&s;s, and my &Verbar; Mercy &s;hall be with Him; &Verbar; and in my Name His horn &s;hall be &Verbar; exalted very high. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 I on the Sea will cau&s;e His hand &Verbar; Do|minion to exert; &Verbar; and on the Rivers His right hand &Verbar; <HI>to do what He &s;hall plea&s;e.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 He &s;hall invoke me at this rate, &Verbar; Thou art my Father; <HI>Thou!</HI> &Verbar; <HI>Thou art</HI> my God; and <HI>Thou</HI> the Rock &Verbar; of my Salvation art. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27">27 Yea, to be my fir&s;t-born is what &Verbar; I &s;hall allow to Him; &Verbar; to be the Highe&s;t one, above &Verbar; the Monarchs of the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 My Mercy I will keep for Him &Verbar; to per|petuity; &Verbar; and fa&s;t my Covenant &s;hall &s;tand&Verbar; confirmed unto Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="29">29 His Offspring I will cau&s;e to be &Verbar; to per|petuity; &Verbar; yea, His Throne &s;hall continue like&Verbar; unto the days of Heaven. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="30">30 If that His Children by their Sin &Verbar; do violate my Law, &Verbar; and if they in my Judg|ments don't &Verbar; maintain their con&s;tant walk;&Verbar;</P>
<P N="31">31 If they profanely do de&s;pi&s;e &Verbar; the things which I appoint; &Verbar; and if they do not carefully &Verbar; keep my Commandements; &Verbar;</P>
<P N="32">32 Their proud tran&s;gre&s;&s;ions then <HI>be&s;ure</HI>&Verbar; I'll vi&s;it with a rod; &Verbar; and their perver&s;e iniquity &Verbar; with &s;courges that &s;hall wound. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="33">33 Neverthele&s;s, my Mercy I &Verbar; will not make void to Him; &Verbar; nor will I fal&s;ify again&s;t&Verbar; the Faith I've given Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="34"><PB N="238" REF="001946_0275_0FFCB4061D6E4D40">
34 I will not by the breach of it &Verbar; pollute my Covenant; &Verbar; and what is gone out of my lips, &Verbar; I will not alter it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="35">35 Once have I by my Holine&s;s &Verbar; taken my &s;olemn Oath; &Verbar; To David I will never lye&Verbar; <HI>(To the Beloved one.)</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="36">36 His Offspring &s;hall continue &s;till I to perpetuity; &Verbar; and his Throne &s;hall before me be I even like unto the Sun. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="37">37 It &s;hall be &s;tabli&s;h'd like the Moon &Verbar; to perpetuity; &Verbar; and there's the faithful Wit|ne&s;s, <HI>there's</HI> &Verbar; <HI>the Rainbow,</HI> in the sky. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="38">38 But now thou ha&s;t rejected and &Verbar; ex|pre&s;&s;ed much di&s;dain: &Verbar; And again&s;t thy A|nointed One &Verbar; thou ha&s;t been very wroth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="39">39 The Covenant of him that was &Verbar; thy Servant ha&s;t thou null'd; &Verbar; his Crown thou ha&s;t prophaned by &Verbar; ca&s;ting it to the ground.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="40">40 Thou ha&s;t quite broken down all of &Verbar; the things that hedged him; &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t brought unto ruin his &Verbar; Holds that were &s;ortify'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="41">41 All who do pa&s;s along the road &Verbar; do tear and trample him; &Verbar; he is become a vile reproach &Verbar; unto his neighbourhood. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="42">42 Thou ha&s;t exalted the right hand &Verbar; of them who trouble him; &Verbar; thou ha&s;t made them for to rejoyce &Verbar; who are his enemies. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="43">43 The whetted edge of his Sword thou&Verbar; ha&s;t giv'n a turn unto; &Verbar; and in the Battle thou ha&s;t not &Verbar; enabled him to &s;tand. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="44"><PB N="239" REF="001946_0276_0FFCB8149C876BC8">
44 His pure and glorious lu&s;tre, thou &Verbar; ha&s;t cau&s;ed that to cea&s;e; &Verbar; and overturning of his Throne: ca&s;t it unto the ground. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="45">45 The days of his protected youth&Verbar; thou ha&s;t dimini&s;hed; &Verbar; with ignominious &s;hame thou ha&s;t &Verbar; quite overwhelmed him. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="46">46 ETERNAL God, How long wilt thou&Verbar; conceal thy &s;elf? forever? &Verbar; Shall thy incen&s;ed wrath burn like &Verbar; to a devouring Fire? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="47">47 Remember thou, that as for me, &Verbar; how little is my time! &Verbar; Wherefore ha&s;t thou created all &Verbar; the &s;ons of Men in vain? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="48">48 What Man &s;hall live, &s;o that he &s;hall&Verbar; never &s;ee Death at all? &Verbar; From the hand of the pit &s;hall he&Verbar; deliver his own Soul?&Verbar; Selah.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="49">49 Thy Ancient loving kindne&s;&s;es, &Verbar; O Lord, where are they now? &Verbar; Ev'n what thou in thy truth ha&s;t &s;worn&Verbar;to David, <HI>(the Belov'd?)</HI>&Verbar;</P>
<P N="50">50 Lord, The reproach of them that are &Verbar; thy People bear in mind; &Verbar; of all the mighty People I &Verbar; do bear upon my heart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="51">51 Becau&s;e that, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; thy Ene|mies have reproach'd &Verbar; for they've reproach'd the foot&s;teps of &Verbar; CHRIST, thy Anointed One.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="52">52 May the ETERNAL God be own'd &Verbar; as the mo&s;t ble&s;&s;ed One, &Verbar; to an unknown Eternity; &Verbar; Amen, <HI>we &s;ay,</HI> Amen! &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the LXXXIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the <HI>Prophetic Spirit,</HI> propounding the Grounds of Hope, which the Jewi&s;h Nation have u<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> their Di&s;per&s;ion; even the &s;ure Promi&s;es made unto
<PB N="240" REF="001946_0277_0FFCB40C836A5038"><HI>David,</HI> concerning the Glorious Kingdom of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> The Throne of <HI>David</HI> for many Ages overthrown &s;hall be exalted at the Second Coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> as <HI>James</HI> in the Fifteenth Chapter of the <HI>Acts,</HI> proves from the Prophecies of <HI>Amos.</HI> And this is here asked for.</P>
<P N="4">4 The Promi&s;e is too Glorious to have a Completion in <HI>Solomon,</HI> and the other Kings of <HI>Judah.</HI> In the P&s;alm there is a di&s;cernible di&s;tinction, between, <HI>The Seed of David,</HI> and <HI>The Sons of David.</HI> The <HI>Seed</HI> is the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> The <HI>Sons</HI> are the other De&s;cendents.</P>
<P N="5">5 By the <HI>Heavens</HI> are meant the <HI>Angels,</HI> [Compare <HI>Job</HI> XV. 15. with IV. 18. See al&s;o, <HI>P&s;al.</HI> L. 4, 6.] The <HI>Wonder</HI> here is that mo&s;t <HI>Wonderful</HI> One, the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> [<HI>I&s;ai.</HI> IX. 6.]</P>
<P N="7">7 'Tis very &s;urprizing that &s;everal of the Jewi&s;h Rab|bi's countenance this Reading of the Ver&s;e; <HI>God is Brui&s;ed in</HI> (or, A Brui&s;ed God is in) <HI>the Great My|&s;tery of the Holy Ones.</HI> [Compare, <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> LIII. 4. and 1 <HI>Tim.</HI> III. 16. and Wonder!]</P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Tabor</HI> and <HI>Hermon,</HI> is, q. d. We&s;t and Ea&s;t.</P>
<P N="15">15 The <HI>Joyful Sound</HI> of the <HI>Trumpet,</HI> which called the People unto the Service of God. [<HI>Numb.</HI> X. 10.]</P>
<P N="19">19 It may nextly refer to the Revelation which GOD gave in a <HI>Vi&s;ion</HI> unto the Holy <HI>Samuel;</HI> [I Sam. XVI.] concerning the <HI>Deliverer,</HI> which He would rai&s;e up for His People. That Chapter well con&s;idered, will give a notable Key to this whole Context.</P>
<P N="25">25 On the one hand, he was to conquer the <HI>Phili&s;tines.</HI> and tho&s;e who lived on the Coa&s;t of the Sea, and on the other hand, the <HI>Syrians</HI> as far as <HI>Tygris &amp; Euphrates.</HI></P>
<P N="37">37 Is not the <HI>Faithful Witne&s;s in Heaven,</HI> the RAINBOW?&mdash; This leads to &s;ome curious tho'ts on the Scriptures, wherein we find the <HI>Rainbow</HI> mentioned, with Relation to the <HI>Kingdom</HI> of our Saviour.</P>
<P N="51">51 It was objected unto the Jews, <HI>Me&s;&s;iam &s;u<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">m e&s;&s;e tardigradum:</HI> That the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> took but <HI>&s;low Steps</HI> in His Coming. But the Word which we render
<PB N="241" REF="001946_0278_0FFCB816CB177270"><HI>Foot&s;teps,</HI> mo&s;t properly &s;ignifies, the <HI>Heel</HI> of a Mans Foot, and it is tran&s;lated from thence to &s;ignify the <HI>End</HI> of a thing. The Enemy now boa&s;ted that they &s;aw the Kingdom of <HI>David</HI> on its la&s;t Legs; They reproach|fully in&s;ulted it, as come to an <HI>End.</HI> The Truth is, it never was re&s;tored unto that Family until the Coming of our JESUS, the Great Son of <HI>David.</HI> And unto the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> &s;undry Pa&s;&s;ages in the P&s;alm, are appli|ed by the Jews: in both the <HI>Bere&s;chith;</HI> and in other Books: and <HI>Aben-Ezra,</HI> and R. <HI>Solomon</HI> con&s;ent unto it.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="4" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>THE FOURTH BOOK OF PSALMS.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="90" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XC.</HI> A Prayer of Mo&s;es, the Man of God.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 LORD, Thou ha&s;t evermore <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o us &Verbar; an Habitation been, &Verbar; from one Age to another Age, &Verbar; <HI>&s;weetly protecting us.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Before the Mountains were brought forth &Verbar; or thou had&s;t form'd the Earth, &Verbar; and World, even from Age to Age, &Verbar; Thou art the Mighty God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Thou to de&s;truction do&s;t reduce &Verbar; poor mi&s;erable Man; &Verbar; and then thou &s;ai&s;t, O Children of &Verbar; Adam, Return again. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Becau&s;e a thou&s;and of years, they do &Verbar; appear unto thine eyes &Verbar; but as a ye&s;terday when pa&s;t; &Verbar; and but a watch by Night. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Thou &s;weep'&s;t them off as <HI>with</HI> a Flood; &Verbar; they're <HI>like unto</HI> a &s;leep; &Verbar; they're in the morning like the gra&s;s; &Verbar; 'tis, Oh! how tran&s;ient &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Tis in the morning flouri&s;hing; &Verbar;
<PB N="242" REF="001946_0279_0FFCB81AA7B632E0">but &s;till, how changeable! &Verbar; <HI>For</HI> in the Ev'ning tis cut down &Verbar; and then 'tis wither'd quite. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Becau&s;e we're utterly con&s;um'd &Verbar; by thy mo&s;t burning wrath; &Verbar; and by thy heated anger we &Verbar; have fears how trouble&s;ome! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Thou ha&s;t &s;et our iniquities &Verbar; before thee in thy view; &Verbar; what we have hidden is in the &Verbar; light of thy Countenance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Becau&s;e that in thy wrath all of &Verbar; our days are pa&s;s'd away; &Verbar; we do con&s;ume our years like to &Verbar; a &s;tory, <HI>told and pa&s;s'd.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 The days of <HI>all</HI> our years, in them &Verbar; there are but Seventy years; &Verbar; or if they are in doubled &s;trength &Verbar; then they are Four&s;core years. &Verbar; But yet their power which is our pride, &Verbar; 'tis labour and 'tis pain; &Verbar; becau&s;e that it is &s;oon cut off, &Verbar; and &s;o we fly away. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Who &s;o con&s;iders as to know &Verbar; what power thine anger has? &Verbar; yea, ev'n according to thy fear, &Verbar; &s;o is thy flaming wrath. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 For the right numbring of our days &Verbar; To do thou give the skill; &Verbar; and unto wi&s;dom we &s;hall then &Verbar; apply this heart <HI>of ours.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Return, O Thou ETERNAL God; &Verbar; How long yet &s;hall it be? &Verbar; And O be thou appeas'd for them &Verbar; who're &s;ervants unto thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 O &s;atisfy us early with &Verbar; thy kind be|nignity; &Verbar; &s;o we &s;hall all our days rejoyce &Verbar; and be exceeding glad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 According to the days <HI>wherein</HI> &Verbar;
<PB N="243" REF="001946_0280_0FFCB413D9C92688">thou ha&s;t afflicted us, &Verbar; the years wherein we have &s;een ill, &Verbar; now do thou make us glad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 To them that are thy Servants now &Verbar; O let thy work be &s;een; &Verbar; thy glory al&s;o unto tho&s;e &Verbar; that are their Children <HI>here.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 And let the lovely brightne&s;s of &Verbar; the Lord who is our God, &Verbar; <HI>with a con&s;picuous lu&s;tre be</HI> &Verbar; <HI>&s;een &s;hining</HI> upon us; &Verbar; And the work of our hands, do thou &Verbar; e&s;tabli&s;h upon us; &Verbar; yea, the work of our hands do thou &Verbar; firmly e&s;tabli&s;h it. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XC. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>R. <HI>David Kimchi</HI> takes the P&s;alm to be made by the Prophetic Spirit, with an Eve to the la&s;t and long Di&s;per&s;ion, under which the Jewi&s;h Nation is now Langui&s;hing. But will the Holy One give that Peo|ple, <HI>as long Time</HI> under His <HI>Ble&s;&s;ing,</HI> as they have had under His Anger? One of the Ancients has a Pious Fancy here. The Name of <HI>Mo&s;es</HI> is, <HI>One drawn from under the Waters.</HI> And &s;o, &s;ays he, <HI>This is a P&s;alm e&s;pecially cut out for all Baptized Per&s;ons.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> thinks, here might be an Eye to the <HI>Ta|bernacle</HI> in the <HI>Wilderne&s;s.</HI> GOD Him&s;elf was <HI>this,</HI> and more than this, and before this was Built, unto His People.</P>
<P N="4">4 When I read <HI>Arnobius</HI> here ob&s;erving, That a <HI>Watch</HI> is the <HI>Fourth part</HI> of a Night, it pre&s;ently led me to think, how <HI>Four Thou&s;and</HI> Years pa&s;&s;ed, and then aro&s;e the <HI>Sun of Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> unto the World; by whom is to be accompli&s;hed that <HI>Re&s;urrection of the Dead</HI> which is here waited and groaned for: When He who <HI>turned Man to De&s;truction,</HI> &s;hall &s;ay, <HI>Return ye Children of Men.</HI></P>
<P N="8">8 <HI>Chemnitius,</HI> by, <HI>our Secret,</HI> here, would have <HI>Original Sin</HI> to be under&s;tood; whereof tho' the <HI>Fruits</HI> are evident and notorious, the <HI>Root</HI> is yet <HI>Secret.</HI></P>
<P N="9"><PB N="244" REF="001946_0281_0FFCB81C2B0BC298">
9 The Ancients read it, <HI>Like a Spider.</HI> And &s;uch was their Glo&s;s upon, <HI>Ut Aranearum Tela, &s;ic bu|mana Vita convellitur.</HI></P>
<P N="10">10 Dr. <HI>Goodwin</HI> ob&s;erves here, an Allu&s;ion to the Condition of a <HI>Bird,</HI> which has been hatching its full time. When the time for it arrives, the Shell breaks, and it <HI>flies away. Death</HI> is the breaking of the <HI>Shell.</HI></P>
<P N="11">11 Unto the common Annotations I will add that of P. <HI>Amana; Siquis te timeat, ira tua ab illo de&s;cedit.</HI> The <HI>Fear</HI> of GOD, will deliver us from His <HI>Wrath.</HI></P>
<P N="12">12 R. <HI>Solomon</HI> is mighty nice here; ob&s;erving that the Letters of the Hebrew Word, <HI>Chen,</HI> SO, con&s;idered as Numerals, make the Number of <HI>Seventy.</HI></P>
<P N="16">16 A CHRIST is here asked for!</P>
<P N="17">17 Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks, <HI>The Beauty of the Lord,</HI> here may mean, the Lovely and Plea&s;ant Land of Pro|mi&s;e. [Compare, <HI>Gen.</HI> XLIX. 15. <HI>Deut.</HI> VIII. 7, 8.]</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="91" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XCI.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 HE who dwells in the &s;ecret place &Verbar; of Him who's the mo&s;t High, &Verbar; under the &s;hadow he &s;hall lodge &Verbar; of the Almighty One. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 I'll &s;ay to the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Thou'rt my &s;ecurity, &Verbar; and thou'rt my tower, my God in whom &Verbar; I place my confidence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Surely He &s;hall deliver thee &Verbar; out of the Fowler's &s;nare; &Verbar; <HI>He &s;hall deliver thee</HI> from the &Verbar; malignant pe&s;tilence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 He with His wings &s;hall cover thee; &Verbar; and thou &s;halt be &s;ecure &Verbar; under His wings; His truth &s;hall be &Verbar; a buckler and a &s;hield. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Of what's the terror of the night &Verbar; thou &s;halt not be afraid; &Verbar; <HI>nor</HI> of the arrow which by day &Verbar; does make a <HI>&s;ini&s;ter</HI> flight. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="245" REF="001946_0282_0FFCB81E70AEFB70">
6 <HI>Not</HI> of the pe&s;tilence which does &Verbar; in darkne&s;s take its walk, &Verbar; <HI>nor</HI> of &s;uch a de|&s;truction as &Verbar; does at the noon-day wa&s;te. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 A thou&s;and at thy &s;ide &s;hall fall &Verbar; and clo&s;e at thy right hand &Verbar; <HI>&s;hall fall</HI> ten thou|&s;and; unto thee &Verbar; it &s;ha'n't come nigh at all. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Thou only &s;halt con&s;iderately &Verbar; behold <HI>it</HI> with thine eyes; &Verbar; and thou &s;halt &s;ee the recompence &Verbar; di&s;pens'd to wicked men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Becau&s;e Thou, O ETERNAL God &Verbar; art my &s;ecurity. &Verbar; <HI>So</HI> ha&s;t thou gone to the mo&s;t High &Verbar; as to thy dwelling place. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 There &s;hall not any evil thing &Verbar; happen to thee at all: &Verbar; nor &s;hall there any plague near to &Verbar; thy habitation come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 For He &s;hall to His Angels give &Verbar; a charge concerning thee; &Verbar; that they in all thy ways may have &Verbar; thee in their cu&s;tody. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 They like to tender nur&s;es &s;hall &Verbar; in both hands carry thee; &Verbar; le&s;t that thou &s;houlde&s;t da&s;h thy foot &Verbar; again&s;t &s;ome <HI>hurtful</HI> &s;tone. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Thou &s;halt victorious tread on the &Verbar; black &s;erpent and the a&s;p; &Verbar; the dragon and great dragon thou &Verbar; &s;halt trample underfoot. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Becau&s;e he hath &s;o loved me, &Verbar; there|fore I'll re&s;cue him; &Verbar; becau&s;e that he hath known my Name, &Verbar; I will &s;et him on high. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 On me he'll call; and Him I'll hear; &Verbar; when he's in trouble, then &Verbar; I'll be with him; I'll re&s;cue him, &Verbar; and I will honour him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16"><PB N="246" REF="001946_0283_0FFCB41940A471A8">
16 I'll fully &s;atisfy him with &Verbar; extended length of days; &Verbar; when upon my Salvation &Verbar; &s;hall cau&s;e him for to look. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P><HI>SAtan</HI> him&s;elf owned the P&s;alm to refer to the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> From the Eleventh Ver&s;e in the P&s;alm the Jews fetch their Maxim, <HI>That the Me&s;&s;iah &s;hall be greater than any of the M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ni&s;tring Angels.</HI> Our Saviour gave to His Apo&s;tles the Powers here mentio|ned, over <HI>Serpents.</HI> The la&s;t Ver&s;e refers plainly to the <HI>Re&s;urrection.</HI> Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks the P&s;alm to have been Penned at the time of the Great Pe&s;tilence towards the End of <HI>David</HI>'s Reign. But then by <HI>Gad</HI> rather than <HI>David.</HI></P>
<P N="6">6 Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> under&s;tands, Malignant Fevers which rage in the hotte&s;t Sea&s;on of the Year.</P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>Jewi&s;h</HI> Criticks ob&s;erve, That <HI>Side</HI> or <HI>Hand</HI> men|tioned without any Addition, &s;till means, <HI>The Left.</HI></P>
<P N="12">12 An Allu&s;ion to the Care which a <HI>Nur&s;e</HI> has of a Child. O Gracious and Wondrous!</P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Bochart</HI> will maintain our Tran&s;lation; which admits none but <HI>Serpents</HI> into the whole Speech of the P&s;almi&s;t.</P>
<P N="14">14 The&s;e are the Words of the Glorious GOD unto His <HI>Angels,</HI> when He gives them their Commi&s;&s;ion to look after His Faithful Servants.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="92" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM XCII.</HI> A P&s;alm. A Song for the Sabbath Day.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 TIS a good thing to celebrate &Verbar; with Prai&s;e the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and to Sing Prai&s;e unto thy Name, &Verbar; O Thou that art mo&s;t high. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In <HI>every</HI> Morning to declare &Verbar; Thy kind Benignity, &Verbar; and in <HI>the darkne&s;s of</HI> the Nights &Verbar; declare thy faithfulne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="247" REF="001946_0284_0FFCB8209AA5D6A0">
3 Upon an In&s;trument that has &Verbar; Ten &s;trings to furni&s;h it; &Verbar; and on the P&s;altery; <HI>and</HI> with &Verbar; a Song upon the Harp. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 For, O ETERNAL God, Thou in &Verbar; Thy Work, ha&s;t made me glad; &Verbar; In the works of thy Hands I do &Verbar; make my triumphant &s;ongs. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O Thou ETERNAL God, Thy works, &Verbar; how very great are they! &Verbar; Thy exqui&s;ite Contrivances, &Verbar; how very deep are they! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 A Man grown &s;tupid like a Brute, &Verbar; is one who does not know; &Verbar; and he that is a fool does not &Verbar; well under&s;tand this Thing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 When like the Herb, the Wicked flowre, &Verbar; and all the Workers of &Verbar; what's evil, flou|ri&s;h; 'tis that they &Verbar; may be de&s;troy'd forever. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 But Thou who art th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; <HI>[JEHOVAH is Thy Name?]</HI> &s;halt be exalt|ed very High &Verbar; to all Eternity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 For, lo Thy Foes, ETERNAL God, &Verbar; For, lo, Thy hateful Foes &Verbar; &s;hall peri&s;h, and all Workers of &Verbar; Evil &s;hall be de&s;troy'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 But thou wilt like unto the Reems &Verbar; exalt my horn on high; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> I &s;hall be a|nointed with &Verbar; a very grateful oil. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 My Eyes &s;hall al&s;o look with thought &Verbar; upon my enemies; &Verbar; my ears &s;hall hear of wicked men &Verbar; that ri&s;e to do me hurt. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 The righteous one &s;hall flouri&s;h as &Verbar; the Palm-Tree u&s;e to do; &Verbar; he &s;hall grow like the Cedar-Tree &Verbar; that is in Lebanon. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13"><PB N="248" REF="001946_0285_0FFCB822C6F937A0">
13 They who are planted in the Hou&s;e of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; the&s;e &s;hall &s;till flouri&s;h in the Courts &Verbar; of Him that is our God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 They even in old age &s;hall &s;till &Verbar; be yeilding of their Fruit; &Verbar; they &s;hall conti|nue in good ca&s;e, &Verbar; and keep their verdure &s;till. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 <HI>All this</HI> to &s;hew the equity &Verbar; of the E|TERNAL God; &Verbar; He is my rock and there is no &Verbar; iniquity in Him. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe Old Rabbins have a Notable Pa&s;&s;age; That the P&s;alm relates to the <HI>World to come,</HI> and the Age wherein the People of God &s;hall enjoy an <HI>entire Sabbath,</HI> which will be, <HI>the days of the Me&s;&s;iah.</HI></P>
<P>The Truth is, we have here, as Dr. <HI>Allix</HI> ob&s;erves, a prophecy of the Happine&s;s to be enjoyed by the Jewi&s;h Nation in the <HI>Great Sabbath,</HI> whereof the Apo&s;tle &s;peaks to the <HI>Hebrews.</HI> GOD promi&s;es here, to give them the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> for their King, after the De&s;truction of the Antichri&s;tian Powers. Compare the fourteenth ver&s;e, with I&s;a. LXV. 20. Probably <HI>David</HI> might write the P&s;alm, after the Lord had given him &s;uch <HI>Re&s;t round about from all his Enemies,</HI> that he concluded he &s;hould be able to &s;ubdue tho&s;e who &s;hould hereafter venture to oppo&s;e him.</P>
<P N="10">10 <HI>Onicorns</HI> are a Fabulous Animal; we'll keep the <HI>Hebrew</HI> Name o <HI>Reems,</HI> until we are better agreed about the true <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> of it; which <HI>Bochart</HI> will have to be the <HI>Arabian Wild-goats.</HI></P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Hugo Victorinus</HI> has this Glo&s;s; &mdash; He per|forms in the <HI>End</HI> more than he promi&s;ed in the <HI>Begin|ing.</HI> As the <HI>Palm</HI> has a &s;mall <HI>Root,</HI> but the <HI>Top</HI> is very great and large.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="93" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="249" REF="001946_0286_0FFCB41DC34F6598">
<HEAD>PSALM XCIII.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 THe ETERNAL God is now the King; &Verbar; High Glory He puts on; &Verbar; Th' ETER|NAL God does now put on &Verbar; a mighty for|titude. &Verbar; He girds Him&s;elf, <HI>ready to act;</HI> &Verbar; The habitable World &Verbar; is likewi&s;e &s;o e&s;tab|li&s;h'd, that &Verbar; it &s;hall be mov'd no more. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Thy Throne, it is e&s;tabli&s;hed &Verbar; from&mdash; who can tell the term? &Verbar; Thou art <HI>&s;till what thou art</HI> from an &Verbar; unknown Eternity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 The floods lift up, ETERNAL God, &Verbar; the floods lift up their voice; &Verbar; the floods have lifted up on high &Verbar; their <HI>hideous</HI> da&s;hing noi&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Th' ETERNAL God, who is on high, &Verbar; is mightier than the noi&s;e &Verbar; of many waters, <HI>mightier</HI> than &Verbar; mighty waves of the Sea. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Thy te&s;timonies <HI>unto us</HI> &Verbar; are very faith|ful ones; &Verbar; Holine&s;s does adorn thy hou&s;e, &Verbar; ETERNAL God forever. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>ONe ob&s;erves, the P&s;alm is an Hymn, wherein the Reign of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> as being the true JEHO|VAH, is de&s;cribed; After the de&s;truction of the <HI>Bea&s;t</HI> which <HI>&s;its upon the great Waters.</HI> In the la&s;t Ver&s;e. The Re&s;toration of the Jewi&s;h Nation is mentioned, as an Act e&s;tabli&s;hed by <HI>many Witne&s;&s;es.</HI></P>
<P>Was not the P&s;alm compo&s;ed, when &s;ome of tho&s;e Enemies, began to take heart again, and threaten a Di&s;turbance to the Tranquility of <HI>David's</HI> Kingdom, to which he was confident, in the foregoing P&s;alm, they
<PB N="250" REF="001946_0287_0FFCB824C4117930">could never give an overthrow? Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> who makes this conjecture, yet adds, That the P&s;alm ought in a more &s;ublime &s;en&s;e to be applyed unto the &s;tability of our SAVIOUR's Kingdom. The Jews them&s;elves do acknowledge this matter, to be prophe&s;ied in this, and all the P&s;alms that follow, unto the <HI>Hundredth.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 <HI>Kimchi</HI> carries this to the Days of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> when (as he renders it) <HI>The Holine&s;s of God's Hou&s;e will be de&s;ireable.</HI> He expounds it from, I&s;a. II. 2. That all People will then <HI>de&s;ire</HI> to go into the <HI>Hou&s;e</HI> of God; yea, all in the <HI>Hou&s;e</HI> will <HI>de&s;ire</HI> to be <HI>Holy;</HI> yea, all will <HI>de&s;ire</HI> to be <HI>Holy</HI> like that <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></P>
<P>But then the <HI>Te&s;timonies</HI> of GOD will be found <HI>cer|tain.</HI> All that GOD hath praedicted and promi&s;ed con|cerning His <HI>Hou&s;e,</HI> will be accompli&s;hed.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="94" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XCIV.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God, The God &Verbar; to whom revenge belongs; &Verbar; Shine forth con&s;picuou&s;ly, O God &Verbar; to whom revenge belongs. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O thou Judge of the Earth, Do thou &Verbar; exalt thy &s;elf on high: &Verbar; a retribution render thou &Verbar; unto the haughty ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 O Thou ETERNAL God, How long &Verbar; &s;hall very impious ones; &Verbar; How long &s;hall very impious ones &Verbar; make their triumphant boa&s;t? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>How long</HI> &s;hall they &s;till belching out, &Verbar; talk what is very hard? &Verbar; How long &s;hall all they boa&s;t them&s;elves &Verbar; that work iniquity? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Thy People, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; they break to pieces quite; &Verbar; and they unto thine heritage &Verbar; humbling affliction cau&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="251" REF="001946_0288_0FFCB42417A498D8">
6 The Widow and the Stranger, the&s;e &Verbar; with &s;laughter they de&s;troy; &Verbar; and them that are the Fatherle&s;s &Verbar; they murder <HI>barbarou&s;ly,</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 And this is that which they have &s;aid, &Verbar; JAH will not &s;ee at all; &Verbar; nor will the God of Jacob take &Verbar; a cogni&s;ance of it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O ye mo&s;t bruiti&s;h ones among &Verbar; the People, under&s;tand; &Verbar; But O ye fooli&s;h ones, when comes &Verbar; the time that you'l be wi&s;e? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 He who with skill did plant the Ear, &Verbar; think you, that He'll not hear? &Verbar; It it is He that form'd the Eye, &Verbar; think you, that He'll not &s;ee? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 He that in&s;tructs the Nations, What? &Verbar; &s;hall He not argue right? &Verbar; Tis He who does communicate &Verbar; all knowledge unto Man. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 But the ETERNAL God does know &Verbar; the thot's of earthly Man; &Verbar; <HI>He knows,</HI> that they are <HI>nothing but</HI> &Verbar; meer fooli&s;h vanity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 O ble&s;s'd the Man, whom thou, O JAH, &Verbar; with cha&s;t'ning do&s;t in&s;truct; &Verbar; and do&s;t out of thy law be&s;tow &Verbar; a teaching upon him! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 That thou from days of evil may'&s;t &Verbar; afford a re&s;t to him; &Verbar; whil&s;t that a pit is digged for &Verbar; him that's the wicked Man. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 For the ETERNAL God will not &Verbar; ca&s;t His own People off; &Verbar; neither will He for|&s;ake what is &Verbar; His own inheritance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 But judgment &s;hall anon return &Verbar; even to righteou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; and all that are upright in he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">t &Verbar; &s;hall follow after it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16"><PB N="252" REF="001946_0289_0FFCB355F225FF58">
16 Who will ri&s;e up for me again&s;t &Verbar; them who do evil things? &Verbar; Who will &s;tand up for me again&s;t &Verbar; workers of vanity? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Unle&s;s that the ETERNAL God &Verbar; <HI>bad given</HI> help to me, &Verbar; my Soul had quickly dwelt in the &Verbar; &s;ad &s;ilence of <HI>the Grave.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 When I did &s;ay <HI>within my &s;elf,</HI> &Verbar; My foot is on the &s;lip, &Verbar; thy mercy, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; was what &s;u&s;tained me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 When I've a multitude of tho'ts, &Verbar; mix'd in the mid&s;t of me, &Verbar; then do thy com|forts make my Soul &Verbar; glad with repeted joys. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Shall the Throne of things tyrannous &Verbar; have fellow&s;hip with thee? &Verbar; That which enacts into a Law &Verbar; what's a mi&s;cheivous wrong? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 They rai&s;e their troops again&s;t the Soul &Verbar; of <HI>every</HI> righteous one; &Verbar; and they condemn to death the blood &Verbar; of him that's innocent. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 But the ETERNAL God becomes &Verbar; the tower for my defence; &Verbar; and He that is my God becomes &Verbar; the Rock in which I tru&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 And He'll to them repay their wrong, &Verbar; yea, He will cut them off &Verbar; in their crime; the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; our God will cut them off. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>'TIS a Prayer both for the <HI>Chri&s;tian Church</HI> and the <HI>Synagogue;</HI> equally oppre&s;s'd by the <HI>Anti|chri&s;tian Party;</HI> who&s;e <HI>Thr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ne,</HI> who&s;e <HI>Titles,</HI> who&s;e
<PB N="253" REF="001946_0290_0FFCB8286443FF20"><HI>Judgments,</HI> mentioned in the Prophecies, are found mo&s;t expre&s;ly in the <HI>P&s;alm</HI> now before us.</P>
<P N="9">9 The <HI>Eye</HI> of Animals, e&s;pecially of <HI>Man,</HI> is a piece of &s;uch a&s;toni&s;hing Workman&s;hip, that it is impo&s;&s;ible for any but a mo&s;t bruitify'd wretch, to behold it without an Acknowledgment of a Glorious and Infinite GOD. <HI>Sturmius</HI>'s Exercitation, <HI>De Vi&s;us Organo,</HI> makes this ju&s;t Remark; <HI>Nobis fuit per&s;uaj &s;&s;imum, Athei&s;munt quem vocant, &s;peculativum, baber<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> locum ant invenire non po&s;&s;e, in co bomine qui oculi fabricam atten<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o ani|mo in&s;pexerit.</HI> The Philo&s;ophy of the <HI>Ear,</HI> would make the &s;ame Remark.</P>
<P N="10">10 He that has taught all Nations His Will (or the <HI>Difference between the Good and Evil</HI>) &s;hall not He <HI>correct</HI> them, when they <HI>tran&s;gre&s;s</HI> it? <HI>Kimchi</HI> thinks it refers to, <HI>Ultiones Dei in&s;igmores,</HI> the more &s;ignal Judgments of GOD &s;ometimes executed among the <HI>Nations;</HI> as the Fate of <HI>Sedom,</HI> and the like.</P>
<P N="19">19 The Quadrate form of the Hebrew Word u&s;ed here for, <HI>make glad,</HI> leads to this Tran&s;lation.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="95" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XCV.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Come, and let us &s;ing with joy &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; O jubilate unto the Rock &Verbar; whence our Salvation comes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Quickly let us before His face, &Verbar; with due confe&s;&s;ion come; &Verbar; and make with P&s;alms to Him the prai&s;e &Verbar; of a glad Jubilee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For the ETERNAL God, He is &Verbar; a God who's very great; &Verbar; and He is a great Sove|reign, &Verbar; plac'd above all the God's. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 He 'tis in who&s;e hand are the deep &Verbar; rece&s;&s;es of the Earth; &Verbar; the weary tops of mountains too &Verbar; do <HI>all</HI> belong to Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="254" REF="001946_0291_0FFCB42976764A90">
5 He 'tis to whom the Sea belongs; &Verbar; for He created it; &Verbar; His hands were al&s;o tho&s;e that form'd &Verbar; the Earth now dry'd from it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 O come, let us pro&s;trate our &s;elves, &Verbar; and let us humbly bow; &Verbar; before th' ETERNAL God who is &Verbar; our Maker, let us kneel. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 For He's our God, and we of His &Verbar; Pa&s;ture the People are, &Verbar; and the Sheep of His hands; if ye &Verbar; will hear His voice to day. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O harden not your hearts, as they &Verbar; in the Contention did; &Verbar; as in the de&s;art on the day &Verbar; of the Temptation <HI>there.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 <HI>The day,</HI> wherein your Fathers did &Verbar; tempt me &s;o <HI>&s;infully:</HI> &Verbar; A trial they did make of me, &Verbar; and they beheld my work. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 I Forty years was grieved with &Verbar; this race of Men, and &s;aid; &Verbar; The People, they wander in heart, &Verbar; and have not known my ways. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 For this cau&s;e I have made an Oath &Verbar; in my incen&s;ed wrath, &Verbar; That they by no means ever &s;hall &Verbar; enter into my Re&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>OUR Apo&s;tle, <HI>Heb.</HI> IV. 1. &s;hows us that the P&s;alm is an Exhortation unto the <HI>l&s;raelites,</HI> to prepare for the receiving of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> who is to bring their Nation into the happine&s;s of the great <HI>Sabbati&s;m.</HI></P>
<P N="4">4 Are not the <HI>Deep Mines of Silver and Gold</HI> in the Bowels of the Earth, particularly referr'd unto? One of the Ancients adds a good Note, <HI>Quae in mann Dei &s;unt, &s;ine Deo nequeunt obtineri.</HI></P>
<P N="9"><PB N="255" REF="001946_0292_0FFCB8B507DEFFD8">
9 They doubted, and they demanded new Proofs, <HI>though</HI> they had already &s;een &s;uch wonderful Works of GOD.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="96" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XCVI.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Sing to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; a Song that &s;hall be new; &Verbar; O &s;ing to the E|TERNAL God, &Verbar; All <HI>that are on</HI> the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O &s;ing to the ETERNAL God: &Verbar; to His Name bow the knee; &Verbar; Evangelize from day to day &Verbar; of His Salvation &s;till. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Of His bright Glory an account &Verbar; unto the Nations give; &Verbar; among all People <HI>give account</HI> &Verbar; of His mo&s;t wondrous works. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 For the ETERNAL God is great, &Verbar; and greatly to be prais'd; &Verbar; He above all the Gods is to &Verbar; be had in reverence. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For Idols vain are all the gods &Verbar; the People do adore; &Verbar; But the ETERNAL God is He &Verbar; who did create the Heav'ns. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Before His face is to be &s;een &Verbar; Honour and Maje&s;ty; &Verbar; and in His &s;anctuary are &Verbar; &s;trength and a diadem. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 O Families of Peoples, Bring &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; Bring ye to the ETER|NAL God &Verbar; glory and fortitude. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Bring ye to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; the glory of His Name; &Verbar; pre&s;ent ye an obla|tion, and &Verbar; &s;o come into His Courts. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Wor&s;hip th' ETERNAL God in the &Verbar; beauty of holine&s;s; &Verbar; tremble before His face, O all &Verbar; <HI>ye dwellers</HI> on the Earth.</P>
<P N="10"><PB N="256" REF="001946_0293_0FFCB8B6D5727A80">
10 Proclaim <HI>this very thing</HI> abroad&Verbar;among the Nations <HI>all;</HI> &Verbar; That the ETERNAL One doth &s;it &Verbar; a King upon His Throne. &Verbar; The World &s;hall be now &s;tabli&s;hed; &Verbar; it &s;hall not be remov'd; &Verbar; He'l judge the People with the things &Verbar; that are forever right. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 O let the Heavens now rejoyce, &Verbar; and let the Earth be glad; &Verbar; Let the Sea lift it's roaring voice, &Verbar; and what it's fill'd withal. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Let the Field have triumphant joy, &Verbar; and all that is therein; &Verbar; Then the Trees of the wood &s;hall all&Verbar;make a loud &s;hout for joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 <HI>Let them do this</HI> before the face &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; Becau&s;e He comes; be|cau&s;e He comes &Verbar; that He may judge the Earth. &Verbar; The habitable World He will &Verbar; now judge in righteou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; and <HI>He will judge</HI> the Poople in &Verbar; His &s;teady faithfulne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold, the Prai&s;es of GOD, that are to be Sung by the <HI>Jewi&s;h Nation,</HI> at the Second, Coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> They invite all Nations that &s;urvive the Judgments on the <HI>Antichri&s;tian Powers,</HI> to acknow|lede Him for their GOD, and reject the <HI>Idolatries</HI> they have hitherto practi&s;ed.</P>
<P N="1">1 Several of the Jews them&s;elves, own that this be|longs to the Times of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> We ought cer|tainly to have Him in our Minds, when we Sing a <HI>New Song,</HI> for the <HI>New Grace</HI> in Him granted to us.</P>
<P N="12">12 Why? The <HI>Earth</HI> is to be re&s;tored unto a <HI>Pa|radi&s;aic State,</HI> at the Coming of the Lord.</P>
<P>By the <HI>Heavens</HI> here called upon, to <HI>rejoyce,</HI> may
<PB N="257" REF="001946_0294_0FFCB42F26D67588">we not under&s;tand the <HI>Angels?</HI> By the <HI>Earth,</HI> all <HI>Mankind</HI> which are di&s;per&s;ed on the <HI>Earth.</HI></P>
<P>By the <HI>Sea,</HI> the <HI>Mariners</HI> and <HI>Pa&s;&s;engers</HI> in Ships, and the Inhabitants of the <HI>I&s;lands.</HI></P>
<P>By the <HI>Fields,</HI> the <HI>Husbandmen</HI> and <HI>Shepherds,</HI> who dwell in the <HI>Fields.</HI></P>
<P>By the <HI>Trees of the Wood,</HI> the <HI>Woodmen</HI> and <HI>Fore&s;ters,</HI> who are with joy to &s;ee the happy Day approaching when all the Idols that are Wor&s;hipped there, &s;hall be thrown down, together with their Groves.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="97" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XCVII.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 NOW the ETERNAL God does reign, &Verbar; O let the Earth rejoyce; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> let the many I&s;les thereof &Verbar; &s;hine with a chear|ful joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 A cloud and a den&s;e darkne&s;s doth &Verbar; en|compa&s;s Him about; &Verbar; Ju&s;tice and Judgment are the firm &Verbar; foundation of His Throne. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Fire goes before His face and burns &Verbar; all round His Enemies; &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 His lightnings fill the World with light; &Verbar; the Earth &s;ees it and &s;hakes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Like melting wax the mountains are &Verbar; di&s;&s;olv'd before the face &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; before &Verbar; the Lord of all the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 O let the Heavens now declare &Verbar; abroad His righteou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; and of His radiant glory let &Verbar; all People have a view. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Confu&s;ion be to all tho&s;e who &Verbar; &s;erve graven Images; &Verbar; who do in Idols boa&s;t them|&s;elves. &Verbar; Wor&s;hip Him all ye God's! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Zion heard and was bright with joy: &Verbar;
<PB N="258" REF="001946_0295_0FFCB8B910830D00">and Judah's daughters were &Verbar; for the &s;ake of thy Judgments glad,&Verbar; O thou ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 For, O ETERNAL God, Thou art &Verbar; High above all the Earth; &Verbar; Thou art exalted very high; &Verbar; <HI>High</HI> above all the Gods. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 O ye who love th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Hate ill; He keeps the Souls &Verbar; of <HI>all</HI> His gracious ones; He &s;aves &Verbar; them from the wickeds hand. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 There's for the righteous one a light &Verbar; &s;own <HI>as an hidden &s;eed;</HI> &Verbar; and for them who're upright in heart &Verbar; there is a joy <HI>re&s;erv'd.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 You that are righteous ones, Rejoyce &Verbar; in the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and when you do commemorate &Verbar; His Holy One, give thanks. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE P&s;alm is of the &s;ame De&s;ign with the fore|going. It in&s;ults the <HI>New Idolaters,</HI> the Anti|chri&s;tian ones, with the Coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> who is to condemn them. It repre&s;ents the Joy which His Coming, will give unto the People of GOD, and unto the Jewi&s;h Nation in particular. Was not the P&s;alm written, on &s;ome Conque&s;ts made by <HI>David,</HI> after the Ark was brought to <HI>Zion:</HI> when the foregoing Hymn was made, in hope of the great things to en&s;ue? In &s;ubduing the&s;e, GOD might fight for His People, with &s;ome &s;uch Tempe&s;t as that, 2 <HI>Sam.</HI> V. 20, 21, 24.</P>
<P N="1">1 Mr. <HI>M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;trezat</HI> ob&s;erves, That &s;ince the <HI>I&s;les</HI> are the <HI>Gentiles;</HI> the Reign here mu&s;t be a <HI>Reign of Grace,</HI> and favourable to them. In &s;uch Expre&s;&s;ions as imply a <HI>Reign of Grace,</HI> the Lord who Reigns mu&s;t be the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> Our Apo&s;tle <HI>Paul</HI> might well apply the P&s;alm to Him!</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="259" REF="001946_0296_0FFCB8BBDCE917B0">
5 <HI>Ma&s;ius</HI> notes, that <HI>Adonai,</HI> is a Name on Illu&s;tri|ous Accounts peculiar to the <HI>Son</HI> of GOD.</P>
<P N="6">6 &mdash;A dreadful Tempe&s;t, managed by Angelical Mini&s;ters, declares the ju&s;t &s;everity of GOD again&s;t His Enemies.</P>
<P N="11">11 Some Jewi&s;h <HI>Rabbi's,</HI> by this <HI>Light</HI> under&s;tand the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> As they do, <HI>Dan.</HI> II. 22. <HI>P&s;al.</HI> XXXVI. 10. &mdash;But, O Chri&s;tian, all the <HI>Felicity</HI> thou hope&s;t for, mu&s;t lie for a while conceal'd, as under the Clods, with a Sentence of <HI>Death</HI> upon it.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="98" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XCVIII. <HI>A P&s;alm.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 TO the ETERNAL God, O &s;ing &Verbar; a new Song; for He hath &Verbar; done wonders; His right hand has Him &Verbar; help'd, and His holy Arm. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Th' ETERNAL God has cau&s;ed His &Verbar; Salvation to be known; &Verbar; In the eyes of the Nations He &Verbar; hath &s;hewn His righteou&s;ne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 He minds His mercy and His truth &Verbar; to th' hou&s;e of I&s;rael; &Verbar; All the ends of the Earth, they have &Verbar; our God's Salvation &s;een. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O Jubilate now all the Earth &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; O rai&s;e your voice, and &s;ing aloud, &Verbar; and celebrate with P&s;alms. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O &s;ing to the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; with a <HI>well-tuned</HI> harp; &Verbar; Do <HI>it</HI> with a <HI>ten-&s;tringed</HI> harp, &Verbar; and the voice of the P&s;alm. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 With trumpets which a&s;&s;emble troops, &Verbar; and with the &s;ound of horn, &Verbar; O Jubilate be|fore the King &Verbar; who is th' ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7"><PB N="260" REF="001946_0297_0FFCB433AB870548">
7 Let the Sea make its thundring noi&s;e, &Verbar; and that which filleth it; &Verbar; <HI>&s;o let</HI> the habi|table World &Verbar; and its inhabitants. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Let the floods clap their hands for joy &Verbar; with acclamations loud; &Verbar; Together with them al&s;o let &Verbar; the mountains make their &s;houts. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 <HI>Let them do this</HI> before the face &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; becau&s;e that He is coming forth &Verbar; that He may judge the Earth. &Verbar; The habitable World He will &Verbar; now judge in righteou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; and He will judge the Peo|ple with &Verbar; things mo&s;t exactly right. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>A New Song; To be Sung at the Second Coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> Compare the Fir&s;t Ver&s;e of the P&s;alm with <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> XII. 5.&mdash;which by the way, invincibly &s;hews, That the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> is GOD. It foretells the Re|calling of the <HI>Jews,;</HI> and Exhorts all Nations to ac|knowledge the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> as GOD. The Judgments on the Antichri&s;tian Powers, mu&s;t be before the Happi|ne&s;s of the Jews, and the Conver&s;ion of the other Nations.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="99" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM XCIX.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 TH' ETERNAL God now reigns as King; &Verbar; O let the People quake; &Verbar; He &s;its be|tween the Cherubim; &Verbar; O let the Earth be mov'd; &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In Zion the ETERNAL God &Verbar; is greatly magnify'd; &Verbar; and above all the Peoples He &Verbar; is now advanc'd on high. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 O let them celebrate thy Name &Verbar;
<PB N="261" REF="001946_0298_0FFCB8BE7B856188">with due co<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">e&s;&s;ions now; &Verbar; It's great, and it is terrible; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> holy too it is. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 The King's &s;trength al&s;o judgment loves; &Verbar; right things thou do&s;t prepare; &Verbar; In Jacob thou do&s;t execute &Verbar; judgment and righteou&s;ne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Exalt ye the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; ev'n Him who is our God; &Verbar; and at His foot&s;tool wor|&s;hip ye; &Verbar; He is the holy One. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Mo&s;es and Aaron eminent &Verbar; among His Mini&s;ters; &Verbar; and Samuel eminent among &Verbar; them that call on His Name. The&s;e did their invocation make &Verbar; on the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and He then granted unto them &Verbar; a gracious audience. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 He in the pillar of the cloud &Verbar; gave O|racles to them; &Verbar; they kept His te&s;timonies, and &Verbar; the Law He gave to them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Thou heard'&s;t them, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; our God; Thou wa&s;t a God &Verbar; that &s;par'd them; and thou did&s;t revenge &Verbar; the things de&s;ign'd at them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Exalt th' ETERNAL God, our God; &Verbar; and at His holy hill &Verbar; Wor&s;hip; for the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Our God's the Holy One. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the XCIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE P&s;alm is Calculated for the Coming &amp; Kingdom of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah;</HI> when His Throne &s;hall be in <HI>Zion;</HI> and the Jews have new Tokens of His Pre&s;ence among them.</P>
<P N="1">1 The <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e is; <Q>Tho' the whole Earth &s;hould be in an uproar, we are &s;afe and &s;ecure; for the Lord is attended with Innumerable Heavenly Mini&s;ters, who are a Guard unto His Faithful Wo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|&s;hippers.</Q></P>
<P N="5"><PB N="262" REF="001946_0299_0FFCB66C61F76B58">
5 The <HI>Ark</HI> was peculiarly <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">he <HI>Foot&s;tool</HI> of the Lord. But the <HI>Ark</HI> was al&s;o a Type of our Saviour <HI>Ambro&s;e</HI> and <HI>Au&s;tin</HI> found this <HI>Fo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">t&s;tool</HI> in the Fle<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> of our Saviour.</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Dru&s;ius</HI> notes, That the Particle, <HI>Among,</HI> ofter intimates one very <HI>Eminent</HI> &amp; <HI>Exernious</HI> among tho&s;e that are &s;poken of.</P>
<P N="8">8 <HI>Patricks</HI> Paraphra&s;e is this; <Q>When they Pray<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> unto Thee, Thou did&s;t fulfil their Petitions, pa&s;&s;ing by for them &s;akes, the Sins of tho&s;e who contemned the &Verbar; Authority, and were contriving how to depo&s;e them [<HI>Numb.</HI> XII. 2, 9, 10. XVI. 3, 31, 32. 1 <HI>Sam.</HI> VIII. 7, 8, 9.]</Q></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="100" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM C.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 NOw unto the ETERNAL God &Verbar; make you the joyful &s;houts &Verbar; which are heard in a Jubilee, &Verbar; all <HI>ye who dwell on</HI> Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Yield &s;ervice with a &s;hining joy &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; with joyful acclamations come &Verbar; ye in before His face. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Know, That th' ETERNAL God, He's God; &Verbar; He made us, and we're His; &Verbar; we are His People, and we are &Verbar; the Sheep which He does feed. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 With due confe&s;&s;ions enter ye &Verbar; His gates, His courts with Prai&s;e; &Verbar; make due confe&s;&s;ions unto Him; &Verbar; &s;peak ye well of His Name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For the ETERNAL God is good; &Verbar; His mercy is for ever; &Verbar; And unto Generations doth &Verbar; His faithfulne&s;s <HI>endure.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="263" REF="001946_0300_0FFCB489FB7D10A0">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the C. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>HAve we not here, an Exhortation o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> the returned Jews unto all People, that they &s;hould acknow|leage their SAVIOUR, as their GOD and Creator, con|&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">er<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ng how faithful He has been in His Promi&s;es, and what great Wonders He hath performed, for the &s;ake of His People? The Jews have a Report that the P&s;alm was appointed peculiarly to be Sung, when their <HI>Sacrifices of Thanksgiving [Lov.</HI> VII. 12, 13.] were to be offered. The <HI>Levites</HI> call'd, <HI>The Companies of them who gave Thanks unto GOD.</HI> [Neh. XII. 31, 38.] were the Singers of it.</P>
<P N="3">3 The Word implies, <HI>Advancing, Preferring, Rai|&s;ing</HI> them, as a People, to be &s;uch a People as they were; a great and a mighty Nation.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="101" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CI.</HI> A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 OF Mercy and of Judgment both &Verbar; I will now make my Song; &Verbar; Unto Thee, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; I will now &s;ing a P&s;alm. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 I'll in a perfect way be wi&s;e; &Verbar; When wilt thou come to me? &Verbar; In the mid&s;t of my hou&s;e I will &Verbar; walk with a perfect heart. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 I will not &s;et before mine eyes &Verbar; a thing of Belial; &Verbar; I hate the work of wanderers: &Verbar; it &s;hall not cleave to me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 An heart that is perver&s;ely bent, &Verbar; it &s;hall depart from me; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> I will take no notice of &Verbar; one that's a wicked man. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 I<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ll cut off him that &s;landereth &Verbar; his neighbour &s;ecretly; &Verbar; One high in looks and proud in heart, &Verbar; I will not bear with him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="264" REF="001946_0301_0FFCB4884055C120">
6 I'll eye the faithful of the Land, &Verbar; that they may dwell with me; &Verbar; He that walks in a perfect way, &Verbar; He'l be my Officer. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 In the mid&s;t of my hou&s;e none &s;hall &Verbar; dwell, who does work deceit: &Verbar; before my eyes e&s;tabli&s;h'd none &Verbar; &s;hall be who telleth lyes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 I as the mornings do recur, &Verbar; with clo&s;e confinement will &Verbar; de&s;troy all of the wicked ones &Verbar; that are upon the Earth. &Verbar; <HI>And this,</HI> that from the City of &Verbar; Him who's th' ETER|NAL God, &Verbar; I may extirminate all them &Verbar; who work iniquity. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P><HI>DAvid</HI> on the Death of <HI>Saul,</HI> was immediately promoted unto the Kingdom. However he had not yet the entire Kingdom. In the mean time he re|&s;olved with him&s;elf how well he would govern when GOD &s;hould make him King over all <HI>I&s;rael</HI> as well as <HI>Judah.</HI></P>
<P>But indeed, We have here the Character of tho&s;e who are to be admitted among the Subjects of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> in His glorious Kingdom; and the manner wherein He will curt off them who pretending to acknowledge His Laws, have overthrown all Righteou&s;ne&s;s in the World.</P>
<P N="1">1 In the&s;e Two Things, <HI>Mercy</HI> and <HI>Judgment,</HI> does con&s;i&s;t really, <HI>Totae Vitae Integritas:</HI> e&s;pecially the In|tegrity of an <HI>Officer.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Au&s;tin</HI> makes a Remark on the Order of the Words; fir&s;t, <HI>Mercy,</HI> then <HI>Judgment.</HI> Now and Here, the former; Anon the Latter. <HI>Par Tempor a di&s;tingui|nuis haec duo.</HI></P>
<P N="2"><PB N="265" REF="001946_0302_0FFCB4C0682E06A8">
2 <HI>Arnobiu,</HI> has a fire Thought here. A Saint will be an <HI>Almagiver.</HI> He will under&s;tand when a CHRIST <HI>comes</HI> to him, in the Per&s;on of a di&s;tre&s;&s;ed <HI>Brother.</HI></P>
<P N="8">8 <HI>Early.] Mun&s;ters</HI> glo&s;s is, <HI>Before others are cor|rupted with them.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Athana&s;ins</HI> has a Note of <HI>Piety</HI> here, which tho' it be not the Sen&s;e of the Place, is worth our thinking on.</P>
<P>As the <HI>Morning</HI> is the <HI>Beginning of the Day,</HI> &s;o, the <HI>Beginning of our Sin</HI> is in the fraudulent <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ugge&s;ti|on of our Enemy the <HI>Devil.</HI> To <HI>De&s;troy the Wicked in the Morning</HI> is to Ob&s;erve and Defeat the Devil, in the <HI>Beginning</HI> of his Temptations. The Soul of Man is the <HI>City of the Lord.</HI> We &s;hould betimes de&s;troy the De&s;igns of the wicked, therein, by an Early Mor|tification be&s;towed upon them.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="102" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CII.</HI> A Prayer of the Afflicted when that be is over whelmed, and poureth out his &s;ad Complaint before the ETERNAL God.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God, Do Thou &Verbar; my Supplication hear; &Verbar; and my loud Cry made in Di&s;tre&s;s, &Verbar; let it arrive to Thee, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In the Day of my Trouble, Oh! &Verbar; Hide not thy Face from me; &Verbar; Bow thine Ear to me, in the Day &Verbar; I call, &s;oon an&s;wer me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For as the Smoak <HI>does pa&s;s away</HI> &Verbar; &s;o are my Days con&s;um'd; &Verbar; and as the Wood laid on the Hearth &Verbar; my Bones are burned up.</P>
<P N="4">4 My Heart is smitten like the Gra&s;s, &Verbar; and it is withered up; &Verbar; In&s;omuch that I do forget &Verbar; to eat my daily Bread. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 By rea&s;on of the Voice that is &Verbar; by my &s;ad Groaning made; &Verbar; my bones do evident|ly cleave &Verbar; unto my wa&s;ted skin.</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="266" REF="001946_0303_0FFCB4A4238717C0">
6 I am made like the Pelican &Verbar; that's in the Wilderne&s;s; &Verbar; I am like to the Bitten<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> which &Verbar; affecteth Solitudes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 I pa&s;s the weary Nights without &Verbar; en|joying any Sleep; &Verbar; and like the Sparrow am on the &Verbar; top of the Hou&s;e alone. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 My Enemies do ca&s;t on me &Verbar; Reproaches every Day; &Verbar; they that are mad again&s;t me do &Verbar; form cur&s;ing Oaths from me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 For truly, as, * and in <HI>my</HI> Bread &Verbar; A&s;hes is what I eat; &Verbar; and my Drink I have min|gled with &Verbar; the Tears that I have &s;hed. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 From the view of thy Anger <HI>'tis,</HI> &Verbar; and of thy boiling Wrath; &Verbar; Becau&s;e that thou ha&s;t lift me up, &Verbar; and ca&s;t me down again. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 My days are like a &s;hadow which &Verbar; is now on the Decline; &Verbar; and like unto a par|ched Herb, &Verbar; ev'n &s;o I wither'd am. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 But, O ETERNAL God, Thou do&s;t &Verbar; endure forevermore; &Verbar; and thy Remem|brance from one Age &Verbar; unto another Age. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Thou wilt ari&s;e, and now thou wilt &Verbar; to Zion mercy &s;how, &Verbar; becau&s;e the time to favour her, &Verbar; yea, the &s;et Time is come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Ina&s;much as thy Servants do &Verbar; take wondrous plea&s;ure in &Verbar; the Stones thereof, and they are kind &Verbar; unto the du&s;t thereof. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 So the Name of th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; the Nations now will fear; &Verbar; and thy con&s;pi|cuous glory all &Verbar; the Kings upon the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16"><PB N="267" REF="001946_0304_0FFCB4BEE486FB90">
16 When the ETERNAL God &s;hall build &Verbar; the Zion <HI>that is fall'n,</HI> &Verbar; He &s;hall mo&s;t vi&s;ibly appear, &Verbar; in His bright Glory [<HI>there.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 He will have a re&s;pect to the &Verbar; Prayer of the humble &s;hrub; &Verbar; and on their Sup|plications He &Verbar; will not ca&s;t a contempt. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 This &s;hall be written for the Age &Verbar; hereafter to come on; &Verbar; A People yet for to be form'd &Verbar; &s;hall al&s;o Prai&s;e the Lord. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 For He hath looked down from the &Verbar; heighth of His Holine&s;s; &Verbar; From Heaven the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; exactly views the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 <HI>It is</HI> that He may hear the groan &Verbar; of him that lies in bonds; &Verbar; that He may &s;et at liberty &Verbar; &s;uch as are &s;ons of death. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 In Zion to declare the Name &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and <HI>to declare</HI> His glori|ous Prai&s;e &Verbar; in both Jeru&s;alems. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 When that united Peoples &s;hall &Verbar; their Congregations form; &Verbar; and Kingdoms <HI>do a|gree</HI> to &s;erve &Verbar; Him who's th' ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 But in the midde&s;t of the way &Verbar; <HI>unto the&s;e Glorious Things,</HI> &Verbar; He &s;orely hath afflicted me; &Verbar; He hath cut off my days. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 I &s;aid, my God, Take me not up &Verbar; in the mid&s;t of my days; &Verbar; Thy Years a Gene|ration to, &Verbar; yea, Generations la&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 In the beginning thou ha&s;t laid &Verbar; Foun|dations for the Earth; &Verbar; the Heavens al&s;o of thy hands &Verbar; are the rare Workman&s;hip. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26"><PB N="268" REF="001946_0305_0FFCB4BD42B22B98">
26 They I peri&s;h, but thou &s;halt endure; &Verbar; yea, like a garment they &Verbar; &s;hall all wax old; Thoul't change them as &Verbar; a robe, and they'l be chang'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27">27 But as for Thee, Thou ever do&s;t &Verbar; con|tinue what thou art; &Verbar; and thy years, they are &s;uch as will &Verbar; not ever be con&s;um'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 The Children of thy Servants &s;hall &Verbar; have a fix'd dwelling place; &Verbar; and their Off|&s;pring before thy face &Verbar; &s;hall be e&s;tabli&s;hed. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>WAS not the Writer of the P&s;alm, <HI>Daniel</HI> the Pro|phet, who in the approaches of a Great Re|volution, and the Deliverance of the Church from the <HI>Babyloni&s;h Captivity,</HI> &s;pent <HI>Three Sevens of Days,</HI> in Secret Prayer, with Fa&s;ting before the Lord? But, methinks, the <HI>Prophetic Spirit</HI> here expre&s;&s;es Prayers and Groans for the Jewi&s;h Nation, in their Di&s;per&s;ion, and in the approach of their Deliverance.</P>
<P N="3">3 The <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e is well; 'My Days are '&s;pent as di&s;mally, as it I liv'd and breath'd in Smoke.</P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>Bochart</HI> will maintain my Ver&s;ion for the Names of the Birds.</P>
<P N="8">8 It may be read, <HI>Sworn upon me. Mun&s;ter's</HI> Glo&s;s is; When they be&s;towed a Cur&s;e on any one, they wi&s;h'd him, <HI>As mi&s;erable as a Jew.</HI></P>
<P N="10">10 <HI>Lifted up</HI> in Glorious <HI>Hopes.</HI> [Fzra. I. 5. II. 68. III. 10.] And then <HI>ca&s;t down;</HI> all da&s;h'd again. [Ezra. IV. 4, 24.]</P>
<P N="14">14 <HI>Arnobius</HI> takes the <HI>Stones</HI> of <HI>Zion,</HI> to be the Books of the <HI>Scripture,</HI> and the <HI>Du&s;t,</HI> the <HI>Dead Saints</HI> who have &s;uffered greatly for the Cau&s;e of GOD. Be&s;ure, the &s;cattered <HI>Stones</HI> of <HI>Zion</HI> liberally taken, were more dear to the Pious Wor&s;hippers, than the goodlie&s;t Palaces in <HI>Babylon.</HI></P>
<P N="23"><PB N="269" REF="001946_0306_0FFCB541F973BF98">
23 Some think , it refers to the Afflictions the Jews met withal, <HI>in the mid&s;t</HI> of their Building.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="103" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CIII. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O My <HI>awakened</HI> Soul, Do thou &Verbar; Ble&s;s <HI>[always]</HI> the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and all my inward powers the Name &Verbar; of His pure <HI>[&s;potle&s;s]</HI> holine&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O my <HI>awakened</HI> Soul, Do thou &Verbar; Ble&s;s <HI>[always]</HI> the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and O for|get not any one &Verbar; of all His <HI>[precious]</HI> benefits. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 'Tis He who gives a pardon to &Verbar; all thy <HI>[mo&s;t vile]</HI> iniquities; &Verbar; 'Tis He who gives an healing to &Verbar; all thy <HI>[mo&s;t &s;ad]</HI> infirmities. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 'Tis He who doth redeem thy Life &Verbar; from the <HI>[dark Grave's]</HI> corrupting pit; &Verbar; 'Tis He who thee with Mercy doth &Verbar; and with <HI>[tender]</HI> compa&s;&s;ions crown. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 'Tis He who with the thing that's good &Verbar; doth &s;atisfy thy <HI>[craving]</HI> mouth; &Verbar; thy Youth it is renew'd; Then like &Verbar; the <HI>[&s;oaring]</HI> Eagle &s;halt thou be. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Th' ETERNAL God is ever One &Verbar; who does mo&s;t righteous things <HI>[to all;]</HI> &Verbar; and Judgments <HI>He doth execute</HI> &Verbar; for all <HI>[that are]</HI> oppre&s;&s;ed ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 A revelation of His ways &Verbar; He did to <HI>[Holy]</HI> Mo&s;es make; &Verbar; and He reveal'd His works unto &Verbar; the <HI>[happy]</HI> &s;ons of I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8"><PB N="270" REF="001946_0307_0FFCB4E1607069B0">
8 Th' ETERNAL God is merciful; &Verbar; and <HI>[He is]</HI> full of clemency; &Verbar; to anger &s;low, but plenteous &Verbar; <HI>[He is]</HI> in all be<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ignity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 He won't di&s;pen&s;e rebukes in wrath &Verbar; to <HI>[la&s;ting]</HI> perpetuity; &Verbar; He will not have it in re&s;erve &Verbar; unto <HI>[Endle&s;s]</HI> Eternity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 His dealings have not been with us &Verbar; according to our <HI>[horrid]</HI> Sins; &Verbar; nor hath He recompenced us &Verbar; according to our <HI>[heinous]</HI> crimes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Becau&s;e that as the Heavens are &Verbar; in heighth <HI>[rais'd up]</HI> above the Earth, &Verbar; &s;o upon them that fear Him doth &Verbar; His <HI>[match+le&s;&s;]</HI> mercy ever come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Even as far as is the Ea&s;t &Verbar; <HI>[remov'd]</HI> in di&s;tance from the We&s;t, &Verbar; our tre&s;pa&s;&s;es He makes to be &Verbar; di&s;tant &s;o <HI>[very]</HI> far from us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 At the rate that a Father to &Verbar; Children is <HI>[very]</HI> pitiful, &Verbar; th' ETERNAL God, for them who do &Verbar; fear Him has <HI>[yearning]</HI> pity too. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 For He is well acquainted with &Verbar; the <HI>[feeble]</HI> frame wherein we're made, &Verbar; He very well remembers this, &Verbar; that we are very <HI>[&s;orry]</HI> du&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 For &s;oon-forgotten Man, his days &Verbar; are like unto the <HI>[fading]</HI> gra&s;s; &Verbar; As the flowre that is in the field, &Verbar; &s;o 'tis He flouri&s;hes <HI>[a while.]</HI></P>
<P N="16">16 For the wind pa&s;&s;es over it, &Verbar; and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">|&s;ently <HI>[at once]</HI> 'tis gone; &Verbar; and in the place where once it &s;tood, &Verbar; it will be <HI>[&s;een and]</HI> known no more. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17"><PB N="271" REF="001946_0308_0FFCB50676101680">
17 But the m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t kind benignity &Verbar; of <HI>[Him who's]</HI> the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; is from un|known Eternity <HI>[la&s;ting]</HI> ev'n to Eternity; &Verbar; Upon &s;uch as do exerci&s;e &Verbar; a <HI>[real]</HI> con&s;tant fear of Him; &Verbar; and unto Childrens Children is &Verbar; His <HI>[faithful]</HI> con&s;tant right'ou&s;ne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 <HI>'Tis meant,</HI> to &s;uch as faithfully &Verbar; do keep His <HI>[Holy]</HI> Covenant, &Verbar; and to tho&s;e who His Precepts mind, &Verbar; that they may do the things <HI>[requir'd.]</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 His Throne has the ETERNAL God &Verbar; <HI>[fir'd and]</HI> prepared in the Heav'ns; &Verbar; His Kingdom al&s;o over all &Verbar; extends its <HI>[Righteous]</HI> Government. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 O ye His A<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">gels, va&s;t in &s;trength, &Verbar; Ble&s;s ye <HI>[and Drai&s;e]</HI> th' ETERNAL God; &Verbar; who do His word, that &s;o the voice &Verbar; of His word may be <HI>[duly]</HI> heard. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 O Ble&s;s ye the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; All ye His Mar&s;ha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">d <HI>[Numerous]</HI> Ho&s;ts; &Verbar; ye Min<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;ters who execute &Verbar; His Will <HI>[when 'tis]</HI> made known to you. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 Ble&s;s ye th' ETERNAL God, O all &Verbar; His works <HI>[that are]</HI> in places all &Verbar; of His Dominion; O my Soul, &Verbar; Ble&s;s thou <HI>[and prai&s;e]</HI> th' ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold now, the Jewi&s;h Nation returned, and re|ceived into the Favour of GOD, and Exhorting, all Creatures to celebrate the Miracles of His Power and of His Goodne&s;s.</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="272" REF="001946_0309_0FFCB504F20505F0">
2 In the <HI>Midra&s;h Tillin,</HI> there is an out-of-the-way Ob&s;ervation, That the P&s;almi&s;t calls on him&s;elf to <HI>Ble&s;&s; the Lord,</HI> no le&s;s than <HI>Five Times</HI> over: which an&s;wers not only to the <HI>Five Books</HI> of the Law: but al&s;o to the <HI>Five Ages</HI> thro' which Man is to pa&s;s. <HI>Fir&s;t,</HI> Fl<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> Condition in His Mothers Womb. <HI>Secondly,</HI> His Con|dition at his Mothers Brea&s;t. <HI>Thirdly,</HI> His Condition while pa&s;&s;ing thro' the Changes of this World. <HI>Fourthly,</HI> His Condition in the pre&s;ence of GOD after Death, <HI>Fifthly,</HI> His Condition after the Re&s;urrection in the World to come.</P>
<P N="5">5 The Ble&s;&s;ings of the <HI>Re&s;urrection from the Dead,</HI> are here celebrated. That Clau&s;e, <HI>He redeems thy Life from de&s;truction,</HI> evidently points unto it. Now 'tis one of the Promi&s;es, concerning the Ble&s;&s;ings of the <HI>Re&s;urrection,</HI> I&s;a. XL. 31. <HI>They &s;hall mount up with wings as Eagles,</HI> which the Jews admirably ap|ply to the <HI>Bodies rai&s;ed from the Dead.</HI> In this Pa&s;&s;age which has hitherto been read, <HI>Thy Youth is re|newed like the Eagles;</HI> there are Two Clau&s;es couched according to the &s;hort Hebrew way of expre&s;&s;ing things; Fir&s;t; <HI>Thou &s;halt renew thy Youth;</HI> which <HI>Bochart</HI> proves to be the true Reading; A thing to be done in the be&s;t &s;en&s;e imaginable, at the <HI>Re&s;urrection.</HI> And then, <HI>Thou &s;halt be like the Eagles.</HI> The mar|vellous Flight and Strength of the <HI>Re&s;urrection-Bo|dies,</HI> is excellently &s;et forth by that Compari&s;on. The Vulgar Tradition of the <HI>Eagle renewing his Youth</HI> is not countenanced here.</P>
<P N="14">14 By, our <HI>Frame</HI> here, the Jewi&s;h Rabbi's under|&s;tand the <HI>Iatzar Harang,</HI> the <HI>Figmentum malum,</HI> the <HI>Evil Frame,</HI> which we call <HI>Original Sin;</HI> whereof we read, <HI>Gen.</HI> VIII. 21. <HI>The imagination of the Heart of Man is evil from his Youth.</HI> The &s;ame which they call, <HI>The Poi&s;on of the Old Serpent.</HI> And <HI>The Enemy,</HI> whereof we &s;o often read in the Sacred Oracles. And, <HI>The Heart of Stone.</HI></P>
<P N="17"><PB N="273" REF="001946_0310_0FFCB53FB4E33710">
17 Let not the Glo&s;s be &s;o received, as to prejudice the Regards due to the <HI>Rightiou&s;ne&s;s</HI> of GOD, illu&s;triou&s;ly di&s;played in &s;howing Favour to us for the <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> of our SAVIOUR. But yet, it may be allowed and ob&s;erved, That <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> is a Term &s;ometimes u&s;ed for <HI>Benignity.</HI> Thus, <HI>A Rain of Righteou&s;ne&s;s,</HI> is a Bountiful Rain. And our <HI>Dru&s;ius</HI> would have, <HI>The Sun of Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> to be a <HI>Sun</HI> that bountifully and liberally imparts <HI>Light</HI> and <HI>Heat</HI> unto the World.</P>
</DIV3>
