<P N="8">8 The mountains, they make their a&s;cent; &Verbar; the valleys, they de&s;cend: &Verbar; <HI>All</HI> &s;till unto the proper place, &Verbar; Thou'&s;t founded this for them.</P>
<P N="9">9 Thou ha&s;t determined a Bound &Verbar; the which they &s;hall not pa&s;s; &Verbar; that &s;o they mayn't return again &Verbar; to overwhelm the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Into the valleys He &s;ends forth&Verbar;<HI>Waters that flow from</HI> &s;prings; &Verbar; which do among the mountains take &Verbar; their never-cea&s;ing walk &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 They do be&s;tow their drink on all &Verbar; the bea&s;ts that range the field; &Verbar; <HI>There</HI> the will a&s;&s;es, <HI>tho' &s;o wild</HI>&Verbar;<HI>and &s;tupid,</HI> quench their thir&s;t&Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 By the&s;e the fowls of Heaven have&Verbar;their habitation made; &Verbar; among the branches here they do &Verbar; give a <HI>melodious</HI> voice. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 He from His chambers doth di&s;till &Verbar; waters upon the hills; &Verbar; from the fruit of thy works the Earth &Verbar; is fully &s;atisfy'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 He for the Bea&s;ts makes gra&s;s to grow; &Verbar; and for the u&s;e of Man &Verbar; He <HI>granteth</HI> herb, that &s;o He may &Verbar; fetch food out of the Earth.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Ev'n wine that chears the heart of Man, &Verbar; that &s;o his face may &s;hine &Verbar; with oil; and bread which does give &s;trength &Verbar; unto the heart of Man. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 The trees of the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; the&s;e do abound with &s;ap; &Verbar; the cedars of the Le|banon &Verbar; which He has planted there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17"><PB N="275" REF="001946_0312_0FFCB53E320FE330">
17 That &s;o the little Birds may there &Verbar; build and enjoy their ne&s;ts; &Verbar; The Stork <HI>par|ticularly</HI> has &Verbar; the fir-trees for her hou&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 The mountains of a &s;tately heighth &Verbar; for the Wild-Goats are the&s;e;&Verbar;the rocks, the&s;e are a refuge where&Verbar;the Rock-rats lodge them&s;elves.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 He form'd the Moon that &s;o it might&Verbar; determine &s;tated times; &Verbar; The Sun is well acquainted with &Verbar; the time of g<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ing down. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 The darkne&s;s thou did&s;t con&s;titute, &Verbar; and then the Night arrives; &Verbar; all the wild-crea|tures of the wood &Verbar; do creep abroad in it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 That &s;o they may come at their prey &Verbar; then the young Lions roar; &Verbar; that &s;o they may by &s;eeking find &Verbar; their &s;u&s;tenance from God.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 The Sun does ri&s;e; <HI>on this</HI> they do&Verbar;gather them&s;elves together;&Verbar; and then they to their dens repair &Verbar; there to lay down them&s;elves.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Man <HI>being &s;o &s;ecure from the&s;e,</HI> &Verbar; goes forth unto his work; &Verbar; and to his <HI>u&s;ual</HI> hus|bandry, &Verbar; until the Evening come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 Thy works, O Thou ETERNAL God,&Verbar; how are they multiply'd? &Verbar; In wi&s;dom ha&s;t thou made them all; &Verbar; Th' Earth's with thy riches fill'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 This great and &s;preading Sea <HI>is &s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">;</HI>&Verbar;the &s;wimming things are there; &Verbar; And there's no number; living things &Verbar; both &s;mall and great are there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 There 'tis the Ships do &s;teer their cour&s;e.
<PB N="276" REF="001946_0313_0FFCB53C53E94658"><HI>There's</HI> that Levia than: &Verbar; him thou ha&s;t form'd that &s;o he may &Verbar; enjoy his &s;port therein. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 All of the&s;e things on thee alone&Verbar;have, their dependence &s;till, &Verbar; that &s;o thou in due &s;ea&s;on may'&s;t &Verbar; afford their food <HI>to them.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 'Tis what thou do&s;t afford to them, that they do gather up; &Verbar; Thy hand thou open'&s;t, &s;o they are &Verbar; then &s;atisfy'd with good. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="29">29 Thou hid'&s;t thy face, they're troubled then;&Verbar;Their &s;pirit thou withdraw'&s;t; they die, and &s;o they do return &Verbar; to their <HI>Original</HI> du&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="30">30 Thou wilt &s;end forth thy &s;pirit; they &Verbar; created are <HI>anew;</HI> &Verbar; and thou to the face of the Earth, &Verbar; wilt a renewal give. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="31">31 The Glory of th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; it &s;hall endure forever; &Verbar; The joy of the ETER|NAL God &Verbar; will be in all his works. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="32">32 He does look down upon the Earth; &Verbar; it falls a trembling then: &Verbar; He to the moun|tains gives a touch, &Verbar; and pre&s;ently they &s;moke,&Verbar;</P>
<P N="33">33 I'll &s;ing to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; as long as I do live; &Verbar; while I have any being I will &s;ing unto my God. &Verbar;</P>
