<DIV1 N="5" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>THE FIFTH BOOK OF PSALMS.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="107" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CVII.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Make you a Confe&s;&s;ion now &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; becau&s;e that He is Good; becau&s;e &Verbar; His mercy is forever. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 So let them &s;ay, who've been redeem'd &Verbar; by the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; tho&s;e whom He hath redeem'd from the &Verbar; hand of the enemy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 And tho&s;e whom He hath gather'd from &Verbar; the Lands, ev'n from the Ea&s;t, &Verbar; and from the We&s;t, <HI>and</HI> from the North, &Verbar; as likewi&s;e from the Sea. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 They wandred in the Wilderne&s;s &Verbar; in &s;olitary ways; &Verbar; they did not find a City which &Verbar; might be inhabited, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="291" REF="001946_0328_0FFCB6014BAF5D10">
5 They were with hunger fami&s;hed &Verbar; and they were parch'd with thir&s;t; &Verbar; their Soul within them overwhel'md, &Verbar; was ready for to faint. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Then in their trouble they do cry &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; He then did them de|liver from &Verbar; their grievous angui&s;hes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 And He in a right way did give &Verbar; a con|duct unto them; &Verbar; that they might to a City go &Verbar; for habitation <HI>there.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Let Men to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; con|fe&s;s His mercy now; &Verbar; and the mo&s;t wondrous things which He &Verbar; does for the Sons of Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 For He doth &s;atisfy the Soul &Verbar; wandring with appetites; &Verbar; and He doth fill the fami&s;hed Soul &Verbar; with what is very good. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 There are tho&s;e who impri&s;on'd &s;it &Verbar; in darkne&s;s and the &s;hades &Verbar; of Death; in great Affliction bound &Verbar; and Iron <HI>chaining them.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 <HI>It is</HI> becau&s;e they have rebell'd &Verbar; again&s;t the words of God; &Verbar; and they've de&s;pis'd the Coun&s;el of &Verbar; Him who is the mo&s;t High. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Therefore He with hard labour did &Verbar; bring down the heart of them; &Verbar; they fell down <HI>under it</HI> and there &Verbar; was none to &s;uccour them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Then in their trouble they did cry &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; He then did them de|liver from &Verbar; their grievous angui&s;hes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 He brought them out of darkne&s;s, and &Verbar;
<PB N="292" REF="001946_0329_0FFCB689843D9240">our of the &s;hades of death; and He did br<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> a&s;under all a the Chains that fetter'd the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">.</P>
<P N="15">15 LetMen to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; con<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> His mercy now; &Verbar; and the mo&s;t wondro<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> things which He &Verbar; does for the Sons of M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters">.</P>
<P N="16">16 Becau&s;e that He hath broke the Ga<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> the which were made of brafs &Verbar; and the &s;tr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters"> Iron Bars, He hath &Verbar; cut the&s;e to peices qui<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">.</P>
<P N="17">17 Fools for the way the which they d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> their tran&s;gre&s;&s;ion take, &Verbar; and for th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> wrong iniquities &Verbar; do with affliction meet.</P>
<P N="18">18 All manner of repa&s;t their Soul &Verbar; d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> then abominate; and they make their <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> pr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">c<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">es to &Verbar; the very Gates or Death. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Then in their trouble they did cry &Verbar; the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; He then did them d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> liver from &Verbar; their grievous angui&s;hes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 He will &s;end forth his word, and will give healing unto them; &Verbar; and He w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ll the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> deliver them &Verbar; out of their Sepulchres. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Let Men to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; co<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> &s;e&s;s His mercy now; &Verbar; and the mo&s;t w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> drous things which He &Verbar; does for the So<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> of Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 And let them &s;acrifice of prai&s;e &Verbar; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;acrifices now; &Verbar; let them al&s;o declare H<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters"> Works &Verbar; with a triumphant &s;ong. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 They who imbark'd in Ve&s;&s;e<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">s do &Verbar; down unto the Sea; &Verbar; they that on many <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">rs have &Verbar; a bu&s;ine&s;s to pur&s;ue. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24"><PB N="293" REF="001946_0330_0FFCB68B108E0D68">
24 The&s;e have a view of the Works done &Verbar; by the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and of the won|drous things that are &Verbar; occurring in the deep. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 And when He gives the word, He makes &Verbar; the &s;tormy Wind to ri&s;e; &Verbar; there|with He makes the rolling waves &Verbar; &s;well to a mighty heighth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 They mount up to the Heavens; they &Verbar; go down unto the Deeps; &Verbar; their Soul does in this evil time &Verbar; a Di&s;&s;olution feel. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="27">27 They're to&s;s'd, and they do &s;tagger like &Verbar; unto a drunken man; &Verbar; and now all of their Wi&s;dom is &Verbar; entirely &s;wallow'd up. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="28">28 Then in their trouble they do cry &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; He then does bring them forth out of &Verbar; their grievous angui&s;hes. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="29">29 Into a Silence He does make &Verbar; the roar|ing Tempe&s;t &s;top; &Verbar; and the unquiet waves to lay &Verbar; a&s;ide their boi&s;t'rous noi&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="30">30 Then are they very glad, becau&s;e &Verbar; they are &s;o quieted; &Verbar; and He does bring them well unto &Verbar; the Port of their de&s;ire. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="31">31 Let Men to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; con|fe&s;s His Mercy now; &Verbar; and the mo&s;t wondrous things which He &Verbar; does for the &s;ons of Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="32">32 Yea, and Let them exalt Him where &Verbar; the People u&s;e to meet, &Verbar; and let them greatly prai&s;e Him where &Verbar; the Elders u&s;e to &s;it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="33">33 Rivers He doth reduce into &Verbar; a parch|ed Wilderne&s;s; &Verbar; and places wherein Wa|ters flow'd &Verbar; into a thir&s;ty Land. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="34"><PB N="294" REF="001946_0331_0FFCB606BB5CF1F8">
34 A fruitful Land <HI>He does reduce</HI> &Verbar; to &s;alt &s;terility; &Verbar; by rea&s;on of the wickedne&s;s &Verbar; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> them who dwell therein. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="35">35 The wilderne&s;s He does reduce &Verbar; into a Pond of Waters, &Verbar; and the for&s;aken Land into &Verbar; places where waters flow. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="36">36 And there He makes the &s;tarving One<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> to find a dwelling place; &Verbar; Yea, they a City do prepare &Verbar; for habitation there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="37">37 And &s;o they cultivate the Fields; &Verbar; they do plant Vineyards too: &Verbar; and there they do obtain the fruit &Verbar; of u&s;ual increa&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="38">38 He does al&s;o be&s;tow on them &Verbar; His ble&s;&s;ing and they are &Verbar; much multiply'd; their cattle too, &Verbar; He don't dimini&s;h <HI>them.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="39">39 Again they are dimini&s;hed, &Verbar; and they're brought very low; &Verbar; thro' Tyranny, Afflicti|on and &Verbar; a mind oppre&s;s'd with grief. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="40">40 He upon Princes does pour out &Verbar; Con|temptuous di&s;grace; &Verbar; and He doth make them wander in &Verbar; a De&s;art where's no Road. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="41">41 But yet He does rai&s;e up the Poor &Verbar; from out of Penury; &Verbar; and He produceth Families &Verbar; that &s;hall be like a Flock. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="42">42 The upright ones &s;hall take a view, &Verbar; and &s;hall be very glad; &Verbar; but all Iniquity &s;hall now &Verbar; <HI>forever</HI> &s;top its Mouth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="43">43 Who is there now that will be wi&s;e, &Verbar; and will ob&s;erve the&s;e things? &Verbar; The&s;e &s;hall the mer|cies under&s;tand &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="295" REF="001946_0332_0FFCB68D929F49C8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>TIS an Hymn for the Jewi&s;h Nation, gathered from its Di&s;per&s;ion, and confe&s;&s;ing the Miracles which the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> performs for their Deliverance.</P>
<P>We have it &s;everal times over, <HI>Then in their trouble they do cry unto the ETERNAL God;</HI> But we do not find it &s;aid &s;o much as once, upon their Deliverances, <HI>then they prai&s;ed the Lord for His Goodne&s;s.</HI> No, that matter always comes in with a <HI>Let Men confe&s;s.</HI> Alas, Tis to be <HI>De&s;ired</HI> that they would; hardly to be <HI>&s;uppo&s;ed,</HI> that they <HI>will.</HI></P>
<P N="16">16 Old <HI>Ayn<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">bius</HI> has an Holy and a &s;olemn Tho'<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">; <HI>Gates of Bre&s;s</HI> and <HI>Bars of Iron</HI> are <HI>Habits of Sin.</HI></P>
<P N="20">20 The Jewi&s;h Writers quoted by <HI>Galatinus,</HI> have many a&s;toni&s;hing Pa&s;&s;ages on this Ver&s;e. They find the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> to be, <HI>The Word,</HI> here &s;ent by God. They find, <HI>Healing Miracles</HI> wrought by Him. They find that a &s;ingular &s;hare of his Favours would be granted unto Per&s;ons, who&s;e <HI>Bu&s;ine&s;s</HI> lies <HI>upon the Waters,</HI> and even unto dull <HI>Fi&s;hermen.</HI></P>
<P N="23">23 <HI>Arnobius</HI> would fain have tho&s;e that <HI>go to Sea in Ships,</HI> to mean, tho&s;e who lead an holy Conver&s;a|tion in the World, and by their In&s;truction and Exam|ple bring many People to Piety. Oh! That they who <HI>go to Sea in Ships,</HI> would more an&s;wer this Character!</P>
<P N="34">34 <HI>Terry</HI> in his Travails ob&s;erves, (as others have al&s;o done) <HI>Can<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">an</HI> was a <HI>Fruitful Land,</HI> and like the <HI>Garden of God,</HI> and able to feed a Prodigious Multi|tude of People. Whereas the Ble&s;&s;ing of God is now &s;o withdrawn from it, that it will not nouri&s;h and &s;u&s;tain an Hundredth Part of &s;uch a Number, as once lived upon it.</P>
<P N="43">43 Who&s;oever will be truly wi&s;e, ought to ponder &s;uch Pa&s;&s;ages of the Divine Providence, that they may make others who are le&s;s con&s;iderate, under&s;tand, how gracious the Lord is to them, who &s;tudy to plea&s;e Him, and obtain His Favour. This is the <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="108" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="296" REF="001946_0333_0FFCB691402DCAA8">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CVIII.</HI> A Song. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O God, With preparation now &Verbar; my heart is well confirmd; &Verbar; I<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ll &s;ing with voice, and &s;ing with &s;trings; &Verbar; yea, &s;o my Glory &s;hall. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O <HI>well-tun'd</HI> P&s;altery, Do thou &Verbar; awake <HI>unto the work;</HI> &Verbar; Awake, O Harp; I' th' early morn &Verbar; I will my &s;elf awake. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Among the Peoples I will prai&s;e &Verbar; Thee O ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and I will unto thee aloud &Verbar; among the Nations &s;ing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 For from above the Heavens is &Verbar; thy mercy magnify'd; &Verbar; and to the terder Clouds <HI>there doth &Verbar; extend</HI> thy faithfulne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Above the Heav'ns, O God the Judge, &Verbar; be thou lift up on high, &Verbar; and over all the Earth let be &Verbar; thy Glory &s;pread abroad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 That thy beloved ones may have &Verbar; a full deliverance, &Verbar; Do thou now &s;ave by thy right hand, &Verbar; and do thou an&s;wer me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 God hath &s;poke in His holine&s;s, &Verbar; I will triumph with joy; &Verbar; Shechem I will divide, I will &Verbar; mea&s;ure out Succoths Vale. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Gilead is what I claim for mine; &Verbar; M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|na&s;&s;eh too is mine; &Verbar; Ephraim is of my &s;trength the head; &Verbar; Judah's my Lawgiver. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Moab's a Pot wherein I'll wa&s;h; &Verbar; On Edom I will ca&s;t &Verbar; my Shoe, <HI>and</HI> I will triumph now &Verbar; over Phili&s;tia. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Who will conduct me unto the &Verbar;
<PB N="297" REF="001946_0334_0FFCB60C223650E8">well-fortified Town? &Verbar; Into the heart of Edom, who &Verbar; is it will lead me on? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Is it not Thou, O God, who did&s;t &Verbar; ca&s;t us off heretofore? &Verbar; Even Thou, O God, who did&s;t not go out with our Armed Ho&s;ts. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 O give us &s;uccour from Di&s;tre&s;s; &Verbar; for vain's the help of Man. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Thro' God we &s;hall do valiantly; &Verbar; And He'll tread down our foes. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe Prophetic Spirit here teaches the Jewi&s;h Nati|on to figh after the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">lorious Reign of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah;</HI> when they &s;hall repo&s;&s;e&s;s their Country and &s;ee the De|&s;truction of their Enemies; e&s;pecially of <HI>Edom,</HI> on the Roman Empire.</P>
<P N="3">3 Some note an Empha&s;is in the Ori<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">nal, <HI>I will wake the Morning.</HI> The <HI>Morning</HI> has not found me <HI>Sleep|ing,</HI> but I have rather wakened <HI>That.</HI></P>
<P N="9">9 <HI>Aben-Ezra's</HI> Glo&s;s is, I will <HI>Water</HI> my Earth, I will do my People no <HI>Hurt,</HI> but <HI>Good,</HI> by the Hands of <HI>Moah.</HI></P>
<P>But rather, like R. <HI>Solomon,</HI> Compare 2. King. III. ii.</P>
</DIV3>
