<P>In the Fifth Ver&s;e of the P&s;alm now before us, we &s;ind the <HI>Idumaeans</HI> and <HI>Arabians;</HI> that is to &s;ay, the <HI>Romans</HI> and the <HI>Mahometans.</HI></P>
<P N="4">4 A <HI>Long</HI> Fire as well as a <HI>Strong</HI> one, is here pointed at. <HI>Juniper</HI> abounds with a piercing <HI>Oyl,</HI> which yields a very <HI>&s;harp</HI> Fire; and <HI>Pliny</HI> &s;ays, <HI>Coals of Juniper,</HI> being raked up, will keep a glowing Fire for a whole Year together.</P>
<P N="5">5 The Hebrew Particle <HI>Gnim,</HI> is to be tran&s;lated, <HI>Like,</HI> as well as, <HI>In,</HI> or <HI>With.</HI> As I remember <HI>Gla&s;&s;ius</HI> thus reads the Text now be ore us. But &s;ome think that the Calumnies of <HI>Doeg</HI> did force <HI>David,</HI> actually to take a flight into the&s;e Countries. Or, <HI>Me&s;heck,</HI> as <HI>Bochart</HI> thinks, may &s;ignify, not a <HI>Place</HI> but the <HI>Length of Time,</HI> which he &s;tayed in his Exile. All the Ancient Interpreters exeept one, under&s;tand it &s;o. <HI>Patricks</HI> Pa|raphra&s;e is; 'I groan, not only in a tedious Bani&s;h|ment from my own Country, but I am forced to &s;eek for &s;helter among the Barbarous <HI>Arabs.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="121" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXI.</HI> A Song for Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 I Lift my Eyes up to the Hills: &Verbar; From whence &s;hould come my help? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 My help's from the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; who made the Heav'ns and Earth, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="350" REF="001946_0387_0FFCB8E7DA5C13D0">
3 He will not let thy foot be mov'd; &Verbar; thy Keeper &s;lumbers not. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Lo, He that keepeth I&s;rael; &Verbar; He &s;lum|bers not, nor &s;l<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">eps. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Th' ETERNAL God is He who is &Verbar; th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>watchful</HI> Keeper &s;till; &Verbar; Th' ETERNAL God becomes thy &s;hade; &Verbar; at thy right hand <HI>He &s;tands.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The Sun &s;hall not &s;mite thee by Day &Verbar; nor &s;hall the Moon by Night. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Th' ETERNAL keeps thee from all ill. &Verbar; He &s;hall pre&s;erve thy Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Th' ETERNAL keeps thy going out; &Verbar; and <HI>keeps</HI> thy coming in; &Verbar; He does it from this time and will &Verbar; do it forevermore. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe Title here a l<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ttle differs from the other Fo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">|teen. <HI>Cajetan</HI> ob&s;erving it, has a &s;troke of <HI>Chri&s;tian Mode&s;ty,</HI> which we may often find occa&s;ion to u&s;e, when Difficultles in the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">acred Scriptures occur unto us; <HI>Re&s;ervo Spiritur Sancto.</HI> Re&s;tored <HI>I&s;ra<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> will thus comfort her&s;elf. Compare, <HI>I&s;ai.</HI> LX. 19. and <HI>Rev.</HI> XXII. 5.</P>
<P N="5">5 An Allu&s;ion to the <HI>Pillar</HI> of <HI>Cloud</HI> and <HI>Firs,</HI> which accommodated <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> travelling thro' the Wil|derne&s;s.</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Sunt Solis et Lunae Tela, Pe&s;tis.</HI> The P&s;alm<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> after the Faith of the Second Ver&s;e comes to &s;upp<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">he <HI>Angels</HI> uttering to him in the <HI>Holy Place,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 words"> Comolations. See, 2 <HI>Sam.</HI> XVII. 1, 6, 22.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="122" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="351" REF="001946_0388_0FFCB8E95D5BF5F0">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXII.</HI> A Song of Degrees. Of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 I Took delight in <HI>hearing</HI> them &Verbar; who &s;aid thus unto me, &Verbar; We will go up unto the hou&s;e &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Our Feer were &s;tanding once within&Verbar;thy Gates, Jeru&s;alem. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Jeru&s;alem's as a City built &Verbar; compacted well together. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Thither the Tribes go up, the Tribes &Verbar; of JAH, to th' Oracle &Verbar; of I&s;rael, for to Prai&s;e the Name &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For there are plac'd the Thrones on which &Verbar; Judgment is given forth; &Verbar; The Thrones which do unto the Hou&s;e of David appertain. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 For the Peace of Jeru&s;alem &Verbar; O make a &s;trong reque&s;t: &Verbar;They who have a true love to thee &Verbar; &s;hall &s;ee Pro&s;perity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Let there be Peace within the Wall &Verbar; which thou'rt &s;urrounded with; &Verbar; Let there be &s;een Pro&s;perity &Verbar; within thy Palaces. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 For the &s;ake of my Brethren, and &Verbar; of my A&s;&s;ociates; &Verbar; this is what I will utter now, &Verbar; Let Peace be found in thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 For the &s;ake of the Hou&s;e which to&Verbar; th' ETERNAL God belongs,&Verbar; <HI>Even the God</HI> who is our God; &Verbar; I will pur&s;ue thy Good.&Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>I Find, the Ancients Expounding the P&s;alm, concerning the State of Things in the <HI>New Jeru&s;alem,</HI> after the <HI>Fir&s;t Re&s;urrection.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="352" REF="001946_0389_0FFCB4752E202AA0">
And &s;o Dr. <HI>Allix</HI> ob&s;erves, The P&s;alm is the Glad|ne&s;s of Re&s;tored <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> It &s;uppo&s;es the Twelve Tribes ga|thered, <HI>Jeru&s;alem</HI> rebuilt, the Twelve Seats of the A|po&s;tles laid, and the Reign of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> e&s;tabli&s;hed.</P>
<P>Some &s;ee this occa&s;ion for the P&s;alm. <HI>David</HI> having &s;etled the Ark at <HI>Jeru&s;alem,</HI> and being at this Time on &s;ome Coca&s;ion in the Country, heard the good Peo|ple there &s;peak one to another, as &s;ome of them did unto him, of going to Wor&s;hip God, at &s;ome of the Three Solemn Fe&s;tivals: This devotion of theirs, as it rejoyced his heart, &s;o probably it moved him to com|po&s;e the P&s;alm, for their u&s;e at &s;uch Times as the&s;e.</P>
<P>The <HI>Talmuds</HI> tell us, they did u&s;e to &s;ing the <HI>Fir&s; Ver&s;e</HI> of the P&s;alm, as they went out of the Country towards <HI>Jeru&s;alem,</HI> carrying their <HI>Fir&s;t Fruits</HI> unto the Hou&s;e of the Lord, as the Law, [Deut. XXVI. 2.] directed them. And when they entred within the Gates of the City, they Sang the <HI>Second</HI> Ver&s;e. There they were met by &s;ome of the Citizens who Sang the re&s;t of the P&s;alm together with them, as they went towards the Temple. Of this Cu&s;tom <HI>Selden</HI> gives us a fuller Account.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="123" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXIII.</HI> A Song of Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 TO Thee I lift my Eyes, O Thou &Verbar; who dwelle&s;t in the Heav'ns. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Lo, as the Eyes of Servants are &Verbar; to the hand of their Lords; &Verbar; as the Eyes of the Handmaid are &Verbar; unto her Ladies hand; &Verbar;even &s;o our eyes are <HI>kept intent</HI> &Verbar; on the ETER|NAL God. &Verbar; <HI>He is</HI> our God <HI>and unto Him&Verbar; w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> do direct our look; &Verbar;</HI> until that He upon us &s;hall &Verbar; compa&s;&s;ion plea&s;e to have, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="353" REF="001946_0390_0FFCB8ECAB135800">
3 Pity us, O ETERNAL God; &Verbar; have pity upon us: &Verbar; for with contempt that's ca&s;t on us &Verbar; We're fill'd exceedingly. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Our S<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ul is fill'd exceedingly &Verbar; with the contemptuous &s;corn &Verbar; of &s;uch as live a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ea&s;e; with the &Verbar; di&s;dain of haughty ones. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE <HI>Prophetic Spirit</HI> here prepares a priver, for the <HI>Jews,</HI> under the oppre&s;&s;ion of <HI>Antichri&s;t,</HI> Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> thinks it a &s;nott Prayer mane by a pious per&s;on, when the King of <HI>A&s;&s;yria,</HI> &s;ent <HI>Ra<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;h kali,</HI> and his other Captains, to the be&s;ie<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ing of <HI>Jeru&s;alem;</HI> when they ca&s;t the utmo&s;t contempt on the People of God. [2. King. XVIII, XIX.] It m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ght be compo&s;ed by <HI>I&s;aiah,</HI> when <HI>Hezekiah</HI> de&s;ired him to <HI>lift up a Pray<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> for th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Remnant that was left.</HI> Perhaps both <HI>Hezekich</HI> and he, <HI>lift up their Eyes to Heaven,</HI> and u&s;ed the&s;e Words.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="124" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXIV.</HI> A Song of Degrees</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BUT that th' ETERNAL was with us, &Verbar; Now this may I&s;rael &s;ay.</P>
<P N="2">2 But that th' ETERNAL was with us, &Verbar; when Men again&s;t us ro&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Then had they &s;wallow'd us alive, &Verbar; when their wrath rag'd at us. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Then had the waters cover'd us, &Verbar; the &s;tream gone o'er our Soul.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="354" REF="001946_0391_0FFCB8EE5F789460">
5 Then the proud &s;welling waters had &Verbar; &s;urely gone o'er our Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Ble&s;s'd be th' ETERNAL, who gives not &Verbar; us to their Teeth a prey. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Our Soul's e&s;caped as a bird &Verbar; out of the Fowlers &s;nare; &Verbar; the &s;nare is broken; and we are &Verbar; e&s;caped out of it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Our help is in the Name of Him &Verbar; who's the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; He is the Pow|erful Maker of &Verbar; the Heavens and the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe Miraculous con&s;ervation of <HI>I&s;rael</HI> among the Idolaters and Barbarians, who have often &s;ought their entire De&s;truction, is here celebrated.</P>
<P N="8">8 The Jews apprehend, not only the <HI>Cau&s;e,</HI> but al&s;o the very <HI>Time</HI> of their great Redemption to be here my&s;teriou&s;ly intimated. The Lord permitted <HI>Six Days</HI> to roll away, <HI>while He made Heaven and Earth.</HI> Even <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o, they &s;ay, the Lord will not appear for their <HI>Help,</HI> till towards the End of the <HI>Sixth</HI> Millennium; For, <HI>A Thou&s;and Years is with the Lord <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">s one day. Then their Soul will e&s;cape as a Bird out of the Snare of the Fowler.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="125" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXV.</HI> A Song of Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 THey who tru&s;t in th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; the&s;e as Mount Zion are; &Verbar; which is not to be mov'd, but &s;tands &Verbar; to perpetuity.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Mountains &s;urround Jeru&s;alem;&Verbar; &s;o the ETERNAL God &Verbar; &s;urrounds His People from this time. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">v<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n for evermore.&Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="355" REF="001946_0392_0FFCB6728115E4A0">
3 For the Rod of Iniquity &Verbar; &s;hall not re&s;t on the Lot &Verbar; of ju&s;t ones: le&s;t the ju&s;t put forth &Verbar; their hands to Wickedne&s;s &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O Thou ETERNAL God, Do Thou &Verbar; plea&s;e to do good unto &Verbar; &s;uch as are good, and to &s;uch as &Verbar; are in their hearts upright:&Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 But &s;uch as turn to crooked ways, &Verbar; th' ETERNAL God will the&s;e &Verbar; with evil Doers make to go. &Verbar; Peace upon I&s;rael now!&Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>DR. <HI>Patrick</HI> looks on the P&s;alm, as an Exhortation unto the People, to tru&s;t in God, when <HI>Senna|cherib</HI> threatned the De&s;truction of <HI>Jeru&s;alem.</HI> The&s;e may be &s;ome of the <HI>Comfortable Words.</HI> which <HI>Heze|kiah</HI> then &s;pake unto them. [2. Chron. XXXII. 6.7.8.] When God cha&s;ti&s;ed them with that <HI>Rod of His Anger.</HI> [See, I&s;ai, X. 5.]</P>
<P>Dr. <HI>Allix</HI> looks further, and &s;ees here; a Proplecy of <HI>I&s;rael's</HI> Pre&s;ervation, and the De&s;truction of the <HI>Antichri&s;tian</HI> Powers, which oppre&s;s them, and per|&s;ecute the Church; and at la&s;t <HI>I&s;raels</HI> Happine&s;s, when this <HI>Rod</HI> or <HI>Scepter</HI> of Wic<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">edne&s;s, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">de&s;t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">oyed.</P>
<P N="2">2 The Original is, <HI>And the Lord is round about His People.</HI> But the Particle <HI>Van</HI> often Signifies <HI>Much more.</HI></P>
<P N="3">3 An Allu&s;ion to the Method u&s;ed for the dividing of <HI>Lands</HI> among the Jews. A <HI>Rod</HI> or <HI>Staff</HI> was u&s;ed in <HI>Sortition;</HI> particularly, in a&s;&s;igning any I and by <HI>Lot.</HI> The meaning is; The <HI>Portion</HI> of the <HI>Wicked,</HI> &s;hall not be the <HI>Portion</HI> of the <HI>Righteous;</HI> they &s;hall not in their future Condition be confounded with one another</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="126" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="356" REF="001946_0393_0FFCB8F20EFD6700">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM. CXXVI.</HI> A Song of Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 WHen the ETERNAL God return'd &Verbar; what was returned of &Verbar; the Captiv'd Zion, we were like &Verbar; to people in a Dream. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Then was our Mouth repleni&s;hed &Verbar; with Notes of cheerful mirth; &Verbar; &s;o was our Tongue with Shouts; they then &Verbar; among the People &s;aid; &Verbar; Th' ETERNAL God hath done for them &Verbar; things that are very great, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Th' ETERNAL God, hath done for us &Verbar; great things; <HI>whereof</HI> we're Glad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O Thou ETERNAL God, Return &Verbar; what mu&s;t return of us; &Verbar; <HI>It will exhilirate us</HI> like &Verbar; Streams running in the South. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 They who do Sow in Tears, &s;hall reap &Verbar; with an exulting Joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Each one of tho&s;e in going forth &Verbar; does mo&s;tly weeping go: &Verbar; He carries forth the Precious Seed, &Verbar; a little, to be &s;own; &Verbar; he &s;urely does return with Joy; &Verbar; he does bring back his Sheaves. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the Surpri&s;e of the <HI>I&s;raelites</HI> Returned and Re&s;tored by the Me&s;&s;iah,</P>
<P N="1">1 Some take it &s;o, We were in &s;uch a <HI>Frame,</HI> and it was at &s;uch a <HI>Time,</HI> that we took all the Prophe|cies about our Deliverance, to have been &s;o many <HI>Dreams.</HI></P>
<P N="4"><PB N="357" REF="001946_0394_0FFCB8F50112AC68">
4 A Thing as welcome as the Enjoyment of <HI>Streams</HI> in a thir&s;ty Land. So <HI>Mun&s;ter: Non mimis erit illud, quam &s;i in De&s;erto &s;qualido et exu&s;to, Rivos facias urrere aquarum.</HI> The <HI>South</HI> of the <HI>Holy Land</HI> is every <HI>parched Land;</HI> a dry and a faint Wilderne&s;s.</P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Kimchi</HI> &s;ays, The Husbandman is here &s;uppo&s;ed, in a dry Soil, falling into <HI>Tears,</HI> thro' Fears that the Droughts will procure the lo&s;s of all the <HI>Seed.</HI> But God looks on his Tears, and with &s;ea&s;onable <HI>Showers,</HI> pro|cures the <HI>Joy of Harve&s;t.</HI></P>
<P>And now the <HI>Spani&s;h</HI> Glo&s;s will more particularly and Emphatically tell you, who the <HI>Weeping Husband|man</HI> are. <HI>Los Trabans pios Ministros del Evangelio, no &s;er an &s;in Fruto.</HI> The <HI>Labouring and pious Mini|&s;ters of the Go&s;pel &s;hall not be without Fruit.</HI></P>
<P>This is Dr. Patricks Paraphra&s;e. <Q>Ju&s;t as we behold the poor Husbandman, going to and fro with a little Seed, which in a &s;carce year, he throws with a heavy heart into the Ground, returning again and again from the Field, with Songs of Joy in his Mouth, when the Har|ve&s;t comes to Reward his pa&s;t Labours with a Plenti|ful Crop of Corn.</Q></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="127" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXVII.</HI> A Song of Degrees of Solomon.</HEAD>
<P>UNle&s;s that the ETERNAL God &Verbar; &s;hall plea&s;e to build the Hou&s;e; &Verbar; they that the Builders of it are &Verbar; do labour but in vain. &Verbar; Unle&s;s that the ETERNAL God &Verbar; &s;hall plea&s;e to keep the Town, &Verbar; in vain does any keeper el&s;e &Verbar; maintain a careful Watch. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In vain is all you do, O you, &Verbar; who do make ha&s;te to ri&s;e; &Verbar; who don't &s;it down till it be late; &Verbar; who eat the Bread of Griefs. &Verbar;
<PB N="358" REF="001946_0395_0FFCB67708A11370">So, * and in a convenient way, &Verbar; He does a &s;weet repo&s;e &Verbar; unto His <HI>Jedidiah</HI> give, &Verbar; * to His Beloved one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Lo, Children are the Heritage &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; the Fruit of the Womb is be&s;tow'd &Verbar; by Him as a Reward. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 As Arrows in the Hand of one &Verbar; that is a mighty Man, &Verbar; &s;o are the Sons of Youth, <HI>to him</HI> &Verbar; <HI>who &s;ees them</HI> in their Youth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O Ble&s;&s;ed is the Man, who hath &Verbar; his Quiver full of them &Verbar; Such won't be &s;ham'd, when they &s;peak with &Verbar; their Enemies in the Gate. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXVII PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>WAS not <HI>Solomon</HI> the Writer of the P&s;alm? None of his more than <HI>Three Thou&s;and Songs</HI> tran&s;|mitted unto Po&s;terity; but only <HI>This</HI> and the <HI>Next</HI> and the CXXXII. P&s;alm, and the <HI>Canticles</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P>The P&s;alm is a Commentary upon a Maxim of Piety often repeated in his Book of <HI>Proverbs; That it is in vain to attempt any thing, if the Lord will not pro&s;per it.</HI> See Prov. III. 6. XVI. 3, 9. XX. 24. XXI. 30, 31.</P>
<P>But R. <HI>David Kimchi</HI> has ob&s;erved, that the P&s;alm refers to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ter Times, than tho&s;e wherein <HI>Solomon</HI> erected the <HI>Temple,</HI> and enlarged the <HI>City.</HI> He finds here the happine&s;s of the re&s;tored &s;ews, under a great|er than <HI>Solomon.</HI></P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>Solomon</HI> had it &s;aid of him, 2 Sam. XII. 24. <HI>The Lord loved him.</HI> Now, to &s;ee how every clau&s;e here belonged unto this <HI>Jedidiah,</HI> con&s;ult, 1. Chron, XXII. 9, 10. <HI>I will give him re&s;t from all his Enemies; I
<PB N="359" REF="001946_0396_0FFCB8F692FE4248">will give Peace and Quietne&s;s to I&s;rael in his Days; He &s;hall build an Hou&s;e for my Name.</HI> Accordingly there are three ben fits applied unto <HI>Solomon,</HI> His Building of the <HI>Temple;</HI> his keeping of the <HI>City;</HI> and his enjoying of <HI>Re&s;t</HI> with his People. But a direction is here given, both <HI>Whence</HI> and <HI>When,</HI> the&s;e Benefits were to be expected. q. d. <Q>You mu&s;t expect the&s;e Benefits from the <HI>Lord</HI> who will not give them unto you, until <HI>Solomon</HI> His <HI>Beloved</HI> one come into the Succe&s;&s;ion.</Q></P>
<P><HI>Arnchius</HI> carries the&s;e things, to the Coming of our SAVIOUR, and the <HI>Inheritance</HI> which his People &s;hall receive at the <HI>Re&s;urrection,</HI> after they have <HI>&s;lept</HI> in their <HI>Graves.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 The <HI>Gate</HI> in which they are <HI>not afraid of &s;peak|ing with their Enemies, is, Cumegrediuntur Corpore in quo Diabolum &s;uperarunt.</HI> Compare, Mat. VII. 14.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="128" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXVIII.</HI> A Song of Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O The va&s;t Ble&s;&s;ings of the Man, &Verbar; <HI>yea, and of</HI> every Man, &Verbar; who does feat the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; who in His ways does walk! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 For what the Labour of thy Hands &Verbar; has gotten, thou &s;halt eat; &Verbar; Ble&s;&s;ings <HI>of all &s;orts</HI> &s;hall be thine, &Verbar; and good &s;hall be to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 In the &s;ides of thy Hou&s;e thy Wife &Verbar; proves as a Fruitful Vine; &Verbar; thy Children round thy Table prove &Verbar; as Plants of Olive Trees. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O give a due attention <HI>to</HI> &Verbar; <HI>this grateful Spectacle;</HI> &Verbar; for &s;o the Man &s;hall ble&s;&s;ed be &Verbar; who fears th' ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="360" REF="001946_0397_0FFCB8F8D4A2DE10">
5 Th' ETERNAL God from Zion &s;hall &Verbar; a Ble&s;&s;ing give to thee; &Verbar; all the days of thy Life, &s;o thou &Verbar; &s;halt &s;ee Jeru&s;alem's good. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Yea, Thou &s;halt &s;ee the Children which &Verbar; are of thy Children born; &Verbar; <HI>Thou &s;halt &s;ee</HI> Peace on I&s;rael; &Verbar; <HI>Peace be on I&s;rael.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold the Happine&s;s of the Jewi&s;h Nation, when anon re&s;tored unto the Favour of GOD. Com|pare I&s;ai. LXV. and Ezek. XXXVII.</P>
<P N="1">1 <HI>Arnobius</HI> ob&s;erves, That <HI>Walking in the Ways of God,</HI> is added unto, <HI>His Fear,</HI> to di&s;tingui&s;h it from the Fear which the <HI>Divels</HI> have, who <HI>Believe and Tremble</HI></P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Luther</HI> has a Note; That GOD be&s;tows <HI>Publick Peace</HI> upon a People, out of re&s;pect unto <HI>well ordered Families;</HI> partly that they may &s;u&s;tain them&s;elves with Daily <HI>Bread:</HI> But chiefly, That they may be&s;tow a good Education upon their Po&s;terity.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="129" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXIX.</HI> A Song of Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 MUch from my Youth they've troubled me, &Verbar; This now may I&s;rael &s;ay. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Much from my youth they've troubled me, &Verbar; but o'er me not prevail'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 The Plowers plow'd upon my Back; &Verbar; they made their Furrows long. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Th' ETERNAL God who's Ju&s;t, has cut &Verbar; the Cords of Wicked ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 They who hate Zion, let them all &Verbar; be &s;ham'd, and turned back. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6"><PB N="361" REF="001946_0398_0FFCB67D53D41C60">
6 As gra&s;s on Hou&s;es let them be, &Verbar; which withers e're 'tis grown. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 He that's a mower don't &s;o much &Verbar; as all his hand therewith; &Verbar; much le&s;s does he that bindeth &s;heaves &Verbar; therewith his bo&s;om <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ll. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Nor &s;hall Men pa&s;&s;ing &s;ay, On you &Verbar; th' ETERNAL's Ble&s;&s;ing be; &Verbar; We ble&s;s you in the Name of Him &Verbar; who's the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>SEE the Re&s;tored Jews, de&s;cribing the Great Mi&s;|chiefs they &s;uffered under <HI>Antichri&s;t;</HI> and the wondrous Ruin of their Oppre&s;&s;ors, abandoned unto the <HI>Cur&s;e</HI> of GOD.</P>
<P N="6">6, 7. We don't u&s;e, either <HI>Sheaves</HI> or <HI>Handfulls</HI> in that kind of <HI>Husbandry.</HI> But the Ancient Writers, <HI>De Re Ru&s;tica,</HI> have &s;uch Expre&s;&s;ions. <HI>Columella</HI> has, <HI>Fanum Vincire,</HI> the <HI>Binding up of Hay. Varro</HI> a&s;|afirms, <HI>De his manipules fieri.</HI> In their mowing, it &s;eems, they did not cut all down clear at once; but u&s;ed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>After-&s;ection,</HI> which they called <HI>Sizilitium.</HI> They did, as <HI>Pliny</HI> Notes, <HI>Falcibus con&s;ec<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">i qa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> Foeni&s;eca praterierunt.</HI></P>
<P>But <HI>Maundril</HI> in his Travels, tells us, They pluck up their <HI>Corn</HI> by <HI>Handful<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">,</HI> at the <HI>Ro<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">t;</HI> that they may loo&s;e none of their Straw; &mdash; No Hay being made there; The <HI>Mower</HI> is no other than he that would in this way <HI>Fill his hand.</HI></P>
<P N="6">6 <HI>Arnobius</HI> has a Nice Fa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">y on the <HI>Hou&s;e Top</HI> here; <HI>Quia maxima pars Hareticorum ad per&s;onas alt as <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">dit.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="130" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="362" REF="001946_0399_0FFE54452C17DF50">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM. CXXX.</HI> A Song <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">f Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 OUt of the Depths I cry'd <HI>[aloud]</HI> &Verbar; the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Lord, Hear my Voice, to the Voice <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> my Pra<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ers be bow'd thine Ear. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 If Thou <HI>[O Thou]</HI> ETERNAL JAH. &Verbar; &s;ould&s;t mark Iniquities, &Verbar; O Lord, who is there that could &s;tand, &Verbar; when in the Judge|ment try'd? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 But <HI>[&s;urely]</HI> there is found with the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> a Pardon for our Sins; &Verbar; that &s;o Thou may|be wor&s;hipped &Verbar; with a Religious Fear. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For <HI>[Him who's]</HI> the ETERNAL Go<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> I wait; my Soul does wait; &Verbar; and on His Word I do rely &Verbar; with an expecting hope. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 My Soul <HI>waits <HI>[and looks]</HI></HI> for the Lord, &Verbar; more than the Watchers do &Verbar; for Morning; more than they that are &Verbar; Watch|ers for morning, do. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 In the ETERNAL God <HI>[O now]</HI> &Verbar; let I&s;|rael confide; &Verbar; for there is mercy to be found &Verbar; with the ETERNAL God. &Verbar; Yea, and with Him there <HI>[&s;urely]</HI> is &Verbar; Redemption plen|teous. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 And He will I&s;rael redeem &Verbar; from alls <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">niquities. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="363" REF="001946_0400_0FFE51B902B2EB00">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>HA<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> not the <HI>Prophetic Spirit</HI> here provided a Prayer for Pardon, unto abdicated <HI>I&s;rael?</HI> And Prote&s;tation of their Expectation, to be redeemed by the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> who is the True GOD?</P>
<P><HI>Patrick</HI> thinks the P&s;alm to be compo&s;ed by <HI>David,</HI> under the <HI>Sauline</HI> Per&s;ecution; [When reduc'd unto <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">at condition, P&s;alm XVIII. 4. and LXIX. 2, 14, 16.] He Be&s;eeches the Holy One, to Pardon his own Sins, and the Sins of the People, which made them de&s;erve the ill Government of <HI>Saul,</HI> which now brought &s;o <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ch Corruption, and Confu&s;ion upon them.</P>
<P N="4">4 Divers of the Jewi&s;h Rabbi's ob&s;erve an Empha&s;is on the Particle <HI>Thee.</HI> God has made His Angels His <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ni&s;ters to di&s;pen&s;e his <HI>Favours:</HI> But the Remi&s;&s;ion of Sins He re&s;erves to <HI>Him&s;elf</HI> alone.</P>
<P N="6">6 The <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> is undoubtedly, <HI>The Lord,</HI> here <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ited for. In the <HI>Morning</HI> the <HI>Prie&s;ts</HI> that <HI>waited,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> their daily <HI>Sacrifices.</HI> Behold a plain and full Inti|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ation, That the Faithful People of God, when they brought their <HI>Sacrifices</HI> unto Him, had their Faith <HI>waiting</HI> for the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> who is to bring in a <HI>Plenteous Redemption</HI> with Him. And in the Reduplication of this Pa&s;&s;age, is there not a Prophecy, that there were to be <HI>Two Comings</HI> of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah?</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="131" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM. CXXXI.</HI> A Song of Degrees. Of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God, My Heart, &Verbar; it is not haughty grown; &Verbar; nor are the&s;e Eyes of mine with proud &Verbar; elation lifted up. &Verbar; Nor have I exercis'd my &s;elf &Verbar; in matters ve|ry great; &Verbar; nor in &s;uch matters as would be &Verbar; too wondrous high for me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="364" REF="001946_0401_0FFE51D5B853F7B8">
2 What? Han't I &s;et and &s;ilenced &Verbar; my Soul ju&s;t as a Child &Verbar; from'ts Mother wean'd? My Soul in me &Verbar; is as a weaned Child. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Let I&s;rael now with hope confide &Verbar; in the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; <HI>Yea let him do it</HI> from this time &Verbar; to all Eternity. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>INto this Humility and Mortification ought the Jew|i&s;h Nation to reduce them&s;elves, that &s;o the promi|&s;ed Redemption may arrive unto them.</P>
<P N="3">3 Tis impo&s;&s;ible to mention a more <HI>Hopeful</HI> Prepa|ration for all the Ble&s;&s;ings of Goodne&s;s, than a <HI>Re&s;ig|nation</HI> to the <HI>Will</HI> of a <HI>Soveraign God. Chri&s;tian,</HI> Become as a <HI>weaned Child,</HI> willing to be any thing that a <HI>Soveraign God</HI> will have thee to be. FROM HENCE|FORTH may&s;t thou <HI>Hope,</HI> that He will deal merci|fully and wonderfully with thee.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="132" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM. CXXXII.</HI> A Song of Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou ETERNAL God, Have Thou &Verbar; in thy remembrance &s;till &Verbar; David and all th' Affliction which &Verbar; he has encountred with. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 How he did take a &s;olemn Oath, &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; he then did make a &s;o|lemn Vow &Verbar; to Jacob's mighty one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 If I do go into the Tent &Verbar; wherein &Verbar; have my Hou&s;e; &Verbar; if I go up unto the Bed &Verbar; that has my Coverlets. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4"><PB N="365" REF="001946_0402_0FFE517597684770">
4 If I do give unto my Eyes &Verbar; the Sleep <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ich they require,</HI> &Verbar; or but unto my Eye-lids once &Verbar; a little &s;lumbring time: &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Until I do find out a place &Verbar; for the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">TERNAL God; &Verbar; Man&s;ions to be inhabited &Verbar; by Jacob's Mighty One. &Verbar; &mdash;</P>
<P N="6">6 &mdash; Behold of it, <HI>ev'n of Thy Ark</HI> &Verbar; we heard at Ephratah; &Verbar; we found it in the fields that were &Verbar; then overgrown with wood. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 We will into the Man&s;ions go &Verbar; inhabited by Thee; &Verbar; and at thy foot&s;tool there we will &Verbar; with bowing down adore. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 ETERNAL God, Ari&s;e to go &Verbar; unto thy place of Re&s;t; &Verbar; <HI>Ari&s;e,</HI> Thou and the Ark from whence &Verbar; Thy Power doth appear. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O let thy Prie&s;ts array them&s;elves &Verbar; with robes of Righteou&s;ne&s;s; &Verbar; and tho&s;e who are thy gracious Ones, &Verbar; O let them &s;hout for joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Becau&s;e of David who has been &Verbar; a Servant unto thee, &Verbar; O turn thou not away the Face &Verbar; of thine Anointed One. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 The Truth has the ETERNAL God &Verbar; unto <HI>His</HI> David &s;worn; &Verbar; He'l not turn from't I'l on thy Throne &Verbar; one from thy bowels &s;et. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 If that thy Children &s;hall keep well &Verbar; my Covenant <HI>with them,</HI> &Verbar; and <HI>keep</HI> the Te&s;ti|mony which &Verbar; I &s;hall in&s;truct them in; &Verbar; Then al&s;o their Po&s;terity &Verbar; that &s;hall come after them, &Verbar; even to perpetuity &Verbar; &s;hall &s;it upon thy Throne. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13"><PB N="366" REF="001946_0403_0FFE52FBE399E440">
13 Becau&s;e that the ETERNAL God &Verbar; of Zion hath made choice; &Verbar; He hath de&s;ired it to have &Verbar; His Habitation there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 This is the Place where I will re&s;t &Verbar; to Perpetuity; &Verbar; Here I will have my dwell|ing place; &Verbar; for I've de&s;ired it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 I &s;urely * and abundantly &Verbar; will her Provi&s;ion ble&s;s; &Verbar; with bread I'll fully &s;atis|fy &Verbar; the Poor which be in her. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Her Prie&s;ts I with Salvation will &Verbar; adorn as with a Robe; &Verbar; Her gracious ones, they al&s;o &s;hall &Verbar; Sing, yea, and &s;hout for joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 There I will for my David make &Verbar; an Horn to I&s;&s;ue forth; &Verbar; I have a Lamp ordain|ed <HI>there</HI> &Verbar; for mine anointed one. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 His Adver&s;aries I will cloth &Verbar; with a Contemptuous &s;hame; &Verbar; but upon him &s;till flouri&s;hing &Verbar; &s;hall be his Diadem. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE Hope of the Jewi&s;h Nation, is here provided by the <HI>Prophetic Spirit.</HI> But what they mo&s;t build upon is, the promi&s;e of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> who, when He comes again is to bring about their glorious Happi|ne&s;s, and bring de&s;truction on their Pnemies.</P>
<P>Was not <HI>Solomon</HI> the Writer of the P&s;alm? He con|cludes his Prayer at the Con&s;ecration of the Temple with part of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P>It may refer to the pious humility of <HI>David,</HI> who cho&s;e to endure many <HI>Afflictions,</HI> rather than by un|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters">ul means <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o advance him&s;elf. See the fir&s;t Ver&s;e o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> the [<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters">oin] <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">alm.</P>
<P><PB N="367" REF="001946_0404_0FFE5335AA79BBC8">
<HI>Mighty One,</HI> is as much as to &s;ay <HI>Lord.</HI> So, <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">aris et Terrae Tempe&s;tatumque potentes.</HI></P>
<P N="6">6. A Di&s;cour&s;e written in <HI>Barhary,</HI> 1610. Entituled, <HI>The Me&s;&s;ith already come,</HI> has this Glo&s;s upon the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>David</HI> after much re&s;tle&s;s &s;tudy, to find out the My&s;tery of the <HI>Place,</HI> where the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> &s;hould <Q>be born;&mdash;At length the My&s;tery being reveal'd unto him, he does as it were point unto the very <HI>Place,</HI> in the words following; <HI>Lo, we heard of it at Ephratah;</HI> which is the &s;ame with <HI>Bethlehem.</HI></Q></P>
<P>It was in the Territory of <HI>Bethlehem Ephratah,</HI> [Gen. XXXV. 16, 19.] In the Fields that the Angel <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ood, and directed <HI>David</HI> to build an Altar to the Lord. [1. Chron. XXI. 18. XXII. 1]</P>
<P N="16">16 Such as have nothing but <HI>Salvation,</HI> and what <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ds to it, con&s;picuous upon them; look on them and on &s;hall &s;ee in them a mo&s;t con&s;picuous care to obtain <HI>Salvation;</HI> A Care worthy of your Imitation. Come to them and you &s;hall be excited unto the Care of <HI>Sal|vation,</HI> and be directed, how to obtain it. <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> a Glo&s;s of this Tendency.</P>
<P N="17">17 An <HI>Horn</HI> &s;ignifies <HI>Might, Strength, Joy, Safe|ty,</HI> and <HI>Pro&s;perity;</HI> anon, <HI>Glory.</HI> And &s;o, a <HI>Royal Power.</HI> From <HI>Keren,</HI> and <HI>Cornu,</HI> may come, <HI>Corona.</HI> flence in the Prophetic. Schemes of <HI>Daniel,</HI> and of <HI>John, Horns</HI> do &s;ignify <HI>Kings.</HI> [Dan. VII. 24. VIII. 7.] The Pagans learnt the Speech; <HI>Pauper Cornua &s;umit. Jupiter</HI> was called <HI>Corniger. Alex|ander</HI> was <HI>Bicornis</HI> on Medals. In the <HI>Alcoran,</HI> his Name is, <HI>Dulcarnain.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="133" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXXIII.</HI> A Song of Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BEhold how good a thing it is, &Verbar; and how delectable, &Verbar; when Brethren down toge|ther &s;it &Verbar; united in their Love! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="368" REF="001946_0405_0FFE517B0E251BE8">
2 Tis like the precious Ointment which &Verbar; poured upon the Head, &Verbar; made its De&s;cent upon the Beard &Verbar; of Aaron here and there. &Verbar; <HI>Yea, and</HI> it did go farther down &Verbar; to the edge of his Robe &Verbar; that clos'd about his Neck, <HI>and reach'd</HI> &Verbar; <HI>the Names of all the Tribes.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Tis like the Dew which is upon &Verbar; Mount Hermon often &s;een; &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> that which on the Mountains of &Verbar; Zion does make de&s;cent. &Verbar; Becau&s;e that it is in that Place &Verbar; that the ETERNAL God &Verbar; commands His Ble&s;&s;ing, <HI>even</HI> Life &Verbar; to all Eternity. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>BEhold an Hymn to be Sung, when the Tribes of <HI>I&s;rael</HI> &s;hall be gathered and re&s;tored.</P>
<P>When the Tribes of <HI>I&s;rael</HI> had no Strife, but who &s;hould be mo&s;t forward in returning to their. Allegiance; and the Children of <HI>Judah</HI> were inclin'd as one Man, to bring back <HI>David</HI> unto his Kingdom, after the Re|bellion of <HI>Ab&s;alom;</HI> then might he fall into this Rap|turous Admiration of their Unity. This is Dr. <HI>Pa|trick's</HI> Tho't.</P>
<P>But the P&s;alm was aptly to be applied unto the <HI>Ba|bylonian</HI> Captivity; when as <HI>Theodoret</HI> Notes, the Tribes which had been divided by the Imprudence of <HI>Re|hoboam;</HI> were again united.</P>
<P>The <HI>Primitive Chri&s;tians</HI> u&s;ed the P&s;alm to expre&s;s their Joy, for the ble&s;&s;ed Union of the <HI>Jews</HI> and <HI>Gen|tiles,</HI> which had been as di&s;tant from one another as, <HI>Hermon</HI> from <HI>Zion.</HI></P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>Aaron,</HI> on the Collar of his Garment, bore the Names of all the Tribes of <HI>I&s;rael;</HI> they were all per|fumed.</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="369" REF="001946_0406_0FFE5427883B9310">
3 Modern Travellers tell us, they found the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;elves <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">et with the <HI>Dew of Hormon,</HI> falling in the Night, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> it had ra<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">'d upon them.</P>
