<DIV2 N="134" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXXIV.</HI> A Song of Degrees.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Give Attention! Speak ye well &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; all you that are the Servants, who &Verbar; wait on the ETER|NAL God; &Verbar; ye who by Night &s;tand in the hou&s;e &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Lift up your hands with Holine&s;s, &Verbar; and ble&s;s th' ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 From Zion may th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; Kis Ble&s;&s;ing g<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ve to thee; &Verbar; <HI>The God</HI> who is. the Maker of &Verbar; the Heavens and the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>B<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">hold the Devotions of the <HI>I&s;raeliti&s;h</HI> Nation, at the return of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah;</HI> and their Prayers or the continuation of their Happine&s;s. Look back to the Illu&s;trations on the CXX. P&s;alm.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="135" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CXXXV.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 <HI>S<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ng</HI> HALLELUJAH. Prai&s;e the Name &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; Prai&s;e, O you that the Servants are &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 You that your Station have in the &Verbar; Hou&s;e of th' ETERNAL God; &Verbar; <HI>&s;tanding</HI> in the Courts of the Hou&s;e &Verbar; of Him who is our God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Prai&s;e JAH; Becau&s;e that truly Good &Verbar; is the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; Sing Prai&s;es to His Name; becau&s;e &Verbar; it is a plea&s;ant thing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4"><PB N="370" REF="001946_0407_0FFE517FB01C6418">
4 Becau&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">hat JAH has made a choice &Verbar; of Jacob for him&s;elf; &Verbar; of I&s;rael for a Trea&s;u<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> to &Verbar; Him&s;elf peculiar. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 For as to me, this I do know, &Verbar; That the ETERNAL God &Verbar; is a Great One, and that our Lord &Verbar; is above all the God's! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Whatever He would plea&s;e to do &Verbar; th' ETERNAL God hath done, &Verbar; in th' Heav'ns, and on Earth, in Seas, &Verbar; and in all Aby&s;&s;es. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 From the ends of the Earth He makes &Verbar; the Clouds ari&s;e; He makes &Verbar; Lightnings with rain; He brings the Wind &Verbar; out of His Trea&s;uries &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Of Egypt He &s;mote the Fir&s;t-born, &Verbar; from Man, ev'n to the Bea&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 In mid&s;t of thee, O Egypt, He &Verbar; did Signs and Wonders &s;end; &Verbar; <HI>This He did</HI> upon Pha|raoh and &Verbar; on all that &s;erved Him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Great Nations He laid &s;trokes upon &Verbar; and He &s;lew mighty Kings. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Sihon King of the Amorites, &Verbar; <HI>He &s;lew,</HI> and Og the King &Verbar; of Ba&s;han, all the King|doms too &Verbar; which were in Canaan found. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 And He di&s;po&s;ed of their Land &Verbar; as an Inheritance; &Verbar; as an Inheritance unto &Verbar; His People I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Thy Name is, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; to Perpetuity; &Verbar; Thy Memory, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; it is from Age to Age. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 For the ETERNAL God will to &Verbar; His People be the Judge; &Verbar; and upon them that &s;erve Him He &Verbar; will now refre&s;h Him&s;elf, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15"><PB N="371" REF="001946_0408_0FFE542B81D8C358">
15 The Idols which the Nations do &Verbar; render their Homage to, &Verbar; are <HI>nothing but</HI> Silver and Gold; &Verbar; what hands of Men have wrought. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Mouths have they, but they do not &s;peak; &Verbar; they've Eyes but do not &s;ee, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Ears have they, but they do not hear; &Verbar; no breath is in their Mouths. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 They that the Makers are of &s;uch &Verbar; <HI>ridiculous things are the&s;e,</HI> &Verbar; are like them; &s;o is every one &Verbar; that puts his tru&s;t in them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Ble&s;s the ETERNAL God, O you &Verbar; the Hou&s;e of I&s;rael; &Verbar; Ble&s;s the ETERNAL God, O you &Verbar; that are of Aaron's Hou&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 Ble&s;s the ETERNAL God, O you &Verbar; that are of Levi's Hou&s;e; &Verbar; Ye who do fear th' ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Ble&s;s you th' ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 O Ble&s;&s;ed out of Zion be &Verbar; now the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; who dwelleth in Jeru&s;a|lem. &Verbar; <HI>Sing</HI> Hallelujah <HI>now!</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>TIs an Hymis of Prai&s;e, to be Sung by re&s;tored <HI>I&s;iael;</HI> Rehear&s;ing the Ancient Miracles done for their Fathers, and in&s;ulting the fal&s;e Gods of Antichri&s;t. The Ideas of the P&s;alm are followed in the XL Chap|ter of <HI>I&s;aiah.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 The <HI>Apollo</HI> of the Ancients was our <HI>Jo&s;hua, Jo&s;hua</HI>'s Conque&s;t of Og, and the <HI>Anakims</HI> in <HI>Canaan,</HI> was <HI>Apollo's</HI> Defeat of <HI>Typhon,</HI> or <HI>Python,</HI> and the other Giants. <HI>Cadmus</HI> the <HI>Gibeonite</HI> with other <HI>Pha|nicians,</HI> carrying a Colony into C<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">aecia, celebrated the
<PB N="372" REF="001946_0409_0FFE542EDCCF7D00">Victories of <HI>Jo&s;i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">a</HI> in &s;uch Hymns as they had learn'd from their New Ma&s;ters in the Land of <HI>Ca<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">.</HI> Might not &s;uch &s;trains as are in the P&s;alm now before us, be among tho&s;e Hymns? And the <HI>E<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">elu Jou Jou</HI> u&s;ed in them, be no other than our <HI>Hallelujah?</HI></P>
<P N="18">18 There is this admirable Force in the mention of the re&s;pects paid by the Hearthen to their Idols. <Q>The Honour the Heathen give to their lifele&s;s Images, ought mightily to excite us all, with a <HI>greater</HI> Devo|tion to Prai&s;e our God, who is the Maker of all things.</Q></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="136" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CXXXVI.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 <HI>[O Now]</HI> a ju&s;t Confe&s;&s;ion make &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; Becau&s;e that He is good; Becau&s;e &Verbar; His mercy is forever. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>[O now]</HI> a ju&s;t Confe&s;&s;ion make &Verbar; unto the God of Gods; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuty. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 <HI>[O now]</HI> a ju&s;t Confe&s;&s;ion make &Verbar; unto the Lord of Lords; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 To Him who <HI>[eber]</HI> only doth &Verbar; things great <HI>and</HI> wonderful; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 To Him who made the Heav'ns <HI>[above]</HI> &Verbar; wifely di&s;po&s;ing them; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 To Him who &s;tretch'd the Earth <HI>[abroad]</HI> &Verbar; upon the Waters laid; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 To Him who made <HI>[and &s;et]</HI> the Lights &Verbar; which are &s;o very great; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mer|cy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8"><PB N="373" REF="001946_0410_0FFE518A063E34A0">
8 The Sun <HI>[it is]</HI> that for the Day &Verbar; does <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">dominion bear; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 The Moon and Stars that have <HI>[in cour&s;e]</HI> &Verbar; Dominion for the Night; &Verbar; Be|cau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 To Him that Egypt &s;mote <HI>[and &s;lew]</HI> &Verbar; in the Fir&s;t-born of them; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 And He <HI>[thereon]</HI> did I&s;rael bring &Verbar; forth from the mid&s;t of them; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 With a &s;trong <HI>[mighty]</HI> Hand, and with &Verbar; a mo&s;t extended Arm; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 To Him who did in <HI>[&s;everal]</HI> parts &Verbar; divide the Reedy-Sea; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 And He made I&s;rael <HI>[&s;afely]</HI> pa&s;s &Verbar; thorough the mid&s;t of it; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mer|cy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 But &s;hook off Pharoah, and <HI>[all of]</HI> &Verbar; his Ho&s;t, i' th' Reedy-Sea; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 To Him who led His <HI>[cho&s;en]</HI> folk &Verbar; thorough the Wilderne&s;s; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 To Him who laid His <HI>[killing]</HI> &s;trokes &Verbar; on great <HI>and potent</HI> Kings; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18"><PB N="374" REF="001946_0411_0FFE543251B46110">
18 And He &s;lew Kings that were <HI>[e&s;teem'd]</HI> &Verbar; exceeding powerful; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 Sihon <HI>was one of the&s;e <HI>[great Kings]</HI></HI> &Verbar; King of the Amorites; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 And Og <HI>mother was <HI>[of them]</HI></HI> &Verbar; who was of Ba&s;han King; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 And He did give their Land <HI>[away]</HI> &Verbar; for an Inheritance; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity, &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 'Tis an Inheritance <HI>[de&s;ign'd]</HI> &Verbar; for I&s;rael &s;erving Him; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Who in our low <HI>[oppre&s;s'd]</HI> E&s;tate &Verbar; hath mindful been of us; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">24 And from <HI>[all of]</HI> our Enemies &Verbar; He <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">th redeemed us; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="25">25 Who <HI>[kindly]</HI> to all Fle&s;h affords &Verbar; and for their fu&s;tenance; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mer|cy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="26">26 <HI>[O now]</HI> a ju&s;t Confe&s;&s;ion make &Verbar; unto the God of Heav'n; &Verbar; Becau&s;e His mercy doth endure &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>AN Hymn to be Sung by <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> after their De|liverance from all their Enemies. In the Third
<PB N="375" REF="001946_0412_0FFE54344AAA7800">Ver&s;e, The <HI>Lord of Lords</HI> is Prai&s;ed; The Title of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> at His next Coming. <HI>Twenty Six Times,</HI> occurs, <HI>His Mercy doth endure to Perpetuity.</HI> The P&s;alm does Commence with the <HI>Creation,</HI> and Conclude with the Entrance into <HI>Cana<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n;</HI> between which there had run <HI>Twenty Six</HI> Generations. The Numeral Let|ters of the Name, JEHOVAH, amount unto ju&s;t that Number. Con&s;ider &s;till the Clau&s;e to which that Con|&s;olation is annexed. It is, q. d. The <HI>Mercy</HI> of GOD, will &s;till do for His People, &s;uch things as the Clau&s;e makes mention of; or things of the like importance with them. Further <HI>Elegencies</HI> may be ob&s;erved in the Analogies.</P>
<P N="10">10 The P&s;almi&s;t having di&s;tinctly mentioned the Works produced in the <HI>Four Fir&s;t Days</HI> of the <HI>Crea|tion,</HI> immediately pa&s;&s;es to the Plagues upon <HI>Egypt.</HI> The Works produced in the <HI>Two next Days</HI> of the Creation, were employed in tho&s;e Plaaues.</P>
<P N="20">20 Why only <HI>Sihon</HI> and <HI>Og</HI> mentioned? R. <HI>David Kimchi</HI> gives this Rea&s;on; Becau&s;e their Lands were not in the <HI>Covenant,</HI> which GOD made with <HI>Abraham.</HI></P>
<P N="23">23 The <HI>Mercy of God,</HI> which has remembred thee in thy <HI>Low E&s;tate;</HI> Chri&s;tian, Let it <HI>Endure to P<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">r|petuity,</HI> in thy Thankful <HI>Remembrance</HI> of it, and of the Obligations it has laid upon thee, to Live unto GOD. Behold, a Noble &s;en&s;e, in which it &s;hould be &s;aid, <HI>His Mercy doth endure to P<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">rpetuity.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="137" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CXXXVII.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 WE by the Rivers which do run &Verbar; thro' Babylon, &s;at there; &Verbar; yea, we pour'd out our Tears when we &Verbar; remembred Zion <HI>there.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Upon the Willows in the mid&s;t &Verbar; there|of we hung our Harps. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="376" REF="001946_0413_0FFE5438162ECD70">
3 For they that Captiv'd us did there &Verbar; demand of us <HI>to Sing</HI> &Verbar; words of a Song, and they who laid&Verbar; us in our ruinous heaps,&Verbar; <HI>demanded</HI> mirth, Sing us, <HI>&s;aid they,</HI>&Verbar; a Song of Zion, <HI>Sing!</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>Our An&s;wer was,</HI> How can we do&Verbar; to Sing a Song that is &Verbar; for the ETERNAL God, in the &Verbar; Land of a &s;tranger here? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O <HI>dear</HI> Jeru&s;alem, If I &Verbar; of thee forget|ful grow! &Verbar; As &s;oon &s;hall my Right-hand forget &Verbar; <HI>what it is us'd unto!</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 My Tongue &s;hall to my Palate cleave &Verbar; when thee I do not mind! &Verbar; If I don't &s;et Jeru&s;'lem at &Verbar; the top of all my Joy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Remember, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; the Sons of Edom, who &Verbar; &s;aid in Jeru&s;'lems day, Ra&s;e, Ra&s;e, &Verbar; to its foundation bare. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Daughter of Babylon, who art &Verbar; to be made de&s;olate, &Verbar; Happy, who &s;hall repay to thee &Verbar; the pay thou'&s;t paid to us! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O the great ble&s;&s;edne&s;s of him &Verbar; who &s;hall lay hold upon, &Verbar; and who again&s;t the &s;olid Rock &Verbar; &s;hall da&s;h thy little ones! &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>WE have here the &s;orrowful State of the <HI>Jews,</HI> under the fir&s;t <HI>Babylonian</HI> Captivity; and then under the <HI>Roman</HI> Domimon, which the Prophet calls, <HI>Daughter of Babylon,</HI> becau&s;e the <HI>Romans</HI> have done to them as the <HI>Babylonians</HI> did. Several Prophets have agreed with our P&s;almi&s;t, in calling the <HI>Romans</HI> by the Name of <HI>Edom.</HI> In the Jewi&s;h Treati&s;e <HI>Git|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">,</HI>
<PB N="377" REF="001946_0414_0FFE544048323888">R. <HI>Jebudah</HI> finds the De&s;truction of both <HI>Temples,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">der the Two Terms of <HI>Babylon</HI> and <HI>Edom. Ar|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">obius</HI> pathetically makes the <HI>Babylonians</HI> here, a Picture of the <HI>Devils</HI> in&s;ulting over fallen Man.</P>
<P N="1">1 When they were tran&s;ported into <HI>Babylon,</HI> they <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ad the &s;ides of <HI>Euphrates</HI> and &s;everal of its Rivers, a&s;&s;igned for their Habitation. [<HI>Ezek.</HI> 1.1.] <HI>Chry&s;o&s;tom</HI> &s;ays, They did not at fir&s;t &s;ufer the Captives to dwell in any of their Towns, but made them dwell along the &s;ides of the Rivers, where they built little Cottages for them&s;elves; and perhaps they were put upon Draining tho&s;e moi&s;t places to make them whol&s;ome.</P>
<P N="3">3 The <HI>Babylonians</HI> here demand, <HI>Sing us, the Words of a Song.</HI> It &s;eems, they had no regard unto the <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">atter.</HI> The <HI>Tune,</HI> The <HI>Sound,</HI> the <HI>Words,</HI> was all they cared for. A Mark of <HI>Babylonians!</HI> Among &s;uch they regard nothing but <HI>Words</HI> and <HI>Forms;</HI> All they mind, is a <HI>Lip-Labour,</HI> an External. Service in Religion.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="138" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CXXXVIII. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 I Will a ju&s;t Confe&s;&s;ion make &Verbar; of thee with all my heart; &Verbar; Before God, * and His Angels, I &Verbar; will Prai&s;es Sing to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Toward thy holy Temple I &Verbar; will bow|ing down adore; &Verbar; and I will celebrate thy Name &Verbar; for thy benignity, &Verbar; and for thy faithfulne&s;s; for that &Verbar; thou above every thing &Verbar; ha&s;t magnify'd thy Name; <HI>Thou ha&s;t</HI> &Verbar; <HI>&s;o magnify'd</HI> thy Word. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 In the day I invoked thee, &Verbar; and thou did&s;t an&s;wer me; &Verbar; Thou in my Soul with manly &s;trength &Verbar; me then did&s;t fortify. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4"><PB N="378" REF="001946_0415_0FFE51916C1297C0">
4 To Thee, O Thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; all the Kings of the Earth &Verbar; &s;hall their Con|fe&s;&s;ions make, when of &Verbar; thy mouth they he<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> the words. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Yea, they'l with voice &s;ing in the ways &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; Becau&s;e that great the Glory is &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 For the ETERNAL God is high; &Verbar; but looks upon the low; &Verbar; whereas what would be high, He does &Verbar; far off take notice of. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Altho' my walk be lying in &Verbar; the mid&s;t of much di&s;tre&s;s, &Verbar; yet thou with &s;weet re|vivals wilt &Verbar; enable me to live: &Verbar; Thou'lt u&s;e thy hand again&s;t the rage &Verbar; of my fierce enemies; &Verbar; and thy Right hand &s;hall unto me &Verbar; give a deliverance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Th' ETERNAL God will perfect what &Verbar; He has to <HI>do for</HI> me: &Verbar; Thy mercy, O ETER|NAL God &Verbar; is to Eternity. &Verbar; O do not thou for&s;ake, * O don't &Verbar; utterly ca&s;t away, &Verbar; tho&s;e <HI>Men and things</HI> that are the Works &Verbar; that thy own Hands have wrought. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>AN Illu&s;trious Prophecy concerning the calling of the <HI>I&s;raeliti&s;h Nation,</HI> to the knowledge of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah;</HI> and the Great Conver&s;ion of the Heathen Kingdoms to His Religion, after the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> has de|&s;troy'd the Enemies of the Kingdom.</P>
<P N="5">5 The Wonderful <HI>Ways</HI> wherein the Lord brings about His Glorious Purpo&s;es will be the Subject of their <HI>Songs.</HI> The Ways of God in bringing of <HI>David</HI> unto
<PB N="379" REF="001946_0416_0FFE5441E4CB3468">his <HI>Kingdom;</HI> were tho&s;e the things which the <HI>Kings</HI> in the Neighbourhood celebrated?</P>
<P N="6">6 The tho'ts of the <HI>Proud</HI> are hid in their Hearts <HI>afar <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">,</HI> out of fight; They have more Wit than to utter me <HI>Proud thot's,</HI> which lie covered and &s;welling in their minds. But the Lord <HI>knows</HI> what they are <HI>afar <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">.</HI> The Proud may be here compared unto a <HI>L<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">per;</HI> one who has little cau&s;e to be <HI>Proud.</HI> God <HI>knows</HI> a <HI>Proud</HI> Man to be no better than a filthy <HI>Leper,</HI> upon <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">om it was enjoyned, that He &s;hould &s;tand <HI>afar off;</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">e might not be approach'd unto; nor will the Spirit of GOD approach <HI>near</HI> unto &s;uch a Man. Compare <HI>L<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">v.</HI> XIII. 45, 46.</P>
<P>The <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e, is; <Q>He will not &s;toop <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the loftie&s;t Princes (as they may &s;ee in <HI>Soul</HI>) whom He de&s;pi&s;es, when they are forgetful of Him, and ungrateful to Him.</Q></P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>Arnobius</HI> here &s;ees our SAVIOUR extending His Hands upon the <HI>Cro&s;s.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="139" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXXXIX.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 ETERNAL God, Thou'&s;t &s;earched me, &Verbar; and ha&s;t known what I am. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Thou know'&s;t full well my &s;itting down, &Verbar; and <HI>know'&s;t</HI> my ri&s;ing up. &Verbar; Thou at the greate&s;t di&s;tance do&s;t &Verbar; well under&s;tand my tho't. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 My path thou &s;ee&s;t round, and my bed; &Verbar; and find'&s;t out all my ways. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Yea, and each word I &s;peak, while it &Verbar; is not yet in my tongue; &Verbar; Behold, O Thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Thou knowe&s;t all of it. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5"><PB N="380" REF="001946_0417_0FFE54437A1F93E0">
5 Me thou ha&s;t formed, * and be&s;et, &Verbar; both as to what's behind, &Verbar; and as to what's be|fore; and thou &Verbar; ha&s;t laid thy hand on me &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Such knowledge as this is, it is &Verbar; too wonderful for me; &Verbar; Sublime it is, and it is more &Verbar; than I can reach unto! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Where &s;hall I from thy Spirit go? &Verbar; And where fly from thy Face? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 If I <HI>&s;hould &s;ay,</HI> I will a&s;cend &Verbar; to Heaven, Thou art there: &Verbar; Or, If I make my Bed in Hell; lo, Thou art al&s;o there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 I'll take the Mornings Wings, I'll dwell &Verbar; at the Seas utmo&s;t bounds. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Even unto that very place &Verbar; thy hand &s;hall carry me; &Verbar; Thy Right hand al&s;o, that &s;hall make &Verbar; a &s;eizure on me there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 If I &s;hould &s;ay, A&s;&s;uredly &Verbar; Darkne&s;s &s;hould cover me; &Verbar; The very Night it&s;elf would be &Verbar; about me as the Light. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Yea, Darkne&s;s nothing hides from thee; &Verbar; but Night doth &s;hine like Day; &Verbar; The Dark|ne&s;s and the Light, they are &Verbar; both but the very &s;ame. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 For my <HI>mo&s;t hidden</HI> Reins thou ha&s;t &Verbar; in thy po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion held; &Verbar; Thou in my Mothers Womb, as with &Verbar; a Tent ha&s;t cover'd me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 I'll prai&s;e thee for with wonders I &Verbar; have &s;eparated been; &Verbar; Thy Works are won|drous, and my Soul &Verbar; knows this abundantly. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 My &s;trength was not hid from thee; when &Verbar;
<PB N="381" REF="001946_0418_0FFE5193260615C8">I was in &s;ecret made, &Verbar; in the Earth's lowe&s;t parts I was &Verbar; mo&s;t curiou&s;ly wrought. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Thy Eyes did &s;ee my unform'd ma&s;s; &Verbar; and in thy Book were all &Verbar; writ down 5 the days when they were form'd &Verbar; and none of them were <HI>lo&s;t.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 And now, how valuable are &Verbar; thy Thot's to me, O God! Into how great a reck'ning are &Verbar; they to be multiply'd! &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 If I &s;hould go to number them &Verbar; more man the Sand they grow. &Verbar; When I awake out of my &s;leep, &Verbar; then I am &s;till with thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 O God, Thou wilt mo&s;t certainly &Verbar; de&s;troy the wicked one; &Verbar; And now you that are bloody Men, &Verbar; Do you depart from me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 The&s;e are they who again&s;t thee &s;peak &Verbar; abominable &s;tuff; &Verbar; They who are enemies to thee &Verbar; are &s;uch as &s;weat in vain. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 Do not I hate tho&s;e who do hate &Verbar; Thee, O ETERNAL God? &Verbar; Tho&s;e who do up again&s;t thee rife, &Verbar; be'nt I offended at? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="22">22 I hate them with perfection in &Verbar; my hatred unto them; &Verbar; They as my Adver&s;a|ties are &Verbar; ever e&s;teem'd with me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="23">23 Make thou a thorough &s;earch of me, &Verbar; O God, and know my heart; &Verbar; A thorough trial make of me, &Verbar; and know my very thot's. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="24">And &s;ee if I have any way &Verbar; that &s;hould be mourned for; &Verbar; but lead me in the way that la&s;ts &Verbar; to perpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="382" REF="001946_0419_0FFE516F5E9091D8">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXXXIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe <HI>Prophetic Spirit</HI> here teaches the Jewi&s;h Na|tion <HI>[Oh! would they learn!]</HI> how little able they are to hide them&s;elves from the Judgments of GOD; And now they are to acknowledge GOD as their Maker and their Saviour; and Pray to Him for the De&s;truction of <HI>Antichri&s;t</HI> and his Abettors.</P>
<P N="9">9 'Tis a&s;toni&s;hing to &s;ee what Pa&s;&s;ages there are in <HI>Plato.</HI> [De Leg. l. 10.] agreeable to the&s;e of the P&s;almi&s;t. O <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> the <HI>Light of Nature</HI> will teach thee &s;uch things as the&s;e.</P>
<P N="14">14 <HI>Galen's</HI> Book, <HI>De U&s;u Partium,</HI> were a notable Commentary and Illu&s;tration on the Text now before us. And when he, who was a Pagan, cries out, <HI>Con&s;i|dera hic marabilem Creatoris Sapientiam,</HI> &s;hall not we reflect, <HI>What Prai&s;es do I, that am a Chri&s;tian, one to the Glorious GOD, upon the view of every thing that belongs to me!</HI></P>
<P>The Modern Improvements in Anatomy add infinite|ly to the Occa&s;ions. <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ellini</HI> would begrutch his Time and Co&s;t and Pains, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;earching out the A&s;toni&s;hing Workman&s;hip, in the &s;everal Parts of an Humane Body, if it were only to di&s;cover a Work of <HI>meer Chance,</HI> or of one who were not infinitely Wi&s;e and Good and Glorious. No, he <HI>does</HI> (as every ju&s;t Contemplator <HI>mu&s;t</HI>) find him&s;elf compelled into the Admiration of a Glorious GOD, and thrown into tho&s;e Tran&s;ports and Raptures and Flames, which extort the&s;e Exclamations from him, <HI>Magnus Dominus! Magnus Fabricator Ho|minum Deus! Magnus atque admirabilis. Conditor rerum Deus, Quam magnus es!</HI> O Thou Maker of Man, How Great and Glorious are Thou!</P>
<P N="16">16 Is not the <HI>My&s;tical Body</HI> of our SAVIOUR prin|cipally intended? The <HI>Sub&s;tance</HI> of the Church, whereof it was to be <HI>formed,</HI> was under the Eye of GOD, as propo&s;ed in the Decree of <HI>Election;</HI> yet
<PB N="383" REF="001946_0420_0FFE519CE8FE81C0">was, as &s;uch <HI>Imperfect.</HI> It was not formed or &s;haped into the Members of the <HI>My&s;tical Body;</HI> but they were all <HI>written</HI> in the <HI>Book of Life.</HI> And in, pur&s;uance of the Purpo&s;e of GOD, there they are by the Holy Spirit, in the whole cour&s;e, and <HI>continuance of Time,</HI> in their &s;everal Generations, fa&s;hioned into the &s;hape de&s;igned for them. Thus our Dr. <HI>Owen</HI> Glo&s;&s;eth it.</P>
<P N="17">17 The Vulgar Latin, and the LXX read it, <HI>How Precious cre thy Friends to me!</HI> The Hebrew may indeed be very well tran&s;lated &s;o. And the Tran&s;lation agrees very well, with what is ju&s;t before &s;aid, about the Members of our SAVIOUR, all which are the <HI>Friends</HI> of GOD. It &s;uits al&s;o very well, with what follows about the <HI>Enemies</HI> of GOD; whom the P&s;al|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">&s;t profe&s;&s;es an <HI>Hatred</HI> of.</P>
<P N="22">22 <HI>A Perfect Hatred.</HI> What is that? <HI>Gregory</HI> M. in his <HI>Pa&s;toralis Cura,</HI> has a &s;ingular Glo&s;s upon it; It is to <HI>Love</HI> the <HI>Creature</HI> and <HI>Hate</HI> the <HI>Sinner:</HI> To <HI>Love</HI> what he <HI>is,</HI> and <HI>Hate</HI> what he <HI>does.</HI> &mdash; <HI>Quod facti &s;unt diligore, et quod Faciunt increpare.</HI> He adds an Ob&s;ervation, <HI>Propheta tantus boo velut in Ho&s;tiam Deo obtulit, quod contra &s;e pro Domino Pravorum in micitias Excitavit.</HI></P>
<P N="24">24 <HI>Kimchi's</HI> Expo&s;ition is very odd; That the <HI>Way Everla&s;ting</HI> is a Periphra&s;is of <HI>Death.</HI> [See 1 Kin. II. 1, and Jo&s;h. XXIII. 14.] As if <HI>David</HI> had &s;aid: <Q><HI>Lord,</HI> If upon &s;earch, thou finde&s;t, that I walk in any <HI>way of Wickedne&s;,</HI> I may venture to &s;ay, Let me Dye; Lead me to the <HI>Grave.</HI></Q>&mdash;I cannot re|commend the Glois; yet was willing to mention it.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="140" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM. CXL.</HI> To the Chief Mu&s;ician. A P&s;alm of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 RE&s;cue me, OETERNAL God, &Verbar; from the malicious Man; &Verbar; pre&s;erve me from the Man, who's us'd &Verbar; to do injurious things. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2"><PB N="384" REF="001946_0421_0FFE544F78962908">
2 They're tho&s;e who in their heart with|in &Verbar; contrive mi&s;chievous things; &Verbar; they do together come for war &Verbar; all day * and everyday. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 They give an edge unto their Tongue; &Verbar; <HI>Tis</HI> as the Serpents <HI>is;</HI> &Verbar; the Poi&s;on of the Adder lies &Verbar; under their Lips <HI>conceal'd.</HI>&Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 From the hands of the wicked one &Verbar; keep me, ETERNAL God; &Verbar; &s;ave me from the in|jurious man: &Verbar; they thought to trip me up &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 The Proud ones have &s;et &s;ecretly &Verbar; a Snare and Cords for me; &Verbar; they've &s;pread <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> Net by the way &s;ide; &Verbar; Gins they have &s;et for me. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 I unto the ETERNAL God &Verbar; have &s;aid, Thou art my God; &Verbar; O Thou ETERNAL God, The voice &Verbar; of my Petitions hear. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 ETERNAL God, the Lord, the Strength &Verbar; of my Salvation, <HI>Thou!</HI> &Verbar; Thou ha&s;t in day of Battle giv'n &Verbar; a covering to my Head. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Grant not, O Thou ETERNAL God, &Verbar; the wicked ones de&s;ires; &Verbar; O let not his de&s;ign obtain; &Verbar; they will exalt them&s;elves. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 As for the *Venomous Head of tho&s;e &Verbar; who compa&s;s me about, &Verbar; the mi&s;chief of their own Lips, let &Verbar; it overwhelm them&s;elves. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Let burning Coals upon him fall; &Verbar; let them be ca&s;t into &Verbar; the Fire, into the deepe&s;t pits <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> let them not ri&s;e again. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Let not an Evil &s;peaker be &Verbar; e&s;tabli&s;h'd in the Earth: &Verbar; let evil the injurious man &Verbar; to Precipices drive. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12"><PB N="385" REF="001946_0422_0FFE54512B426EB0">
12 I know that the ETERNAL God &Verbar; will judge the poor * and meek; &Verbar; on the behalf of needy Ones &Verbar; He'll Judgment execute. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Surely the Righteous Ones will make &Verbar; Confe&s;&s;ion to thy Name; &Verbar; and the upright before Thy Face&Verbar;&s;hall have their Sitting down. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXL. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE <HI>Prophetic Spirit</HI> here prepares a Prayer for them that are &s;uffering under <HI>Antichri&s;t.</HI></P>
<P>Yea, it looks as if here were &s;ome Eye, to what the Ancient Propheeles have al&s;o &s;poken concerning the De&s;truction of <HI>Gog.</HI></P>
<P>And indeed when the&s;e Two Enemies are gone, the <HI>Righteous</HI> will dwell with the greate&s;t Prai&s;es in the <HI>Pre&s;ence of God.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1 The <HI>M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">dr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;h Ti&s;lin</HI> has a &s;trange Pa&s;&s;age here. The <HI>Malicious Man,</HI> and the <HI>Man bent on violent things,</HI> is the <HI>Fourth Bea&s;t</HI> in the <HI>Seventh</HI> of <HI>Daniel.</HI></P>
<P N="10">10 An Allu&s;ion to the Fate of <HI>Sodom.</HI> Tis the Fate of <HI>Rome.</HI> Remember &s;till <HI>David</HI> was a Type of our Lord JESUS CHRIST. <HI>Antichri&s;t</HI> with his adhe|rents, the Ant type of <HI>David's</HI> Enemies. Read &s;uch P&s;alms as this, O <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> with a great Attention; and compare them with the Pa&s;&s;ages in the New Te&s;ta|ment, which de&s;cribe <HI>Antichri&s;t</HI> unto us, and thou wilt <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ee, <HI>Wendrous Things in the Law.</HI></P>
<P N="13">13 Pebel a Charming H<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">rmony, between the <HI>Ex|erci&s;es</HI> o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> Flety, and the <HI>Recompences</HI> of it. The Fi|nal and Endle&s;s and Compleat Ble&s;&s;edne&s;s of <HI>Upright</HI> Men, will be to, <HI>dwell in the Pre&s;ence</HI> of God. Even In that <HI>Pre&s;ence</HI> in which there is <HI>fulne&s;s of Joy;</HI> and &s;o to be <HI>&s;orever with the Lord.</HI> Now what an agree|ment is ther<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> between the <HI>Uprightne&s;s</HI> and the <HI>Ble&s;&s;ed|ne&s;s? Uprightne&s;s</HI> lies in this thing; To <HI>be always in the Pre&s;en<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">e of God;</HI> always <HI>to Act as in the Pre&s;ence
<PB N="386" REF="001946_0423_0FFE5452AE87BE40">of God;</HI> A Behaviour governed by a Sen&s;e of being un|der the <HI>Eve</HI> of God. An <HI>Upright Man,</HI> Oh! how &s;uitably is he <HI>Rewarded,</HI> when he is brought at length <HI>to dwell in the</HI> Pre&s;ence of God.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="141" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXLI.</HI> A P&s;alm Of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 ETERNAL God, I cry to thee: &Verbar; O ha&s;ten Thou to me! &Verbar; when I do cry to thee, do thou &Verbar; give Ear unto my Voice. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Let my Pray'r be directed &s;till &Verbar; <HI>as</HI> In|cen&s;e in thy View; &Verbar; As the Meat-Off'ring of the Eve &Verbar; the lifting of my hands. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 O Thou ETERNAL God, Set Thou &Verbar; a Watch before my Mouth; &Verbar; at the gate of my Lips do Thou &Verbar; maintain a con&s;tant guard. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 O do not Thou incline my Heart &Verbar; unto an Evil thing; &Verbar; to practi&s;e wicked Works with Men &Verbar; that work Iniquity. &Verbar; And in their Delicacies let &Verbar; me not Communicate. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 (The Ju&s;t &s;hall kindly &s;mite me, and &Verbar; &s;hall give reproofs to me); &Verbar; But the rich Oil of &s;uch an One &Verbar; &s;han't mollify my Head: &Verbar; For &s;till my Prayer it is again&s;t &Verbar; the Wicked th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">gs they do. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 By the &s;ides of the Rock it was &Verbar; their Judges were let down; &Verbar; they then did heark|en to my words, &Verbar; for they were plea&s;ant ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 As when one plougheth up the Earth &Verbar; and it a&s;under tears; &Verbar; our hones are &s;catter|ed &s;o about &Verbar; at the Mouth of the Grave. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8"><PB N="387" REF="001946_0424_0FFE5455E2988D58">
8 But, O ETERNAL God, the Lord, &Verbar; My Eyes are unto thee; &Verbar; on thee I my reliance place; &Verbar; O do not &s;trip my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Keep me from the Hands of the &s;nare &Verbar; which they have laid for me; &Verbar; and from th' intangling gins of tho&s;e &Verbar; that work ini|quity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 O let the wicked fall into &Verbar; the Nets they've &s;pread them&s;elves: &Verbar; I will keep clo&s;e <HI>with thee and mine</HI> &Verbar; until that I e&s;cape. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXLI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>A Frayer provided by the <HI>Prophetic Spirit,</HI> for the People of God, &s;cattered by the Power of <HI>An|tichri&s;t.</HI></P>
<P N="2">2 <HI>Mun&s;ter</HI> ob&s;erves, <HI>David</HI> was now an Exile, and could not attend the <HI>Daily Sacrifions.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 Far from Excluding the more obvious and common Sen&s;e of the Words, and from neglecting to learn the Duty of a <HI>Reproved Chri&s;tian</HI> in them, I would ask, Whether we may not have a CHRIST, in a <HI>Tran&s;con|dent Sen&s;e</HI> here Offering Him&s;elf, as well as in many other Pa&s;&s;ages of the Sacred Oracles, which we do not at the <HI>fir&s;t view,</HI> &s;ee <HI>Te&s;tifying of Him?</HI> Does not our SAVIOUR here de&s;ire, That His <HI>Interce&s;&s;ion</HI> may come in the Room of <HI>Incen&s;e,</HI> and <HI>Mincha</HI> under the Law? Don't we &s;ee Him here &s;tanding as a <HI>Surety</HI> for Sinners, with the&s;e Conce&s;&s;ions. <Q><HI>Let the Righte|ous</HI> GOD <HI>&s;mite me with an Hammer,</HI> in His Nail|ing me to the <HI>Cro&s;s:</HI> It will be a <HI>Mercy</HI> to His cho|&s;en, for whom, I am now to be <HI>Smitten. Let Him reprove me,</HI> &s;till I have the <HI>Oil of the Head</HI> upon me; I am the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> His <HI>Anointed,</HI> His Chri&s;t and His Prie&s;t. Whatever is now done to me, it &s;hall
<PB N="388" REF="001946_0425_0FFE57A3DB3D57C8">not <HI>break my Head;</HI> It was the Ancient Promi&s;e, That not <HI>my Head,</HI> but the <HI>Serpents</HI> only, &s;houl be broken. And nothing &s;hall hinder my <HI>Interce&s;&s;ion</HI> from its being &s;till continued. &mdash; After that, <HI>Their Judges &s;hall be overthrown by</HI> an <HI>Hand</HI> of <HI>Stone,</HI> (as the <HI>Syriac</HI> renders it). The <HI>Monarchia,</HI> o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> the World &s;hall be broken in Preces by a <HI>Ston cut out which is not in Hands.</HI> And this Di&s;pen&s;ation &s;hall be attended with, yea, effected by, <HI>my Words</HI> being <HI>made &s;weet unto them.</HI></Q></P>
<P>To return unto the Type. <HI>The Rich Oil of &s;uch an One &s;ha'nt mollifie my Head,</HI> may be, q. d. I'll never vi&s;it him. In a Vi&s;it this was the u&s;ual Com|plement. So, what we read, of <HI>the Ju&s;t &s;hall kindly &s;mite me,</HI> is but a Rapturous Parenthe&s;is. A Modern Traveller, who has pre&s;ented us with an Ingenious Cal|lection of <HI>Orientali&s;ins,</HI> for the Illu&s;tration of the Sa|cred Scriptures, has be&s;poke a Reception for this Illu&s;t|ration.</P>
<P N="6">6 We have a Key to this Pa&s;&s;age, in 1. Sam. XXIV. 2. When the <HI>Judges</HI> of <HI>I&s;rael, (Saul</HI> and his <HI>Offi|cers,) were let down</HI> (to pur&s;ue and &s;urpri&s;e <HI>David) by the Sides of the Rock</HI> (the <HI>Rocks of th Wild-Goats</HI> leading into the Cave;) Then they heard the Words of <HI>David's</HI> Apology for him&s;elf, which were &s;o plea&s;|ing to <HI>Saul,</HI> that he went home, and gave over di&s;turb|ing of <HI>David</HI> any more. Dr. <HI>Roberts</HI> gives us this Illu&s;tration in his <HI>Key of the Bible.</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 <HI>Robu&s;ti Davidis erant a Davide di&s;per&s;i.</HI> This is <HI>Aben-Fzra's</HI> Glo&s;s.</P>
<P>Dr. <HI>Patrick's</HI> Paraphra&s;e is this, <Q>They &s;till per&s;e|cute me, and the &s;mall Body of Men that follow me; whom they have reduced unto &s;uch Extremities, that like the Earth, when it is ploughed up, we break in Pieces and are ready to di&s;per&s;e, and flee for our Lives, with little hope of Safety.</Q></P>
<P N="10">10 q. d. I'll keep with my Friends, not &s;catter and
<PB N="389" REF="001946_0426_0FFE51A16C7F5F68">wander from them. The Safety and Wi&s;dom of good Men, lies much in their keeping <HI>Together;</HI> not going <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">funder.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="142" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXLII.</HI> Ma&s;chil; Of David. A Prayer when he was in the Cava.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 WIth my Voice I did make a Cry &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; with my voice to th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; I made my humble Pray'r. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 Before His Face I poured out &Verbar; what I had thought upon; &Verbar; Before His Face I utter|ed what &Verbar; was trouble&s;ome to me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Within me when my Spiritfaild, &Verbar; then Thou did&s;t know my Path; &Verbar; In the way where I &s;hould have walk'd &Verbar; they laid a Snare for me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Look on the Right hand, and behold; &Verbar; there's none does know me there; &Verbar; Refuge does peri&s;h from me, and &Verbar; there's none to &s;eek my Soul. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O Thou ETERNAL God, To Thee &Verbar; I made my cry, I &s;aid, &Verbar; Thou art my Hope, my Portion in &Verbar; the Land of Living Ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Attend unto my cry, becau&s;e &Verbar; I am brought very low; &Verbar; Save me from my pur|&s;uers, for &Verbar; they are more &s;trong than I. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 From out of Pri&s;on bring my Soul; &Verbar; That I may prai&s;e thy Name; &Verbar; the ju&s;t &s;hall be a Crown to me, &Verbar; when thou rewarde&s;t me. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="390" REF="001946_0427_0FFE57A7F08DA448">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXI II. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>A Prayer made ready for the Captives under the Tyranny of <HI>Antichri&s;t.</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 Remember, O <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> thou art here concerned with the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> Now, <HI>Aben-Ezra</HI> renders this Pa&s;|&s;age thus; <HI>Ju&s;ti coronabunt &s;e&s;e mecum.</HI> q. d. They &s;hall Glory in me, as having a <HI>Crown of Glory</HI> on their Head. Thus the Spani&s;h Tran&s;lation; <HI>Commigo &s;e to|ronoran los Ju&s;tos.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="143" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM. CXLIII.</HI> A P&s;alm Of David.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 ETERNAL God, hear Thou my Prayer, &Verbar; hearken to my Reque&s;ts: &Verbar; An&s;wer me in Thy faithfulne&s;s, &Verbar; <HI>and</HI> in thy righteou&s;ne&s;s. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 And with thy Servant, O do not &Verbar; thou into Judgment come; &Verbar; For in thy &s;ight no man alive &Verbar; &s;hall ju&s;tify him&s;elf. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 For th' En'my has pur&s;u'd my Soul; &Verbar; my Life &s;truck to the ground; &Verbar; made me in darkne&s;s dwell as tho&s;e &Verbar; that have been dead an Age. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 My &s;pirit therefore is in me &Verbar; faint * and quite overwhelm'd; &Verbar; My Hearts with|in the mid&s;t of me &Verbar; frighted * and de&s;olate. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 I do remember Ancient Days; &Verbar; I medi|tate upon &Verbar; all of thy Works; I think upon &Verbar; the Work thy Hands have wrought. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 I unto thee <HI>with Anxious Prayers</HI> &Verbar; ex|tend the&s;e Hands of mine; &Verbar; my Soul is as a thir&s;ty Land &Verbar; <HI>&s;till thir&s;ting</HI> after thee. &Verbar; Selah. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Hear me with &s;peed, ETERNAL God; &Verbar;
<PB N="391" REF="001946_0428_0FFE57A998AF9480">My Spirit fails; Thy Face &Verbar; hide not from me, le&s;t I be like &Verbar; them who de&s;cend the Pit. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 O that thy mercy Thou would&s;t make &Verbar; me in the Morning hear; &Verbar; Becau&s;e that I do ever place &Verbar; my Confidence on thee. &Verbar; Cau&s;e me to under&s;tand the way &Verbar; wherein I ought to walk; &Verbar; Becau&s;e that I <HI>with Pray'r and Hope</HI> &Verbar; lift up my Soul to Thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 O Thou ETERNAL God, Do Thou &Verbar; grant me Deliverance, &Verbar; from them that are my E|nemies: &Verbar; I hide my &s;elf with Thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 O teach me for to do thy Will, &Verbar; Be|cau&s;e Thou art my God; &Verbar; let thy good Spi|rit lead me to &Verbar; a Land of Rectitude. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 For thy Names &s;ake, ETERNAL God, &Verbar; Thou wilt enliven me; &Verbar; Thou for thy righte|ou&s;ne&s;s my Soul &Verbar; wilt out of trouble bring. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 And Thou wilt in thy mercy &s;lay &Verbar; my Enemies; and all &Verbar; the Troublers of my Soul de&s;troy; &Verbar; for I thy Servant am. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXLIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THE <HI>Prophetic Spirit</HI> here makes a Prayer for the Church, and for the Jewi&s;h Nation, lying in the State of <HI>Death,</HI> which is now de&s;cribed in the Prophe|cies of <HI>Ezekiel;</HI> and particularly Prays for the Out pou|ring of the <HI>Spirit,</HI> in &s;uch Gifts as are to be expected at the Second Coming of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI></P>
<P>But, O <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> Think on thy Dying and Ri&s;en SAVIOUR &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> finds the P&s;almi&s;t longing to get in|to an <HI>hone&s;t Country.</HI> But, O <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> Tis an <HI>Hea|venly World</HI> that is the true <HI>Land of Rectitude.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="144" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="392" REF="001946_0429_0FFE51A573DDC178">
<HEAD>PSALM CXLIV. <HI>Of David.</HI></HEAD>
<P N="1">1 BLe&s;&s;ed be the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; He is a Rock for me; &Verbar; He doth in&s;truct my hands for War, &Verbar; my fingers for a Fight. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 He is my Mercy, and my Tower, &Verbar; my Refuge &s;et on high; &Verbar; and He it is who doth be&s;tow &Verbar; deliverances on me. &Verbar; He is my Shield, and upon Him &Verbar; I do repo&s;e my tru&s;t; &Verbar; 'Tis He who to &s;ubjection brings &Verbar; my People under me. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 ETERNAL God, Oh! What is Man &Verbar; that Thou take cogni&s;ance &Verbar; of him? The Son of Man, that Thou &Verbar; e&s;teem him any thing? &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Man is no other than a piece &Verbar; of flying vanity; &Verbar; his days are like a &s;hadow which &Verbar; does quickly pa&s;s away. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 ETERNAL God, O bow thou down &Verbar; Thy Heavens and de&s;cend; &Verbar; The Mountains touch <HI>with Thunderbolts,</HI> &Verbar; and they &s;hall yield a &s;moke. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The Lightning do thou lighten forth; &Verbar; and do thou &s;catter them; &Verbar; Thy Arrows, O do thou &s;hoot forth, &Verbar; and do thou run them down. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 O from on high &s;end out thy hands; &Verbar; &s;ave me, and re&s;cue me &Verbar; from mighty wa|ters; from the hand &Verbar; of a <HI>ba&s;e</HI> &s;trangers brood. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 The mouth of the&s;e does u&s;e to &s;peak &Verbar; nothing but fal&s;ity; &Verbar; and their right hand a right hand is &Verbar; in which is found a lie. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9"><PB N="393" REF="001946_0430_0FFE57AE370E6FC8">
9 O God, I'll Sing thee a New-Song &Verbar; upon a P&s;altery; &Verbar; upon a Ten-&s;tring'd in&s;tru|ment &Verbar; I'll &s;ing a Ver&s;e to thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 He 'tis who on advanced Kings &Verbar; Sal|vation does be&s;tow; &Verbar; He &s;aves His Servant David from &Verbar; the mo&s;t de&s;tructive Sword. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Save me, and rid me from the hand &Verbar; of the <HI>ba&s;e</HI> &s;trangers brood; &Verbar; who&s;e mouth &s;peaks fal&s;e, and their right-hand's &Verbar; the right-hand of a lie. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 Let &s;o our Sons be like to Plants &Verbar; well <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">med in their Youth; &Verbar; Our Daughters like to corner Stores &Verbar; poli&s;h'd in Temple-form. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Our Garners full, affording &s;tore &Verbar; of e'ry &s;ort of food; &Verbar; Our Flocks yield thou|&s;ands; Myriads &s;o &Verbar; increa&s;ing in our &s;treets. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Our Beeves both fat * and &s;trong, to work; &Verbar; <HI>&s;afe</HI> * when they are with Young; &Verbar; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> breaking in, nor going out; &Verbar; nor clamour in the &s;treets. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 Happy tho&s;e People are <HI>e&s;teem'd</HI> &Verbar; who are in &s;uch a ca&s;e; &Verbar; Happy the People are, who&s;e God &Verbar; is the ETERNAL One. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXLIV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe Jewi&s;h Rabbi's, particularly <HI>Saadias</HI> and <HI>Kim|chi,</HI> own the P&s;alm to relate unto the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah.</HI> The Temporal Pro&s;perity here arrives after the De|&s;truction brought on the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">nemies of the <HI>Jewi&s;h</HI> Nation.</P>
<P N="1">1 Tho' I do with <HI>Hilary,</HI> di&s;like the LXX foi&s;ting that Clau&s;e, <HI>A P&s;alm against Goli<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">,</HI> into the Title of the P&s;alm. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;u&s;pect, the P&s;almi&s;t now on the
<PB N="394" REF="001946_0431_0FFE57AFC0231478">Throne, may have &s;ome Remembrances of, and Referen|ces to, his old Victory over <HI>Goliah;</HI> in this Ver&s;e par|ticularly. <HI>Arnobius</HI> thinks, here is an Allu&s;ion to <HI>Mo&s;es</HI> lifting up his <HI>Hands</HI> for the Conque&s;t of <HI>A<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">|lok;</HI> and adds, <HI>Docuit manus no&s;tras, in pralio, non Armis &s;ed p<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ecibus pugnaturas.</HI> The holy Martyr <HI>Barlam,</HI> thru&s;ting his hands into the burning Flames, Sang this Ver&s;e of the P&s;alm.</P>
<P N="4">4 That ever &s;uch things as are here celebrated; &s;hould be done for a, <HI>Man who is no other than a piece of flying vanity?</HI></P>
<P N="5">5 The proude&s;t Oppre&s;&s;ors will vani&s;h away like <HI>Smoke,</HI> when GOD appears to re&s;cue His People.</P>
<P N="9">9 <HI>Arnobius</HI> will tell you, <HI>A New Song,</HI> is, <HI>A New Life;</HI> And Kings are <HI>Victoros Vitiorum.</HI></P>
<P N="11">11 <HI>A Right Hand of a Lye,</HI> Take R. <HI>Obadiah Gaons</HI> Glo&s;s upon it; <HI>Scribere fal&s;a.</HI> It <HI>writes fal&s;ehoods.</HI></P>
<P>What is it they &s;peak? Some take it, for the Opi|nion, That <HI>Happine&s;s</HI> lies in Temporal Ble&s;&s;ings here. Corrected at la&s;t &s;o, <HI>Happy that People who&s;e God is the Lord.</HI> An Happine&s;s not enjoyed until the <HI>Re|&s;urrection-World.</HI></P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Kimchi</HI> ob&s;erves, That the Method and Order of the <HI>Ble&s;&s;ings</HI> here, is taken from, Deut. XXVIII. 4.</P>
<P N="14">14 Dr. <HI>Patrick's</HI> Paraphra&s;e, is not all that I have to ju&s;tify my Tran&s;lation.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="145" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD><HI>PSALM CXLV.</HI> Davids Prai&s;e.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 O Thou that art my God, the King, &Verbar; I'll thee extol <HI>[and &s;et]</HI> on high; &Verbar; and I will &s;peak well of thy Name &Verbar; to <HI>[endle&s;s]</HI> Ages &s;till to come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 All day, * and ev'ry day, I will &Verbar; keep <HI>[ever]</HI> &s;peaking well of thee; &Verbar; And I will celebrate thy Name &Verbar; to [<HI>endle&s;s</HI>] Ages &s;till to come. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3"><PB N="395" REF="001946_0432_0FFE51A9D3533078">
3 Mo&s;t Great is the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and greatly to be prais'd <HI>[is He.]</HI> &Verbar; And of His Greatne&s;s there cannot &Verbar; be <HI>[ever]</HI> any Searching out. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 One Generation &s;hall relate &Verbar; thy Works unto the next <HI>[that comes:]</HI> and the mo&s;t powerful things thou do&s;t, &Verbar; they &s;hall de|clare <HI>[them all]</HI> abroad. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 The Beauty, Oh! The Glory of &Verbar; His <HI>[more than]</HI> Royal Maje&s;ty; &Verbar; and the mo&s;t wondrous things thou do&s;t; &Verbar; of the&s;e <HI>[it is]</HI> I will di&s;cour&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 The Might of thy tremendous Acts, &Verbar; others &s;hall <HI>[al&s;o]</HI> &s;peak about; &Verbar; and of thy Greatne&s;s I my &s;elf &Verbar; will declarations make <HI>[with them.]</HI></P>
<P N="7">7 The mem'ry of the Greatne&s;s of &Verbar; thy Goodne&s;s <HI>[amply]</HI> they'l pour out; &Verbar; and of thy Right'ou&s;ne&s;s they &s;hall &Verbar; &s;ing with a <HI>[loud and]</HI> mighty noi&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Gracious is the ETERNAL God, &Verbar; and He's <HI>[truly]</HI> compa&s;&s;ionate; &Verbar; to anger He is very flow; &Verbar; but in His mercy <HI>[wondrous]</HI> great. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Even to all th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; is ever <HI>[Oh! how]</HI> &s;weetly good; &Verbar; yea, and His tender mercies are &Verbar; towards all <HI>[the Works]</HI> that He has wrought. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 All thy Works, O ETERNAL God, &Verbar; &s;hall <HI>[ever]</HI> celebrate thy Prai&s;e; &Verbar; and all that are thy gracious ones, &Verbar; they <HI>[ever]</HI> &s;hall &s;peak well of thee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11"><PB N="396" REF="001946_0433_0FFE5A02D9F8F8B8">
11 The Glory of thy Kingdom is &Verbar; what they &s;hall &s;peak <HI>[&s;o much]</HI> about; &Verbar; and thyn illu&s;trious pow'r is what &Verbar; they &s;hall make <HI>[&s;o much]</HI> mention of. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 For to make known His mighty Acts &Verbar; <HI>[this way]</HI> unto the Sons of Men; &Verbar; and the mo&s;t &s;plendid Glory of &Verbar; the Kingdom which He <HI>[ju&s;tly]</HI> claims. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Thy Kingdom is a Kingdom which &Verbar; &amp; <HI>[unknown]</HI> Ages doth extend; &Verbar; and thy Dominion does anto &Verbar; all <HI>[future]</HI> Ge|nerations la&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 Th' ETERNAL God does all &s;u&s;tain &Verbar; when <HI>[He &s;ees]</HI> they are falling down; &Verbar; and all <HI>of His</HI> He rai&s;es up &Verbar; when <HI>[He &s;ees]</HI> they are bowed down. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 The eyes of all do wait on thee &Verbar; with <HI>[Hope and]</HI> Expectation &s;till; &Verbar; and thou in the due &s;ea&s;on do&s;t &Verbar; give them their <HI>[wanted]</HI> &s;u&s;tenance. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 Thou open'&s;t* and thou do&s;t extend &Verbar; thy <HI>[kind and] <HI>all-relieving</HI></HI> Hand, &Verbar; and thou do&s;t &s;atisfy the wi&s;h &Verbar; <HI>[fully]</HI> of ev'ry living thing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 Righteous is the ETERNAL God &Verbar; <HI>[even]</HI> in all the ways He takes; &Verbar; and He is al&s;o merciful in all the Works He <HI>[ever]</HI> does. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="18">18 Th' ETERNAL God is near unto &Verbar; all <HI>[of tho&s;e]</HI> who do call on Him; &Verbar; <HI>near</HI> unto all who call on Him &Verbar; with truth* and <HI>[with due]</HI> con&s;tancy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19"><PB N="397" REF="001946_0434_0FFE5A078C4EC5A8">
19 He'l the de&s;ire fulfil of them &Verbar; that have the <HI>[Godly]</HI> fear of Him; &Verbar; He'l al&s;o hearken to their cry, &Verbar; and He'l <HI>[&s;ave and]</HI> deliver them. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 In &s;afety the ETERNAL God &Verbar; keeps all that have His Love <HI>[in them:]</HI> &Verbar; But all them that are impious ones &Verbar; He'll utterly de&s;troy <HI>[forever.]</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="21">21 My mouth &s;hall utter forth the Prai&s;e &Verbar; of <HI>[him who's]</HI> the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; and all fle&s;h ble&s;s His Holy Name &Verbar; ever <HI>[let it]</HI> and evermore. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXLV. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe P&s;alm was always e&s;teem'd &s;o excellent that the <HI>Title</HI> of the whole <HI>Book of P&s;alms</HI> was taken from it. It is wholly &s;pent in Prai&s;ing of GOD, with &s;uch admirable Devotion, that (as has been by <HI>Schindler</HI> long &s;ince ob&s;erved) the Ancient Hebrews did u&s;e to &s;ay, <HI>He could not fail to be a Child of the World to come, who would recite this P&s;alm Three times every Day.</HI> And, as Dr. <HI>Patrick</HI> ob&s;erves, This might be the Rea&s;on, why it was compo&s;ed <HI>Alphabe|tically;</HI> even that &s;o every Body might the more ea&s;ily learn and remember &s;o u&s;eful a P&s;alm.</P>
<P>Dr. <HI>Allix</HI> will have it, An Hymn of the Synagogue, Re&s;tored unto the Favour of GOD. The De&s;truction of the Wicked, and the Conver&s;ion of the Nations, under the Glorious Reign of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> is here par|ticularly celebrated.</P>
<P N="13">13 How did the Letter <HI>Nun</HI> come to be lo&s;t at this Ver&s;e of the <HI>Acro&s;tic?</HI> If it were lo&s;t when the P&s;alm came to the Hands of the Collector of this Book, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">he would not &s;upply it with one of his own. The
<PB N="398" REF="001946_0435_0FFE51ACDBB66028">Modern <HI>Greek,</HI> (I &s;ay <HI>Modern,</HI> for the <HI>Ancient</HI> and <HI>Theodotion</HI> and <HI>Aquila</HI> have it not;) and &s;o the <HI>Ara|bic</HI> and <HI>Syriac,</HI> and vulgar <HI>Latin</HI> &s;upply it &s;o, &mdash; <HI>The Lord is Faithful in all His Words, and Holy in all His Works.</HI> But this differs little from the <HI>Seventeenth</HI> Ver&s;e. And why might not the P&s;almi&s;t be carried, [as in the XXV. P&s;alm,] thro' the &s;trength of the In&s;piration upon him, out of the method he at fir&s;t propo&s;ed? Or, O <HI>Ma&s;orites,</HI> Do you give us a rea&s;on for this Omi&s;&s;ion.</P>
<P N="16">16 The Affectionate Glo&s;s of Old Chri&s;tianity was; <HI>Quanda aperui&s;ti manus tuas in Cruce.</HI> On the <HI>Cro&s;s!</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="146" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CXLVI.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 <HI>LEt</HI> HALLELUJAH <HI>now be Sung.</HI> &Verbar; <HI>And now,</HI> O thou my Soul, &Verbar; Do thou <HI>awake and</HI> utter Prai&s;e &Verbar; to the ETERNAL God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 I in my life,* and while I live, &Verbar; will Prai&s;e th' ETERNAL God; &Verbar; while I have any being I &Verbar; will &s;ing unto my God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Place not your confidence in Men &Verbar; of Princely pow'r and grace; &Verbar; Nor in an eminent Son of Man &Verbar; who can't a Saviour be. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 His &s;pirit* with his breath goes forth; &Verbar; He to his Earth returns; &Verbar; and in that very day his Thot's &Verbar; all come unto an end. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 O happy Man that has the God &Verbar; of Ja|cob for his help; &Verbar; who&s;e hope is in th' E|TERNAL God &Verbar; become a God to him. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 'Tis He who made the Heav'ns and Earth, &Verbar; the Sea, and all in them; &Verbar; 'Tis He who doth maintain the Truth &Verbar; to petpetuity. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7"><PB N="399" REF="001946_0436_0FFE5A09904FA0F0">
7 He Judges for oppre&s;&s;ed ones; &Verbar; He gives the hungry food. &Verbar; 'Tis the ETERNAL God who &s;ets &Verbar; the bound at liberty. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 Th' ETERNAL God opens the blind; &Verbar; th' ETERNAL God doth rai&s;e &Verbar; the bowed down; th' ETERNAL God &Verbar; doth love the right'ous ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Th' ETERNAL God doth Strangers keep, &Verbar; He gives &s;upport unto &Verbar; Orphan and Wi|dow: and &s;ubverts &Verbar; the way of wicked Men. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 Forever &s;hall JEHOVAH reign; &Verbar; thy God, O Zion, He &Verbar; <HI>&s;hall reign</HI> to Generations all. &Verbar; <HI>Sing</HI> Hallelujah <HI>now.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXLVI. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>HAve we not here an Hymn of the Re&s;tored Jewi&s;h Nation, under the Reign of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah?</HI></P>
<P N="3">3 The <HI>Per&s;ian</HI> Emperours, put a &s;top unto the Building of the Temple; To prevent a di&s;tru&s;t of God on this difficult occa&s;ion, One of tho&s;e Two Prophets <HI>Haggai</HI> or <HI>Zechariah,</HI> might compo&s;e the P&s;alm that is now before us; exhorting them notwith&s;tanding the ill pro&s;pect of their Affairs, to <HI>put their Tru&s;t in GOD.</HI> Well; <HI>Camby&s;es</HI> dies; and then in &s;pite of all oppo&s;ers, the City, Temple, and Wor&s;hip of God, were gloriou&s;ly carried on.</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>Gods on Earth,</HI> and vet but <HI>Gods of Earth.</HI> 'Tis not &s;aid, They return to <HI>their Cities,</HI> to <HI>their Ca&s;tles,</HI> to <HI>their Kingdoms;</HI> The&s;e now become <HI>anothers;</HI> But <HI>their Earth.</HI> A Little <HI>Earth</HI> is now all they have. It may be the <HI>Earth</HI> is all they &s;et their hearts upon.</P>
<P N="8">8 Above a Thou&s;and Years after, the&s;e <HI>Works</HI> were notably exemplified; And on <HI>Sabbaths</HI> too; A My&s;tery pointing at the Kingdom of our SAVIOUR, in the
<PB N="400" REF="001946_0437_0FFE51B5C7DCC970"><HI>Sabbath</HI> of the World, foretold at the clo&s;e of the P&s;alm. There were <HI>Seven Sabbaths</HI> which our Lord &s;ignaliz'd, in the Time of His Mini&s;try with working <HI>Miracles</HI> thereupon. The Fifth of them was, when He <HI>rai&s;ed</HI> up one that had been <HI>bowed down.</HI> [Luk. XIII.] The Sixth of them was, when He <HI>opened the Eyes</HI> of one that had been born <HI>Blind</HI> [Joh. IX.] <HI>Grotius</HI> truly ob|lerves, <HI>Mire haec congruunt in Chri&s;ti Tempora.</HI> But, O <HI>Chri&s;tian,</HI> there is more to come. On that, <HI>He &s;ets the Bound at Liberty,</HI> the <HI>Midra&s;h Tillin</HI> has that wonderful Glo&s;s; <HI>In the future Age, God per|mits the u&s;e of all &s;orts of Foods. Yea, He relea&s;es tho&s;e that are Bound in Death and the Grave.</HI> O Jews, Con&s;ider of it.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="147" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CXLVII.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 <HI>SIng</HI> HALLELUJAH. For 'tis good &Verbar; to Sing unto our God; &Verbar; Becau&s;e it is a plea&s;ant thing: &Verbar; Prai&s;e is a comely thing. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 'Tis the ETERNAL God who does &Verbar; build both Jeru&s;alems; &Verbar; and the Out-ca&s;ts of I&s;rael He &Verbar; will &s;urely gather in. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 He heals the broken-hearted ones; &Verbar; and He binds up their wounds. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 He tells the number of the Stars; &Verbar; He calls them all by name. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Great is the Lord on whom we lean; &Verbar; and very much His power; &Verbar; There is no number of the things &Verbar; His wi&s;dom knows and does. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Th' ETERNAL God, He rai&s;es up &Verbar; the meek-afflicted ones; &Verbar; He bringeth down the wicked ones &Verbar; unto the very du&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7"><PB N="401" REF="001946_0438_0FFE5A0C9FC90DF0">
7 An&s;wers to the ETERNAL God &Verbar; with a Confe&s;&s;ion give; &Verbar; Sing with a Ver&s;e unto our God &Verbar; upon the Ten-&s;tring'd Harp. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 With Clouds the Heavens He does cloath; &Verbar; Rain for the Earth prepares; &Verbar; He makes the lofty Mountains to &Verbar; produce the tender herb. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 He doth be&s;tow upon the Bea&s;t &Verbar; for each their proper food: &Verbar; Upon the Ravens Young Ones, when &Verbar; they makes their piteous cry. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10">10 In the &s;trength of the Hor&s;e he doth &Verbar; not any plea&s;ure take; &Verbar; nor is He plea&s;ed in the Legs &Verbar; of Man; <HI>He needs them not.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 Th' ETERNAL God takes plea&s;ure in &Verbar; &s;uch as maintain His fear: &Verbar; in them who on His mercy do &Verbar; maintain a lively hope. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 O both Jeru&s;alems, Do ye &Verbar; Prai&s;e the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; O Zion, Do thou offer up &Verbar; thy Prai&s;es to thy God. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Becau&s;e He giveth &s;trength unto &Verbar; the bars that keep thy gates; &Verbar; on thy Sons in the mid&s;t of thee &Verbar; His ble&s;&s;ing He be&s;tows. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 He makes thy borders to enjoy &Verbar; peace and pro&s;perity; &Verbar; richly He doth &s;upply thee with &Verbar; the fine&s;t of the wheat. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="15">15 He to the Earth &s;ends His command; &Verbar; His Word does &s;wiftly run. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="16">16 The Snow He gives like wool; the Fro&s;t &Verbar; He does like a&s;hes ca&s;t. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="17">17 The Ice* and Hail like mor&s;els, He&Verbar;throws down <HI>to nouri&s;h it;</HI>&Verbar;Before the Face of His &s;harp Cold, &Verbar; who is there that can &s;tand?&Verbar;</P>
<P N="18"><PB N="402" REF="001946_0439_0FFE5A138FA003E8">
18 He does <HI>again</HI> &s;end forth His Word, &Verbar; and &s;o He melteth them; &Verbar; His Spirit He doth make to blow, &Verbar; whereon the Waters flow. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="19">19 He of His Words to Jacob doth&Verbar; a reve|lation make: &Verbar; His Statutes and His Judg|ments He &Verbar; reveals to I&s;rael. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="20">20 In &s;uch a manner He hath not &Verbar; with any Nation dealt; &Verbar; For they right things dont under&s;tand. &Verbar; <HI>Sing</HI> HALLELUJAH <HI>now.</HI>&Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXLVII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P><HI>JEru&s;alem</HI> is here &s;uppo&s;ed as re-e&s;tabli&s;hed, and the Marks of the Divine Pre&s;ence and Ble&s;ting in the mid&s;t of it, fixed; and the Jewi&s;h Nation gathered. It is an Hymn of Thanksgiving for this Revolution. The Condition of the <HI>Chri&s;tians</HI> turned <HI>Heathens</HI> at this time, under the Wrath of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> is bewailed.</P>
<P N="4">4 <HI>Kimchi</HI> &s;ays, The <HI>Stars</HI> are the <HI>Ju&s;t</HI> mentioned, <HI>Dan.</HI> XII. 3. who &s;hall be then employed in <HI>Turning many to Righteou&s;ne&s;s. Arnobius</HI> has a Glo&s;s a little akin to it. <HI>Numerare Multitudinem &s;tellarum eum credamus, in Sanctis.</HI> Dr. <HI>Patrick's</HI> Paraphra&s;e is; <Q>Whom He knows how to gather out of all their Di&s;|per&s;ions, and to find every one of them, wherever they are, tho' as numerous as the <HI>Stars</HI> of Heaven. [<HI>Gen.</HI> XV. 5.] which He as di&s;tinctly and exactly un|der&s;tands (how confu&s;ed &s;oever they &s;eem to us to be &s;cattered in the Sky,) as we do tho&s;e things which we call by their proper Names.</Q><HI>Mun&s;tors</HI> Glo&s;s is the &s;ame, <HI>Eadem facilitate qua &s;tellas in Caelo di&s;|per&s;as m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">merat.</HI></P>
<P N="8">8 The <HI>Clouds</HI> and <HI>Rains</HI> are mentioned becau&s;e of the Plenty now granted <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">hem. [<HI>Hag.</HI> II. 19.]</P>
<P N="10">10 Dr. <HI>Patrick's</HI> Paraphra&s;e is; <Q>Let us not be afraid, tho' we are of little Force, [<HI>Neh.</HI> IV. 3, 4. VII. 4.]
<PB N="403" REF="001946_0440_0FFE5A1515FAD0D8">and have no Armies of <HI>Hor&s;e</HI> and <HI>Foot</HI> to defend us. For the Lord who Fights for us [<HI>Nab.</HI> IV. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">0.] hath no need of the&s;e; and will not take part with our Enemies, becau&s;e they are Superiour to us, in the &s;trength of their <HI>Hor&s;es,</HI> and the nimblene&s;s of their <HI>Soldicrs.</HI></Q></P>
<P N="12">12 The Reduplication of the invitation to the Prai&s;es of God, is not without a <HI>My&s;tery,</HI> and a <HI>Pro|phecy</HI> for Two Returns from Captivity. Moreover that Name, <HI>Thy GOD,</HI> more peculiarly carries the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> in the Signification of it. It is in Him, that God be|comes <HI>OUR GOD.</HI> In the <HI>Second Return,</HI> the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> will be more eminently acknowledged and glorified.</P>
<P N="15">15 The Intention of introducing the Circum&s;tances of the <HI>Winter</HI> here, is well touched in the <HI>Patrician</HI> Paraphra&s;e. <Q>GOD &s;hews us, by the <HI>Fruitful Sea&s;ons</HI> He &s;ends, after all things &s;eem to be kill'd by the hard <HI>Winter,</HI> that He doth not intend by our Affliction to de&s;troy us; and that He can ea&s;ily bring all our Bre|thren hither, who remain &s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ill in Captivity. For when He would have any Alter<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">tion made in the Earth,</Q> it is done as &s;peedily as we can &s;peak.</P>
<P N="16">16 Our Husbandmen burn heaps of Rubbi&s;h on their New-ploug'd Ground. Probably the <HI>I&s;raeliti&s;h</HI> Hus|bandmen did &s;o too. They <HI>&s;cattered A&s;hes</HI> on their Fields; or perhaps ca&s;t <HI>A&s;hes</HI> on their Dunghills, where being diluted by the <HI>Rains,</HI> the Salt very deeply im|pregnared them, and the diffu&s;ion of &s;uch a <HI>Salt</HI> was a notable way to produce a Fruitful Soyl. <HI>Virgil</HI> &s;peaks divers times of this Practice in his <HI>Georgicks.</HI></P>
<P>The Greeks of Old called <HI>Snow,</HI> by the term of <HI>Wet-Wooll.</HI> The Latin, <HI>Floccus,</HI> is both a <HI>Lock of Wool,</HI> and a <HI>Flake of Snow.</HI> There is a Saline Spirit in this <HI>Woollen Mantle;</HI> and it has a <HI>Fructifying Vertue.</HI> A <HI>Winter</HI> of &s;ea&s;onable <HI>Snows,</HI> is u&s;ually followed with a <HI>Fruitful Summer. Floods</HI> of <HI>Snow-Water</HI> enrich the Earth exceedingly.</P>
<P N="19"><PB N="404" REF="001946_0441_0FFE5A1706C50458">
19 The <HI>Word</HI> of God, gives us, yet more full In|&s;tructions, than what we have in the <HI>Meteors</HI> of the <HI>Winter,</HI> to depend upon GOD.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="148" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CXLVIII.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 LEt HALLELUJAH <HI>now be Sung!</HI>&Verbar; Now from the Heav'ns above &Verbar; Prai&s;e the ETERNAL God; prai&s;e Him &Verbar; in the high places there. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 All you His Angels, O Prai&s;e Him; &Verbar; Prai&s;e Him, O all His Ho&s;ts. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Prai&s;e ye Him, O thou Sun, and Moon; &Verbar; Prai&s;e Him all Stars of light. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Prai&s;e Him, ye that the Heavens are &Verbar; of Heavens, <HI>Seats of Bli&s;s:</HI> &Verbar; and <HI>Prai&s;e Him,</HI> you the Waters which &Verbar; above the Heavens are. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Let them give Prai&s;es to the Name &Verbar; of the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; For He gave His Com|mandement, &Verbar; and they created are. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 He al&s;o hath e&s;tabli&s;h'd them &Verbar; forever, Evermore; &Verbar; He hath made a Decree, and it &Verbar; &s;hall never be tran&s;gre&s;s'd. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Now from the Earth below, give Prai&s;e&Verbar; to the ETERNAL God; &Verbar; <HI>Do it,</HI> ye Dragons* and ye Whales, &Verbar; and <HI>do it</HI> all ye Deeps. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 <HI>Do it</HI> both O thou Fire and Hail; &Verbar; O Snow and Vapour too; &Verbar; <HI>Do it</HI> O thou Tem|pe&s;tuous Wind, &Verbar; which does &s;ulfil His Word. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 <HI>Do it,</HI> O you High Mountains, and &Verbar; all of you le&s;&s;er Hills; &Verbar; <HI>Do it,</HI> O you Fruit-bear|ing Trees, &Verbar; and all you Cedars <HI>join.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="10"><PB N="405" REF="001946_0442_0FFE5A1893466AF0">
10 <HI>Do it,</HI> O all you Animals, &Verbar; and all you Cattle kind; &Verbar; <HI>Do it,</HI> O ev'ry creeping Thing, &Verbar; and <HI>ev'ry</HI> flying Fowl. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="11">11 <HI>Do it,</HI> O all Kings of the Earth, &Verbar; and all ye People too; &Verbar; <HI>Do it,</HI> O Princes, and all you &Verbar; the Judges of the Earth. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Do it,</HI> O you that Young Men are, &Verbar;yea, and Young Women too; &Verbar; <HI>Do it,</HI> O you that Old Men are, &Verbar; with Babes in Infancy. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="13">13 Let the&s;e with Prai&s;es <HI>due to Him</HI> &Verbar; &s;o celebrate the Name &Verbar; of the ETERNAL; for His Name &Verbar; alone is Excellent. His Glory is above the Earth, &Verbar; yea, and above the Heav'ns. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="14">14 And He, of His own People doth &Verbar; ex|alt the Horn on high; &Verbar; the Prai&s;es of His gracious ones, &Verbar; the Sons of I&s;rael; &Verbar; a People that are near to Him. &Verbar; <HI>Sing</HI> HALLELU|JAH <HI>now.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXLVIII. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe People of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah</HI> are here &s;uppo&s;ed, to be gathered unto Him, and all Creatures are ex|horted now to prai&s;e Him.</P>
<P N="12">12 <HI>Kimchi</HI> &s;aies, <HI>Old Men</HI> are joined with <HI>Children</HI> in the Invitations to <HI>Prai&s;e the Iord;</HI> becau&s;e the <HI>Old Men</HI> are to teach the <HI>Children</HI> who know not how to do it of them&s;elves. Yea, <HI>Old Men</HI> often &s;an|cy to have <HI>Children</HI> under their tuition; perhaps mo&s;t of them <HI>Grand Children. Young Men</HI> and <HI>Young Women</HI> are added in the Ver&s;e. Thus the <HI>Thre<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> Ages</HI> are called upon. The Apo&s;tle <HI>John,</HI> may allude hereto, when he &s;ales. I write unto you, <HI>Fathers, Young Men. and Children.</HI> And when the Seryants of God be<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">an
<PB N="406" REF="001946_0443_0FFE5A209B763E30">their Speeches, <HI>Men, Brethren, and Fathers';</HI> By <HI>Brethren,</HI> with a humble Figure they may mean <HI>Children.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="149" TYPE="Psalm">
<HEAD>PSALM CXLIX.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 <HI>SIng</HI> HALLEUJAH. A New Song &Verbar; Sing to th' ETERNAL God; &Verbar; His Prai&s;e is in the Church of tho&s;e &Verbar; that are His gra|cious Ones. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 In Him who is his maker now &Verbar; let I&s;|rael rejoice; &Verbar; Them that are Sons of Zion let &Verbar; be joyful in their King. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 With a Tripudiating Joy &Verbar; O let them Prai&s;e His Name; &Verbar; let them &s;ing Prai&s;es unto Him &Verbar; with Timbrel and with Harp. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 For the ETERNAL God doth in &Verbar; His People take Delight; &Verbar; He'll beautify the low * and meek &Verbar; with His Salvation &s;till. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 In Glory let the Gracious Ones &Verbar; * mo&s;t gloriou&s;ly rejoyce; &Verbar; on their Beds, <HI>where they re&s;t or fea&s;t,</HI> &Verbar; O let them &s;ing aloud. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 High Prai&s;es of the mighty God &Verbar; let warble thro' their Throat; &Verbar; and in their hand let there be held &Verbar; a double-Edged Sword. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="7">7 Due Vengeance for to Execute &Verbar; upon the Nations &s;o. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="8">8 To bind their Kings in Chains, and their &Verbar; Nobles in Iron Bonds. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="9">9 Upon them for to Execute &Verbar; the Judg|ment written down. &Verbar; This honour all His gracious Ones &Verbar; enjoy. Prai&s;e ye the Lord. &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<PB N="407" REF="001946_0444_0FFE5A22203B7700">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CXLIX. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe P&s;aim is fitted unto the Time, when the <HI>Me&s;|&s;iah</HI> reigns over the re&s;tored Jewi&s;h Nation; and and their Joy on the Occa&s;ion mentioned it the XXXVIII of <HI>Ezekiel,</HI> and the XIV of <HI>Zechariah.</HI></P>
<P N="3">3 <HI>Tripudiating Joy.</HI> Or, the <HI>Dance.</HI> They <HI>Prai&s;e the Lord in the Dance,</HI> who u&s;e much <HI>Activity,</HI> in the Prai&s;ing of God; They who are ever in <HI>Motions</HI> which have a Tendency to utter or produce the Prai&s;es of God; They who al&s;o <HI>a&s;&s;ociate with others</HI> in Vigo|rous E&s;&s;ays to do tho&s;e things wherein God may be glo|rified. Behold the <HI>Dance</HI> of the Evangelical Di&s;pen&s;a|tion. The <HI>Choreutic Agitations</HI> of the Body, are too mean things to be chiefly intended here.</P>
<P N="4">4 When God &s;hall be&s;tow <HI>Salvation</HI> on His People, He will al&s;o <HI>beautify</HI> them. How? <HI>Sanctify</HI> them. The <HI>Beauties of Holine&s;s</HI> will be &s;een upon them.</P>
<P>Think on this, O Pretenders to a <HI>Ju&s;tified State,</HI> and behold all <HI>Antinomian</HI> Pre&s;umptions fulminated. But one Singular <HI>Beauty</HI> on the <HI>&s;aved</HI> People of God, and indeed one that prepares them for <HI>Salvation,</HI> is <HI>Meek|ne&s;s</HI> and <HI>Patience.</HI> Pro&s;ecute this with a Thou&s;and Holy Meditations.</P>
<P N="6">6 It hath been the Cu&s;tom of all Nations, to pre|pare and excite them&s;elves for a Fight, by &s;ome In&s;tru|men of Mu&s;ick. <HI>Clemens</HI> of <HI>Alexandria</HI> enumerates the Variety. But it was proper unto the <HI>I&s;raelites,</HI> to go forth again&s;t their Enemies, with <HI>P&s;alms</HI> of Prai&s;e to the God, who had given great Victories unto their Ance&s;tors.</P>
<P N="8">8 An Allu&s;ion to Judges 1.7. The State of things in the Days of the <HI>New Jeru&s;alem</HI> is referr'd to. Now, turn to I&s;aiah. LX. 11, 12. and you have a Key to this Pa&s;&s;age. Yea, in the Pre&s;ent time, the People of God, by their <HI>Prayers,</HI> obtain the <HI>Re&s;traints</HI> of His Provi|dence, to be laid upon &s;uch Per&s;ons, a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">are here &s;poken of.</P>
<P N="9">9 <HI>The Judgment written of.</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ee Deut. VII. 20. and XXXII. 41, 42, 43.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="150" TYPE="Psalm">
<PB N="408" REF="001946_0445_0FFE51B74AEA1528">
<HEAD>PSALM. C L.</HEAD>
<P N="1">1 PRai&s;e ye the Lord. In's holine&s;s &Verbar; Prai&s;e ye the mighty God; &Verbar; Prai&s;e ye Him in the Firmament &Verbar; where His &s;trong Pow'r is &s;een. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="2">2 O Prai&s;e Him for the mighty things &Verbar; which have been done by Him; &Verbar; Prai&s;e Him; as there are many things &Verbar; wherein His great|ne&s;s <HI>&s;hines.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<P N="3">3 Prai&s;e Him with &s;ound of Trumpet; with &Verbar; P&s;altry and Harp Him prai&s;e. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="4">4 Prai&s;e Him with Timbrel and with a &Verbar; tripudiating Pipe. &Verbar; Prai&s;e Him with &s;tringed In&s;truments &Verbar; and with the Organ too. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="5">5 Prai&s;e Him upon the Cymbals which &Verbar; are very audible, &Verbar; Prai&s;e Him on Cymbals heard on high &Verbar; * as for a Jubilee. &Verbar;</P>
<P N="6">6 Prai&s;e JAH, O every thing that breaths. &Verbar; <HI>Sing</HI> HALLELUJAH <HI>now.</HI> &Verbar;</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="explanation">
<HEAD>ILLUSTRATIONS on the CL. PSALM.</HEAD>
<P>THe P&s;alm relates to the Reign of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> when <HI>every thing that hath Breath</HI> will <HI>Prai&s;e the Lord. Maimonides</HI> gives us a Jewi&s;h Tradition, That when the People brought up their <HI>Fir&s;t Fruits,</HI> to pre&s;ent them unto the Lord, according to the XXVI. of <HI>Deuteronomy,</HI> as &s;oon as they came to the Mountain of the Temple, every one took his Basker into his hand, and Sang this whole <HI>P&s;alm;</HI> till they came to the Courts of the Hou&s;e of the Lord: And then the <HI>Le|vites</HI> met them, Singing, the XXX P&s;alm.</P>
<P N="1">1 Of Old they read it, <HI>Laudate Deum in Sanctis ejus.</HI> And their Glo&s;e was; 'Tis done, <HI>Quando corum imi|tamur
<PB N="409" REF="001946_0446_0FFE5A23E3E69CE0">Exempla, &s;equimur Monit<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">, Regulam obtine|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">us. Aben-Ezra</HI> ob&s;erves, we have no way left now, to know, what the&s;e Mu&s;icial In&s;truments were; There being many found in the Country of the <HI>I&s;hmaelites,</HI> (or Mahometans) which are not among the Men of <HI>Edom,</HI> (or <HI>Chri&s;tians.</HI>)</P>
<P>It may not be ami&s;s here to mention, what Mon&s;ieur <HI>Jurieu</HI> has ob&s;erved.</P>
<P>There are Three Sorts of <HI>In&s;truments</HI> frequently mentioned in the <HI>P&s;alms;</HI> The <HI>Cymbals,</HI> the <HI>P&s;alie|rys,</HI> and the <HI>Harps.</HI></P>
<P>The <HI>Cymbals</HI> were large and broad pieces of Bra&s;s bent, and giving a &s;trong &s;ound; which were beaten very near in &s;uch a manner, as we now beat our <HI>Drums;</HI> and are known by the Name of <HI>Tymbals</HI> in our Days. Our Apo&s;tle <HI>Paul</HI> in a famous Text alludes unto them.</P>
<P>The <HI>P&s;alterys</HI> were <HI>Violins,</HI> on which they play'd. with a Bow, Ten Strings belong'd unto it; and the &s;eve|ral Notes were managed with the Bow and the touch, as tis done on the <HI>Violins</HI> in our days.</P>
<P>The <HI>Harps,</HI> had Twelve Notes, and every Note had its own String, which was managed with the Fingers, and could not be altered by the different way of touching.</P>
<P>The <HI>Levites</HI> were the only Per&s;ons that were to play on the&s;e In&s;truments. Indeed we read of <HI>David,</HI> and all the Hou&s;e of <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> playing on In&s;truments, at the Tran&s;portation of the Ark. But Mon&s;ieur <HI>Jurieu</HI> thinks, this might be one of the Irregularities which oc|ca&s;ioned the Death <HI>Unzah.</HI> At lea&s;t it may be &s;uppo&s;|ed, that this was not allowed of, Except in the Coun|trey and in private Hou&s;es. But in the <HI>Temple,</HI> no body dur&s;t play on In&s;truments, unle&s;s he were a <HI>Levite,</HI> or the Son of a <HI>Levite.</HI> We &s;ay, the Son of a <HI>Levite,</HI> becau&s;e the <HI>Rabbi's</HI> tell us, that &s;uch of the Levites as were Singers, did u&s;e to bring their Sons along with them, into the Court of the Prie&s;t, tho they were not come to their Full Age required unto the performance
<PB N="410" REF="001946_0447_0FFE51C5484DB798">of any Service there on their own bohalf. There is ano|ther Tradition of the <HI>Rabbi's,</HI> That is was allowable to make choice of <HI>Singers</HI> from among the People of <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> provided they were by Marriage near akin to the <HI>Sacerdotal Race.</HI></P>
<P>But, O <HI>Sincere Chri&s;tians, Lifted up to Heaven!</HI> You all are <HI>Prie&s;ts of God:</HI> And of the Tribe, who may and &s;hall <HI>Sing</HI> His Prai&s;es. His <HI>Graces</HI> in your Souls, will be the Glorious In&s;truments wherewith you &s;hall perform the Noble Exerci&s;e.</P>
<P N="6">6 The <HI>Bere&s;chith Rabba</HI> carries it, as if every Breath of a good Man &s;hould Prai&s;e the Lord; There &s;hould be a Prai&s;e of God in every Breath of &s;uch a Man. In the &s;trict Sen&s;e of it, this is not attainable by any Man Breathing in this Evil World. However to be Breath|ing after as much of this Attainment as can be come at, becomes a Chri&s;tian.</P>
<TRAILER>The End of the PSALMS.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
